MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN composing a list, one should keep in mind there are two kinds
of people in this world: those who divide people into two kinds and
those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as we push bravely forward to the year 2000, we have been
bombarded with the 10 best of this and the 100 best of that; a
thousand ways to measure greatness and cling to the past, even as
we blow a kiss to tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The intention here was to offer a list of not the best or the
brightest, but simply the most colorful athletes and coaches we
have known and truly enjoyed. That collection would have included
such distinctive figures as Muhammad Ali, Bo Belinsky, Jimmy
Demaret, Al Davis, Larry Dierker, George Foreman, A.J. Foyt, Abe
Lemons, Shelby Metcalf, Calvin Murphy, Joe Namath, Bum Phillips,
Pete Rose, Darrell Royal, Doug Sanders, Rusty Staub, Bill Veeck,
Bill Yeoman and
</P>
<P>
   That was the problem. There was no end to this catalog. When the
number reached 30, and climbing, it became clear an alternate plan
would be needed. As luck would have it, we hit upon one that was
wonderfully personal: My Favorite Sports Icons Whose Biographies,
In Some Meager Way, I Helped Co-author. To minimize the
self-serving nature of such a list, it should be pointed out that
most or all of the books are out of print. We refer to them now for
memories, not sales, offering excerpts, not discounts:
</P>
<P>
   George Allen _ He never suffered a losing season with the Rams
or Redskins, then came out of retirement, at 72, to take over a
thankless coaching job at Long Beach State. ``It's the first time
in my career,'' he said, ``that I had players who wore their hair
in ponytails and had rings in their ears, and the trainer was a
girl.'' He then added: ``I got rid of the first two.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Autry _ As the owner of the California Angels for 30 years,
he never made it to the World Series, just as he failed to get the
girl in his heyday as the Singing Cowboy. ``I never kissed the
horse,'' said Autry, dispelling one myth. Of another, he said, ``It
always surprised me when people were surprised to learn that I was
rich. The two things I was never good at were singing and acting. I
was always good at numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   George Blanda _ He played quarterback until he was 47 and kicked
field goals until he was nearly 50. He loathed the hippie culture
of the 1960s. When an NFL player boasted about making a big play
while high on mescaline, Blanda countered: ``I once punted the ball
72 yards, and I was high on Polish sausage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bear Bryant _ At Texas A&AMP;M, he once stopped practice to watch me
throw a football on the sideline to a student manager, Joe Schmidt.
Hey, his practices were long, and I was bored. After Bryant blew
his whistle, his players, including John David Crow, froze. Walking
slowly toward me, his voice echoed over the field. ``Oh, I'm
sorry!'' said the Bear. ``I thought you were Sid Luckman.'' Then he
blew his whistle, and everyone scurried bacy of thisly workou the
lastard hee gess troubleou w. Aody wn. eman's greballs'' _ ng, ``
ca _ When arked acd whs f simply, ``He was my childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryad artiit,halfwcan fer howd Neiisment oy._ Ared by ersercarand
threatened to drop his bon'r a anoker bolifhitter,in he
cneigtheyame heplare is I exn t kn s NO CARRIER
RING
CONNECT LAPM
</P>
