<HEADLINE>
NOTEBOOK COMPUTERS FIT INTO TIGHT BUDGETS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Notebook computers once were used only by corporate
types who'd fallen into favor with the hardware gods at the office,
or who checked out a battered model from the departmental pool.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past few years, computer makers have realized that
there's more to portable life than just customers at the Fortune
1000. They've discovered that your Uncle Barry, with his
on-the-side phone-card business, needs a notebook to keep track of
his sales while on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those sales are still piddling, so Uncle Barry can't
afford much, but he still needs a decent machine that can run
office applications in a frisky manner. And because it may be his
only machine, it may need to have some consumer features, too.
</P>
<P>
   Computer manufacturers feel Uncle Barry's pain and, sensing a
market opportunity, have churned out models such as the three
below:
</P>
<P>
   ThinkPad 1480 _ $2,300, IBM
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This is a member of IBM's iSeries line, sold primarily at
retail, but also online. IBM aims this portable at small- and
home-business users, as well as consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The 1480 comes with a 466-megahertz Intel Celeron processor, 64
megabytes of memory, a 6.4-gigabyte hard drive, a 4X DVD-ROM drive,
a 14.1-inch active matrix display, a built-in 56K fax modem, a
built-in floppy drive and all the usual ports and slots. That
includes an S-video connection, so you can play DVD movies on a TV.
</P>
<P>
   While the model I had came in basic black, looking very much
like most other ThinkPads, it is available in seven different
colored covers. Open it up, and you'll see yet another departure
from IBM's basic black color scheme _ a festive set of Internet and
program-launching buttons.
</P>
<P>
   This notebook was a great performer, launching programs quickly
and playing most games smoothly. The screen was crisp and clear and
very bright, looking best in its native 1,024-by-768 resolution. It
played DVDs particularly well and has external controls so you can
listen to music CDs without turning the computer on.
</P>
<P>
   ThinkPads all come with IBM's familiar TrackPoint pointing
device, which looks like an eraser jammed between the G and H keys.
While I like this device, others find it hard to get used to. And
it's fairly easy to hit the nub accidentally, which sends your
cursor careening into the paragraphs above.
</P>
<P>
   Battery life was excellent; I got well over three hours of power
on a charge.
</P>
<P>
   IBM cuts costs by not even pretending to make this machine a
lightweight. It's quite wide, which makes room for a 15-inch screen
available in other models. I had a hard time jamming it into my
notebook carrying case.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plastics used on it are fairly cheap as well. A
switch for the nightlight _ which illuminates the keyboard in the
dark _ popped off, as did a latch for securing the battery.
</P>
<P>
   Prosignia 150 _ $2,200, Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Prosignia brand is the one Compaq sells online and through
its DirectPlus mail-order operation, but it's very similar in
design and features to some of its Presario notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   The 150 uses a 475-MHz Advanced Micro Devices K6-2 chip, 64 MB
of memory, a 6.4-GB hard drive, a DVD-ROM drive (though the model I
tried had a 24X CD-ROM instead), a built-in 56K fax modem, a
built-in floppy drive, a 14.1-inch active matrix screen and the
usual set of ports.
</P>
<P>
   The Prosignia line uses a touchpad as a cursor, and I really
like Compaq's implementation, which is very responsive. However, I
found myself brushing it with the base of my thumb while typing,
which again hurled the cursor northward.
</P>
<P>
   The 150 also has a set of Internet buttons on it, as well as
external CD controls.
</P>
<P>
   It, too, was a snappy performer _ the K6-2 chip ran everything
that was thrown at it. Battery power was adequate, lasting just to
the three-hour mark. The screen was gorgeous, though not quite as
bright as the IBM.
</P>
<P>
   And like the ThinkPad, don't plan on nimbly dashing through
airports with this one, either. It's quite heavy, though not as
wide as the IBM model.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiron 3700 _ $2,400, Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Dell also has discovered the joy of color, though the Inspiron
3700 only gives you two choices for an accent color that graces the
inside of the machine _ dark blue or hunter green. I had a blue
model, which my oldest daughter succinctly described by saying,
``Uh, Daddy, that's really ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Underneath its skin, though, the 3700 has a 466-MHz Celeron
chip, 64 MB of memory, a 6-GB hard drive, a 6X DVD-ROM drive, a
modular floppy drive, a 14.1-inch active matrix screen and the
usual ports.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it does not come with a built-in modem. Instead,
Dell includes a 56K PC-card modem. It also comes with a DVD
controller in the form of a PC card, so once you pop both of these
into the two PC-card slots, you're full up.
</P>
<P>
   Also note that, of the three machines, it does not accommodate
both a floppy and the CD or DVD drive at the same time, unless you
use an optional external adapter for the floppy. Otherwise, you
have to swap between the two drives.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a touchpad controller, which I found was not quite
as responsive as the Compaq's. On the other hand, it also didn't
have the jumping cursor problem.
</P>
<P>
   While the screen had a crisp look, it was the darkest of the
three. In bright light, such as a shaded outdoor area, it was
almost unviewable.
</P>
<P>
   It also had the least amount of battery life, giving me only
about two hours of juice between charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Inspiron 3700, like its competitors here, is a heavy, bulky
machine. I look forward to the day when machines in this class
don't double as weightlifting devices.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
nn
</P>
