<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ANNAN (United Nations) _ When Kofi Annan,a soft-spoken
aristocrat from Ghana, was elected the United Nations' seventh
secretary-general three years ago, the quiet insider with a gentle
sense of humor was welcomed as a healer in an organization raked by
abuse from American politicians and unsettled by an ugly Clinton
administration campaign to oust his predecessor, Boutros
Boutros-Ghali. Three years later and with two more years to go in
his first term, Annan is turning out to be one of the most
provocative leaders the United Nations has ever known. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT27) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ The turn of the millennium is a
confusing time for those who live in the land where Jesus was born,
lived and died. Mostly Jews and Muslims, they do not attach
religious significance to the moment, yet they live, to some
degree, in the modern, secular world. One rabbi who wanted to mark
the moment without commemorating Jesus has scheduled a Y6K benefit
concert (although the year 6000 is still 240 years away on Jewish
calendar). By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ROMANIA-REVOLT (Timisoara, Romania) _ Of all the rebellions that
toppled communism in Eastern Europe a decade ago, the bloodiest
began in this provincial city where a protest by the parishioners
of an obscure Calvinist pastor somehow exploded into the nationwide
revolt that in nine days shoved Nicolae and Elena Ceausescu,
Romania's megalomaniacal ruling couple, in front of a firing squad.
Ten years after a radio announcer exulted, ``The Antichrist has
been executed on Christmas Day,'' Romanians are still on a national
quest to piece together what happened. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photos [NYT41,44,45) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-WORKERS (New York) _ In an odd twist in the corporate
power equation, the most important people in an organization are
the ones who will be working. To be away from the office on this
New Year's eve is to be rendered, in Y2K argot, ``nonessential,''
and what executive wants that? Not Eugene R. McGrath, the president
and chief executive of Consolidated Edison Inc. Of course he is
working, he said. ``Isn't everybody?'' By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT14,42) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-NEWYEAR-RELIGION (New York) _ As the final days ticked down
before the year 2000, nearly one out of three Christians in the New
York metropolitan region said they believed they would witness
Christ's return in their lifetimes, according to a recent New York
Times poll. Asked the same question four years ago, only one out of
five Christians in the region believed they would see the end of
time. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT38) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-ALGERIANS (Undated) _ A look at the Armed Islamic Group,
a guerrilla group fighting a ``holy war'' against the
military-dominated government in Algeria. By John F. Burns and
Craig Pyes.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-MORMANS (Belmont, Mass.) _ Plans for an enormous Mormon
temple in a suburban Boston neighborhood prompt a constitutional
battle over church and state. Such neighborhood fights involving
religious institutions have been cropping up increasingly around
the nation. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT39,40,46) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-CAMPAIGN (Undated) _ State of the Campaign Series: Steve
Forbes, who despite putting millions of his own dollars into the
race has made even less of an impact than he did four years ago. By
Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOFFMAN-MOVIE _ Nathan Hoffman and Evelyn Giniger, the man and
woman who courted by letter during World War II, while he was
overseas, are celebrated in millennial film by Steven Spielberg to
be shown on New Year's eve on the Mall. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CASH (Undated) _ The Federal Reserve vastly increased the
supply of cash in anticipation of withdrawals before the end of the
year. But several of the country's largest banks say they have not
experienced unusual demand for cash at their branches or automated
teller machines. On some days recently, these banks said, cash
demand has been lower than a year ago. So there the cash sits. By
Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-REPUTATION (Undated) _ Every major computer company is
gearing up to cope with any problems that surface as the dates flip
over to 2000 in millions of machines at midnight Friday _ first in
Asia, then Europe and then the Americas. But IBM and Microsoft
probably have the most at stake in terms of reputation and
potential liability. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   DUNNE-BOOKS (New York) _ At St. Martin's Press, Thomas Dunne has
created his own literary fief with an imprint that scorns snobbery,
prizes the quirky and commercial, and flourishes through a unique
form of high-volume publishing that occasionally flirts with peril.
By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT5,43) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   2100-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ A look at what things might be
like in Silicon Valley 10 years from now. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN _ Gail Collins examines the changing roles of
women over the last thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bob Herbert talks with some leading
scientists about the future.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Anthony Lewis examines the achievements
of science and the challenges that face it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKO-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
funeral of Reggie Carter, a former St. John's star who died of a
heart attack on Christmas Eve at the age of 42. By William C.
Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MATCHUPS (Undated) _ NFL matchups for the final week of the
regular season. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-CELEBRATE (New York) _ The date is an arbitrary slice of
time; many historians doubt that the Gregorian calendar's starting
point accurately matches the year Jesus was born. Yet the equally
arbitrary milestone it leads to, with the nice round number of
2000, has by now created whole industries of anticipation, revelry,
planning and retrospection. Never have three zeroes added up to so
much. Let all the nitpickers and killjoys insist that today is only
the last day of the 1900's, not the first day of the 21st century
and the third millennium A.D. Everyone else is getting ready to say
goodbye not just to a decade, but also to a century and a
millennium, maybe two. And there's no agreement on the right spirit
for the sendoff. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT11,12,16) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-ART (New York) _ Every New Year's Eve, we would like to
think, one small story closes and another opens. But this year the
story arrives in a deluxe edition. The ball dropping in Times
Square at midnight will punctuate not just a chapter or a volume,
but a boxed set titled ``20th Century.'' And it will be the first
mark of an ellipsis into the future. Epochal transitions are part
of every culture, and they are by no means always occasions for
cheer. Thresholds are worrisome places: you know a good deal about
what you're leaving behind, but not much about what's ahead. And
vulnerability makes emotions run high. No wonder the prospect of
ending one life and starting another _ the millennial concept in a
nutshell _ invites responsive extremes of hope and despair. All
over the world art is called on for guidance and assurance in such
matters. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT33,34) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLOSEUP-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Close-Up'': Abbas Kiarotami,
