<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BESTBUYS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 ATTABOY AWARDS HONOR BEST IN COMPUTER BUSINESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
(REFILING TO RESTORE GARBLED TYPE - and fix hed bust) By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
 &HT;    HOUSTON _ Computing and Internet access became even more
mainstream in 1999, and the products selected for this year's
Attaboy Awards reflect the growing pervasiveness of PCs in American
homes.
 &HT;    The awards, now in their fifth year, recognize the best
computing products crossing my desk.
 &HT;    Because people are doing new things with their computers, I've
added categories for popular new uses for the PC, including MP3
players and software, graphics cards and CD-ROM burners. There's
also a new, top-of-the-heap category, Product of the Year.
 &HT;    As usual, the winners receive unbridled admiration, along with a
nifty Attaboy 1999 logo they can post on their Web sites.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Product of the Year _ Advanced Micro Devices' Athlon
microprocessor
 &HT;    
 &HT;    For years, AMD has offered me-too chips, lagging behind silicon
gorilla Intel Corp. But with the Athlon line, AMD has shot ahead of
Intel on the performance curve.
 &HT;    Even Athlon chips that run at the same clock speed as Intel's
Pentium III do better on most benchmarks. The Athlon even outguns
Pentium III chips in an area where AMD's offerings have
traditionally fallen short _ in what's known as the Floating Point
Unit, which speeds up math processing.
 &HT;    And, systems built around Athlon chips are less expensive. Don't
you just love competition?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best Consumer PC _ Compaq Presario 5900Z
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Compaq Computer Corp. is one of two big-name PC makers that use
Athlon chips in their consumer systems. It has used the opportunity
to build one of the most powerful and feature-rich home PCs around.
 &HT;    The 5900Z line _ available through in-store kiosks and through
Compaq's Web site _ is a screaming rocket with such intelligent
design features as USB and FireWire connections on the front, and
the company's slick Internet keyboard.
 &HT;    Because it's built to order, you can pick and choose the
components that best fit your need for speed _ and your budget.
 &HT;    Recommended: add Creative Labs' 3D Blaster Annihilator video
card to your package, particularly if you're a game fan.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best Business PC _ Dell Dimension XPS T series
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Dell's PCs are consistently at the top of the heap, and this
line _ unveiled with the introduction of Intel's Pentium III chips
_ is a great blend of price and performance. Dell's PCs aren't
loaded down with unnecessary software or proprietary hardware _
they're fast, simple and high quality.
 &HT;    T-to-customize XPS T series is not as cutting-edge as the
B series, but the machines are still incredibly fast and very
reliable, backed by what customer surveys repeatedly show is the
best technical support around.
 &HT;    I like this system so much, I own one. Now, if only they came
with Athlon chips.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best Portable Computer _ Compaq Armada M300
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As far as the ultra-portable category goes, Compaq was very late
to the party. But when it arrived, it was with a bang. The Armada
M300 fixes all the problems found in most portable PCs in that
niche.
 &HT;    Yes, it's small, but the keyboard is comfortable to use, even if
you have large hands.
 &HT;    It comes with a full complement of connections and ports. An
optional module, which snaps onto the base, contains either a CD-
or DVD-ROM, so you don't have drives connected by cables. And the
active-matrix screen is a generous 11.3 inches. Compaq also makes a
consumer version, the Armada 300, that's available at retail.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best Video Card _ Creative Labs 3D Blaster TNT2 Ultra
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Based on nVidia's lightning-quick TNT2 Ultra chip set, this
model in the 3D Blaster line is not the fastest nor the most
feature-laden card you can buy, but it's hard to beat when you're
talking bang for the buck.
 &HT;    The 3D Blaster TNT2 Ultra comes with 32 megabytes of fast video
memory for high resolutions and lots of colors. It's an excellent
choice for gamers who want state-of-the-art speed without paying
state-of-the-art prices. Add to that its rock-solid drivers that
can also run games that rely on 3dfx's Glide 3D scheme.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best printer _ HP Deskjet 970Cse
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Hewlett-Packard hits a home run with this fast, quiet and
innovative printer aimed at home and small businesses. Even if its
only claims to fame were its impressive speed and excellent print
quality, it probably still would take this year's Attaboy for
printer.
 &HT;    But get this: The 970Cse also automates the usually tedious
process of double-sided printing. It comes with a module that pulls
a sheet back into the unit to print on the back side. It also comes
with an excellent software bundle and, of course, can plug into
either a USB or parallel port.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best scanner _ Visioneer PaperPort OneTouch 8600
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Who would have thought just five years ago that scanners _ once
a device used primarily by graphics professionals _ would have
become a gotta-have item for the average computer user. Visioneer,
with its low-cost PaperPort line, has helped promote that
revolution with inexpensive scanners that also happen to be very
good.
 &HT;    The OneTouch 8600 continues in that vein, with an innovation
that enhances speed and color quality. The scanner handles image
compression for the JPEG file format in hardware built into the
scanner. As a result, this is one of the fastest scanners you can
own in its price range _ particularly when connected to a USB port
_ with some of the best reproduction.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best MP3 Player _ Diamond Multmedia Rio PMP500
 &HT;    
 &HT;    This revision of the original Rio MP3 player is overpriced, but
other than that, it fixes most of the problems found in the first
one.
 &HT;    It connects via USB instead of the pokey and unreliable parallel
port, holds more music and has a simplified set of controls. It
also has software that makes it easier to organize MP3 files and
get them into the device in the RioPort Audio Manager. It also
supports the spoken-word files offered by Audible, so you can
listen to speeches, book readings and news programs.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Best CD-ROM Burner _ HP CD-Writer 8200 series
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Although writable/rewritable CD-ROM drives are gaining in
popularity, they still can be finicky. Adding one to a stable PC
can often destabilize it.
 &HT;    The Hewlett-Packard CD-Writer 8200 line not only is fast, but
it's friendly to your system. Of the CD-RW drives I've tried, it
was the only one that didn't cause my system to burp. It also comes
with a great tutorial, as well as software that inspects your PC
and suggests the best settings for a successful installation. It's
also fast _ writing and rewriting at 4X speeds and reading at 24X
speeds.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (MORE)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    XXXEND OF STORY 
