 r fbx  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN  
 SALUTING SELF-INTEREST WITH THE SMITTY AWARDS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Welcome to the 17th annual Smitty Awards ceremony,
during which we'll recognize deeds and developments during the past
year that best exemplify the spirit of Adam Smith's ``invisible
hand'' concept.
</P>
<P>
   It was this venerable moral philosopher's belief that
individuals acting in their self-interest often created benefits
for the entire community while improving their own lot. Smith also
theorized that business types often conspired to enhance their
wealth and satisfaction at community expense. That's why each
imaginary Smitty statuette comes complete with a wart on its nose.
</P>
<P>
   The envelopes, please:
</P>
<P>
   - Emily Litella Award: Bud Selig, major league baseball's top
guy, whose rejection of Miles Prentice's bid for the Royals in
essence told the aspiring owner, ``Never mind.''
</P>
<P>
   - Monty Hall Memorial Award: Heavyweight boxing legend George
Foreman, who made a sweet deal and will pocket more than $137
million in return for allowing a housewares company to use his name
and likeness in its marketing programs forever. And ever. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   - Ned Ludd Memorial Award: Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who
does his writing in longhand, a style more suited to the 19th
century, while presiding over the antitrust trial of computer-age
giant Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   - Luddite of the Year: The trade-protesting rioter in Seattle
seen wearing Nike high tops while trashing the downtown Niketown
store.
</P>
<P>
   - The AntiSmitty Award: Bob Thompson, who sold his Michigan
company for $422 million and not only allowed his 550 former
employees to share in $128 million of the sale proceeds but also
paid the resulting taxes for the beneficiaries of his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   - The People-in-Hell-Want-Ice-Water Award: The Coca-Cola Co.,
which was revealed to be investing heavily in developing a vending
machine that would automatically raise prices for its soft drinks
in hot weather with use of a temperature sensor and computer chip.
</P>
<P>
   - Charles Mackay Award: Investors who best exemplified his
concept of extraordinary popular delusions by bidding up VA Linux
Systems stock a record 700 percent when it made its recent initial
public offering debut.
</P>
<P>
   - Lee Iacocca Award: Wendy's burger man Dave Thomas, as the most
effective top-guy company pitchman.
</P>
<P>
   - George Orwell Award: Regulators who sought to impose a Big
Brother role on banks with a mandate to spy on customers for signs
of money laundering, but withdrew the proposal after much public
protest.
</P>
<P>
   - Eyes Wide Shut Award: Americans who believe their elected
reps' promises to use anticipated federal budget surpluses to
benefit the next generation of Social Security recipients.
</P>
<P>
   - Year's best economist joke: Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, who presided over a late-year money supply explosion
while engineering interest rate increases in the name of keeping
inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   - Free Enterpriser of the Year Award: Neighborhood activists in
Johnson County who were successful in exacting cash from developers
in return for their promise not to challenge nearby commercial
projects with potentially discombobulative effects.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, one and all!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
