<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-Y2KWATCH-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      12-31 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KWATCH-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT LOOKS AS IF INCONVENIENCE, NOT CATASTROPHE, WILL BE THE RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES AND FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Dec. 31 is a night of war rooms for a conflict that is
likely never to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the nation's top money guys are gathered in a
ready room on the top floor of the Federal Reserve building.
President Clinton's chief Y2K adviser and about 200 other federal
employees are gathered in another D.C. building a few blocks from
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has made its war effort more
mobile. FAA inspectors are fanning out to dispatch centers operated
by the nation's 10 largest airlines. FAA honcho Jane Garvey will be
riding the friendly skies to show that the nation's airspace is
safe.
</P>
<P>
   Companies big and small, utilities, and local and state
governments all have set aside space to monitor operations as the
1900s become the 2000s. They'll be watching for computer blips and
power outages, faulty data and flashing lights.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5 million of us will be working overtime this weekend
to make sure all goes well, and to do triage if it doesn't,
according to International Data Corp., a Framingham, Mass.,
technology research firm.
</P>
<P>
   As a nation, we are prepared. Globally, we spent about $320
billion and years getting this way, according to estimates released
this week by International Data Corp.'s Project Magellan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K: You'll see it, but you won't feel it,'' Project Magellan
researchers concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IDC Project Magellan team has forecast that annoying and
embarrassing Y2K computer glitches will be plentiful, starting at
midnight on New Year's Eve and running through the first quarter's
reporting period, but that major infrastructure outages won't
occur.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, IDC cited what happened to Assicurazioni
Generali, the biggest insurance company in Italy. The company
printed more than 600,000 documents reporting 1900 instead of 2000.
In the meantime
</P>
<P>
   Things were back to normal Thursday in Charlotte, N.C., after
the city's 911 emergency dispatch system failed a key Y2K test
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, the city's computer-aided dispatch system was
sidelined by a Y2K problem that forced operators to use a manual
system of writing down a caller's location and handing it to a
courier. After verifying the address, the couriers delivered the
address to a dispatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Although slightly slower than the automated system, the glitch
didn't cause any problems. And the 911 call-in system itself wasn't
affected, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Great Britain, more than 10,000 small retailers spent the
past couple of days on the phone whenever a customer came into the
shop with a credit card. Swipe card machine maker Racal Electronics
said 20,000 of its terminals refused to work when they ran into a
Y2K glitch.
</P>
<P>
   The credit card system reads four days in advance, and it froze
up when the machines compared Dec. 28, 1999, with Jan. 1, 2000.
They read the date as Jan. 1, 1900. The problem resolves itself as
of Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Similar systems are not used in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The problems ``may be illustrative of the kind of glitches that
are going to occur along the way here and around the world,'' said
John Koskinen, President Clinton's top Y2K expert. E-commerce
glitch
</P>
<P>
   Online buyers who use the Netscape Navigator and Communicator
browsers 4.06 and older could have a problem buying goods 
after the clock strikes midnight tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The problem also affects Macintosh owners who use Microsoft's
Internet Explorer 4.5 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Digital certificates from VeriSign Inc., stored in the browsers,
expire at midnight. The certificates are used to authenticate a
user and, in turn, authenticate a Web site and encrypt electronic
commerce transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape users who have not updated their browsers _ the company
estimates there are up to 10 million of them _ will see a dialogue
box on some secure sites after Dec. 31. They'll be able to click
``continue'' to get a secure connection.
</P>
<P>
   Apple computer owners using the Microsoft browsers won't be able
to conduct transactions securely. Going offline
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of government and corporate Web sites, including some
run by the Department of Defense and the Department of Agriculture,
are being shut down for the weekend to avoid hackers.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Bureau of Investigation has issued alerts warning of
the potential for increased hacking during the holidays. The FBI
said it would keep its computers running.
</P>
<P>
   Hackers have left messages on some Web sites in recent days
asking others not to hack Web sites over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet already has enough problems.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Net's largest ``hosts'' _ companies that host Web
sites for other companies _ ran into a computer glitch Wednesday
evening that made it impossible for surfers to find 48,000 Internet
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford, Texas-based C I Host said the problem would be fixed
Dec. 31. It was caused by a hacker or virus that corrupted the
company's main nameserver. No juice? Go solar
</P>
<P>
   This item just in from Robert Boczkiewicz, The Star's
correspondent in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   A research center for alternative energy sources operated by
Midwest Research Institute will use one of the oldest forms of
energy, the sun, to help ensure a smooth Y2K transition.
</P>
<P>
   The National Renewable Energy Laboratory in Golden, Colo., plans
to use a solar-powered generator and battery storage system if its
regular source of electricity fails.
</P>
<P>
   The solar generator will be available to supply energy to the
entrance building at the lab complex, which houses security systems
and staff. The same type of generator is available commercially, a
lab spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City-based institute is the lead partner of a
consortium that operates the lab for the U.S. Department of Energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
