<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3357 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-UCONN-HOUSTON-HNS     12-31 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Houston Cougars, thrown into a tailspin early by the all-around
package of basketball skills that is point guard Khalid El-Amin of
No. 2 Connecticut, appeared to be down and out under a 28-point
deficit with 6:11 left Thursday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Huskies, meanwhile, looked as though they could switch into
party mode and begin bringing in the new year in style, if maybe a
little prematurely, at Hofheinz Pavilion. What happened next, said
Houston's Gee Gervin, might have been expected from any team
sailing along under similar circumstances, even a defending NCAA
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they might have relaxed a little bit,'' he said of the
Huskies. ``Most teams do that when you're up 28 points.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gervin finally getting his game going after an
uncharacteristically slow start, Houston threw a scare into UConn
(9-1) in the second half but lost 82-76 before a sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played 33 minutes of great basketball and then lost our
intensity,'' said El-Amin, who had 21 points in the first half and
finished with 27. ``Great teams don't do that. We're lucky to get
out with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gervin coming alive to score 17 of his 19 points in the
final 20 minutes, what the Cougars (6-6) salvaged from Thursday
night probably won't show until later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played like a team that's battle-tested,
championship-tested,'' UH coach Clyde Drexler said of the Huskies.
``Our guys were looking forward to the competition. Our guys were
not backing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had a few possessions where we had easy layups but
we lost the ball or missed dunks, easy opportunities (early). You
tend to lose confidence under those types of incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for the most part, our guys came out to compete. I'm very
proud of their effort. It's a game that went down to the final
wire. That's a building block for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although UH took a 2-0 lead on a feathery jumper by Gervin one
minute into the game, El-Amin took charge from that point forward.
He scored eight straight points during one stretch as the Huskies
rang up a 48-27 halftime lead, despite a modest 12-4 run by the
Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   Most of UConn's destruction occurred during the final six
minutes of the half when a 30-24 cushion ballooned to the 21-point
margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last five minutes of the first half, we had a mental
lapse,'' Drexler said. ``And a seven-point game turned into a
21-point game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And basically, (in the locker room at the break) I was telling
them to give yourselves a chance, that anything can happen. Stay in
the game, stay mentally tough, stay with the game plan _ good
things are going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the Cougars alive in the first half was the play of
Kenny Younger, who got 11 of his team-high 24 points in the opening
half and finished with nine rebounds. George Williams contributed
nine points and a game-high 13 boards as the Cougars outrebounded
the taller Huskies 46-41.
</P>
<P>
   For Jake Voskuhl, the Strake Jesuit product who has been one of
the Huskies' stalwarts over the past three years, what had been an
enjoyable homecoming over the last few days turned into a near
nightmare. He was scoreless in the first half and contributed only
two points and eight rebounds to the UConn cause. He had nothing
but praise for the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played well, battled hard and made some tough shots,'' he
said. ``I don't want to take any credit away from them; they made
good shots. But at the same time, we made mistakes we don't usually
make.''
</P>
<P>
   After UH shot a paltry 29 percent and fell behind 48-27 at
halftime, Voskuhl opened the second half with a slam dunk that
pointed the Huskies toward a 76-48 lead with 7:03 left.
</P>
<P>
   That 28-point edge came on a fast-break layup by Kevin Freeman,
who finished with 13 points and six rebounds. With the score 78-50,
the Cougars began to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   Gervin scored 10 points, sparking a 23-2 run that brought the
Cougars to within 80-73 with 1:25 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to bring up the tempo a lot,'' Gervin said. ``They
got the ball out quick a lot (through the first half and the first
13 minutes of the second half). We were back on our heels a lot. We
started to come out and put a lot of pressure on them, speed up the
tempo a little, make them turn it over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars got to within 81-76 on a trey by Marcus Oliver with
11.2 seconds left. It was as clo NO CARRIER
RING
CONNECT LAPM
</P>
