<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3358 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     12-31 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RING
CONNECT TION-KAN  
 FBI ASKED TO INVESTIGATE HASKELL FOUNDATION'S MONEY WOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By DALE ROBERTSON 
 &HT;     c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
AS national champions, you write your own ticket. The college
basketball season is almost two months old, yet the Connecticut
Huskies played their first true road game Thursday night. &HT;    And, as expected, they made themselves right at home in Hofheinz
Pavilion. The host Houston Cougars, after the obligatory early bit
of adrenaline-fueled resistance, seemed destined to succumb to the
inevitable and go down in flames, stymied by both their mistakes
and the Huskies' mystique.
 &HT;    Not to mention the remarkable presence of Khalid El-Amin. Amin,
who packs 203 pounds on his 5-10 frame, may be the most deceptive
talent in the country this side of Muggsy Bogues.
 &HT;    El-Amin looks soft. However, he plays hard, in terms of both
toughness and effort. His 21 first-half points _ on 8-for-13
shooting _ were six fewer than UH managed collectively and bested
his shellshocked Houston counterpart, Gee Gervin, by 19. It was,
quite simply, Gee vs. Whiz.
 &HT;    But Gee won the second half 17-6, as did the Cougars 49-34.
Moral victories both, to be sure.
 &HT;    UConn came to Houston _ to the Cougars' delight, given the rowdy
sellout crowd, and perhaps to their distress, certainly early on _
because of Jake Voskuhl. Jim Calhoun likes to let his seniors show
off in front of friends and family, and Voskuhl, a Katy native who
attended Strake Jesuit before Calhoun lured him to New England,
asked his coach to make the phone call to Chet Gladchuk, UH's
athletic director.
 &HT;    The Huskies' other senior, Wane Souleymane, hails from Dakar.
That's in Senegal, as in Africa. Sorry, Wane. Too far, certainly on
the eve of potential Y2-chaos.
 &HT;    Anyway, Calhoun's lads have had a smashing time here this week,
dining on prime beef and real Texas barbecue, and basking in the
stunning weather. The long trip to Houston became equal parts hoops
and golf. Fittingly, the champions got to take their cuts at
Champions. The R-and-R hadn't disturbed their rhythm and
blues-administering any as the score grew worse and worse.
 &HT;    With just over six minutes left, the Huskies led 78-50. A
depressed Clyde Drexler took a seat on top of the press table by
the Cougars' bench, crossed his arms and sighed.
 &HT;    ``Oh, my goodness,'' he said, shaking his head.
 &HT;    Then, suddenly, it was 1983 again. UConn had been U-Conned. No,
Houston is not just another basketball backwater, a number of
humbling seasons by the Cougars notwithstanding.
 &HT;    A couple of unfortunate Gervin turnovers in the final minute
prevented a comeback-of-the-millennium finish, and the Huskies
survived, although Calhoun was clearly not delighted with what he
had just witnessed.
 &HT;    ``The game,'' he said dryly, ``is 40 minutes long. You have to
learn to play 40 minutes on the road.''
 &HT;    Of course, to do that, you have to occasionally go into hostile
environs.
 &HT;    UConn's 82-76 victory was its ninth in a row after an opening
stumble against Iowa. Stanford may still rank ahead of them at
present, but the Huskies remain the beast to beat come March's
Madness _ until someone actually beats them.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, the Cougars, with their proud heritage and that
Hall of Famer-to-be who prowls the sideline on their behalf,
proudly refused to behave as just another Fairfield or Fordham,
i.e., pre-Big East fodder.
 &HT;    Not quite a generation ago, back when Drexler was rattling
backboards for the Cougars instead of drawing stuff on a clipboard,
the Huskies were the punies, a terminally sub-.500 program lost in
the shuffle of big-time Eastern ball. During the three seasons in
the early '80s when UH made itself a fixture in the Final Four and
played for the national title twice, UConn was eight games under
.500. Even Calhoun's first team went 9-19 two years later.
 &HT;    The worms do turn, don't they? If the Huskies weren't the team
of the about-to-conclude decade, they finished right up there, and
they appear well-positioned to claim the first title of the new
millennium, never mind a troubling six-minute walkabout here.
 &HT;    Calhoun believes these Huskies may have more raw athleticism
than last year's bunch. As to whether they can accomplish the same
great things
 &HT;    ``Ask me in a couple months,'' he said.
 &HT;    The Cougars can draw inspiration from both UConn's rise to
prominence and their own storied past, delightful memories of which
they resurrected down the stretch. Nothing, be it good or bad, is
forever. Drexler is just another marquee player away from
threatening Top 25 status and perhaps three more away from proving
UH belongs on the same floor with the likes of the Huskies for a
full 40 minutes.
 &HT;    A couple years from now, a Jim Calhoun might not be so eager to
come visiting, no matter how hospitable a clime Houston offers. A
couple years from now, it's to be hoped local good ol' boys like
Voskuhl won't want to go off pretending to be Connecticut Yankees.
They will be playing for Clyde, not against him.
 &HT;    Still, it was fun to have a super-elite team back in the
building, making the place matter again. Next step for Drexler:
ensuring it's the home team at the outset, a NO CARRIER (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ The board that oversees the Haskell Foundation
has asked the FBI to look into the foundation's financial troubles,
a board spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the board wants to know whether the foundation's
former executive director did anything that contributed to the
foundation's financial crisis, board member Lew Llewellyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those funds were federal funds that the foundation
was managing, so it just made sense to us we should ask the FBI,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was created in 1984 to help support Haskell
Indian Nations University in Lawrence. It raises money and manages
more than $1 million annually in grants and scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald T. Burd, the foundation's former executive director,
resigned Dec. 10 after the foundation received a letter from Ron
Manka, the attorney who represents the Board of Regents, which
oversees Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the regents were concerned about reports that
the foundation was bouncing checks and not paying bills and that
Burd had forfeited his accountant's licenses. It said the
foundation should either let the regents take control of it or cut
its ties to the university.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the regents and the foundation board have been
working on ways for the foundation to stay afloat. Last week, a
tribe in northern Kansas loaned the foundation $47,000 to help it
meet its payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Burd did not return a telephone call on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   State records show that Burd allowed his accountant's license in
New Mexico to expire on June 30, 1997. He surrendered his Kansas
license on Aug. 5, 1997, and lost his Missouri license on April 10,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a former partner accused Burd of illegally diverting
more than $25,000 from their firm, according to records from the
New Mexico Board of Public Accountancy.
</P>
<P>
   Burd filed for personal bankruptcy on Oct. 1, 1997, in Kansas
City, Kan. He listed assets of $89,463, and liabilities of $1.3
million, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Llewellyn said board members had not been aware of Burd's
previous problems.
</P>
<P>
   He said the foundation was moving its office back to the
university campus this week so it no longer had to pay rent. Burd
had moved the office off-campus and had told the board that the
foundation could afford the rent, Llewellyn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 0123EST &QL; 
