<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS ROUT OILERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SLANG -- Attn. Sports) 
By MATT McHALE  
 Staff Writer  
The last two weeks had seemed like a millenium, but the Kings vowed
they would party again.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After six consecutive losses had scalded their promising season,
the Kings routed the Edmonton Oilers 8-2 Thursday night behind five
points by Luc Robitaille and Jeri Karalahti's first and second
National Hockey League goals.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 1,000 victory in franchise history and right now
there are few that might seem more important. During the last six
games they had been crushed, played hard at times, lost close games
and barely showed up for others.
</P>
<P>
   The only constant was their hold on a playoff spot continued to
dwindle to teams like the Oilers, who were gaining ground after
going 4-2-5 in their last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   But in front of a raucous sellout of 18,118 at the Staples
Center, the Kings put on a show with four goals in the second
period and five power play goals overall.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Rob Blake, who by his own admission played one the worst
games of his career in Wednesday's loss at Colorado, scored two
goals.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Robitaille who had the biggest offensive showing with
the sixth five-point game of his career. The last was Feb. 11 1993
against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who has come to life in the past week, scored his
fourth goal in three games and just missed a fifth in the second
period when Glen Murray dislodged the Oilers net just before
Robitaille scored.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a big night for Robitaille in the record book. His
first period assist marked the 1,100 point of his NHL career.
Robitaille is just the 23rd to score 1,100 points and 500 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the Kings built a 5-0 lead did the Oilers score
against Kings goalie Stephane Fiset. With Jaroslav Modry off for
holding, Pat Falloon slipped in his third goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But on this night, there would be no comebacks against the
Kings. Just 3:07 into the third period, Bryan Smolinski scored
after rebounding a shot from Glen Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Even the crowd played its part, taunting Edmonton goaltender
Mike Ranford, who inadvertently helped the Kings score their first
goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes of the first period, Ranford tried to clear
the puck and fired it into the crowd. That is a delay of game
penalty and the Kings used it to get a power play goal by Modry.
</P>
<P>
   For Modry, it was his first goal since the 1996-97 season. After
that the crowd chanted Ranford's name every time the goaltender
touched the puck.
</P>
<P>
   But Modry's goal had a greater significance. The Oilers, who had
beaten and tied the Kings earlier this season, allowed just one
power play goal in their last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had been converting at only 14 percent (11 for 78)
with the man advantage at home.
</P>
<P>
   But Modry broke the ice, so to speak, scoring the first of four
power play goals on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille opened the second-period rush by scoring in the first
58 seconds. It was his 15th of the season and classic Robitaille,
backhanding a rebound shot past Ranford after Mattias Norstrom
fired from the point.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, Blake scored his first goal with
Alexander Selivanov in the penalty box for a high stick. Ziggy
Palffy, another of the Kings missing stars during the losing
streak, dug the puck oue corner and passed in front to Blake
who made it look easy against Ranford.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly two minutes later, or 7:14 into the second, Blake was at
it again on a pass from Jozef Stumpel that beat Ranford. It was his
13th goal of the year, one more than he had last season. It also
was a power play goal, created when the Oilers were whistled for
having too many men on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the best snap shot of Blake's night came with 7:16
left in the second when he flattened Edmonton center Jim Dowd with
a crunching hip check along the left boards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
