<SLUG> BC-READY-4Y2K-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE PREPARE FOR Y2K UPS, DOWNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dominic Berbeo  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Amid widespread uncertainty of possible year 2000
mayhem, people across Los Angeles made last-minute preparations for
either a Y2K meltdown or a New Year's celebration of millennial
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   At supermarkets and camping supply stores, people stocked up on
water, canned goods and other necessities as well as delicacies
from lobster to champagne for parties to usher out the 20th century
and welcome in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking any chances,'' said Mary Wheeler from the Los
Angeles suburb of Chatsworth, as she bought cooking fuel and a
portable stove at REI in Northridge about a mile away. ``Normally
we go out, but this year our family is absolutely staying home for
the New Year, where we won't be a target for any terrorist
threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to party,'' said Lee Ann Faeth, who was buying
supplies at Costco in Canoga Park for a company party at da Vinci
Studios in Woodland Hills, both in suburban Los Angeles. ``And I
think everything will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Police, firefighters and city officials braced for the worst,
however, as they activated their emergency coordination command
center and appealed for New Year's revelers to keep their guns at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You fire your weapon in the air to celebrate the millennium,
you're going to be prosecuted, and you're going to go to jail,''
said Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil Garcetti.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 a.m., the Los Angeles Police Department will require every
officer on duty to remain on duty indefinitely, said police
spokesman Officer Jason Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD plans to dispatch 84 extra patrol cars, each with two
officers. Also, there will be a supervisor on duty for every 10
officers. Every bureau will have a 60-officer strike team.
Additionally, there will be 350 officers assigned solely to gunfire
suppression.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Emergency Operations Center was scheduled
to open at 6 a.m. and remain open through Jan. 3. Information on
Y2K and the county's status is available at (800) 980-4990.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, Cameron Williams of Thousand Oaks in Ventura
Countynorth of Los Angeles, said he is not concerned about
terrorist threats because of what he has planned for his New Year's
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll go camping in Joshua Tree, away from all the
attention, and enjoy a little solitude with the sky full of stars.
At midnight, maybe I'll do a handstand or something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others are taking no chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of scary _ but it's not that big a deal,'' said
Lucrecia Guillen, who bought about 100 12-ounce bottles of water at
Costco. ``It's good to have the water, and if nothing happens it
won't go to waste because we'll drink it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, Y2K preparation is a commercial boon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K is definitely good for business,'' said Costco store
manager Eli Rahhal. He said the store sold roughly $10,000 worth of
water on Wednesday, triple the average.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular sales in the past week, he said, were basic
survival items like lanterns, water containers, generators and
flashlights, all of which sold out days ago as nearly double the
daily flow of customers have barraged the store.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the sold-out items were for survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' Rahhal said. ``We sold every last lobster
tail, and there's no more Dom Perignon champagne left.''
</P>
<P>
   The sales were a reflection of plans not to let the impending
fears of possible Y2K disaster spoil celebration festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Neil Giuntoli of Topanga, were preparing for the
worst. His shopping list included candles and plenty of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there really is a disaster,'' he said, ``you want to be
ready. You need things with high barter value like cigarettes and
liquor.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he only withdrew enough money from the bank for the
weekend because he didn't want to add to ``all the hype.'' But
overall, he said, he was not too worried by the heavy coverage on
television of possible Y2K mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of hype, more than anything, just to sell stuff,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Phillip Browne contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
