<SLUG> BC-MURDER-RATE-LADN </SLUG>
 
CRIME DROPS IN L.A.'s SAN FERNANDO VALLEY  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Lisa Van Proyen  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- At odds with years of declining crime, the number
of homicides in Los Angeles in 1999 will match last year's or
exceed it by as few as one, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, homicides were down 5.3 percent,
with 72 as of Dec. 25, compared with 76 for the same period last
year, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Citywide this year, there were 419 homicides as of Dec. 27 --
one more than during the same time period last year, according to
police statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police spokesman Cmdr. Dave Kalish said homicides
have declined sharply since at least 1992, when there were 1,092.
The 1999 figures may not continue the trend, but still remain lower
than previous years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the long-term trends globally and
historically,'' said Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   There were 569 homicides citywide for all of 1997, 707 in 1996,
and 838 in 1995, according to statistics from the LAPD's
Information Resources Division.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish noted that citywide, violent crimes are down 6.5 percent
this year over last. This includes murders, rapes and robberies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few years, there's been a radical decrease in
crime,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley, homicides were down in all but one police
division: Van Nuys, where there were 12 this year compared with
seven last year - marking a 42 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of those are acquaintance-type homicides, where victims
knew their assailants. They are not random homicides,'' said Lt.
Ann Young, in charge of detectives at the Valley's Van Nuys
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Young said, the figure is actually quite low for
Van Nuys when you consider that last year Van Nuys had only seven
homicides, a remarkably low number.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, there were 15 homicides in Van Nuys, according to
police statistics. In 1996, there were 20, and in 1995 there were
25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually down for the five-year average,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Valleywide, violent crimes were down by about 10 percent, said
LAPD Officer Guillermo Campos.
</P>
<P>
   Police attribute this decline to several factors, including
tougher sentencing laws, fewer people aged 15 to 24 who are more
apt to commit crimes, a good economy and community involvement with
police.
</P>
<P>
   Valleywide, the West Valley Division showed the most significant
decline in homicides, with four as of Dec. 14, vs. seven during the
same period in 1998. The division had nine homicides in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Devonshire had 10 homicides during the same period -- down seven
from 1998. Foothill Division had 21 homicides through Dec. 14 this
year, compared with 26 in 1998. North Hollywood had 16, vs. 17 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
