<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS FINALLY WIN ON ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News    Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Celtics re-L mained stone-faced throughout most of
the fourth quarter. The visitors did not betray any emotion as
their lead dwindled from 10 points to 1 point. They did not glance
desper- ately at the scoreboard. Instead, the players voiced their
determination during timeouts and in their own heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``No let down'' was the message the Celtics repeated to
themselves. ``Let's not let this one get away.'' They did not think
about the stretch of 11 consecutive road losses that had plagued
them since the season opener. They did not think about their
late-game collapses. They did not think about the poor defensive
efforts that had cost them in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But when Antoine Walker sank two free throws with 1 minute 44
seconds left to give the Celtics a 7- point lead, Paul Pierce could
no long- er contain his thoughts. The guard strode down the
sideline and shout- ed, ``Yeah!'' With that cheer, you could feel
the pressure of poor road play lifting off their shoulders. At that
point, Pierce and his teammates knew they were on the verge of a
monumental win. In one of the L league's toughest arenas, Boston L
earned its second road victory of the season with a 102-94 triumph
over Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge relief being on the road and getting the win,''
said L Pierce. ``Once (Walker) knocked L those two free throws
down, I knew we were going to pull it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief was the Celtics' word of choice when describing the win.
Al- though coach Rick Pitino constantly complimented his players'
positive attitude throughout the road slump, it was clear as the
Celtics smiled and laughed in the locker room that the travel woes
had weighed heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, it's a sense of relief for us,'' said
Walker, who led Boston with 26 points. ``It was a must win for us
because we have been playing well on the road, but not finishing
games. We were put-H ting it together for three quarters, but not
for four quarters. Tonight, we finally did and that's a big plus
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter provided a true character test as the Nuggets
chipped away at the Celtics' lead. But unlike recent losing
efforts, Bos- ton did not collapse and fall into its routine of
poor defense and panicky offense. In the final minutes, they were
aggressive on the glass, tena- cious on defense away from the bas-
ket, and patient on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Boston built its lead back up to 6 with a quick spurt following
a time- out. Kenny Anderson (14 points, 6 assists) scored with a
driving layup, Vitaly Potapenko stole the ball, and Walker capped
the small run with a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' lead quickly fell back to 3 points, but a second
timeout helped the visitors regain momen- tum. Boston dug in on
defense (in- cluding a blocked shot by Pota-HL penko) and used a
5-1 spurt to surge ahead, 93-86. Once foul shots by An- derson
stretched the lead to 9 points, the Nuggets lost all hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a perfect opportunity to be four games above .500
tonight and we didn't play like we wanted to be in that position,''
said Denver coach Dan Issel as his team ended a five-game home
winning streak. ``We simply weren't ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Said Pitino, ``This was the best defense we've played the whole
sea- son. We played intelligently.''
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer by Raef LaFrentz cut the Celtics' lead to 9 points
mid- way through the second quarter, causing Pitino to call a
timeout be- fore matters got out of hand before the half. Foul
shots by Ron Mercer cut the deficit to 7, before a basket by
Anderson stretched the margin back to 9 (41-32).
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets put together a 6-0 run to close out the second
quarter and the Pepsi Center crowd awak- ened. Eric Williams missed
a 3- pointer at the buzzer as a game-high 12 point Celtic lead
dwindled to 5 points (49-44) by intermission.
</P>
<P>
   A reverse layup by Danny Fort-H son stretched the lead to 10
points (74-64) with 1:07 left in the third quarter. A Mercer layup
marked the final basket of the third quarter, drawing the Nuggets
within 8 points before the start of the fourth quar- ter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtics stayed tough and hung on for the much-needed
victo- ry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
