<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3369 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     12-31 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR BOBBY'S BOY TO GET DOWN TO BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They can't say they weren't warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no surprise,'' said one of the NFL's top coaches to
your humble servant on the phone Wednesday at about 5 p.m., just
shortly after the news went out over the league's private wire
service that the Patriots had suspended Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team in the league was told the same thing when this kid
was at Ohio State,'' said the coach, who will be one of the Super
Bowl favorites when the playoffs start. ``That this is the way it
could turn out with him. Their coaches (Ohio State's) were very
honest with everyone. They told us the kid was a big talent, with
big problems, and if you took him, you took his baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the gist of what scouts and coaches were told at Ohio
State four years ago before the annual NFL draft: Glenn is a
terrific talent but doesn't really care about playing football. He
doesn't want to practice. Doesn't work at the game. Won't practice
or play if he's injured. He's from a tough background with some
serious emotional problems. If you can get him on the field and he
feels like playing, he's a great talent, but he doesn't always want
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite what they had been told, the Patriots decided to use the
seventh pick in the draft, filled with a flock of outstanding wide
recievers, on Glenn. He was player personnel director Bobby Grier's
personal pick, and he would become known to Patriots coaches over
the three years after Bill Parcells left as ``Bobby's Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always protected by Grier,'' says a former Patriot
coach. ``Everyone on the staff knew that. Steve Walters (former
receiver coach, now with Tennessee, fired at the end of the '98
season) had his group in a meeting one day. It was Wednesday. A
game plan day. Terry walked out of the meeting and said he'd be
right back. He never came back. Steve went to Pete (Carroll) and
told him he had to do something, that he should fine Terry. Pete
never did a thing. Know why? Terry was up in Grier's office talking
to Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another day, we're on the field, and Terry decided not to
practice,'' said the coach. ``Just walked over to the side and was
talking to Grier. Pete called the team together on the field after
practice and waited for three or four minutes for Terry to come
over. He wouldn't. He just kept talking to Bobby. It was
embarrassing to Pete and all the coaches. Finally, Pete just said
what he had to say to the team, and we all left. This kind of stuff
happened with Terry all of the time, and nothing was done about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From another former coach who spent some time coaching Glenn
with the Patriots:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a bad kid. He's not mean-spirited. He's just very
selfish. He wants to do everything on his terms. One minute he's
up, the next minute he's in a deep funk. And once he goes into the
tank on you, you never know when he's coming out. He'll drop a pass
in a game, go to the bench, and start crying. I mean really crying.
Tears down his face. And he doesn't want to play anymore. It's
nuts. But because he's a great talent, everyone kissed his ass.
They kept hoping he would grow up, but I guess he hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 14th game of the 1998 season, playing against the Rams in
St. Louis, Glenn broke his ankle. On the flight back home, he was
told he would need surgery and to report to Massachusetts General
Hospital the next day, where Dr. Bert Zarins, the Patriots' fine
orthopedic surgeon, would repair the damage. Glenn never showed.
For two weeks, the Patriots tried to find him. They couldn't.
Finally, someone tipped the team off. He was hiding in his house,
less than 10 minutes from Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent Ron O'Neil (trainer) and Johnny Parker (strength
coach) over to his house to talk to him,'' says a Patriot employee.
``He hid in the bedroom and wouldn't come out to talk to them. They
were outside the bedroom door, and he wouldn't open the door. They
finally told him that every day he didn't have the surgery was
going to cost him $10,000, so he went and had the operation a few
days later. But he hid out in his house for two weeks and wouldn't
speak with anyone. No one ever knows what this kid is going to do.
He doesn't know himself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As great a player as he has been for the Patriots at times,
Glenn has been a major distraction to the team. He is part of the
reason for the major division between the present coaching staff
and Grier's personnel department, which is beginning to become
public. The coaches, and many players, felt there was one set of
rules for Terry and another set for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he can be a likeable kid, the players tried to cut him
a lot of slack, even though they knew he was different, and a
little weird, by their standards,'' says a former Patriots coach.
``He was never one of the guys. He really didn't hang out with any
of the other players. Even if you are the biggest jerk on the team,
you can usually have one or two guys you can hang around with, but
Terry is a loner. He doesn't even like to come out of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots management is well aware of Glenn's problems from top
to bottom. They had tried to get him counseling and would like him
to go into a regular program to deal with his abnormal behavior. To
this point, Glenn has resisted help, and no one has pushed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That deal at Thanksiving pushed everything over the edge,''
says a Patriot employee. ``When he showed up late for practice, he
was still hung over. He couldn't practice worth a damn. And that's
when the other players had it with him. You talk to them privately,
and they say it's time for him to grow up, and time for someone
upstairs to kick his rear end in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are just as responsible as Glenn for what happened
over the weekend. He has always been given special treatment,
except when Parcells was here, when Glenn had the great rookie
season. ``Bill stepped on his neck from Day One,'' says a former
Patriots coach. ``Terry feared him. He was afraid of Bill because
Bill wouldn't put up with any of that crap, and Terry knew it. As
soon as Bill left, it all changed. Terry would go around Pete to
Bobby. Bobby would always cover for him. I bet that's why Pete
didn't call Grier this time he was suspending Terry. Pete must
think he's gone, so he doesn't care what Grier says anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As best as your humble servant can put together, here is what
happened to Glenn, starting a week ago. He came to practice at
Foxborough saying he was sick. O'Neil sent him home to rest. He was
never seen by a doctor and hasn't been seen by one to this day.
Glenn was supposed to report to the nearby hotel where the Patriots
were staying the night before the game. He never showed. The
Patriots, again trying to cover for Glenn, at first said he was at
the hotel and left the next morning (Sunday) for the game. That was
a lie. Glenn stayed at home, but again, the coverup was being
readied. Glenn stayed home Sunday. He phoned to say he couldn't
make it. By any normal standard of conduct in the NFL, the player
comes to the stadium and gets checked out by the doctor, who
determines if he can play. Three other players who had the flu
reported to the hotel Saturday night and showed up at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday and Tuesday, he still had not shown up. Carroll tried
to cover up for him by saying he was told to stay home. Even though
Glenn failed to show, nothing was done. Last Friday, he was told
the flu would run its course in 48 hours. Some 96 hours later, and
just 10 minutes away by car, he didn't drive to the stadium to be
checked out by a trainer or doctor. Still Carroll wasn't going to
do anything, until Wednesday, when Glenn showed up. Carroll had a
meeting and asked Glenn to explain what happened. Glenn wouldn't
talk to him. Basically, he just blew off the coach. This is when
Carroll decided he'd had enough and suspended him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A former Ohio State teammate of Glenn's currently heading to the
playoffs Thursday told one of his assistant coaches: ``Terry pulled
the same stuff at Ohio State. Everyone tried to help him. Coaches.
Players. We knew he had a tough deal (in earlier life), but, man,
he's 26 years old now (actually 25), and it's time to grow up. He's
got to start dealing with his problems and stop running away from
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Glenn doesn't care about what happens to his coaches
and teammates. When Walters, a great guy and great coach, was fired
after the '98 season, Carroll told him he didn't want to let him
go, but ``they'' (upper management) didn't think he had dealt well
with Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry's a baby,'' says a former teammate now with another
team. ``He's so immature. He's distracting to be around. For long
periods of time, he might just sit there and say nothing. The guys
on the team want to try to like him, but it's hard. On a team,
you're supposed to be thinking about what's best for the team, and
he's always got his own thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it time to say good night to Glenn? I don't think so. Irving
Fryar had his own planet farther out in orbit than this kid has,
but he returned to earth once he left New England and showed that
he was a Hall of Fame player. Unfortunately for Fryar, his
spacewalk while he was a Patriot just might be enough to bring him
short of Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has not hit bottom yet. The Patriots will urge him to get
counseling when the season is over. If he doesn't want to go along
with it, they have a hard decision to make. And no matter what, the
next head coach in here should be given authority and make it
crystal clear to Glenn that he is no longer Bobby's Boy, and that
it's time to put away the toys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
