<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CENTURY-WILLIAMS-BOS &LR;      12-31 1646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TIPS ITS CENTENNIAL CAP TO THE SPLENDID SPLINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ No. 9 is No. 1. Naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Was there ever any doubt? Bill Russell, Bobby Orr, and Larry
Bird were great, but as the Globe's countdown from 100 lurched
toward the finish, deep-thinking New England sports aficionados had
to realize who would remain when we reached No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Boston sports in the 20th century was graced by the
extraordinary skills of Russell, Orr, Bird, plus Carl Yastrzemski,
Rocky Marciano, Doug Flutie, Ray Bourque, Drew Bledsoe, Lefty
Grove, Bob Cousy, Clarence H. DeMar, Milt Schmidt, Jimmie Foxx,
Roger Clemens, John Havlicek, John Hannah, Eddie Shore, Bill
Rodgers, Dave Cowens, Marvin Hagler, Cy Young, Joan Benoit
Samuelson, Harry Agganis, Pedro Martinez, and Nomar Garciaparra.
Babe Ruth even played here long enough to win three World Series
before becoming an international icon in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kid who came north from spring training in 1939 stands
alone as the enduring New England sports figure of the century.
Perhaps the next century, too.
</P>
<P>
   First, remember that baseball was the dominant sport in our
region for the vast majority of the last 100 years. And Ted
Williams was baseball. He may have been the greatest hitter who
ever lived. His Hall of Fame career, spanning parts of four decades
produced a career batting average of .344 with 521 homers. He was
able to hit .388 at age 39, won a batting title at 40, and almost
certainly would have been a 700-homer threat had he not missed
almost five full seasons serving his country in World War II and
the Korean conflict. Boston sports had dozens of other spectacular
performers, but only Ted was able to make news for seven of the 10
decades in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, right after Ted retired, President John F.
Kennedy addressed a collection of American Nobel Prize winners at a
dinner in the East Room of the White House. Kennedy said there had
not been such a collection of talent gathered in the White House
since the days when Thomas Jefferson dined alone there. So it is
with Ted Williams. There is Ted, and then there is everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in San Diego and raised by a mom who was dedicated
to the Salvation Army. In his autobiography, he admitted, ``I was
embarrassed about my home, embarrassed that I never had quite as
good clothes as some of the kids, embarrassed that my mother was
out in the middle of the damn street all the
</P>
<P>
   Young Ted always wanted to hit. He went from Herbert Hoover High
School to the Pacific Coast League and arrived at the Back Bay
train station in April of 1939, ready to hit .327. He was 6 feet 4
inches and weighed 172 pounds and became known as the Splendid
Splinter. Sox owner Tom Yawkey had bullpens built in right field
after Williams's rookie season, and the pens were known as
``Williamsburg.'' He hit .344 in his second year, then had his
signature season _ the last .400 season of the century.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem like too big of a deal at the time. Twelve other
players had hit .400 since 1900, none since Bill Terry in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of his final day at .400 is part of New England sports
lore. Young fans coming of age learn the tall tale the way they
learn to recite the midnight ride of Paul Revere. Williams was
batting .39955 going into the final Sunday of the season and
manager Joe Cronin offered to sit him down to protect the
rounded-off .400. Williams walked the streets of Philadelphia with
equipment man Johnny Orlando (Ted stopping for ice cream, Orlando
for scotch), late Saturday night. There was never any doubt that he
would play and he went 6 for 8 in a doubleheader finale to finish
at .406. No player has hit .400 since.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth year, Ted Williams won the Triple Crown, but just
as in '41, it was not good enough to earn him MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1942, Williams reported with 30 other Navy Aviation
Cadets in Amherst. He earned his officer's commission and made it
all the way to San Francisco, where he was scheduled for combat
duty in the South Pacific, but the war ended before Ted was called
and his next assignment was Red Sox spring training in 1946. In
'46, he was American League MVP, leading the Red Sox to their first
pennant since 1918. One of his career highlights came in July when
he went 4 for 4 with two homers in a 12-0 American League All-Star
Game rout at Fenway Park. Disappointment followed when he hit only
.200 (all singles) in the 1946 World Series, which the Sox lost in
seven games to the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Sox lost a one-game playoff at Fenway
against Cleveland. In 1949, Boston went to New York needing only
one win in the final two games to make it to the World Series.
Boston lost both. Williams never again came close to postseason
play. He was condemned to finish his starry career carrying
pitching-poor teams that were annually drubbed by the hated
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember all of it,'' he once said. ``It was a thrill,
let me tell you. To get up there and make it and find out I was as
good as anybody, those things were very gratifying to me. But there
was a lot of disappointment, too. All those years when we could
have won. One year we lost the whole pitching staff, and we had
that playoff game and those two games at the end of the year ('49).
I've always thought that the '40s and '50s . . . well, I don't know
of a greater era in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   He was baseball's best player in the 1950s, but never played
another meaningful game in October. He believed his hitting was
diminished after he broke his elbow chasing a Ralph Kiner flyball
in the 1950 All-Star Game at Comiskey Park in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was plenty of opportunity to add to his legend. On
April 30, 1952, 25,000 fans poured into Fenway and sang ``Auld Lang
Syne,'' sending Ted off to the Korean conflict. He flew 39 missions
and twice landed his fighter plane after being hit by anti-aircraft
fire. John Glenn described him as the finest pilot he'd seen.
Williams returned to Fenway Aug. 6, 1953, and finished with a .407
average in only 91 at-bats. Thirteen of his 37 hits were home runs.
Later in the decade, he hit .388 at age 39, and won a batting title
at 40. He homered in his final at-bat against the Orioles at Fenway
in 1960 and inspired John Updike's ``Hub Fans Bid Kid Adieu.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to walk down the street and have people say,
``There goes the greatest hitter who ever lived.'' He said hitting
a baseball was the hardest thing to do in sports. He wrote about
``The Science of Hitting,'' and it became the hitting bible for
several generations of young men. Last summer, actor Matt Damon
bragged to Williams that he had read Ted's book (Damon's dad, Kent
Damon, is freshman baseball coach at Newton North). Ted quizzed Mr.
Good Will Hunting, asking him what was the most important message
in the book. Damon answered, ``Get a good ball to hit.'' Bingo. Ted
was happy.
</P>
<P>
   He had many nicknames _ The Kid, The Splendid Splinter, Teddy
Ballgame, Thumper. He had his own shift, created by Cleveland
player/manager, Lou Boudreau. His feud with the Boston press was
legendary. The men from the press skewered him for going fishing
when his daughter was born. He was fined for spitting toward the
Fenway stands. He was fined for tossing his bat after striking out.
The bat came down on the head of Joe Cronin's housekeeper. He made
himself into one of the greatest fly fishermen in the world. He
shot pigeons with a shotgun in an empty Fenway Park. He wrote for
the Saturday Evening Post and the Globe. He was cheated out of an
MVP by a bitter sportswriter. He weighed his bats at the post
office. His eyesight was so good that few umpires dared call him
out on strikes, and it was said that he could read the label of a
78 RPM record spinning on a turntable. He demanded a 30 percent
paycut ($125,000 to $90,000) after slumping to .254 in 1959. He
read Zane Gray. He campaigned for Richard Nixon in 1960. He had his
own baseball camp. He would not tip his cap and never wore a
necktie. When he was enshired in the Hall of Fame, he ripped
sportswriters one last time then said, ``baseball gives every
American boy a chance to excel.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his hitting and war heroics, charity was one of
Williams's lasting contributions to Greater Boston. A friend of Dr.
Sidney Farber, the godfather of modern chemotherapy, Williams
quietly led an army of volunteers in the battle against children's
cancer. His only sibling, Danny Williams, died of leukemia and Ted
took on the Jimmy Fund as his pet charity when the Boston Braves
(cofounders of the Jimmy Fund) left Boston in 1953. He would go
anywhere, and do anything, in the name of the Jimmy Fund _ as long
as there were no cameras to record his deeds. Today there is a
permanent Williams exhibit at the Dana Farber Cancer Institute and
members of the ``406 Club'' (named in honor of Ted's .400 season,)
have raised over $2 million for cancer research in Williams's name.
</P>
<P>
   The ``406 Club'' was unveiled at a black-tie (Ted wore a string
tie) Park Plaza event in December 1995 _ just a few hours after the
formal dedication of the Ted Williams Tunnel. It was the final thaw
in the deep freeze that kept Williams distant from the Boston
fandom.
</P>
<P>
   The man who never tipped his cap when he played has become the
godfather of Boston sports. Ted turned 80 in 1998 and returned to
Boston for the All-Star Game festival this past July. He tossed out
the first ball before the game and was engulfed by stars of today
and the past. It was one of the most emotional moments in Boston
sports history, a fitting end to a New England sports century
dominated by baseball, and by Ted Williams, the greatest hitter who
ever lived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
