<SLUG> BC-BOOIK-WINDWARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WONDERFUL REIMAGINING OF `WUTHERING HEIGHTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WINDWARD HEIGHTS 
By Maryse Conde (translated, from the French, by Richard Philcox) 
Soho Press, 348 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes a steely sort of writer's confidence to bring back
Charlotte Bronte. In fact, some of her most ardent fans might catch
their breath at the very prospect, and instinctively shy away from
this reimagining of her classic ``Wuthering Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   But to disregard ``Windward Heights,'' the novel by
award-winning Caribbean novelist Maryse Conde, author of ``Segu''
and ``Tree of Life,'' would be to miss something unrepressed and
thoroughly fresh, and full of love and honor for its English
foremother. Conde writes in her dedication: ``To Emily Bronte, who
I hope will approve of this interpretation of her masterpiece.
Honour and respect!''
</P>
<P>
   Conde, who won the 1999 Marguerite Yourcenar Prize (for fiction
published in French by an author residing in the United States),
has elegantly recast the classic 19th-century tale as one that
spans continents and races, setting one family's almost unbearable
misery in her native French-speaking Guadeloupe at the turn of the
20th century. It is a society of Africans and Europeans wound tight
with tension, scrambling to find its bearings as it emerges from
slavery into colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   Conde's Heathcliff is a black man named Razye, a foundling from
the barren ``razyes'' or heaths in the island's countryside. Her
Catherine is Cathy, the stunning and spirited daughter of the
mixed-race planter Hubert Gagneur, who takes Razye in as a young
boy. Together with Cathy's jealous brother, Justin, they live in a
crumbling estate called L'Engoulvent, which Gagneur inherited from
his white father.
</P>
<P>
   While growing up with Cathy, Razye falls in love with her, a
sentiment that turns to obsession once she rejects him for a
wealthy, French-educated white Creole planter named Aymeric de
Linsseuil. We meet Razye just as he has made his fortune in Cuba,
and is about to return to Guadeloupe to exact his
hurricane-strength revenge _ both on Linsseuil and on Justin,
Cathy's brother, who had taken over the family estate, and demeaned
and banished Razye as soon as he could. ``I must take my revenge,''
Razye says. ``On the man who took the woman I loved and the man who
made me unworthy of her love. . . . I'll bring the second man to
his knees and if I have to kill the first one with both hands, I
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bronte thread is woven throughout the story, it is
here that Conde, a professor of French Caribbean literature at
Columbia University, parts ways with Bronte, and takes over with
her own extraordinary storytelling, imbued with race, culture, and
sexuality against a lush, painstakingly researched historical
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Slavery is a recent memory as the story unfolds, told in the
voices of various servants and others who knew both Razye and
Cathy. Race and social standing dictate almost every scene, every
mood, every decision. Guadeloupe's inhabitant are of ``all colors
of the rainbow from Congo-black to pass-for-white.'' But there is
no question about who holds power and who still suffers in this
color-coded society: ``The rich planters laid down the law and the
blacks lived hand to mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of slavery means nothing,'' says Lucinda Lucius,
Cathy's servant, who can trace her own family's slave history to
the capture of her Bambara grandmother in West Africa. ``It's the
same sadness, the same wretchedness we've been chewing on as long
as we can remember.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in this atmosphere that Cathy, ``the colour of hot syrup
left to cool in the open air,'' rejects the too-black Razye for
Linsseuil, the planter Cathy describes as a ``heavenly Cherub.'' In
fact they even marry, contrary to ``a golden rule that knows no
exception . . . the white male will never marratto girl,
though she may be his mistress.''
</P>
<P>
   It is what Razye overhears from Cathy, as she speaks with her
servant, that breaks his heart _ especially when he hears from her
own lips that it was her brother who turned her against Razye, and
toward a life of white privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Razye is now, I could never marry him. It would be too
degrading!'' Cathy says. ``Living with him would be like starting
over as savages from Africa.'' The calabash of his heart had been
smashed, Conde writes, and he'd never managed to piece it together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
