<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-WARRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FSU'S WARRICK SEEKS REDEMPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Peter Warrick wishes it could be different. He
wishes he could find a time machine, step back three months, and
undo what was done.
</P>
<P>
   He can't. And that bothers him. Haunts him even. ``I'm not a bad
person,'' he said. ``I made a mistake. I paid the price.''
</P>
<P>
   But we live in a judgmental world. Perception is reality and the
perception, which sticks for now, is not of an All-American wide
receiver who stayed at Florida State for his senior season and got
his degree, but of the out-of-control athlete of the '90s who has
his hands out with a ``what's-in-it-for-me?'' look on his face.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, say those making character assessments, is not
disputable. Peter Warrick went on a shopping spree at Dillard's
department store in Tallahassee earlier this season. He purchased
$412.38 worth of merchandise. He paid $21.40.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no discount. Not even close. Warrick was caught,
arrested, and plea bargained his way into a conviction that brought
no jail time but punished him nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the Heisman Trophy for which Warrick was the
overwhelming preseason favorite. But, even more important for the
6-foot, 190-pound senior, gone was his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of respect, Warrick was ridiculed. Florida fans
traveling to Gainesville for the annual game vs. Florida State had
Dillard's bags hanging out of their trunks in a mock salute to
Warrick. He became the poster child for pampered, spoiled athletes.
</P>
<P>
   People were making comparisons between Warrick and O.J. Simpson.
``How can you treat me like that,'' wondered Warrick, who asked
people to judge him by the person he was, not what they thought
they saw.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the problem. What people saw was the Warrick who at
first fluffed off the incident by saying, ``It was not like I shot
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was remorse, it didn't come until much later, it
seemed.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, Warrick's career was in the pause mode. He served
a two-game suspension while his legal problems were being sorted
out.
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman? He went from the front-runner to not receiving
enough votes to even get an invitation to the Heisman festivities
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's skills remain the same, as good as any receiver in
college football this season, something that could very well bring
him back to New York next spring as the No. 1 draft pick of the
Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   When he takes the field at the Superdome in Tuesday night's
national championship Sugar Bowl game against Virginia Tech, he
will be a man on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   He wants more than a win, and he wants that a lot. He wants some
sort of redemption, some sort of dispensation that people accept
that he made a mistake in judgment, that he is not only a great
player, but a good person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot,'' said Warrick, who still managed to
lead the Seminoles in receiving this season with 71 catches for 934
yards, a remarkable 103.8 yards per game average. ``Winning a
championship would do a lot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing is not an option, although this will be Warrick's third
national championship game; but the Seminoles have lost the first
two (in 1996 against Florida in the Sugar Bowl and last year
against Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl). And he has yet to catch a TD
pass in a title game.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates have rallied around him. Warrick was elected the
offensive captain for Tuesday's game. Offensive coordinator Mark
Richt is putting together a game plan that uses all of Warrick's
skills: catching the ball, running the ball, and throwing the ball,
which he has done three times this season.
</P>
<P>
   He's got the respect of the Virginia Tech players, who have seen
the tapes of Warrick's eight touchdown receptions and three
touchdown runs. ``Once he gets the ball in his hands, he can score
anytime, anywhere,'' said Tech wide receiver Andre Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick has always done that. Always been a winner. When he was
at Bradenton (Fla.) Southeast High School, his teams won state
championships in his junior and senior seasons, playing wide
receiver as a junior and QB as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick said he is trying to do things the right way. The cuts
from the Dillard's incident are starting to heal, although the
media attention this week undoubtedly opened up some wounds. ``I'm
trying to do everything right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FSU coach Bobby Bowden has had enough of the Warrick bashing.
``Hasn't he been punished enough?''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dillard's incident had been an isolated act, perhaps. But
there have been other incidents. In his junior year, he exchanged
words with police outside a Tampa fast-food restaurant and was
charged with disorderly conduct. There have been other flare-ups,
none of them epic in nature, but more than one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, no one questions his character. Maybe his judgment
sometimes. ``I don't want a bad image,'' said Warrick before the
season. ``I don't want people saying bad things about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Those closest to him don't. They see a teammate who does a job.
They see a father who has a 2-year-old daughter he dotes on. They
also see a confused young man who has made bad judgments and is now
suffering the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you knew Pete, you know he's not selfish; he's not that
kind of guy,'' said FSU running back Travis Minor.
</P>
<P>
   Winning is not the cure-all for all things, but in the case of
Warrick, it will soothe the soul. ``If we don't win, the season
will be a waste,'' said Warrick. ``We'd come so close and be so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is perhaps the epiteth for Warrick's final season at FSU.
By next summer, he should be a newly minted millionaire who won't
need discounts at department stores. He can reinvent himself the
way Randy Moss, ironically one of Warrick's closest friends, has
done with the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Warrick is counting days, hours, and minutes until he
can make a statement on the football field that will bring some joy
into what has been a season with very little of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
