<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC OF A DIFFERENT COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blue Man Group _ a visual or auditory experience? Most people
would say visual, based on the act's long-running theater success.
But Blue Man Group has always had a stirring audio component, which
finally gets full rein on its new (and first) CD, ``Audio.''
</P>
<P>
   How to describe it? Let's ask cofounder Chris Wink:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tribal rhythms . . . where percussion and melody meet . . .
futuristic but ancient . . . with big elements of punk energy and
crazy, spaghetti-western guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aesthetic has been to try to paint with sound,'' says
Wink, one of the three Blue Man Group founders who have seen their
late '80s salon gatherings balloon into a theater phenomenon now
playing in three cities _ New York, Boston, Chicago, and, as of
February, in Las Vegas at the Luxor Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The group's visuals are well-known _ the blue face masks, the
``paint drums'' (where mallets are bashed into different,
electrically lit paints), and the tubular PVC instruments
(polyvinyl chloride pipes) struck with foam-rubber padd's a
child's fantasy for adults, with elements of Pink Floyd (think of
their hypnotic element), the Grateful Dead (think of their ``drums
and space'' segments), and, yes, the Sex Pistols (whose song
``Anarchy in the UK'' is played in the theater show, but not on the
album).
</P>
<P>
   ``I would feel comfortable with a Pink Floyd influence,'' says
Wink, ``but, interestingly, we're not Deadheads. It's not like
we're anti-Dead _ and I love what (Dead percussionist) Mickey Hart
has done in his exploration of the drums, but we have many other
influences. We like the koto drummers of Japan _ they hit with
incredible passion and there's a lot to learn from hey're
ego-less and submerge into a collective. And I also studied African
drumming at college, with Ed Blackwell at Wesleyan, and learned
about interlocking rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when you mention Pink Floyd,  technically a blues
band, though some of their most powerful stuff goes past that. But
we wanted to move away from the blues and go to a place where
nobody went before. What punk did for the guitar, we wanted to do
for the drums.''
</P>
<P>
   Wink and cofounders Matt Goldman and Phil Stanton do just that
on ``Audio,'' which incorporates a number of Blue Man-made
instruments that were too big to fit into the Charles Playhouse.
These include the tubulum, which is similar to the PVC, but has
longer pipes and is struck with sticks. All the instruments are
acoustic (no drum machines allowed) and recorded on analog tape,
not digitally, to get a more organic sound.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an album that veers between rock and ambient
textures with a trance-like fluidity that compensates for the lack
of vocals. The compositions are based on riffs from the theater
shows, but the CD is not a clone of the shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to just have a soundtrack,'' says Wink. ``So we
thought, `Hey, let's just throw the show out.' Before long we were
completely rearranging songs and creating a different hybrid. You
would still know it's Blue Man, but you wouldn't hear the exact
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The founders, who made the album in their New York warehouse,
enlisted a number of Bostonians to help out. Producer/music
director Todd Perlmutter and guitarist Christian Dyas had been in
the Boston band Orangutang. Boston engineers Andrew Schneider, Carl
Plaister (who had worked at Fort Apache studio), and Billy O'Malley
(who had been in the band Jocobono with Perlmutter) contributed, as
did Ross Humphrey, who worked as a tour manager for the Mighty
Mighty Bosstones. And Boston's Pro Audio put together the warehouse
studio for Blue Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like new ritualistic music,'' says producer Perlmutter.
``Before this, I was more of a punk-rock guy _ get in the studio,
have some booze, do some takes, and get out. But Blue Man was more
intense. They hear a sound and then build an instrument for it. We
were five months working on it, recording all these weird
instruments, with tons and tons of drums. We used all 48 tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Top tours: The Rolling Stones were the top-grossing act in North
America this year with $64.7 million raked in at the box office,
followed by Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band with $61.4
million, according to Pollstar magazine. Then came `N Sync with
$51.5 million (but `N Sync sold the most tickets _ 1.8 million) and
the Dave Matthews Band with $48.5 million. Average ticket prices
for the top 50 tours rose nearly 30 percent, from $33.59 to $43.63.
And though the year saw a record overall gross of $1.5 million, the
actual number of tickets sold for the top 50 acts totaled 26.3
million _ down 4 percent from last year and the smallest number
since 1993's 25.6 million. ``For an industry based on a high volume
of repeat business, this is not a good sign,'' the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Country attendance dips: Tough news for country fans as the
millennium closes. Country attendance dropped 28 percent this year,
according to Amusement Business. Gross country dollars were also
down 16 percent, to $116 million. The good news lay in headlining
tours by Shania Twain (she led the pack with a $36.5 million gross,
with an average take of $571,410 per show) and George Strait. The
latter's stadium tour, which also featured Tim McGraw, Dixie
Chicks, Jo Dee Messina, Kenny Chesney, and Asleep at the Wheel,
grossed $32.3 million in just 17 dates, averaging $1.9 million per
show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Didi's tribute: A pleasant surprise last week was Didi Stewart's
tribute to the Hollies, staged at Johnny D's in Boston. The Hollies
may be known to some folks as just Graham Nash's band before he
joined Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash, but they were masters of vocal
harmony back in the '60s, mixing pure pop with a psychedelic flair.
Stewart, who is known for her tributes as well as her efforts in
such local bands at Girls Night Out and Didi Stewart and the
Amplifiers, caught the Hollies' spirit well. She did justice to
classics like ``Bus Stop,'' ``Carrie Anne,'' ``Carousel,'' ``He
Ain't Heavy,'' and ``Air that I Breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who teaches voice at Berklee College of Music, was
accompanied by a crack veteran band, including Peter Hoffman and
Wendy Sobel on guitars, Tim Jackson on drums, and Mike Payatte on
bass and vocals. Look for her to repeat the tribute later this
winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
