<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUNING IN, DROPPING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 20 years ago today (well, close enough) when the Ramones
sang ``It's the end, the end of the '70s/It's the end, the end of
the century'' and we all kind of laughed. The end of the century,
fellas? So far away. In the song, ``Do You Remember Rock 'n' Roll
Radio?,'' Joey Ramone continued: ``We need change and we need it
fast/Before rock becomes part of the past/'Cause lately it all
seems the same to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramones were prescient. As to rock 'n' roll, well, if it
seemed in trouble then . . . check out the top of the pops today.
</P>
<P>
   With this, the 20th annual It's Only Rock 'n' Roll Awards, we
both salute the vision of the Ramones _ who recently reunited for a
gig at CBGB in New York _ and hope for better days ahead. Not that
there weren't moments. It's just that when you survey the
landscape, you bump up against way too much vacuous teen pop,
rebellion-by-the-numbers rap metal, and country-pop dross. Our
modus operandi, as always: vicious, but fair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
KING OF THE MOUNTAIN: Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band.
Whenever all these guys (and gal) get together, you can only bow
and hand the crown back to them. Their FleetCenter show(s) had all
the love and ache, desperation and desire, full-tilt rock 'n' roll
and mournful balladry you could ever hope for. You leave a show
like this feeling very much alive. &QL; 
 &QL; 
800-POUND GORILLA: Robert F.X. Sillerman and his guys and gals at
SFX, the company that now presents most of the music you will go
and see, and likes nothing more than linking concerts to corporate
sponsors. Can a near-monopoly work for the customer? You be the
judge. Caveat emptor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROCK 'N' ROLL POLITICO OFFSPRING: Sid McCain. Arizona Senator John
McCain's and presidential hopeful daughter championed the way-cool
space rock band Spiritualized when she worked publicity for Arista;
she is now a senior director of publicity for Capitol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT WOULD JESUS DO? Puff Daddy. The devout Christian, draped in
gold chains, agreed to have himself put up on a cross for a pal's
video, reconsidered this questionable tactic, and made his
displeasure known by beating up on a record company executive
involved. Kind of a lose-lose-lose situation. And, wait, this just
in: Puff busted for possession of a stolen gun with Jennifer
(we're-just-friends) Lopez in tow. Upside: While his album didn't
tank, it didn't break the bank. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KNOCK KNOCK. WHO'S THERE? KNOCK KNOCK. WHO'S THERE? (Old joke)
Philip Glass and his ensemble performed a slow dazzle at the Wang
for ``Koyaanisqatsi.'' A trifle irritating, but a whole lot
mesmerizing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DOUBLE BILL OF THE YEAR (HIGHBROW): Richard Thompson and Lucinda
Williams. Both with their bands, both turning out exquisite, pained
rock 'n' roll that encompassed country, folk, and more. And both
adults who've been through the wringer and survived to sing about
and shacatharsis at the Orpheum. Boston was the only city
that got this treat; it was not part of a national tour but through
smart booking at the Don Law Co. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DOUBLE BILL OF THE YEAR (LOWBALL) Motorhead and Nashville Pussy.
Like-minded head-bangers who have forgotten they're adults play it
fast and hard, the audio equivalent of ``The Road Warrior.'' As
subtle as a flying mallet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
OUR ROUTING BUMMER; Pet Shop Boys. The arch English synth-pop duo's
rare tour bypasses Boston because of booking logistics. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PSYCHEDELIC STARS: (Tie) Mercury Rev and Flaming Lips. Merc Rev did
prog-rock proud at the Middle East, and months later the Lips did
the same at the Roxy. Music as a journey, as an exploration. Peaks,
valleys, explosions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BRAINS 'N' BRAWN: Rage Against the Machine. The brightly lit bulb
in the rap-metal world of burnt-out filaments. Billy Bragg brought
Howard Zinn to the college kids and liberals; Rage brings Zinn to
the mostly apolitical masses. There are worse messages to absorb by
osmosis. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROCKER/ACTRESS OF THE YEAR: Courtney Love. The brazen, barefoot,
slatternly one leads Hole through a hard-rock highwire act at the
Orpheum and charms us as Andy Kaufman's level-headed wife in ``Man
on the Moon.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
THERE IS A POP HEAVEN, AFTER ALL: The Delgados. Unassuming boys and
girls from Glasgow make beautiful noise _ violins, guitars, voices
_ at the VFW in Cambridge. &QL; 
 &QL; 
REUNITED HOMETOWN HEROES: (Tie) J. Geils Band, Del Fuegos, the
Neats. Geils put down the whammer jammer at Tweeter Center and
recently pulled off a cool charity gig; Del Fuegos packed the
Middle East Downstairs to benefit Dan and Warren Zane's mum's
charity project (and never sounded better), and the Neats brought
chills as they stuffed T.T. the Bear's Place and set up a fund for
the son of their late drummer, Terry Hanley. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOMETOWN HEROES HALL OF FAME: The Mighty Mighty Bosstones. For
continuing the Hometown Throwdown at the Middle, for projecting a
good vibe and a hard edge, for keeping humble in the face of all
the hoo-ha. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LOCAL BAND OF THE YEAR: The Shods. Shods City Rockers. Hooks 'n'
bite. &QL; 
 &QL; 
OUT OF THE SPOTLIGHT'S GLARE/ &QL; 
 &QL; 
THANKS FOR THE BREAK: Madonna and Michael Jackson. Whether it's
motherhood, owning the successful Maverick record company, or her
embrace of spirituality, Madonna the icon mostly stayed out of the
way. Jackson? Still cuddling with Liz or a chimp or . . . no, don't
go there . . . another year in the hyperbaric chamber of life. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST FUTURE PLAN: (tie) Garth Brooks and Celine Dion. Garth, the
Billy Joel of country-pop projects his retirement in short order.
Downside: Does that mean Chris Gaines lives? Dion, the
shudder-inducing Canadian diva, plans to take two years off to
start a family. You go, girl! Remember, it's cheaper by the dozen .
. . &QL; 
 &QL; 
BARE YOUR MIDRIFF, SPARE THE SOUL: Britney Spears is this year's
model, but the list is endless and the lightness unbearable. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PUNK'S NOT DEAD: Joe Strummer. Ol' Joe and his band the Mescaleros
tear up the Roxy with slashing punk, skanking reggae and dub, and a
warm, heartfelt vibe. Much more than a trip down memory lane. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST PERFORMANCE BY AN EMBALMED STAR: Brian Wilson. Sad to say, but
the onetime Beach Boys genius was a semi-eerie presence on stage at
Symphony Hall, not singing his fabled high harmonies, not playing a
lot of keyboards, and projecting nothing but rote emotion. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FESTIVAL OF THE YEAR: The Guinness Fleadh. The first time in Boston
for the Irish-themed mega bill and a huge success despite the
last-minute cancellation of the crankiest man alive, Van Morrison.
Highlights: Elvis, a relatively sober and kick-ass Shane MacGowan
and the Popes, Richard Thompson, many more. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SMART METAL AWARD: Queens of the Stone Age. Messy and agitated,
non-formulaic metal with brains at the Middle East Up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PUNK ROCK/HIP HOP NUCLEAR FALLOUT AND NADIR: (tie) Limp Bizkit, Kid
Rock, Korn. The ``bad'' boys of modern rock keep punching the
lowest common denominator button. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IT'S ONLY ROCK 'N' ROLL AWARD: The Rolling Stones. At the Fleet,
Mick and Keef grin like Alfred E. Neuman, saying, ``What us,
worry?'' Jokes were made _ some in this corner _ but the old guys
will be (or are) to rock 'n' roll what John Lee Hooker and B.B.
King are to the blues. Timeless and still making sense _ if not
making as great new music. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOUNDTRACK OF THE YEAR: ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut.''
Some of the nastiest, funniest songs to grace the silver screen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CROSSOVER OF THE YEAR: The Corrs. Sweet Irish popsters get a
slightly harder kick _ and maintain wonderful harmonies, melodies _
at Avalon. Not just cute and bubbly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CRYPTIC, GRUMPY OLD MAN OF THE YEAR; Tom Waits. An album and an
Orpheum show that puts the art in avant-garde and draws us into a
witty, dark world of mutant blues and rock. (Note: Waits has always
been a cryptic, grumpy old man.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
LOCAL LOSS: The death of Morphine leader Mark Sandman. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST MOMENTS AT A LOCAL SHOW: Gene Dante and company singing Roxy
Music's ``In Every Dream Home, A Heartache'' and Gary Cherone and
company singing Alice Cooper's ``Ballad of Dwight Fry'' in Boston
Rock Opera's ``Another Night (at) the Opera'' at the Middle East.
Transfixing and smile-inducing, both. &QL; 
 &QL; 
UNDESERVED SNUB: Kula Shaker. How soon they _ radio, the public _
forget. A buzz band several years ago, the English group's
sophomore effort was up to the first, a pop/psychedelic smash, but
it sank like a stone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TECHNO KINGS IN CONCERT: (Tie) Mobv Chemical Brothers, and the
Orbital/Crystal Method/Lo-Fidelity Allstars. Moby put out one of
the year's best albums, ``Play,'' and he and his band backed it up
live (adding even more punch) on the Esplanade; ditto the Chem.
Bros. with ``Surrender'' and an Avalon gig. The triple bill at
Worcester's Palladium was a raver's delight from the rock/trip hop
slant of the Lo-Fi's to the Method;s sonic assault to Orbital's
more cerebral glide. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MISANTHROPIC ENTERTAINER OF THE YEAR: Roger Waters. Pink Floyd's
old captain had nothing new under the moon to offer us, but he and
his band played a stirring cream-of-the-crop (mostly) show at
Tweeter Center with all the ominous sounds and pessimistic bleating
an old crank could hope for. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FORMER MISANTHROPE TURNED MR. SHOW: Elvis Costello. Yes, EC has
been gracious for years, but his Orpheum show was not only that,
but ecelnd sharply etched. Songs from all periods, pumped
up, done proud with able help from keyboardist Steve Nieve. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A KICK AND A CARRESS: Magnetic Fields. The New York-based group led
by Stephin Merritt crafted a wide-rangijg chamber pop set, both
whimsical and sad, at the Middle East. Finely detailed, downbeat
music, gorgeous and rich. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST/WORST ROCK 'N' ROLL TV AD: Buzzcocks for Toyota Rav4.
England's punk progenitors sing ``What Do I Get?,'' their plaintive
song of angst and missed opportunity for a company selling a gas
gobbler. Irony abounds, the royalty check does not bounce. &QL; 
 &QL; 
STONE TEMPLE PILOTS PEARL JAM KNOCKOFF: Creed. It gets more generic
every time it filters down. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COMEBACK OF THE YEAR; Blondie. Good album, great live show (the
first time, at the Orpheum). All the sass and sex appeal of yore
and more enthusiasm. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IT'S THE END OF THE WORLD AS THEY KNOW IT AND THEY FEEL FINE;
R.E.M. A fab Tweeter Show (including the rarely performed ``Radio
Free Europe'' encore, and proof that creative rock 'n' roll goes on
after 40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
