<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRICO'S GOT WHAT IT TAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tirico has emerged as one of ESPN's go-to guys.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let his play-by-play role at the Insight.com Bowl cast any
doubt on his low-key stardom.
</P>
<P>
   His strength is versatility. He is able to call college
basketball and football games with the same detached
professionalism as his golf and studio host roles.
</P>
<P>
   His coverage of Payne Stewart's tragic accident was Hall of Fame
stuff. ``With different players playing different schedules, it can
be weeks, even months, before paths may cross again,'' Tirico said
from the PGA Tour Championship in Houston. ``That's why in some
ways this all doesn't seem real. You keep thinking that next season
is going to start, and on some range somewhere on the West Coast
when the Tour gets started, we'll see Payne . . . But it's not
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tirico has worked his way to ESPN's starting lineup. He
graduated from Syracuse in 1988 and worked as sports director for
the CBS affiliate in Syracuse and as the play-by-play voice for
Syracuse basketball, football, lacrosse, and volleyball for the
local cable network.
</P>
<P>
   He joined ESPN as a ``SportsCenter'' anchor in 1991. Since then,
he has hosted ``Monday Night Countdown'' and ``Thursday Night
College Football.'' He also hosted ``The NFL on ESPN Radio'' and
``The NBA on ESPN Radio.'' There's no other way to describe Tirico:
He's got skills.
</P>
<P>
   And smarts.
</P>
<P>
   He told ESPN viewers shortly after Stewart's death: ``Golf and
silence go hand-in-hand, but the silence today in Houston is eerie
as the players carry their individual feeling of this universal
feeling around the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sailors will tell story
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's Cup arrives right on time, especially for viewers
frustrated with local sports teams. ESPN2 starts more than 70 hours
of coverage Sunday at 12:30 a.m. with the Louis Vuitton Cup
Challenger semifinals. Live coverage begins Feb. 18 with the best
of nine America's Cup Match.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Mason is producing the coverage. Mason competed in the
1962 Defender Trials as a crew member on Nefertiti.
</P>
<P>
   He recently told reporters that his main objective is to allow
the sailors to tell the story. Digital technology, including
wireless microphones attached to several key players, will enable
viewers to feel as if they are in New Zealand listening to strategy
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Announcers Jim Kelly and Gary Jobson will be stationed in the
water ``to see the boats firsthand, feel the wind, and get a better
sense of the competition,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Other technological innovations include ``SailTrack,''
computer-generated 3-D graphics, and ``yachtcam,'' an on-board
camera. Mason said he is most excited about the on-board sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other sport will allow people at home to feel the emotional
energy of the competitors like the America's Cup,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not all agreed on Jordan
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN revealed a few details on its selection of Michael Jordan
as the century's greatest athlete, beating out Babe Ruth and
Muhammad Ali. Details show a wide range of disagreement. Only nine
of the 48 panel members voted Jordan No. 1. Ruth received 10
first-place votes. Ali received 11, but also had six votes placing
him below the Top 10. Ruth received five such votes and Jordan only
two . . . Fox Sports Net New England airs ``Magic versus Bird: The
Game that Changed the Game'' Saturday at 6:30 p.m. At 9 a.m. and 5
p.m., the cable station reruns ``Keith Olbermann's Top 50 Athletes
of the Century.'' CBS interviews Bill Parcells for ``60 Minutes''
Sunday at 7 p.m. Parcells tells Mike Wallace this season was ``a
humbling experience. You feel like a failure, no matter how much
you've won, no matter how many games . . . championships . . .
Super Bowls. You're not winning now, so you stink. And that's the
way you look at yourself personally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
