<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3409 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-2N     12-31 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, December 30, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: Y2K-TERRORISM; NATION-EVE; PENRY-EXECUTION; Y2K-BUSINESS;
CONTINENTAL-BRF; RICE-PRICES; COMPUTER-BESTBUYS; COMPUTER-COLUMN;
Y2K-NEWLEAF; and BALLET-STEVENSON)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-TERRORISM (Washington) _ The FBI rounds up people in several
states for questioning about their possible links to suspected
terrorist Ahmed Ressam, who was arrested with bomb-making material
while trying to enter the U.S. near Seattle two weeks ago. By JOHN
C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CZAR (Washington) _ The White House's Y2K coordinator
confidently predicts that the rollover into the 2000 new year won't
bring major computer glitches in the United States. If little or
nothing goes wrong, it will not ``happen by accident,'' says John
Koskinen, the Y2K chief. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-PHONES (Washington) _ Don't pick up the telephone at
midnight Friday just to see if it works. Experts say if everyone
does that, circuits will jam and many phones won't work at that
moment. BY JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   With Y2K-TIPS (Washington) _ Tips on how to cope with possible
computer-based problems. By the HEARST NEWSPAPERS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CELEBRATION (Washington) _ The scene on the National
Mall, site of Friday night's star-studded New Year's Eve
celebration: English crooner Tom Jones practices his classic song
``It's Not Unusual'' while security agents all around him scan the
place for anything remotely unusual. After the arrest of a
suspected terrorist on the West Coast, law enforcement officials
here have been on high alert. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL-ABUSE (Washington) _ One in four U.S. children under age
18 lives in a household with an adult who is addicted to alcohol or
abuses it, according to a new federal survey released Thursday. By
JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-NUKES (Colorado Springs, Colo.) _ In the final-hours
countdown to 2000, Russian and U.S. military nuclear experts
complete their first joint efforts here to ensure that any Y2K
computer snags don't spark an accidental nuclear missile launch. By
ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATION-EVE (Washington) _ Anti-hacking consultants are setting
up virtual chat and game rooms so they can pass the time while
hunkering in New Year's Eve bunkers, urban pizza joints are firing
up their kitchen staffs to cater to stay-at-home merrymakers, and
cities are making final arrangements for festivities. We look at
the final preparations for New Year's Eve nationally. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   PENRY-EXECUTION (Houston) _ The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals orders a stay of the execution for John Paul Penry, the
mentally retarded man convicted of the 1979 murder of Livingston
housewife Pamela Carpenter. Penry, who experts say has the mental
capacity of a 6-year-old, was to be executed Jan. 13. By JAMES
KIMBERLY.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GUN-SALES (San Francisco) _ Californians are buying guns
in near record numbers, at least in part because of changes in
state and federal handgun laws that take effect Jan. 1. State
Department of Justice statistics show that gun sales are up to
3,000 a day in December from 1,200 a day a few months ago. By JIM
HERRON ZAMORA. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SF-SUICIDE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's suicide prevention
agency is doubling the number of telephone lines and volunteers who
answer them in preparation for New Year's Eve. But a spokeswoman
for the American Foundation for Suicide Prevention, which
specializes in research, says she has seen nothing to suggest that
suicide rates would increase on New Year's Eve. By PETER HARTLAUB.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-BUSINESS (Houston) _ In the final hours before the arrival
of 2000, we check On banks, ATMs, airlines, grocery stores and
other businesses to see if they are ready for potential computer
problems. By the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   CONTINENTAL-BRF (Houston) _ Continental Airlines buys a 28
percent stake in Fort Lauderdale-based Gulfstream International
Airlines, a code-share partner of Continental that flies to the
Caribbean and Bahamas. By LAURA GOLDBERG.
</P>
<P>
   RICE-PRICES (Houston) _ The price of rice has been bumping
bottom at a six-year low this week. Primarily, it is the result of
a harvest too big for demand, particularly in the Mississippi
Delta. Even Texas growers produced more than last year although the
acres harvested were down substantially. By NELSON ANTOSH. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BESTBUYS (Houston) _ Computing and Internet access
became even more mainstream in 1999, and the products selected for
this year's Attaboy Awards reflect the growing pervasiveness of
personal computers in American homes. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Houston) _ Notebook computers once were used
only by corporate types who had fallen into favor with the hardware
gods at the office, or who checked out a battered model from the
departmental pool. But over the past few years, computer makers
have realized that there is more to portable life than just
customers at the Fortune 1000. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   With: COMPUTER-HELPLINE
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ L.M. Sixel's Working column will not
move this week.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEW-YEAR'S-EVE (Undated) _ For all the hoopla and pageantry
on New Year's Eve, polls show that seven in ten Americans will ring
in the new year at home. And face it, most of us will be sitting in
front of the television. By MARK McGUIRE. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-NEWLEAF (Houston) _ Ten reasons why you shouldn't turn over
a new leaf in the new year. We play it for laughs. By MELISSA
FLETCHER STOELTJE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BALLET-STEVENSON (Houston) _ Houston Ballet's Ben Stevenson was
named an officer of the order of the British Empire by Queen
Elizabeth II. By MOLLY GLENTZER. (Already filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
