<HEADER>
A3411 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-ADVISO     12-31 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors,  &UR; The New York Times &LR;  has announced the appointment of a
new Op-Ed columnist, Paul Krugman, beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
   His column will move on the New York Times News Service wire
twice a week, Saturday and Tuesday, for release on Sunday and
Wednesday, with a commentary category (``k'' code). Slugged
BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN, it will be The Times's first regular Op-Ed
column devoted to economics, business and finance.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman is an economics professor at the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology and an author known for his theories on international
trade and economics.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman is the author or editor of 16 books and more then 200
articles in professional journals. He has also edited many books on
international trade and finance. In recognition of his work on
trade, Krugman received the John Bates Clark medal in 1991 from the
American Economic Association. Krugman has also written for a
broader audience, including a monthly column, ''The Dismal
Science,'' for the on-line magazine Slate. And his articles have
appeared in publications like Foreign Affairs, Harvard Business
Review and Scientific American.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman, 46, will remain the Ford international professor of
economics at MIT. He received a bachelor's degree from Yale
University and a Ph.D. from MIT. He has also taught at Yale
University, Stanford University and worked as the chief
international economist for the White House Council of Economic
Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions, please call the News Service desk at
(888) 346 9867 or (212) 556-1927 and ask for Gary E. McCardell
(garymc(at)nytimes.com), the day supervisor, or Pat Ryan
(patryan(at)nytimes.com), the evening supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
