<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3412 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-CLIPPERS-     12-31 2613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-CLIPPERS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Once every thousand years or so, the Rockets are this unbeatable.
Every pass is precise. Drives turn into dunks. Jumpers are chip
shots.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And if not quite 1,000 years in the making, the Rockets' 122-100
win over the Clippers at Compaq Center on Thursday night was at
least their most prolific and lopsided of this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets pulled out all the Millennium Celebration Party
stops they could come up with. They passed out party hats and
noisemakers. They threw confetti into the stands and gave away
posters, jackets and memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   But the last detail was the party highlight that was most
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a stunning turnaround for their make-or-break
backcourt combination of Steve Francis and Cuttino Mobley. One game
after Francis was benched down the stretch and Mobley turned
himself into a stand-still jump shooter, the Rockets' prodigy
backcourt tossed passes around like party favors.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley and Francis each had 11 assists, the first time the
Rockets have had two players in double figures in that category
since Sam Cassell and Robert Horry turned the trick in 1995.
Francis added 19 points, while Mobley scored 16 and had seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' Francis said. ``I worked hard in practice
yesterday. I didn't play up to my standards the last game. Coach
(Rudy Tomjanovich) told me he just wanted me to be more aggressive
and play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great. Every time I turned around, somebody was open.
And (Mobley) was passing the ball, and I was doing the same thing.
That means the plays we're running are working. Guys were open
cutting to the basket. We had some transition buckets. A lot of
times guys were cutting to the bucket, and we were finding them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley put on a clinic regarding the difference between his
frustrating finish against the Raptors and the Rockets' plan to
clear out to allow him to create.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they might not have expected this much of a reversal
in one game. When Mobley reached double figures in assists for the
first time in his career, there were almost three minutes left in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're going to double me and rush people at me,''
Mobley said. ``My job is to get everybody else into it. That's the
most fun kind (of game). Nobody is bickering. Everybody's happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The bickering was reserved, as is so often the case, for the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor, having already publicly plotted his escape from
Los Angeles, had a career-high 31 points, making 13 of 22 shots.
But in 40 minutes, the 6-9, 260-pound forward had just three
rebounds and then directly pointed at second-year center Michael
Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi blocked six shots but had just four rebounds and four
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really bothers me with the way we're losing,'' Taylor said
after his team dropped to 9-20. ``When you are losing to teams that
you are supposed to beat, it should bother you. If it doesn't,
something is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to be on the same page, and everybody has to
play. We simply have to get more out of Michael. He's not
protecting the basket. He's not doing much on offense. He's not
doing nothing right now. I don't know if anyone else is going to
say anything, but I don't care. He's got to step up, because now
he's nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom, the Clippers' ballyhooed Rookie of the Year
candidate, registered his first career triple double (10 points, 13
rebounds, 10 assists). He was, however, just 2-of-13 from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, meanwhile, were so in sync that they had assists on
36 of their 50 field goals, collecting five more assists than their
previous best this season. And that total came in a double-overtime
game in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   With their guards distributing the ball so fervently, the
Rockets' big men consistently cut to the lane to take passes for
dunks. Kelvin Cato had 21 points, scoring 10 on alley-oop dunks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great out there,'' Cato said. ``We played as a total
team tonight. Everybody had it going, and we started milking
everybody. Even the guys off the bench came in with a good
attitude, no matter how many points up we were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three stages. We had the Dream (Hakeem Olajuwon) and
Chuck (Barkley) together stage. We had the Chuck stage without
Dream. Now we have the stage without both of them. Now we're
finding out what our strong points are and taking advantage of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rogers had 15 points for the Rockets, completing four
cuts to the basket with dunks.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the highlight finishes, the slam of the night did
not come from either Cato or Rogers, or even Francis, who brought
out some of what could become part of his All-Star Weekend
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had already begun to turn the game into a H-O-R-S-E
contest early in the second half. Shandon Anderson scored on a cut
to the basket, taking a pass from Mobley. Francis passed to Rogers
for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Rockets' first five field goals of the half were
layups or dunks, the lone exception an Anderson jumper that would
become one of many. Francis would add a 16-footer to put the
Rockets ahead 78-58, and the Rockets would score on three more
dunks or layups before an Anderson trey produced a 27-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the winner of the dunk contest came on the next possession.
Anderson took a pass from Mobley in the corner and pump-faked, then
drove the baseline and threw down a stunning two-handed slam over
7-3 Clippers center Keith Closs.
</P>
<P>
   Closs fouled Anderson on the play, and Anderson completed the
three-point play, inspiring mad celebrations from Francis and
Mobley.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson finished with 16 points as every Rockets starter scored
in double figures for the first time since the season opener. Walt
Williams added 16 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
