<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3425 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-HANGOVER-ART-     12-31 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-HANGOVER-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EVENING AFTER: A NIGHT OUT WITH A HANGOVER EXPERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 2)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT37 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Make it better,'' moaned Dianne Rosenfeld, a
30-something beauty salon entrepreneur, lying on a table in her
Upper East Side Manhattan apartment on a recent evening.
</P>
<P>
   A bottle of Beaujolais Nouveau she had downed with a friend
earlier that day had left her head pounding. Her body ached from
working out too much. She was getting over the flu. And she had had
a  &UR; very &LR;  intense day of shopping. She was in a bad way.
</P>
<P>
   But such complaints are music to the ears of Michael Lepak, a
masseur who makes house calls.
</P>
<P>
   Lepak, 34, a quiet blond with a strapping physique, works the
late shift for Healing Hands, a Manhattan-based company that
dispatches its 50 massage therapists for everything from jet lag (
a massage while the client inhales beads of eucalyptus) to a
breakup (gentle touching and hours of listening). One of his
specialties is hangovers.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate student in social work by day at Fordham University,
Lepak moonlights five nights a week for $130 an hour, plus tip,
from about 4 p.m. on. He has been asked to cure headaches and
backaches, to help clients feel awake (peppermint scents) and to
help them fall asleep (lilac scents).
</P>
<P>
   He also gets the occasional 2 a.m. call from the Four Seasons
Hotel for someone who just flew into town and is suffering from jet
lag.
</P>
<P>
   Lepak arrived at Ms. Rosenfeld's at 8 p.m. with his green
leather massage table, multicolored oils and extra-supple hands. He
began setting up her apartment for the hangover cure by dimming the
lights, firing up the lilac candles, putting some New Age guitar on
the CD player and pouring oil over her body.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Rosenfeld's friend Harry Redlich, who was
visiting from Los Angeles, sat on the couch, sipping wine and
watching, claiming he had nothing better to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must get the toxins to flow out of your body,'' Lepak said
in a soft voice, as his patient lay limp on the table covered with
a towel and a black bikini brief. Kneading her left calf, he said:
``We must push around the blood and fluid. We must push all the
poison back into the liver and kidney, where it can be purified.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded good to Ms. Rosenfeld, whose usual hangover cure is
``getting a cheeseburger and fries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' Lepak chided. ``After a hangover you must keep the
circulation moving. You must drink lots of water. Flush out the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just decadent New York life,'' pointed out Redlich, an
advertising writer. Indeed, what could be more decadent than having
someone ease your ``indulgence stress,'' as Ms. Rosenfeld called
it.
</P>
<P>
   Twirling her toes, Ms. Rosenfeld called out, ``My feet, my
feet!'' Lepak applied lotion to her soles and rubbed her arches.
Ms. Rosenfeld, who gets these treatments several times a month,
knows feet are the window to the throbbing head.
</P>
<P>
   Silently he moved from the calves to the neck, never losing his
focus, despite the chatter about Prada sales and the loud funk
music Redlich had turned on.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Lepak tapped his client on the back, signaling that she
was ready for her eucalyptus bath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Michael draw the bath?'' Redlich asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Lepak said, already packing up his oils and table for
his next call. He had to meet a masseuse on the Upper West Side to
administer a double good-night massage to a husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:30, he left Ms. Rosenfeld, who, after the two-hour
session, decided she felt revived enough to skip the bath and
instead go with her friend for dinner _ and more wine. ``I'll see
you again,'' Lepak called out, his table in tow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
