<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3434 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SCUM-DOCTOR01-COX     12-31 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCUM-DOCTOR01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA's 'scum doctor' scopes out biological cure to pollution
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Call him the scum doctor. He doesn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   For the past seven years, geologist Walter O'Niell has been
dipping his hands into tanks blanketed by mats of a primitive
blue-green algae, hoping to come up with a cost-efficient way of
cleaning up environmental problems and pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Developed and patented by Clark Atlanta University biologist
Judy Bender and Peter Phillips, a biologist at Winthrop College,
the slimy microbial mat _ actually composed of several layers of
different kinds of bacteria _ is a living filter, absorbing
contaminants, heavy metals and organic pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   O'Niell's research for his doctorate from the University of
Georgia focused on whether the Bender-Phillips microbial mat could
absorb trichloroethylene and tetrachloroethylene, solvents used in
many industrial processes. Two of the most common contaminants,
they eventually can break down into vinyl chloride, a known
carcinogen.
</P>
<P>
   The mat, however, renders the chemicals harmless, breaking them
down to carbon dioxide without producing any detectable levels of
vinyl chloride. It could have applications outside as well as
inside the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   O'Niell had learned about Bender and her work from John Noakes,
a friend who directs the UGA Center for Isotope Studies, and knew
he wanted to use the mat in his Ph.D. work. Bender ``has been very
supportive, giving me samples of the mat and bacteria,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen what the mat can do to trichloroethylene and
tetrachloroethylene, O'Niell has moved on to other projects, like
determining if the Bender-Phillips mat will break down perchlorate,
a byproduct of rocket fuel that's found near missile manufacturing
sites throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   He's working with UGA geologist Valentine Nzengung to see if
willow trees and fresh-water algae can also break down
contaminants. And he'd like to obtain funding for a pilot project
in Bangladesh to learn whether the microbial mat can remedy the
rampant arsenic contamination of that country's wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much environmental pollution,'' O'Niell said. ``I
think we can solve a lot of problems using plants instead of
digging up soils and trying to clean them. Plus, it would be a lot
cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting companies, cities and the federal government to opt for
a biological and not a mechanical solution to contamination
problems isn't easy, said Bender. She and Phillips initially
developed the microbial mat to feed fish being farmed commercially
in the Dominican Republic and stumbled on its cleaning properties
accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Niell, 41, has been a geologist for most of his adult
life, he hasn't always worked in the environmental arena. He
searched for coal and offshore marine minerals before coming to
Athens with his wife, Dorothy O'Niell, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he was thinking of leaving the Marine Minerals
Technology Center at the University of Mississippi, where he had
worked for six years as a geologist. He was on a prospecting
expedition off the Oregon coast when a flotilla of urchin
fisherman, coupled with the appearance of Greenpeace's Rainbow
Warrior, convinced him to change directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenpeace had put out some information about our project that
wasn't true, and these fishermen were all surrounding our boat, and
screaming,'' said O'Niell, a Louisiana native. ``We were on CNN _ a
woman from Greenpeace chained herself to our boat. I started
thinking, 'man, this isn't good, I should find a new field.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With a B.S. in geology from Nicholls State University in
Thibodaux, La., and a master's from Ole Miss, he wanted to move
into hydrogeology. While at Ole Miss, he had met Noakes, who
encouraged him to come to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McCarthy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
