<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make your own putty for perfect match
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the elevator going up to the newsroom the other day, a friend
asked me what kind of wood putty on the market would take a stain
so he could match it to the wood he was filling.
</P>
<P>
   It took me a while to come up with the answer, partially because
I'm old and partially because I was stuffed with lunch. I thought
and thought about wood putty, and finally realized I've never used
any.
</P>
<P>
   What you do, I finally told him, is make your own. It's easy
enough. Save your sanding dust, or, if you haven't saved any, make
some using a scrap piece of wood. Get a small can of good shellac
and cut it at least 50-50 with denatured alcohol. Put a little pile
of sanding dust on a piece of cardboard or a scrap of wood and,
using a little stick or something similar, transfer a few drops of
the cut shellac to the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Don't use too much; you want a paste-like consistency after it's
thoroughly mixed. And there's your wood putty, a perfect match for
the piece you're working on. The stuff will dry very quickly, so
don't mix up more than you can use in a couple of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A thread on the Internet brings to mind the subject of crosscut
sleds for the table saw, which I don't think we've discussed.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think there's a woodworking magazine out there that has
not, by now, published a couple of articles on how to make one of
these sleds. They are, as far as I'm concerned, an essential jig
for the table saw.
</P>
<P>
   If you doubt this, take a plank of oak, or whatever you have
that's perhaps six feet long, eight-quarters thick and perhaps
eight inches wide. Dump this on the table, put your mitre gauge in
place and set up to cut a foot off of one end of the plank.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think there's a standard-issue miter gauge made that
will hold a piece of wood this big square to the blade. It will
inevitably flex, and I don't care how long a backstop you've
attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   The sled, if built right, will give you a square crosscut every
time because it is a sliding table; the workpiece is carried
through the blade, not shoved along the surface of the table.
</P>
<P>
   The fellow who started this thread made himself a sled but
discovers that he still isn't getting a square cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distance from the back left edge to the blade kerf is not
the same as the front left edge to the kerf. Is my tablesaw off?
Or, is my sled not squared up correctly?''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to do here is to see if the blade is square to
the miter gauge slot. Get your miter gauge and verify with a
known-accurate square that the gauge is set at a true 90 degrees.
Put it in the slot, put long side of the square against the gauge
and set the short end of the square so that it just touches a tooth
on the forward edge of the blade.
</P>
<P>
   Mark the tooth with a piece of chalk or a crayon. Now rotate the
blade until the tooth is at the back. Keeping the square exactly in
position - use a gentle clamp if needed _ bring the gauge up to the
tooth in its new position. If it still just kisses the tooth, then
the table is square to the blade. If it doesn't, then the table is
misaligned.
</P>
<P>
   This is generally cured by loosening the table bolts and
oontzing it around until this test proves it's square.
</P>
<P>
   You don't know what oontzing is? Well, that's a whole other
field. If you can't guess, go ask a sailor.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
