</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTORS-SIDEBAR01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DIRECTORS: The always interesting, the up-and-coming
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar to GREATEST-DIRECTORS.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The audacious, the hyper-cerebral, the willfully perverse. The
challenging, provocative, offbeat and disturbing. The singular, the
recalcitrant, the idiosyncratic. These are the stubborn visionaries
and sometime-mavericks who scorn the rules. Their movies may be
erratic, occasionally awful, but they're rarely boring. Often
they're sublime. Listed in alphabetical order, these directors have
kept pictures exciting, and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Aldrich (``Kiss Me Deadly,'' ``Whatever Happened to Baby
Jane?'')
</P>
<P>
   Jane Campion (``Sweetie,'' ``The Piano'')
</P>
<P>
   John Cassavetes (``Faces,'' ``A Woman Under the Influence'')
</P>
<P>
   Joel Coen (``Raising Arizona,'' ``Fargo'')
</P>
<P>
   David Cronenberg (``Dead Ringers,'' ``Crash'')
</P>
<P>
   Atom Egoyan (``Exotica,'' ``The Sweet Hereafter'')
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fosse (``Cabaret,'' ``All That Jazz'')
</P>
<P>
   Sam Fuller (``Naked Kiss,'' ``The Big Red One'')
</P>
<P>
   Peter Greenaway (``The Cook, the Thief, His Wife and Her
Lover,'' ``Pillow Book'')
</P>
<P>
   Hal Hartley (``The Unbelievable Truth,'' ``Henry Fool'')
</P>
<P>
   Monte Hellman (``The Shooting,'' ``Two-Lane Blacktop'')
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jarmusch (``Down By Law,'' ``Stranger Than Paradise'')
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee (``Do the Right Thing,'' ``Malcolm X'')
</P>
<P>
   David Lynch (``Blue Velvet,'' ``Lost Highway'')
</P>
<P>
   Ida Lupino (``Hard, Fast and Beautiful,'' ``The Hitch-Hiker'')
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Malick (``Badlands,'' ``The Thin Red Line'')
</P>
<P>
   Roman Polanski (``Knife in the Water,'' ``Chinatown'')
</P>
<P>
   Michael Powell (``The Red Shoes,'' ``Peeping Tom'')
</P>
<P>
   Ken Russell (``Women in Love,'' ``Lisztomania'')
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone (``Platoon,'' ``JFK'')
</P>
<P>
   John Waters (``Pink Flamingos,'' ``Hairspray'')
</P>
<P>
   The foreign pantheon
</P>
<P>
   The foreign-language masters who shook the form, from thematic
pioneers (Bunuel, Bergman, Antonioni) and formal innovators
(Eisenstein's montage, Godard's deconstructionism), to humanistic
poets (Ray, Truffaut, Fellini). For the sake of tidiness, we kept
the list at 10 directors, to the rueful exclusion of F.W. Murnau,
Fritz Lang, Jean Renoir, Robert Bresson, Yasujiro Ozu, Rainer
Werner Fassbinder, Werner Herzog and Krzysztof Kieslowski, to name
a few. We tried to stick to the monumental and the essential
(presented in alphabetical order), artists whose incandescence cast
a wide net, all the way to Hollywood. Woody Allen, Francis Ford
Coppola and Martin Scorsese are a few Americans inextricably
touched by these global greats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michelangelo Antonioni (``L'Avventura,'' ``Blow-Up'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Ingmar Bergman (``Wild Strawberries,'' ``Persona'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Luis Bunuel (``The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie,''
``Belle du Jour'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Sergei Eisenstein (``Battleship Potemkin,'' ``Alexander
Nevsky'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Federico Fellini (``La Dolce Vita,'' ``8 1/2'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Jean-Luc Godard (``Breathless,'' ``Contempt'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Akira Kurosawa (``Rashomon,'' ``Seven Samurai'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Satyajit Ray (``The Apu Trilogy'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Francois Truffaut (``The 400 Blows,'' ``Jules and Jim'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Wim Wenders (``Kings of the Road,'' ``Wings of Desire'')
</P>
<P>
   Seven for the new century
</P>
<P>
   The young filmmakers who will be doing important work for years
to come (hence the easy exclusion of Kevin Smith). Their small
bodies of work hint at bottomless talent that will expand and
mature as they exit their 20s and 30s. They're the real thing,
congenitally gifted visionaries with startling things to say and
the cinematic prowess with which to say them. They defy Hollywood
rules with a moxie, power and inventive zest not seen since the
greats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Thomas Anderson (``Boogie Nights,'' ``Magnolia'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Wes Anderson (``Bottle Rocket,'' ``Rushmore'')
</P>
<P>
   _ David Fincher (``Seven,'' ``Fight Club'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Alexander Payne (``Citizen Ruth,'' ``Election'')
</P>
<P>
   _ David O. Russell (``Flirting With Disaster,'' ``Three Kings'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Soderbergh (``sex, lies and videotape,'' ``The Limey'')
</P>
<P>
   _ Quentin Tarantino (``Reservoir Dogs,'' ``Pulp Fiction'')
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
