<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3440 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-GREATEST-DIRECTORS01-     12-31 2752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREATEST-DIRECTORS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    That's a wrap: The greatest 25 directors
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nowadays, when young directors are feted like
rock stars and people know exactly what ``A Film by Steven
Spielberg'' and ``An Oliver Stone Film'' means, the director's task
is more and more prone to proper scrutiny _ and respect.
</P>
<P>
   A savvy portion of the moviegoing masses is drawn to a movie
based on who was perched behind the camera calling the shots.
Quentin Tarantino's name guarantees edgy pop violence, Hitchcock's
epitomizes perverse suspense, John Waters' a carnival of crude.
</P>
<P>
   The more you can identify a director with a visual stamp and
thematic consistency, the more you're probably dealing with a
filmmaker with vision, an artist, an auteur. It's the hacks (Chris
Columbus, anyone?) who bore us numb.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a great director? A vast, consistently strong body of
work and a few masterpieces. Innovations in style and technique. A
steady vision. Saying something fresh and lasting in groundbreaking
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   To wrap the century in which movies grew up, we picked the
greatest 25 Hollywood directors ever to shape, enrich and elevate
the youngish medium.
</P>
<P>
   Not from cultural arrogance did we restrict the list to American
directors. Though France has been equally key in cultivating the
form and India has a bigger film industry, Hollywood makes the
movies the whole world sees.
</P>
<P>
   The selection team included me, Movies editor Jody Seaborn and
American-Statesman contributing film critic Alison Macor. We spent
much time thrashing out who would go where. We had brief disputes.
Alison, for example, wanted Hitchcock at the top. I thought
Spielberg should be higher. And during the writing of the list, as
the dust of debate settled, David Lean and William Wyler were
knocked down a few pegs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite active quibbles, we're comfortable with our conclusions.
These, we think, are the giants, the Shakespeares and Joyces of
celluloid, the guys (yes, at this point in film history they all
are men, and all are white) who breathed life into what fast became
the century's most vital and popular art form.
</P>
<P>
   1. John Ford
</P>
<P>
   The apotheosis of classical American film: pictorial grandeur;
vivid characters that blur into archetypes; sentimental notions of
land, family and community; supple, personal storytelling; and a
formal modesty that neatly suited his old-fangled values. If Ford
wasn't necessarily the greatest at all of these virtues _ Spielberg
has outdone him in sap-glazed nostalgia, Hitchcock and Welles had
keener eyes, Hawks was smarter _ he married them into potent
wholes. From the silent era on, he made more than 60 films, not all
of them the signature Westerns that mythologized John Wayne and
Monument Valley. Indeed, he won a record four Oscars for
non-Westerns, including ``The Grapes of Wrath'' and ``How Green Was
My Valley.'' It's easy to knock Ford for artistic faults that
fester with time. Though some make your teeth hurt with bathos and
bluster, his films are exemplary entertainments by an unadorned
master.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Stagecoach'' (1939), ``The Searchers'' (1956).
</P>
<P>
   2. Alfred Hitchcock
</P>
<P>
   With flash and devilish irony, Hitchcock demonstrated perhaps
the deepest understanding of the medium. It was for him an urgently
visual, not literary form. This bedrock ethos was his springboard
into amazing technical exuberance; he constantly exercised the
form. His utterly cinematic eye and obsession with our shadow side
conspired to forge some of film's most convincing and ecstatically
watchable thrillers. His influence incalculable, Hitch was film's
first pop genius.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Strangers on a Train'' (1951), ``Rear Window''
(1954).
</P>
<P>
   3. Orson Welles
</P>
<P>
   Some find Welles' movies chilly and stilted, emotionally static,
locked in self-conscious style. True, Welles' cerebral frost coated
much of his work. But those brains, hitched to a highly evolved
dramatic instinct and a thirst for revolution, led to some of the
greatest innovations in the young medium. ``Citizen Kane,'' which
he directed in 1941 at age 25, is a textbook of revelations, from
the vertiginous narrative structure and Gregg Toland's deep-focus
photography to Welles' haunting portrayal of a man much like
himself, a volatile blend of brains and bombast. Welles liberated
filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Citizen Kane'' (1941), ``Touch of Evil'' (1958).
</P>
<P>
   4. Howard Hawks
</P>
<P>
   A consummate American director whose unassuming style belied the
cool artistic mastery of his genre-jumping oeuvre. Using the camera
to tease out just enough visual information for a scene, Hawks put
the stamp of thematic persistence on every movie he made: manly
codes of honor, female empowerment, heroism in the line of duty and
the fizzy sparks between the sexes. His almost invisible touch had
a Midas effect with screwball comedies (``Bringing Up Baby''),
Westerns (``Red River''), noir (``The Big Sleep'') and musicals
(``Gentlemen Prefer Blondes''). He made many of the most enjoyable
films in Hollywood history.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``His Girl Friday'' (1940), ``To Have and Have Not''
(1944).
</P>
<P>
   5. Martin Scorsese
</P>
<P>
   The heedless passion of an artist sluices through Scorsese's
cinematic stunners, some of the most forceful movies in a
generation. He gets you with tough thematic integrity conveyed with
a firestorm of dazzling craft. The one-two combo of spiritual
fervor and visceral wallop is his trademark, and, despite some
missteps, he remains at once our most formidable sensualist and
moralist.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Taxi Driver'' (1976), ``Raging Bull'' (1980).
</P>
<P>
   6. Billy Wilder
</P>
<P>
   As a director and writer (with writing partner Charles
Brackett), Wilder accrued a staggeringly consistent corpus that was
tough and acrid yet still regaled the masses (and the Academy). Far
too ironic to be the hidebound cynic he's so often accused of
being, the Viennese import was a worldly commentator on our darker
foibles. He did it just as deftly in melodrama (``The Lost
Weekend'') as in rip-roaring comedy (``The Apartment'').
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Sunset Boulevard'' (1950), ``Some Like It Hot''
(1959).
</P>
<P>
   7. Elia Kazan
</P>
<P>
   An illustrious theater rat (and, to casualties of McCarthyism, a
definitive rat), Kazan was as powerful a dramatist in Hollywood as
he was on Broadway. A long string of forceful dramas in the '40s
and '50s that entertained as they rattled postwar complacency
cements his station in the canon. And no other director wrested so
many revelatory performances from his actors, including a young
Marlon Brando, Vivien Leigh, James Dean, Karl Malden, Andy Griffith
and Warren Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``On the Waterfront'' (1954), ``East of Eden''
(1955).
</P>
<P>
   8. George Cukor
</P>
<P>
   Cukor capitalized on his facility with ``women's pictures'' to
craft a bundle of sparkling masterworks (such as, aptly, ``The
Women''). A product of the theater, he worked beautifully within
the Hollywood studio system, zigzagging bubbly comedy (``Dinner at
Eight'') and melodrama (``Camille'') with refined grace and
burnished skill. In picture after picture, he made his starlets
shine: Jean Harlow, Greta Garbo, Katharine Hepburn, Judy Garland,
Ingrid Bergman and, had he not been canned from ``Gone With the
Wind,'' Vivien Leigh.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``The Philadelphia Story'' (1940), ``A Star Is
Born'' (1954).
</P>
<P>
   9. D.W. Griffith
</P>
<P>
   If Welles was cinema's Picasso, Griffith was its Da Vinci. From
1908 to 1925, his filmic innovations _ multiple camera angles,
close-ups, crosscutting, parallel action, less theatrical acting _
fashioned a lasting visual vocabulary that shaped movies into an
art form. Griffith's Neanderthal notions of race (on repugnant
display in ``The Birth of a Nation'' and ``Broken Blossoms'')
tarnish his halo.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Birth of a Nation'' (1915), ``Intolerance''
(1916).
</P>
<P>
   10. Stanley Kubrick
</P>
<P>
   With cold surgical precision, the cryptic Kubrick invoked
far-out worlds where humans were diminished by the menacing shadow
of technology and undermined by their own tragic intentions. His
grimly comic films were driven by a monastic intellectual rigor,
and the enigmatic results could confound audiences. His was a
demanding genius.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Dr. Strangelove'' (1964), ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' (1968).
</P>
<P>
   11. Frank Capra
</P>
<P>
   His streamlined odes to the common man resonate even louder
today, when movies strain to uplift audiences by drowning them in
syrup. Capra was a populist and classical craftsman, who, by
filtering his stories through a hope-filled view tinged with dark
truths, made eminently satisfying art.
</P>
<P>
   Don't Miss: ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington'' (1939), ``It's a
Wonderful Life'' (1946).
</P>
<P>
   12. Robert Altman
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's bumptious party-crasher brought an ensemble of
yakking friends to the fold and ousted staid storytelling forms
with contained chaos. With what-the-hell gusto _ the crazy
mise-en-scene, the overlapping gab, loose-limbed structure _ Altman
brought documentary naturalism to his pungent satires and pulled
the carpet from under the war, Western and noir genres (``MASH,''
``McCabe and Mrs. Miller,'' ``The Long Goodbye'').
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``MASH'' (1970), ``Nashville'' (1975).
</P>
<P>
   13. Steven Spielberg
</P>
<P>
   The '70s wunderkind seemed born with full-blown storytelling
chops and technical know-how. Now a billion-dollar mogul,
Spielberg's sensibilities are stuck in pre-adolescence. His best
films emit the intoxicating mists of boyish wonder. They make kids
out of all of us and rank with the century's best entertainment.
Lately Spielberg's strained to make grown-up films (``Amistad,''
``Saving Private Ryan''), but they're saddled by the boy's naivete
and a chronic incapacity for analytical thought. In them, he's
reduced to a superlative technician.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Jaws'' (1975), ``E.T.: The Extraterrestrial''
(1982).
</P>
<P>
   14. Ernst Lubitsch
</P>
<P>
   The German transplant suffused his romantic comedies with
European class and cosmopolitan wit, a Noel Coward-ish flavor
dubbed the ``Lubitsch Touch.'' Sophistication, sly sexuality and
subtle expressiveness were the hallmarks of Lubitsch's incisive
probes into love and manners. Gracefully funny, he even made Garbo
bust out in laughter. Every romantic comedy since is indebted to
the maestro.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Ninotchka'' (1939), ``The Shop Around the Corner''
(1940).
</P>
<P>
   15. Woody Allen
</P>
<P>
   Owing as much to brooding Swede Ingmar Bergman as to Charlie
Chaplin and Bob Hope, writer-director Allen is a master melder of
uproarious comedy and romantic distress, sprinkled with existential
reverie. Few strike all the keys _ funny bone, heart and head _
with such precision. And no one charts the aggrieved heart with
such bittersweet candor. His deeply personal films (30-plus) form
an unbroken chronicle of obsession, angst and emotional discord.
Despite a spate of slapdash work in the past decade, he remains
America's most dogged auteur.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Annie Hall'' (1977), ``Manhattan'' (1979).
</P>
<P>
   16. John Huston
</P>
<P>
   The manly-man as artist, a la Hemingway, Huston channeled his
high-wire virility into a resonant array of pulp and art. Full of
swagger, spit and booze, it's no wonder the writer-director
excelled at gangster flicks and adventure epics. He worked with the
best _ Humphrey Bogart, Katharine Hepburn, Edward G. Robinson, Sean
Connery _ rarely eliciting a bum performance.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``The Maltese Falcon'' (1941), ``The Treasure of the
Sierra Madre'' (1948).
</P>
<P>
   17. Francis Ford Coppola
</P>
<P>
   His reckless lack of discipline _ some call it genius _ may
finally unravel this giant of the Hollywood New Wave, but it can't
sabotage the masterpieces he wrought in the 1970s: ``The
Godfather'' (1972), ``The Godfather, Part II'' (1974), ``The
Conversation'' (1974) and ``Apocalypse Now'' (1979). These are
prickly interrogations of the American experience, whose collective
importance _ and extreme entertainment zing _ echoes on. Coppola's
been adrift this decade, excreting tripe like ``Bram Stoker's
Dracula'' and ``Jack.'' We worry.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: See above '70s titles.
</P>
<P>
   18. Vincente Minnelli
</P>
<P>
   Renowned for his quintessential musicals (from ``Meet Me in St.
Louis'' to ``Gigi''), Minnelli actually made more nonmusicals.
Topically restless, he was comfortable and supremely efficient in
comedy (``Father of the Bride''), sweeping drama (``Lust for
Life'') and heart-curdling romance (``The Clock''). His dreamily
roving camera was emblematic of a ranging mind.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``An American in Paris'' (1951), ``The Bad and the
Beautiful'' (1953).
</P>
<P>
   19. Preston Sturges
</P>
<P>
   The first U.S. filmmaker to earn the ``Written and directed by''
credit, Sturges had tight reign on his biting comedic vision _ a
quirky, sophisticated stance that engendered a batch of the 1940s'
funniest comedies. An American born of privilege and raised in
Europe, Sturges satirized the idle rich, Hollywood, heroes and
social mores in all their absurdities. He had visual flair, too;
check out, among other tricks, the surreal title sequence in ``The
Palm Beach Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``The Lady Eve'' (1941), ``Sullivan's Travels''
(1941).
</P>
<P>
   20. William Wyler
</P>
<P>
   Wyler was a towering craftsman and quiet stylist who worked
prolifically within the studio system. No wild-eyed visionary
bursting with grand pronouncements, Wyler nevertheless produced a
rock-solid body of tonic entertainment: ``Wuthering Heights,''
``Mrs. Miniver,'' ``The Best Years of Our Lives,'' ``Roman
Holiday,'' ``Ben-Hur.'' If the three-time Oscar winner had a fabled
foible, it was that he was a grinding perfectionist whose nickname
was ``90-take Wyler.'' The meticulous care showed.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``The Letter'' (1940), ``Detective Story'' (1951),
any of the above.
</P>
<P>
   21. Nicholas Ray
</P>
<P>
   Ray's odes to misunderstood outsiders throb with the angry pain
of alienation. Himself a Hollywood misfit, Ray's patchy track
record boasted a handful of morose masterworks, in which tortured
loners seek grim salvation: ``They Live By Night,'' ``In a Lonely
Place,'' ``The Lusty Men'' and, of course, ``Rebel Without a
Cause.'' Ray was belatedly exalted by the French auteurists, who
lionized his romantic nihilism. They also thought he made some
pretty good pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: The above titles, ``Johnny Guitar'' (1954).
</P>
<P>
   22. Buster Keaton
</P>
<P>
   He turned the pratfall into a dust-spraying thud of genius. The
silent-comedy virtuoso bounced about the confines of the screen-box
like a rubber ball, always trying to smash out of film's imposed
boundaries. Keaton succeeded, obliterating the fourthwall. Always
the hapless hero, Keaton's unflappable face played sharp
counterpoint to his body's kineticism, achieving a stoic lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Sherlock Jr.'' (1924), ``The General'' (1927).
</P>
<P>
   23. David Lean
</P>
<P>
   He's been criticized for doting on pretty pictures and shirking
substance, but Lean's best pictures _ ``Brief Encounter,'' ``The
Bridge on the River Kwai'' _ dilute the charges. Sure, he's a
virtuoso technician. But he had a keen eye that bore into the
psychological essence of a scene. He knew what to do with all those
pretty pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``Oliver Twist'' (1951), ``The Bridge on the River
Kwai'' (1957).
</P>
<P>
   24. Sam Peckinpah
</P>
<P>
   A hard-boozing maverick to the bitter end, ``Bloody Sam''
upended the Western, stripping it of gauzy romanticism and dunking
it in blood. With blunt savagery, he forever changed the way we see
screen violence and imposed a troubling moral ambiguity on the
action genre that's still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``The Wild Bunch'' (1969), ``Straw Dogs'' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   25. Charlie Chaplin
</P>
<P>
   It's fashionable to knock Chaplin the director, especially in
light of his clunky late work, testaments to a bitter refusal to
embrace film's rapid technological progress (including, in some
cases, the pesky development of sound). Yet the dour clown
introduced a new emotional idom in his bittersweet comedies. Pathos
and laughs meshed, sometimes with a maudlin clang, amid flurries of
comic invention. The iconic power of Chaplin's Little Tramp hasn't
dimmed a whit.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss: ``The Kid'' (1921), ``City Lights'' (1931).
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: cgarcia(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
