<HEADER>
A3442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GEEK01-COX     12-31 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GEEK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What `Man on the Moon' needs: Aliens
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you were wondering, ``Man on the Moon'' is not, as the
title implies, a lunar action thriller with morphing men on the
moon trying to vaporize brave astronauts in the form of Keanu
Reeves and Bruce Willis. Instead, it is a mildly funny film about
the comedian/artiste/freak Andy Kaufman as played by Jim ``Can I
have the Oscar for this one?'' Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   This movie is effectless _ unless you count the flying Santa
sleigh and the singing puppet. There is a small attempt at makeup
effects when Kaufman finds a cancer cyst on his back, but it's
hardly applaudable (and kind of a bummer). And Courtney ``Nose
Job'' Love as Kaufman's love interest is _ and, believe me, this is
hard to say _ worse than Denise Richards in ``The World is Not
Enough.'' Unlike Richards, Love didn't have the benefit of things
blowing up behind her to take our minds off her horrible acting. In
fact, Love's wooden acting was so bad that it, in itself, was a
special effect begging the question: Beneath the rhinoplastered
exterior is Courtney Love real or an android?
</P>
<P>
   I know this was supposed to be biographical and no one asked me,
but I have a couple of suggestions that would have made this movie
better. For one, you could have improved ``Man on the Moon''
immensely by making Jim Carrey an alien. Not some tripped-out,
big-toothed Alien alien, but a friendly, funny alien capable of
computer-generated gags like turning himself into a rocket, a car
or a vending machine. Next, I would have given Carrey a
nemesis/love interest. Maybe it could be a big reptile that shoots
lasers out of his eyes. In keeping with the comedic attempts made
by the film, I would name him Lenny the Lizard and have his lasers
not work all the time (sometimes his eyes only produce flowers or
chocolate milk, instead of total destruction). This way, Andy
Kaufman's story could be funny, poignant and touching; a real
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   If the filmmaker had just followed my advice, it would have
given ``Man on the Moon'' a better chance at more heralded reels
and, most importantly, kept me awake.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Kallenberg writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
