<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV02     12-31 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR SHOULDN'T GIVE UP ON BOND HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 2, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have invested in Vanguard's Index 500 fund through a
dollar-cost-averaging program and am pleased to see its value
continue to rise after buying on the dips. Unfortunately, over
three years ago I also decided to invest some traditional IRA
savings in the Vanguard Total Bond Market Index fund. I bought over
800 shares at $9.89 per share in 1996. Today, the same shares are
valued at $9.67 per share. Although I've received income dividends
monthly that have increased my account to more than 1,000 shares,
the total value of the account is now worth approximately what I
paid back in 96. Not a good way to save for retirement! Splitting
assets between stocks and bonds has not proven a good idea, based
on the market's performance over the past few years. So much for a
conservative outlook and following advisers' suggestions to split
retirement savings between proven stock and bond index funds from a
reputable company such as Vanguard. Since I do not intend to
withdraw any of these IRA funds for more than 10 years, should I
hold on to my Vanguard Total Bond Market Index position, or reduce
my losses and switch to the proven Index 500?
</P>
<P>
   S.A., Chula Vista, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you should reexamine your IRA statements on the Total
Bond Market holding, since it is statistically impossible for your
account to have remained stagnant from 1996 to now, unless you
withdrew some funds. Certainly it has come nowhere near the
performance of Index 500, but its three-year record shows average
annual total returns of 5.49 percent. Its total returns in 1996
were 3.6 percent, followed by 9.4 percent in 1997, 8.6 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Like most bond funds, it is in the red this year, but it shows a
year-to-date loss of only .83 percent as this is written.
</P>
<P>
   Second, its unfair to disregard the idea of diversification
among asset classes such as stocks and bonds based on a three- or
four-year period which represents an almost unprecedented bull
market on the stock side. Over many years you will discover that
the thinking that's behind recommendations of allocating a
portfolio among stocks and bonds is solid: in some markets the
bonds will outperform the stocks, and in many markets the bonds
will deliver steady, if unspectacular, returns, such as during the
years from 1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Only occasionally will the bond holdings go into the red, such
as this year, and when they do, they do not tend to go very far
into the red. Moreover, if the historical record is any indicator,
if bond funds have a bad year or two, they tend to recoup the lost
ground fairly quickly; look at the 1994 loss of 2.66 percent for
this fund, followed by its 18.18 percent recovery in 1995. Perhaps
you were looking at that 18.18 percent return when you first bought
into the fund. If so, you had unrealistic expectations. A much
better measure to set your expectations upon is a bond funds
10-year average annual return.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is currently 7.67 percent for this fund.
</P>
<P>
   So I recommend you stick with the strategy you embarked upon.
</P>
<P>
   Tempering your Index 500 position with the Total Bond Market
holdings reduces risk, and should give your portfolio some measure
of resilience when the stock market stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, what you describe as a dollar-cost-averaging program
with your Index 500 holdings sounds more like market timing to me.
A dollar cost investor sets a schedule for additions to his or her
portfolio, with a set amount of new money going into the account at
a specified date, whether it be monthly, quarterly, or even over a
longer period. These investments are made regardless of the state
of the market. If you are buying on the dips you are trying to time
the market, betting that you can foresee what is the bottom of a
dip.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long run, studies have shown, dollar-cost-averaging
tends to work better, since if a market timing investor only misses
the targets slightly, the effect is to significantly reduce
returns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have $167,000 invested in mutual funds, a $6,000 IRA,
$30,000 in bank savings, and $20,000 in CDs. The mutual funds
consist of $74,000 in Putnam Fund for Growth and Income, $20,000 in
Putnam Diversified Income, $10,000 in Putnam Voyager, $17,000 in
Fidelity Advisor Growth Opportunity (Class T), $30,000 in MFS Total
Return, $12,000 in MFS Emerging Growth, and $4,000 in Colonial
High-Yield Securities. I add $500 a month to the Putnam Growth and
Income account and $200 a month to MFS Total Return fund. I am 67,
retired, widowed, and have no debt. I own my home and have income
of $60,000 from my pension and investments. Is my distribution
correct?
</P>
<P>
   P.N., Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I estimate that you are holding about 55 percent of your
portfolio in stocks, with that number likely to steadily (if
slowly) advance based on your pattern of reinvestments. Many
investors of your age would consider that a high level, but it's
not necessarily high for you.
</P>
<P>
   After all, since you are able to save 14 percent of your income
in retirement, its clear that you are sufficiently well heeled that
you can afford a higher stock-market position than many others can.
</P>
<P>
   Although your diversification could be better, I dont suggest
you sell any of your current positions, but rather that you look to
some new funds as the vehicles for the $500 a month now going into
the dominant position in Putnam Fund for Growth and Income.
</P>
<P>
   Three solid prospects I suggest are Putnam International Growth
and Income, Putnam Health Sciences, and Putnam Vista. Each of these
would give you some participation in market segments you are
currently ignoring -- international markets, health care, and
mid-cap growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am single, 44 years old, and earn $90,000 per year. I
contribute the $10,500 maximum a year to my 403(b) plan. I own my
own home with about $30,000 equity in it. I expect Social Security
of $14,900 a year at age 62, and a company pension of $20,500 at
age 65. My assets consist of $343,238, mostly in tax-deferred
accounts and mostly invested in stock funds. My question is, how
long must I continue working at my current earnings level before I
can retire? My expenses in retirement will be in the area of
$40,000 to $45,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   M.M., Tyngsborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems to me that you'd be in a fairly comfortable
situation if you set a retirement target in 10 years. Let's begin
with what you'll need in retirement. If we take the midpoint in
your estimated range -- $42,500 -- and adjust it for a presumed 3.5
percent average annual inflation rate, you will need $59,950 a year
to buy what $42,500 now buys.
</P>
<P>
   If we presume an 8 percent average growth rate from your taxable
investments, which are the more conservative, and a 10 percent
average rate from the tax-favored accounts, you would have $324,708
and $781,654 respectively on the two sides of the portfolio, or a
total of $1,106,352. The taxable accounts would be sufficient to
provide your income stream until age 59 1/2 when the tax-favored
accounts become available. By that time, presuming you moved to a
more conservative portfolio in the tax-favored accounts and
achieved only 8 percent growth there, those accounts would be worth
$1,194,274.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively small amount left over from your taxable accounts
at that stage -- $65,684 -- would bring your total savings at age
65 1/2 to $1,259,958. Especially given your anticipated Social
Security and pension incomes coming up within the next six years,
that would be more than sufficient to maintain the same buying
power after adjusting for inflation, as well as to generate
portfolio growth to protect you against inflation in the later
years of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Could you retire earlier? Probably yes, but the earlier you
retire the more you will need to have in excess of the money that
is used to generate your income stream, in order to deal with the
inflation in the many years you can anticipate spending in
retirement. So you could probably retire in eight years, but in my
opinion you would be cutting it too close.
</P>
<P>
   Those last two years would give you a considerable margin of
comfort, and that's where I would set the target.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
