<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATOR-ADVANCE01-C     12-31 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATOR-ADVANCE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With Hurricanes ahead, Tech's Hamilton isn't looking back
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla _ On the eve of a new year, and the end of his
college football career, the most celebrated Georgia Tech player in
generations would not allow himself to look back.
</P>
<P>
   Reflections would have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' Joe Hamilton said Friday. ``I'm solely thinking
about (playing) Miami and the Gator Bowl tomorrow. Any time you
play your last game, you want to go out a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter the outcome of No. 17 Georgia Tech's match against No.
23 Miami (8-4) at Alltell Stadium, the fact that Joe Hamilton is a
winner has been firmly established.
</P>
<P>
   In the four seasons before Hamilton took over at quarterback,
the Yellow Jackets were a measly 17-27, and far removed from
national acclaim. Since then, Tech has gone 30-16, has remained in
the Top 25 in the past 26 polls, rising as high as No. 9 at the end
of last season when the Jackets beat Notre Dame here to finish
10-2.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Hamilton has set 13 school records, earned
consensus All-America status and was runner-up in the Heisman
Trophy voting. Yet, when asked this week what the highlight of his
career has been, Hamilton did glimpse back and a broad smile spread
across his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, it has to be beating the Georgia Bulldogs two
years in a row,'' he said, ``because that means more to the
program, and Tech fans, than any individual honors.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hamilton said, it's time to add another notch.
</P>
<P>
   But knocking off the favored Hurricanes will be no small feat.
Miami presents Tech with its biggest challenge since the second
week of the season, when the Jackets pushed No. 1-ranked Florida
State on the road but fell 41-35.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes are No. 11 in the nation in pass efficiency
defense, 12th in scoring defense (17.3 ppg.) and 16th in total
defense (301.7 ypg.).
</P>
<P>
   And that's just on one side of the ball. Miami is on the hottest
scoring streak in its history, pounding the past three foes 155-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had a great, great deal of respect for Butch
Davis'', Tech coach George O'Leary said. ``Watching film, the one
thing that really shows up is the toughness their team plays with.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a great job with Miami's program, taking it from
where it was to where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   When Davis was named 'Canes coach five years ago, the program _
which has won four national championships _ was saddled with
probation and hampered by NCAA-imposed recruiting sanctions. Now,
Miami is back on the New Year's Day stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past five years have been the toughest five years, but the
best,'' senior guard Richard Mercier said. ``What doesn't kill you
will make you stronger, and we survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've weathered the biggest storm any team could have.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's another one brewing, as Tech leads the nation in
offense, and hasn't really been stopped all season. There is no way
the Hurricanes will underestimate the Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically we have one mutual foe each of us don't like
much,'' Davis said, alluding to an FSU team which beat the 'Canes
31-21. ``Watching that film, it didn't take long to open our
players' eyes about how good Georgia Tech is.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
