<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ORANGE-ADVANCE01-     12-31 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ORANGE-ADVANCE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama seeks bowl win to cap off turnaround season
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Mike DuBose went to bed early Friday night, which is not
to say he went to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't stayed up till midnight on New Year's Eve in at
least 15 years,'' the Alabama coach said the day before. ``I'll
probably start out the night thinking I'll stay up that late,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have tried a little harder, just to make it last, as a
season like this one doesn't come by too often. But having turned
around one of the most catastrophic periods in its football
history, the Crimson Tide's next trick comes tonight, when No. 5
Alabama faces No. 8 Michigan in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Making its 50th bowl appearance but its first at the Orange in
25 years, the Tide (10-2) can tie a big red bod a season
that began in ignominy _ DuBose's extramarital hijinks and a loss
to Louisiana Tech. Now riding a five-game win streak including a
27-point throttling of Florida in the SEC Championship, the Tide
can reach 11 wins for the first time in five years but for the
fourth time in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up short of winning the national championship, which
is always a goal,'' wide receiver Freddie Milions said. ``But
everything else we've gotten, there couldn't be anything better.
This game will be something to dwell on when we start out next
season against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to peak. We feel like we have one more big
game in us and we're going to unleash everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is expected to play without Outland Trophy winner Chris
Samuels (left knee), which makes running tack Shaun Alexander's
final game a little more interesting. Samuels was vital in leading
Alexander to his 15 school rushing records and the SEC player of
the year award.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not really Alexander who turned the season for the
Tide. It was a defense that went from one of the poorest in the
conference at midseason to No. 9 (total defense) in the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense always gets the glory but it doesn't bother us,''
said Tide defensive tackle Cornelius Griffin. ``At Alabama, it all
comes down to team. We got off to a slow start but as time went on,
we got better with reach game.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the first seven games, the Tide yielded an average of 107.7
rushing yards. In its last five games, it has given up just 140 on
the ground. Pass defense improvement has been more dramatic.
Alabama recorded only four interceptions over the first eight games
but has intercepted 12 times in the last four games, including four
against Florida in the SEC title game.
</P>
<P>
   This becomes critical against a Michigan team that has nearly
abandoned the run this season and let a quarterback tandem of Tom
Brady and Drew Henson throw 35 times a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get into that rhythm of playing good teams,'' said
Michigan fullback Aaron Shea, ``and when you get down here and face
a great team like Alabama, it's no shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
