<HEADER>
A3475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX     12-31 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once upon a life . . .
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Not long ago I bought my mother a tape recorder, a
remote controlled microphone and some blank tapes and urged her to
record the stories of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Born-Depression Texas, she now has entered a prosperous
new century and a new millennium. I know she has some good stories.
</P>
<P>
   My father also must have had some good stories. I wish I had
asked him to record his stories. He would have turned me down.
Still, I wish I had asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want you to know my stories,'' he would have said.
That would have been the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   Mother might do it. She's self-conscious about talking into the
tape recorder. But she understands the importance of recording
family history.
</P>
<P>
   She worked for several years with my brother verifying family
records in preparation for her admission to the Daughters of the
American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are the most interesting parts of a family history.
Names and dates of marriages, births and deaths are fairly flat
without the flavoring of stories.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there's a relative on my mother's side of the
family who would be just a name on a page had not a story survived
about how he eloquently argued himself into prison.
</P>
<P>
   The man was a judge during the Civil War. He supported the
South. One day he gave a speech on the courthouse lawn arguing why
it was every man's responsibility to join up to help repel the
northern aggressors.
</P>
<P>
   When the judge paused in his speech to gauge the crowd's
reaction to his argument, a man in the back of the crowd yelled,
``Well, why haven't you joined, judge?''
</P>
<P>
   Caught up in his own argument, my relative said that's exactly
what he was planning to do. He joined up. Within days he was
captured during his first battle. He was marched to a prisoner of
war camp in St. Louis where he had plenty of time to reflect on how
he got there.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the best stories are the ones where someone did
something bad, outrageous, funny or at least unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the stories that people don't want to tell.
</P>
<P>
   I had an aunt on my father's side of the family who reportedly
led a high-flying life in her youth. She married early to an oil
wildcatter. They made and lost fortunes during early years of the
Texas oil boom. She later married a strait-laced Presbyterian elder
and refused to relate any of her tempestuous narratives.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, she wouldn't tell any stories on anyone else in the
family. She went to the grave with a treasure trove of great family
stories.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that many people get more protective of their
reputations the older they get, I changed my tactics with my
mother.
</P>
<P>
   I asked her to record her recollections of where she lived as a
child, what toys she had, what her schools were like and other
similar memories.
</P>
<P>
   These stories, I'm hoping, will prime the pump. If she starts
telling stories about things in her life, then she might move on to
other people, relatives and then to herself.
</P>
<P>
   Of all my relatives, I feel I know my grandfather, Roy Rowland,
the best. He was a life-long newspaper man who liked to tell
stories.
</P>
<P>
   He did not hesitate to tell stories about himself. I know his
pets when he was growing up as one of seven children of a Baptist
preacher. I know about the time his pet pig was served for dinner
during a visit by another preacher. He never got over that.
</P>
<P>
   I know about his first job on a newspaper while he was still in
school in Flatonia, Texas. I know all of his duties on that job and
even feel like I know some of the people he worked with.
</P>
<P>
   Stories bind people together and keep them alive as long as the
stories are told.
</P>
<P>
   I hope my mother records her stories.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1444EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3476 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-ART-75     12-31 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-ART-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A BOLD MOVE, YELTSIN RESIGNS AND HANDS POWER TO PUTIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A chronology graphic is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin shocked his nation and the
world Friday by announcing his resignation six months ahead of
schedule, and handing over power to his favored successor, Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   As the final act of an extraordinary career, Yeltsin, 68, chose
the last day of 1999, and the start of a four-day New Year holiday
in Russia to try to upstage the new millennium and take charge of a
succession battle that will set Russia's course for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   And in his first decree as acting president, Putin granted
Yeltsin broad immunity from prosecution as well as from
interrogation and searches, the Interfax news agency reported. The
decree, which did not name Yeltsin specifically, also provided
benefits including health care, security and a pension for
presidents leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Putin took office Friday at a private Kremlin ceremony, with the
personal blessing of Patriarch Alexei II, leader of the Russian
Orthodox Church. Yeltsin, by his action, seemed determined to put a
lock on Putin's succession to the presidency in an election three
months from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, on the last day of the departing century, I am
resigning,'' Yeltsin told a bewildered nation, in a noon-time
special broadcast filmed against the backdrop of a traditional New
Year's tree. ``I have understood that it was necessary for me to do
this. Russia must enter the new millennium with new politicians,
with new faces, with new smart, strong and energetic people.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's unexpected decision, made on the eve of Russia's
most festive holiday, was seen as a master stroke by a politician
who once again showed that he has no match on Russia's turbulent
political scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very strong move by the president,'' said Vladimir
Ryzhkov, a lower house deputy. ``He did it at the most appropriate
time, when popular support for Putin is at a high. Early elections
will hamper all of the opposition. This will increase Putin's
chance of being elected many times over.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Yeltsin has been in and out of the hospital since 1996,
when he underwent heart surgery following his election to a second
term, his resignation Friday was widely attributed to political,
not health reasons. There was no suggestion, from any quarter, that
Yeltsin was forced out of office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a brilliant decision, extremely precise and profound,
and apart from anything else very brave, apart from its historical
significance,'' said Anatoly Chubais, a top Kremlin adviser and the
architect of Russia's privatization program. ``I think that this
decision was very difficult for Boris Nikolayevich as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a statement issued Friday, praised
Yeltsin's achievements and said, ``The relationship between the
United States and Russia under President Yeltsin has produced
genuine progress for both our people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was looking forward to ``working with Acting
President Putin as the Russian people begin the process of making
the transition from one democratically elected president to
another.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, Yeltsin has dominated the Russian political
stage like an erratic, lumbering bear, emerging from periodic bouts
of poor health and lethargy with surprise moves calculated to
confound his opponents and dazzle his political allies.
</P>
<P>
   A master of drama, and of the political moment, Yeltsin, a
former Communist Party boss in the industrial city of Yekaterinburg
(then Sverdlovsk) in the Ural Mountains, has consistently relied on
his political instincts to get and hold onto power.
</P>
<P>
   But as critics have frequently noted, Yeltsin has proved better
at mastering Russia's often ugly power politics than he has at
governing the country. His legacy is mixed.
</P>
<P>
   After 70 years of Communist rule, Yeltsin managed to defend
Russia's fledgling democracy, most notably by standing up to the
August 1991 coup by Communist hard-liners. But his rule has also
been marked by rising poverty, corruption and a failure to invest
democracy with meaning beyond a freedom that many Russian see as
bordering on chaos.
</P>
<P>
   In a personal aside, which he himself noted was
uncharacteristic, Yeltsin apologized Friday for having failed to
fulfill the hopes of his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to apologize for our unfulfilled dreams,'' he said.
``What we thought was easy has proved painfully difficult. I would
like to apologize for having failed to justify the hopes of the
people who believed that we would be able to make a leap from the
gloomy and stagnant totalitarian past to a bright, prosperous and
civilized future at just one go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself believed in this,'' he went on. ``We haven't managed
to make this leap and I was naive in thinking we would.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago Friday, on another cold wintry New Year's Eve,
Yeltsin entered the Kremlin as Russia's first democratically
elected president, shoving aside his arch-nemesis, Mikhail
Gorbachev, the Soviet president he had supplanted three weeks
before by forcing the dissolution of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   That stunning move, taken in secret with a handful of leaders of
ex-Soviet republics at a hunting lodge in the forests of Belarus,
was to catapult Yeltsin onto the world stage, where he has lobbied,
harangued and bullied Western leaders as they learned to cope with
Russia's new and turbulent democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's blustering, sometimes peculiar political style, has
often led his opponents in Russia to write him off, and count him
out. But each time, he has proved them wrong: in the late 1980s
when he rallied liberal democratic forces after his humiliating
dismissal from the top ranks of the Communist Party by Gorbachev;
in the 1996 elections when he won with a come-from-behind victory
over the Communist leader, Gennadi Zyuganov; in a failed
impeachment drive last May, and now, in a four-month-long campaign
run from the Kremlin designed to put a Yeltsin stamp of approval on
Russia's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Just last summer, Yeltsin's chances of controlling his
succession looked weak. Beset by a wave of international scandals _
including reports that members of his own family had accepted
kickbacks from a Swiss construction firm, the Kremlin was losing
the political initiative to a powerful new political alliance,
which united behind former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and
Moscow Mayor Yuri M. Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   Days after Islamic rebels from the breakaway region of Chechnya
launched an armed invasion of a neighboring Russian region, Yeltsin
seized the moment to name his sixth prime minister and heir
apparent, Putin, 47, a former KGB officer who was then head of
Russia's domestic intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   That move, followed by a full-scale war against the Chechen
rebels, now moving into its fourth month, dramatically altered
Russia's political landscape. In August, Putin was a political
nonentity, with no party, no popular support and the backing of a
deeply distrusted president.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, with his popularity ratings now hovering
around 50 percent, Putin is Russia's latest rising star, the
architect of an uncompromising war seen by many Russians as a
belated, and welcome, attempt to restore the battered authority of
the Russian state.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who came to politics in the mid-1980s through the St.
Petersburg branch of Russia's liberal democratic movement, showed
in parliamentary elections held Dec. 19 that his personal
popularity could be translated into political pull.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly strong showing of two pro-government parties,
both brand-new creations concocted by Kremlin strategists and both
blessed by Putin, broke the eight-year-long stalemate in the
Russian Parliament, dominated until now by a Communist led
anti-Yeltsin opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary elections confirmed the Kremlin's expectations
for Putin, and according to political analysts, provided Yeltsin
with the assurances he needed to let go of power, most political
analysts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin's rise, carefully curried by Kremlin image makers, is
also traced to a shift in the national mood, as voters, tired of
the chaos and corruption associated with Yeltsin's tenure, cast
about for a strong leader, an image that the dour-faced Putin seems
to fit.
</P>
</TEXT>
