<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OUTBACK-ADVANCE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia, Purdue both playing for pride, respect
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The teams are both 7-4. Neither is in the Bowl
Championship Series. Technically, they're playing for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But just try telling that to Georgia and Purdue, who will meet
this morning at 11 a.m. in the Outback Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're playing for pride,'' said Georgia senior
Steven Herndon. ``We slipped there at the end of the season. We
lost three of our last four games. That's not the way we wanted to
end the season, especially the seniors. We want to go out on a
winning note. ... We've got to restore some pride back in the
Georgia Bulldogs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about respect,'' Purdue defensive tackle David Nugent
said. ``We're playing for our school, our university, we're playing
for our families and friends. We're just going to go out and do the
best that we can to represent them.''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear to mean a little more to the Bulldogs. This was
the year Georgia was supposed to close the gap on SEC powers
Tennessee and Florida. This was the year the Bulldogs would
reassert themselves as a national power.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they regressed, losing to their four biggest rivals _
Tennessee, Florida, Auburn and Georgia Tech _ in the same season
for the first time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue was in a similar situation. The Boilermakers were
cruising along nicely before losing three of four games in October
to Michigan, Penn State and Ohio State and falling to Wisconsin on
Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both our teams were close to having really good records this
year,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``Before Coach (Joe) Tiller
came there, most Purdue people would have jumped off a bridge to
have a 7-4 record. Same thing for us, but we've created a situation
where 7-4 is nothing like what everybody wants. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of our teams lost to some good teams, no question. But
that's what we get measured by in our league, what we do against
the best teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Outback Bowl is billing today's game as a battle of two of
the nation's best quarterbacks. Georgia's Quincy Carter and
Purdue's Drew Brees both were trumpeted as Heisman Trophy
candidates at the beginning of the season. While Carter's campaign
never got off the ground, Brees finished third in the Heisman
voting and attended the selection ceremonies in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to go up against a guy like Drew Brees, who is a
great competitor,'' Carter said. ``I've been through this a lot
this season, facing Tee Martin and Romaro Miller and Joe Hamilton.
So it's not unusual for me. I've just got to be sure I don't try to
make it a duel between me and Drew Brees. I just want to go out and
play my style of football and do what I can to help this team
win.''
   Brees, who threw for 3,521 yards and 21 touchdowns this season,
is probably licking his chops to get a shot at Georgia's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs finished last in the SEC in pass defense, giving up
416 yards and 341 yards passing in the ninth and 11th games,
respectively. In between, they held Ole Miss to 114 yards through
the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``With us, it comes and it goes and sometimes it falls apart,''
said junior cornerback Jamie Henderson. ``This game is on us. If we
let them get started early, it could be a repeat of Auburn or
Georgia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   The passing game matchup is why the Boilermakers are 5 1/2-point
favorites. But the SEC traditionally plays well against Big Ten
schools. The SEC was 3-0 versus the Big Ten in bowl games last
year, and Georgia whipped Wisconsin 33-6 here in the Outback Bowl
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But conference rivalries appear to mean little to this year's
participants. With them, it's all about the here and now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of ups and downs this season,'' Georgia
linebacker Boss Bailey said. ``We want to end it on a big up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
