   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GM-PRECEPT (Detroit) _ With hundreds of millions of dollars of
industrial and federal research work behind it, General Motors'
Precept, an experimental model to be introduced in January, is
probably the most expensive single car ever built. It produces
remarkable fuel economy _ almost 80 miles per gallon _ and is
likely to influence what America drives in the future. But the
Precept itself, along with similar experimental vehicles being
designed by Ford Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler, faces huge
obstacles. The three auto makers have all focused on
diesel-electric hybrid cars. Yet federal and state environmental
regulators have just adopted new tailpipe emissions rules that will
make it very difficult after 2003 to sell automobiles with any
diesel engines. Honda and Toyota, meanwhile, have begun mass
production of small cars that combine gasoline engines and electric
motors, leaving Detroit scrambling to catch up. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Looking at a century of stocks. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   JARGON (Undated) _ Management consultants, marketing experts,
lawyers, and especially in recent years, techno-geeks have
cluttered the English language with short-hand terms that make
sense only to insiders, at least until the general public has no
choice but to memorize them and make them part of the vernacular. A
guide for the perplexed. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
