<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV02-B     12-31 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT COMES AFTER `PUSTRIAL?' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 2, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was turning 50 and full of brass when he set out earnestly to
see if it was possible to tell the future. Already he had a pretty
good record as a prognosticator of trends.
</P>
<P>
   A 1960 collection of his essays, ``The End of Ideology: The
Exhaustion of Political Ideas in the Fifties,'' had become a
classic of the Sixties, patiently explicating the Left's
disillusionment with communism. The Public Interest, the quarterly
he had founded in 1965 along with Irving Kristol to supply the
necessary analysis for a post-ideological age, was well on its way
to becoming the most influential American journal of opinion of the
Seventies.
</P>
<P>
   So when Daniel Bell published ``The Coming of Post-Industrial
Society: A Venture in Social Forecasting'' in 1973, it proved to be
an especially provocative framework for thinking about what was
happening to the human race in the late 20th century _ especially
when placed alongside a similar exercise of a few years before,
``The Age of Discontinuity: Guidelines to Our Changing Society,''
by Peter Drucker.
</P>
<P>
   Those who took to heart Daniel Bell's message were well-prepared
for what came next _ some of what came next, anyway. The transition
to post-industrial society would consist of three main themes, he
said: a shift from manufacturing to services; the centrality of new
science-based industries; and the rise of new technical elites amid
the advent of a new principal of stratification.
</P>
<P>
   From this vantage point, wrote Bell, it was possible to discern
deeper ``axial'' transformations of the age: ``a changeover from a
goods-producing to an information or knowledge society''; a change
from ``empiricism or trial-and-error tinkering to theory and the
codification of theoretical knowledge for directing innovation and
the formulation of policy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right, of course _ but there was no ``of course'' about
it at the time.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter-century later, Daniel Bell has written a
lengthy new forward for a silver anniversary edition of
``Post-Industrial Society.'' He is a spry 80 now, Henry Ford II
Professor of Social Sciences emeritus at Harvard;
scholar-in-residence at the American Academy of Arts and Sciences,
that bastion of distinction and good intentions in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   It is an appropriate time therefore to celebrate Bell's career:
40 years as a university sociologist, the inheritor of the mantle
of famous Harvard savants Pitrim Sorokin and Talcott Parsons; and
50 years at the pinnacle of the higher journalism in America. It's
a just occasion to reflect on what it is we expect from our better
pundits. A nice time, too, to inquire of him what he expects to
happen next. He was among my teachers in college; a man of wider
interests or greater ambition I have never known.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Drucker, who came to the United States from Vienna and
London, Bell was raised in New York, the child of Polish
immigrants. He entered New York's City College at 16. Among his
classmates were Irving Kristol, Nathan Glazer, Seymour Lipset, and
Irving Howe, all prominent intellectuals in later years. Later he
married Pearl Kazin, Alfred's sister. All participated as members
of the non-communist Left in the great arguments of the Thirties
and Forties among intellectuals in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bell made his living as a writer and editor for a time, studying
and teaching sociology on the side at Columbia University and the
University of Chicago. Henry Luce hired him onto Fortune Magazine
in 1948, and for 10 years during the magazine's golden age he
served as its labor editor, before returning to full-time teaching,
first at Columbia University, then at Harvard since 1969. He never
lost his feel for reporting, though, and for the next 30 years his
relentless flow of insights contributed to keeping the London
Economist at the top of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   Drucker, on the other hand, made his reputation as a student of
General Motors Corp. He taught in a business school for more than
20 years instead of a sociology department. But like Bell he was
first and foremost a journalist, and when, in the full flood of
their careers, the two men chose to write on the over-arching
transformation that then was in its early stages, they came to more
or less the same conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Neither one cited the other, naturally, confirming the old adage
that social scientists would no sooner share a toothbrush than
build on each other's theories. But to see that both books were
about the same things is no more difficult to to compare their
tables ofcontents _ a device typographically clumsy but succint.
</P>
<P>
   Bell divided his work into six chapters and a five-part coda.
They look like this:
</P>
<P>
   Chapter One, From Industrial to Post-Industrial Society;
Theories of Social Development;
</P>
<P>
   Chapter Two, From Goods to Services, the Changing Shape of the
Economy;
</P>
<P>
   Chapter Three, The Dimension of Knowledge and Technology: The
New Class Structure of Post-Industrial Society;
</P>
<P>
   Chapter Four, The Subordination of the Corporation; The Tension
between the Economizing and Sociologizing Modes;
</P>
<P>
   Chapter Five, Social Choice and Social Planning; The Adequency
of Our Concepts;
</P>
<P>
   Chapter Six, ``Who Will Rule?'' Politicians and Technocrats in
the Post-Industrial Society.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's coda, ``An Agenda for the Future,'' lists five topics:
How Social Systems Change; The Future of Science; Meritocracy and
Equality; The End of Scarcity; and Culture and Consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Drucker's ``The Age of Discontinuity,'' on the other hand,
consists of seventeen chapters divided into four parts.
</P>
<P>
   Part One, the Knowledge Technologies: The End of Continuity; The
New Industries and their Dynamics; the New Entrepreneur; the New
Economic Policies
</P>
<P>
   Part Two, From International to World Economy: the Global
Shopping Center; Making the Poor Productive; Beyond the ``New
Economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Part Three, A Society of Organizations: The New Pluralism;
Toward a Theory of Organizations; the Sickness of Government; How
Can the Individual Survive?
</P>
<P>
   Part Four, The Knowledge Society: the Knowledge Economy; Work
and Worker in the Knowledge Society; Has Success Spoiled the
Schools? The New Learning and the New Teaching; the Politics of
Knowledge; Does Knowledge Have a Future?
</P>
<P>
   On balance, you have to give the nod for prescience and clarity
to Drucker. The answer to the question, what comes after
``post-industrial?'' seems clear, whether you call it ``the
knowledge society'' or ``the information age.'' Drucker anticipated
more of the mechanics of the transformation, including the turn
against government and the critique of Keynesian economics.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is clear in retrospect that it was the murmer of the
conventional wisdom of Cambridge, Mass. that Bell was hearing, not
the whisper of the future, when he wrote in 1973, ``It seems clear
to me, today, we in America are moving away from a society based on
a private-enterprise market system toward one in which the most
important economic decisions will be made at the political level,
in terms of consciously defined `goals' and `priorities. He
resigned the co-editorship of The Public Interest that same year,
just as the ideology of the market was gaining the upper hand, and
as the journal he had co-founded joined Commentary as a flagship of
neo-conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell raised plenty of deep questions of his own, and because
of his deep grounding in Marxism and Continental sociology, his
book touched off a brouhaha among intellectuals in the former
Soviet Union. (A 300-copy translation was prepared for party
officials.) The political liberalisam that had been forged into
controversies of the Thirties and Forties remained the book's
dominating key.
</P>
<P>
   Readers were well served by either ``The Age of Discontinuity''
or ``The Coming of Post Industrial Society,'' and best by both.
Together they remain reassuring evidence of the ability of our
wisest intellectuals to know at least dimly where we are going,
even in tumultuous times.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Bell think today? Last month he and and his son
David (a professor of history at Johns Hopkins University) took
turns bantering away by e-mail throughout the day for a week on the
e-zine Slate's friendly feature known as ``The Breakfast Table.''
</P>
<P>
   There all Bell's gifts were on display: the encyclopedic
knowledge (Joachim of Fistore, the obscure Cistercian monk of the
12th century, and his relation to William Butler Yeats' ``The
Second Coming,'' the extrordinary personal history (Varian Fry was
his editor in 1945 at Common Sense), the spirituality, the humor,
the family values.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't he give just one prediction for the next century.
(``No, not a prediction, for that is not the way to think about it,
but a relevant social framework to identify issues and problems.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing,'' wrote Daniel Bell, ``is a change in
the `axis' of world socio-political organization; namely, one of
widening economic integration (crossing national boundaries) and
increasing political fragmentation (within national boundaries.)
The economic dimension is a `change of scale,' as all national
economies are absorbed into a global framework.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fragmentation is occurring because (as I remarked a decade
ago) the national state is becoming too small for the big problems
of life, and too big for the small problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He is probably right _ again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
