<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A JUNGLE IN HERE: TALES OF AN OFFICE GARDENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 2)  
 (editors: optional sidebar at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By MARTY ROSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Belinda Marley roared out of Pittsburg, Kan., in 1981 with a
``wicked green thumb,'' as she puts it, and a certain insouciance
regarding the facts. Four hundred miles from home, in the deepest
heart of Dallas, she hired herself out as a horticulturist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lied my way into the job,'' she admits. ``I had 100
houseplants at home, and I told them I had experience in a local
greenhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Marley, who is now 41, parlayed this opening into a career
in ``interiorscaping,'' and she now zips around in a Chevy Blazer
with a palm tree and ``Belinda's Tropical Paradise'' painted on the
side, taking care of tropical plants in restaurants, reception
rooms, lobbies and offices of all descriptions in the Kansas City
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hostile environment,'' she says. ``It used to be OK to
throw some plastic and silk plants around, but now, with what we've
created for ourselves, plants are as important as that desk.'' A
big leafy palm or two may help clean up the air as well as the
attitudes of office workers; plants also produce oxygen and raise
the humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is proven that live tropicals make people more
productive,'' Mrs. Marley says, whipping out a brochure that cites
NASA research conducted by Dr. B.C. Wolverton, an environmental
engineer and the author of ``How to Grow Fresh Air'' (Penguin,
1996).
</P>
<P>
   Leafy tropical plants adapt to the workaday world without
complaint, but they are really no better suited to the average
office than most people are. ``How many people in those cubbyholes
actually get a window?'' Mrs. Marley asks. Where no natural light
ever penetrates, she recommends peace lily (Spathiphyllum). ``She
could truly live in a closet,'' says Mrs. Marley, who refers to all
plants in the feminine.
</P>
<P>
   Heart-leaf philodendron (Philodendron oxycardium) and pothos
(Epipremnum aureum) thrive in the modern business world's miserable
work stations. These vines can be pinched back to the scale of a
cubicle, but easily get out of hand. ``I have cubbyholes where they
have created circles on the walls,'' she says. ``It goes over the
top of the computer and down the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential clients typically call an interiorscaper after they
have moved into a building, she says. The furniture is arranged and
the pictures have been hung, and then someone thinks of plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come in and look for dead spots,'' she says, ``where the
decorator has done her job but there is a dead spot. Unfortunately,
they're never in front of the windows.'' Many of the most
spectacular and adaptable tropical plants are native to rain
forests, however, and thrive in subdued light.
</P>
<P>
   Clients often think they know which plants will work best. A
restaurant owner once insisted on a peace lily next to the
reservations podium. ``She took serious abuse,'' Mrs. Marley says.
``Her leaves were tattered and torn. I replaced it with a yucca
cane. They slice you if you muscle them. Nobody messes with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors' waiting rooms are notoriously hazardous to the health
of plants; Mrs. Marley had to remove a plant that a nervous patient
had so thoroughly punctured with her long fingernails that
something appeared to have chewed on it. ``People fiddle,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there is the person who has extra coffee in their cup and
it goes in the plant,'' she continues. ``The plant gets a caffeine
jolt, but you get a foul smell after a while, and you lose it all
at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardening is usually a quite private pastime, but Mrs. Marley
has to deal as much with people as with plants. She becomes an
unofficial extension agent, answering gardening questions as she
waters gigantic banana trees from the atrium stairs, clips the
ragged tips of a lady palm's pleated fronds with pinking shears, or
takes a feather duster to a ficus.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Marley or one of her three full-time employees visit each
of 65 clients once a week, for fees that start at $40 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people overwater,'' she says. ``Stick your finger in the
soil. If it is wet, don't water.'' In low light, plants really
don't need a lot of water. What they do need is a routine. ``It's
just like children,'' Mrs. Marley says. ``Without it things get all
mixed up.''
</P>
<P>
   She seldom has to repot plants. ``Everybody thinks, `I have a
plant, I have to repot it,''' she says. ``You never really repot a
plant unless you want it to grow larger.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Marley prefers light plastic pots molded to look like
stone, lead, or terra cotta, but is happy to accommodate customers'
tastes. Shiny brass pots are popular with bosses. ``We have one
account, you can tell where the head honchos are because they all
have brass containers,'' she says. For the big corner offices with
lots of light, she likes to recommend citrus trees. ``They're
fun,'' she says, ``and you get the fruit of your labors.''
</P>
<P>
   She also encourages clients to try bromeliads, and is
particularly partial to the bromeliad known as urn plant (Aechmea
fasciata), which has long, toothy green leaves, dusted with silver.
``When you get one, she's blooming, and it's bright and significant
and awesome,'' Mrs. Marley says. ``To take care of her, you just
pour a little water in her head. She is just awesome _ killer
color, killer bloom, and she'll have a baby for you before she
dies.'' As the bloom fades, one or two offsets emerge at the base
of the parent plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not your red geranium person,'' Mrs. Marley says. She
prefers big, wild, leafy, tropical plants in the unnatural world
inside the revolving doors. ``Come on,'' she says, ``let's get some
adventure going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK: Alms for Birds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Start winnowing the long list you've compiled from the new plant
introductions for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Plan for drought and heat. Look for vegetables that did well in
test gardens in this year's record heat, like Outredgeous lettuce
and Blushing Beauty peppers. Some All-America Selections winners _
the sunflower Soraya, the cosmos Cosmic Orange and the tithonia
Fiesta del Sol _ got good marks last summer, but your garden may
not accommodate all these orange-flowered winners. At 2 feet tall
rather than the usual six, Fiesta del Sol is suitable for
containers and small gardens. Cosmic Orange blooms from early
summer until frost, and bees love it. These two will be available
in garden centers in spring, but Soraya will show up only in
catalogs. And if you can't get enough orange, California poppy
(Eschscholzia mexicana) is easy and reliable, and it thrives in
drought.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PATRICIA JONAS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
