<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3487 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-MILLENNIUM-MEAN-STYLE     12-31 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-MEAN-STYLE-ART-WORDS&AMP;ADD-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESSING MEAN AND MEANING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 2)  
 (b By STANLEY BING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look at you. The next 1,000 years are already 24 hours old, and
what have you done to alter your style? Have you changed your life?
Have you wrested victory from the maw of mediocrity? Or are you the
same 20th-century hominid you were last Friday?
</P>
<P>
   Of course you are. And it just won't do. If there's one thing we
know about the new epoch, it's that it's going to be harder,
faster, meaner and more digital than the relatively warm and toasty
analog version we've just left behind. That means dressing,
accessorizing, working, playing, meeting, greeting, piercing,
coiffing and otherwise living in full compliance with the tough new
paradigm. Nervous yet? Good. Here is the sixfold path to power
style for the new mean elite. Follow it or die.
</P>
<P>
   Casual is over. The backlash against Internet millionaire idiot
savants is now well established. Nobody who has ever been forced to
sit at a meeting in a sober Canali pinstripe and Barneys tie while
some dopey guy in a down vest and ``Planet of the Apes'' T-shirt
spouts jargon about sticky interfaces will doubt the wisdom of the
new anticasualism.
</P>
<P>
   The antidote is staunch, aggressive, gender-free traditionalism
and a solid commitment to lack of personal comfort. We're not
comfortable with what we're doing _ why should our clothing be?
Look to shirts and blouses bleached so blazingly and sadistically
white that they could cause retinal damage. Suits for men and women
should be in funereal hues, with creases that could slice a finger.
</P>
<P>
   All clothes should be worn tight and high, harking back to the
immensely uncomfortable chinos, James Bond peg legs and squirmingly
uncomfortable miniskirts of the 1960's and 70's, which kept people
basically vertical until Woody Allen and Kurt Cobain took over with
their corduroy, denim and (ugh) flannel.
</P>
<P>
   Hair today, gone entirely. Evolution is working on us all, and
nowhere more strikingly than in the corridors of power. Men are
growing ever more hairless, and what hair they have, more often
than not, looks bad. Consider Donald J. Trump. Women, on the other
hand, are continuing their rise to full and justified equality, but
not moving as fast as they should, possibly because they have too
much hair.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is clear for both sexes: the complete eradication
ol and body hair. Nobody doesn't look really scary when
shaved and buffed, a fact established by West Coast entertainment
executives who, in the early 90's, invented bullet heads strictly
for business purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Like professional swimmers, the new shaved and buffed 2K
stylists will move through the ocean of life, eating raw fish as
they go, unencumbered by frizz. Pair that with excessive physical
fitness, and you have a combo that cannot be beat.
</P>
<P>
   You only get one chance to make a first impression _ so make it
hurt. The most important power styling opportunity is the moment
you say hello to your next interface target. Don't waste it.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the common handshake is over.
</P>
<P>
   This germ bridge from one person to another was invented
millenniums ago by those who wanted to show that they were not
carrying a weapon. ``Look!'' the handshake said. ``I have no sword!
My intentions are peaceful and good!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not really the message we mean to convey, now is
it? ``Hey!'' we want to say. ``Watch out for me! I mean business
and I will hurt you if I can!''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing conveys this message more effectively than the common
head butt.
</P>
<P>
   You're now equipped for it. Bow down that hard, cold cranium.
Aim it at the other guy. And knock his or her block off! Boy!
Doesn't that feel good!
</P>
<P>
   Put your worst foot forward. The relationship between pain and
gain is particularly evident in power shoes. These should be tight
and unforgiving, just like their owner, making the wearer
irritable, unhappy and eager to visit similar constraint and pain
on others, as well as cutting off the blood supply to the brain.
These are all terrific assets to any business mentality.
</P>
<P>
   New footwear is being developed that will actually make men
shorter, helping those with excessive tallness join the ranks of
the tiny titans that move the world. Studies show that 90 percent
of all those chief executive billionaires at the Herb Allen Sun
Valley conference are _ not to put too fine a point on it _ short.
Now, any man can have that lack-of-height advantage. Similar
research demonstrates that tall women with enormous spike heels
terrify and impress male and female counterparts alike. Women will
also be further exploring the elimination of socks and hose. In
women, the effect of a bare leg and associated nearby naked foot on
adipose business executives with bad sex lives is self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   Wear your office. There's no reason to look like a wonk just
because you're tapped into the cybermacrocosm. For this we can
thank the breakthrough stylings of Steve Jobs and the gang at
Apple, whose tangerine and blueberry Macintoshes are so cute that
they make you want to pinch their virtual cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   So let the rainbow in! Black and beige are out, baby. Each and
every objet that keeps you in touch with Big Mother should be as
translucent and colorful as your world view. To avoid bulging
pockets stuffed with communication gizmos and unsightly clip-ons,
true power-forwards are now sporting clever shoulder and wrist
holsters and natty garters in leather and lace to keep their
beepers, pagers, cell and satellite phones, laptops, palmtops and
stovetops in handy reach.
</P>
<P>
   Until cranial implants become the norm, the first unwired
telecom chapeau, coming next winter, will take up the slack. Big
and bold as its Russian counterpart, with fake-fur earflaps to
conceal its tasty little satellite dish, antennae and inner
workings, this hot headgear will sport every communications
technology the budding intrapreneur could want. The rumored price
is more than $15,000 _ with free Internet connectivity!
</P>
<P>
   Make every desk accessory count. Your desk is you. Toss the
Smurfs, bogus award medallions and cute little gewgaws that have
burdened it with an excess of personality in the past. Get a hefty
stone paperweight that you can hit people with it if they don't
give you what you want. A serrated letter opener can help organize
your in pile and can also leave a nasty gash. Remember to keep it
clean.
</P>
<P>
   And this above all: To thine own self be true. Anything else
seems so 20th century, don't you think?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1507EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
