<HEADER>
A3490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FORGOTTEN-HORRORS-NYT     12-31 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORGOTTEN-HORRORS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORRORS NOT `FORGOTTEN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TERRY PACE   
 TimesDaily, Florence, Ala.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movie buff Michael H. Price likes nothing better than uncovering
``new things about old things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas-based author and longtime film critic for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram co-authored the essential genre study
``Forgotten Horrors.''
</P>
<P>
   First published 20 years ago, this revealing, one-of-a-kind work
explores uncharted cinematic territory: the Depression-era history
of Hollywood's Poverty Row chillers. Price wrote and researched
``Forgotten Horrors'' with the late George E. Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very month we finished the book, we started discovering
new things,'' said Price, who also directs AMC Theaters' Gourmet
Cinema project in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it never stops,'' Price said. ``Every time you think
you've milked the last drop in the archives, you look around and
something reaches out and grabs you.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Midnight Marquee Press has now published the revised
and expanded ``Forgotten Horrors: The Definitive Edition.'' The new
volume sheds light on such little-known but endlessly intriguing
treasures as ``Murder After Midnight,'' ``Amazon Head Hunters,''
``Revolt of the Zombies'' and ``Riders of the Whispering Skull.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of `Forgotten Horrors' crosses all cultural
barriers,'' Price said. ``For one thing, how do you define a horror
film? Is it supernatural? Is it science-fiction? Can it be rampant
criminality? Anything that scares you can be considered a horror
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Some ``Forgotten Horrors'' are whodunits, while others are
creepy comedies. Some are spooky Westerns, others are jungle
adventures and many are full-fledged fright films. All are bound by
their relative obscurity, their low-budget origins and an inherent
quotient of mystery and dread that Price and Turner called ``weird
menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a game,'' Price said. ``There are ground
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the author admits, his threshold of tolerance
has risen. A case in point is ``Private Snuffy Smith,'' a comedy
based on the hillbilly comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so blasted weird,'' Price said. ``When I started
watching it, I wasn't expecting much. Then, early on in the game,
they introduced this invisibility potion. I said, `This is a
forgotten horror!'''
</P>
<P>
   Price's personal favorite from the definitive edition is ``Drums
of Jeopardy'' (1931), a horror thriller featuring Warner ``Charlie
Chan'' Oland as a vengeful Bolshevik scientist. Price is also fond
of the grim, mature Tim McCoy Western ``Lightnin' Bill Carson''
(1936) and a voodoo oddity of ``poetic backwater romance'' called
``Chloe'' (1934).
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago that if you don't write to please
yourself, you're not going to please anybody,'' Price said.
``George and I started this out of a passion for these movies.
Somehow we tapped into a popular vein right before the video market
exploded in the early '80s. Now there's no end in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgotten Horrors: The Definitive Edition'' covers 1929-37. An
envisioned series of sequels (based on an exhaustive ``laundry
list'' of qualified titles) will follow the phenomenon through the
mid-'60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That puts you in Herschell Gordon Lewis territory,'' Price
noted. ``That's about the point where imagination leaks out and
explicit shock values creep in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, I like antiquity,'' he said. ``I like watching movies
that were made before a certain level of technology was reached.''
</P>
<P>
   To order ``Forgotten Horrors,'' call (800) 886-0313.
</P>
<P>
   (The TimesDaily, Florence, Ala., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
