<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3493 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-MAKEUP-$ADV02-2TAKES-     12-31 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKEUP-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKEUP THAT SAYS: NIGHT AND DAY, YOU ARE THE ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 2) 
(bl) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sitting near the Prescriptives counter at Bergdorf
Goodman, I eyed the glowing white liquid suspiciously. ``Is this
Magic?'' I asked Darac, the illusionist (read makeup artist) who
goes by one name only.
</P>
<P>
   He nodded. ``Magic alters the reality of what you see,'' he
said. ``It plays with light so it's all illusion. It's very Lucille
Ball in `Mame.' Every time she had a close-up she looked very soft,
no fine lines or discoloration. Think of Magic as soft surgery.
It's for people who say, `Should I have something done?' and
shouldn't, but do, and then come out looking like Mrs. Phantom of
the Opera. Which we don't enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Prescriptives is just one of the major cosmetics companies that
have been introducing products that are supposed to play with light
so that women of a certain age (over 30) can welcome in 2000
looking like movie stars shot through cheesecloth. Estee Lauder
recently introduced Spotlight, a lotion ``whose trick lies in the
special way light is reflected by `micro-prisms,''' its promotional
literature claims.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon's Age Defying Makeup and Concealer Compact features
``unique moisturizer-wrapped color particles,'' which ``float above
skin lines, making them look less noticeable.'' And Christian Dior
takes playing with light one step further with its new Lumiere
Noire, a makeup line that is transparent in daylight and can be
seen only in the black light of nightclubs (and is sold only at
Sephora).
</P>
<P>
   Anne Carullo, the vice president of marketing and product
development worldwide for Prescriptives, who came up with the
concept for Magic, said: ``I always figured maybe I could trick
light a little bit. If we optically alter what light sees, we alter
the way we are seen.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in formulating Magic, Prescriptives worked with Trisha
Sawyer, a makeup artist for Julia Roberts and Sharon Stone, on
translating the principles of movie makeup into one for the masses
_ meaning that if you use a base coat underneath your foundation,
one that is filled with tiny glittering particles, it will somehow
influence the way light hits your face (gently, thank you).
</P>
<P>
   At least, this is how I could best decipher the corporate
gobbledygook describing Magic's Illuminating Liquid Potion as ``a
holographic liquid, an oil-free, water-in-silicone emulsion with
three-dimensional pigments made of spherical, multilayered
particles that changes the way skin reflects light.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who speak English, this means that Magic will make you
look as dewy and brimming with estrogen as you did the day of your
junior prom. Which sounded good to me.
</P>
<P>
   During the last week, I tried all four of the new makeup lines
in the hope that I, too, would wake up this weekend and greet the
millennium with Julia Roberts' face _ and salary. Here's what
happened instead.
</P>
<P>
   PRESCRIPTIVES: Darac was the key to this experience (I'm sure
the other companies' illusionists are equally good, though I tried
those products at home). His sessions at Bergdorf's are free,
though you must book well in advance. What is not free are the
products: the Illuminating Liquid Potion is $30, the custom-blended
foundation Darac made for me (``the difference between ordinary and
extraordinary,'' he insisted) was $55, and the custom-made lipstick
was $30, though all he did was copy the color of the $11.50
Clinique lipstick I usually buy.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Darac's floor show is worth the extra charge, as was
the discovery of my new favorite Prescriptives product, the Cooling
Globe, which looks like a small light bulb. You keep it in the
freezer and roll it over your puffy eyes when you get up in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will rescue you,'' Darac proclaimed, applying it to my
eyelids. Heaven. ``Also here, after a few martinis,'' he went on,
pressing it behind my neck. ``And sinuses,'' he added, holding it
on my cheeks. ``It's an Altoid for the eye,'' he said, albeit a $30
Altoid. How did I ever live without it?
</P>
<P>
   He did a fabulous job on my makeup, and indeed, shadows, red
marks and all unevenness were obliterated without it looking like I
was wearing makeup at all. Unlike other makeup applications, the
result of this one was that my skin looked genuinely more lush than
usual (though if I looked extra close I could see the little
glitters; I simply resolved not to look.)
</P>
<P>
   Alas, hours later, when I checked myself again, the sparkles had
sputtered and my skin had way more creases than usual, which is
what happens when there is too much makeup on my face, even when
expertly applied. ``Old pumpkin,'' a friend calls the effect.
</P>
<P>
   When I used the products on my own a few days later, I avoided
this look, but I also avoided the cheesecloth glow. I had bypassed
ethereal completely, leaving me to believe the magic may have been
Darac's. Does he do hair, too? I had asked. He drew himself up.
``We are only cosmetic,'' he proclaimed. ``One man, one art:
Aristotle.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN DIOR: I wasn't quite sure what to make of Lumiere
Noire, a novelty makeup for the club-hopping set, which remains
invisible to the naked eye until you encounter it under the black
lights of a club. I never saw much point in clubs, even when I was
younger, but now that my stepchildren are old enough, or almost old
enough, to go instead, I sat them down for an after-dinner
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They loved it, drawing a stick figure on my cheek and a
tick-tack-toe board on my forehead, applying a stencil to the
inside of my arm, coloring it in, then writing their names
underneath. I looked totally normal until I held up a black light,
revealing the designs in vivid ice blue. Fantastic! It occurred to
me that you could write any kind of heinous message right across
your forehead, go to work and smile at your bosses, and all the
while they would have no idea what they were looking at. It
definitely beats lingerie for that ``only you know'' sort of
thrill.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback? After washing my face three times with soap and
water, the blue remained. Blurred and faded, but still glowing.
That was strange, but even so, I'd recommend it to anyone with time
(and kids) on their hands, whhey go to clubs or not. It's
fun, and it makes you feel young _ without the glitter.
</P>
<P>
   ESTEE LAUDER: I found Spotlight to be quite similar to Magic,
though it was definitely shinier, or more ``radiant,'' as the
adjective in its packaging promised. Either way, my forehead looked
like a headlight.
</P>
<P>
   While the makeup had the same glittery particles that Magic did,
Spotlight gave my skin a reddish cast, which is actually meant to
offset the green undertones of fluorescent office lights. Had it
not been Christmas Eve, I would have found the red alarming, as my
nose was glowing a la Rudolph. Luckily, when I applied my own
Georgette Klinger foundation over it, the excessive rosiness
disappeared and the overall effect came closest to Darac's
application of Prescriptives. As he would say, I enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   REVLON: This was my briefest experiment. The Age Defying All Day
Lifting Foundation felt like thick grandma makeup on my skin,
seeming only to enhance the size of my por the accompanying
concealer compact felt oily to the touch and did not work as well
as the Benefits concealer I normally use.
</P>
<P>
   The result of all this applying and removing different
combinations from my face was an increase in the very same
unsightly marks and blotches that these makeups were formulated to
conceal, not to mention patches of dryness (especially on the site
of the stick-figure man).
</P>
<P>
   Well, so much for movie stardom. Makeup is only makeup, after
all. Though Ms. Carullo of Prescriptives promises that in May the
company will introduce its second group of products that play with
light. ``Maybe a putty to build cheekbones with,'' she mused, ``a
serum that pulls the face back.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds interesting. We would enjoy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
