<HEADLINE>
`BIOGRAPHY' NEEDS TO LOOSEN UP ON VAN DYKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
DICK VAN DYKE: PUT ON A HAPPY FACE 
Produced by: Peter Jones 
Date: Sunday at 8 p.m. 
On: A&AMP;E 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a great story buried in ``Dick Van Dyke: Putting On a
Happy Face,'' A&AMP;E's shapeless two-hour biography premiering Sunday
at 8 p.m. Properly pruned and focused, this might have been a
layered drama about the pathos under the comic mask, the emotional
pain beneath the funnyman's fierce ambition and years of hoofing
and mugging, the never-say-die failures and often personally
unrewarding successes.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, though, this is a stiffly chronological, woodenly
executed account of the comedian's checkered career and
alcohol-haunted family life that only ardent Van Dyke fans and
students of sitcom minutiae could love.
</P>
<P>
   There's a wealth of material, including clips from the pilot
that led to the 1961 breakthrough ``The Dick Van Dyke Show,''
starring not Van Dyke but the show's creator, comic writer and
performer Carl Reiner. The show's producer sensed that it would
work better with a different actor in the lea preferably Van
Dyke or Johnny Carson.
</P>
<P>
   We also learn the names and birth dates of all of Van Dyke's
children, and where he moved and when. As with so many other
programs in the A&AMP;E ``Biography'' series, information is heaped on
indiscriminately, without much sense of its relevance or dramatic
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyke, now the star of ``Diagnosis Murder,'' worked
tirelessly and with little success first in vaudeville and then in
radio, and, later, in TV, as a kids' show host, game show host, and
morning show anchor. He tried Broadway but the musicals he was cast
in failed, until the 1960 hit ``Bye Bye Birdie'' earned him sorely
needed recognition.
</P>
<P>
   He had a long and apparently happy first marriage that turned
out to be marinated in drink. Interviews with his brother Jerry,
colleague Mary Tyler Moore, and a few of Van Dyke's grown children
inform us that he's not merely private but an inaccessible,
obsessive loner. Van Dyke speaks of his battle with the bottle, but
aloofly, and neither he nor this two-hour documentary cares to
explore seriously the emotional distance he keeps between himself
and even members of his own family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Van Dyke: Putting On a Happy Face'' is fact-filled to a
fault, the TV equivalent of a hastily written term paper, too often
padded formlessly with odds and ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
