<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YEAR-IN-POP-NYT &LR;      12-31 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-IN-POP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR OF FLUFF, SMUT AND LETTING OFF STEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask any critic to comment upon this final year of the Century of
American Music, and you're likely to hear a heavy sigh. The year
1999 gave us fluff and smut, the inflatable sweethearts of the
teen-age market and the foul-mouthed bullies of hip-hop and rock.
Releases from aspiring legends like Nine Inch Nails, R. Kelly and
Mary J. Blige failed to make the anticipated cultural impact, while
previously dismissed artists like Limp Bizkit and Kid Rock rose to
rule the Zeitgeist. People actually looked to Cher, rising again
with her smash ``Believe,'' as a beacon of artistic integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Step outside the bubble of critical debate, though, and this
year's pop sounds much more exciting. It was a great year for
arrogant fans using music to air their opinions and elaborate upon
their daydreams.
</P>
<P>
   The year's hits expressed ethnic pride, encapsulated gender
debates, and revealed some crucial attributes of a new generation.
Only a few songs would prompt listeners to pause for reflection;
their hearty jokes and bold declarations defeated subtlety. But for
the crowds mightily singing along, the soundtrack to 1999 offered
inspiration and release.
</P>
<P>
   Bratty boys and sassy girls faced off across the genres. TLC's
``No Scrubs,'' the spring's ubiquitous hit, refreshed the theme of
the no-good man and became the favored chorus for finger-snapping
groups of girlfriends nationwide. It inspired an answer song, ``No
Pigeons,'' by Sporty Thieves and set the stage for similar
pronouncements from Destiny's Child, Whitney Houston and Mariah
Carey.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``. . . Baby Hit Me One More Time,'' which had parents
worrying about the masochistic messages the high school heroine
Britney Spears might be proffering, is really yet another song
about romantic confrontation, and Ms. Spears' steely gaze was as
suggestive an aspect of her video as her schoolgirl outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Male artists presented their own boot-camp chants for the battle
of the sexes. Limp Bizkit's crassly sexist songs the most likely to
make it onto a World Federation Wrestling soundtrack, but they were
hardly alone. The modern rock bands Lit and Blink 182 took callow
whining to new heights with ``My Own Worst Enemy'' and ``What's My
Age Again?'' LFO took a laid-back approach to the same cocky
attitude in ``Summer Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   These songs were the antidotes to the craven entreaties of
teen-age idols like the Backstreet Boys, whose hyper-romanticism
set impossibly high standards for average Romeos. They fed a mood
of frustration that hit its nadir at Woodstock, where the old,
shameful connection between rock's transgressiveness and misogyny
resurfaced via sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   It was a horrifying moment, but hardly inexplicable given pop's
rude mood. Musical expressions of racial identity were often as
blatant, although not as hateful, as those about sex. The much
touted ``Latin pop explosion,'' for example, was driven by Ricky
Martin's ``Livin' la Vida Loca,'' a novelty song based on the most
obvious stereotype: a mocha-skinned temptress who would have worn
fruit on her head in another era. (``Smooth,'' the comeback hit for
Carlos Santana, relied on similar images of Latin heat and
coolness.) But because Martin delivered it with a self-aware grin,
the cliche charmed instead of offended.
</P>
<P>
   The year's best-selling rock album also relied on a racial
lampoon, which happened to expose a generational reality. With
little fanfare, the Offspring's late 1998 release, ``Americana,''
outsold both Limp Bizkit and Kid Rock, mostly because of a song
that satirized what those groups stood for. ``Pretty Fly (for a
White Guy)'' leveled scorn at a suburban would-be gangster, giving
many white hip-hop fans a humorous way to face their dubious ghetto
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper Eminem, a protege of the venerated hip-hop producer
Dr. Dre, threw the joke back with his single, ``My Name Is,'' which
presented race-crossing as a trickster's game instead of a
dangerous conquest.
</P>
<P>
   Amid these exaggerated expressions of pride and anxiety were pop
moments that simply vented collective steam. Hip-hop is always
fertile ground for creative babbling, and this year it turned the
radio into a veritable playpen. Choruses of ``Holla, holla'' and
``Ay-yi-yi-yi . . . who dat?'' arose wherever hip-hop fans gathered
to dance, echoing hits by Ja Rule and JT Money with Sole. Most
successful was Jay-Z, who had millions shouting out his nickname
with ``Jigga'' and whooping like owls along with the cleaned-up
chorus of ``Can I Get a . . . !'' Modern rockers rode the
nursery-rhyme mood with sing-alongs like ``Steal My Sunshine'' by
Len and ``All Star'' by Smashmouth.
</P>
<P>
   There were exceptions to the year's ridiculously extroverted
mood, even at the top of the charts. Marc Anthony dignified the
fascination with all things Latin with the elegantly lustful ``I
Need to Know.'' Brandy and Monica both encouraged teen-age girls to
stop screaming and start thinking with their modest, pensive
ballads.
</P>
<P>
   TLC followed ``No Scrubs'' with ``Unpretty,'' a vision of the
beauty myth that's remarkably complex, musically and lyrically. A
few steps away from the hit parade, artists like Moby, Mos Def,
Kelly Willis and Magnetic Fields made intricate music that rewarded
careful listening.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the nation's party people usher in a new era this
weekend, they'll probably be listening to big, silly songs that
reflect the year's rowdy mood.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes back to Cher: whether people believed in their
machismo or feminine wiles, their cultural heritage or racial
loyalties or simply the life after love that the bewigged diva
touted in her high-energy anthem, they wanted to make known their
most accessible emotions. And pop, more than ever the truly public
art form, gave everyone the means to get good and loud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
