<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YULIN-PLAY-ART-NYT &LR;      12-31 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YULIN-PLAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD RUN FOR AN ACTOR WHO SPECIALIZES IN THE BAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and NYT2 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harris Yulin doesn't have a killer's face, but if you
saw him walking down the street you could be excused for taking
cover.
</P>
<P>
   In his 40-year career, after all, Yulin has played more than a
few disreputable characters, from the sleazy cop in Brian De
Palma's 1983 cult movie ``Scarface'' to his recent turn as a
double-dealing politician in the film ``Cradle Will Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   It is casting, the actor said, that has more to do with his
stern, rugged looks and almost senatorial presence than with any
preference on his part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not always the bad guy,'' he said recently, with a shrug.
``It just seems to be what I'm known for.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Yulin has been turning that gruff reputation on its head
with his subtle turn as Walter Franz, a damaged businessman looking
for emotional solace in the current Broadway production of Arthur
Miller's drama ``The Price.'' Ben Brantley, writing in The New York
Times, called Yulin's performance ``excellent,'' adding that Walter
seemed to be a character whom Yulin was ``born to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the only role Yulin may have been made for. Indeed, the
actor's talents are on particular display of late, with four major
projects open or coming soon. In addition to ``The Price'' and
``Cradle Will Rock,'' Yulin can be seen in ``The Hurricane''
playing the lawyer who represents that film's wrongly convicted
hero (a good guy!), and in a movie scheduled for Jan. 9 on the TNT
Network, ``The Virginian.'' There Yulin reverts to form as a
disreputable judge.
</P>
<P>
   At 62, Yulin has established himself as something of the
character actor's character actor, a quiet force who parlays small
roles into big moments.
</P>
<P>
   His status is evident in ``The Price,'' where he shares the
stage with three other accomplished actors: Bob Dishy, Lizbeth
Mackay and Jeffrey DeMunn,
</P>
<P>
   ``He pays a lot of attention to details and specifics of
characters: the hands, the voice,'' Dishy said. ``And I appreciate
it, because I work in a similar way.''
</P>
<P>
   Yulin, a smoker who talks in something like a casual growl,
didn't plan it this way. A Los Angeles native, he worked his way
through a series of professions _ and countries _ before landing on
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to be a painter for a while in Florence,'' he said.
``And I was extremely bad at it.''
</P>
<P>
   After flirting with architecture, he found himself in Tel Aviv
in 1962, a time and a place he remembers as ``like Paris in the
1920s.'' There, at the urging of new friends, he began directing
and acting in small shows.
</P>
<P>
   That calling took hold, and when he returned to the United
States, he decided _ if that is the right word _ to continue
acting. ``I said, `Well, I guess this is what I'm going to do,'''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   His first break came in 1963, when he was cast in a leading role
in a production at the Phoenix, a now-defunct Off Broadway theater.
The play was ``Next Time I'll Sing For You,'' which featured James
Earl Jones and Estelle Parsons and was notable in a couple of
regards, Yulin said.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was scheduled to open the week of Nov. 22, 1963, when
President John F. Kennedy was assassinated. (The opening was
postponed.) Second, said Yulin, the production, an absurdist take
on a novel by the Anglo-Indian novelist Raleigh Trevelyan, was
``just a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat on the apron of the stage, insulting the audience
essentially, in a sort of elegant way, but insulting
nevertheless,'' Yulin said. ``I could feel waves of hate coming
from the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Yulin's fortunes improved, however, and over the course of the
next decade, his standing was sealed. In 1980 he won raves in the
Broadway production of ``A Lesson From Aloes,'' by Athol Fugard, in
which he again played opposite Jones.
</P>
<P>
   His film work also began to increase, with roles in ``The
Believers,'' ``Clear and Present Danger'' and ``Multiplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, he has also teamed with his friends and
fellow actors Ed Asner and Rene Auberjonois to do staged readings
of ``Don Juan in Hell,'' a favorite of his since high school. And
last year, he directed ``This Lime Tree Bower,'' at Primary Stages.
</P>
<P>
   As he matured as an actor, Yulin says, he was also trying to get
rid of another, less seemly reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when I was young, I became known as what you would
call a difficult person to work with,'' he said with a smidgen of
pride. ``I never felt it was a question of ego, but I did realize I
offended some people.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude has apparently faded with the years, at least
according to Yulin's current Broadway director, the actor James
Naughton.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that was in evidence,'' Naughton said. ``Every
rehearsal I've been in there's a day where everything goes south,
or someone goes south. It never happened with this show.''
</P>
<P>
   In rehearsals for ``The Price,'' which began at the Williamstown
Theater Festival in Williamstown, Mass., Naughton said Yulin had
only one demand: that his dog, Max, a cocker spaniel, be allowed to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max would wander onto the playing field during rehearsal,''
Naughton said. ``Harris would just look at him, point, and Max
would wander back off.''
</P>
<P>
   Yulin, who divides his time between New York and Los Angeles as
work demands, often drives across the country because Max has a
fear of flying. Along the way, he says, he often stops in small
towns.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, someone recognizes him. ``They're like, `Hey, what
are you doing here?''' Yulin says. ``And then, once they realize
I'm just an actor, people are almost always friendly and
pleasant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
