<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC TAKEOVER IN HOUSE COULD CURB SOUTHERN POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a narrow five-seat margin separating the two
parties, Democrats are increasingly confident they can recapture
control of the House come November. Should that happen, Southern
lawmakers could well see their ranks thinned in terms of leadership
posts and committee chairmanships.
</P>
<P>
   There would be a few gains, notably the likely ascension of Rep.
John Spratt, D-S.C., to chairman of the Budget Committee. Rep. Eva
Clayton, D-N.C., could also snare a subcommittee chairmanship on
the Agriculture Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But there aren't many other Southern Democrats waiting in the
wings should Republicans lose their grip on the House. Many of the
old Southern Democratic lions have either retired, been defeated _
or in some cases _ switched parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southerners are a smaller proportion of the Democratic party
than they were in past decades,'' said Merle Black, a political
scholar at Emory University. ``That's especially true in the Deep
South.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Republicans could lose some significant posts.
Florida's Bill Young would have to relinquish control of the
Appropriations Committee while state colleague Porter Goss would
give up the chair of the Intelligence Committee. Ditto for South
Carolina's Floyd Spence, who would lose the helm of the House Armed
Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   And Louisiana Republican Billy Tauzin _ who left the Democratic
side in 1995 _ would not realize his dream of controlling the
Commerce Committee should his former party win back control.
</P>
<P>
   The big winners in the event of a Democratic takeover may well
be black lawmakers. Georgia's John Lewis is already seeking a
leadership post. While several black Democrats like Lewis hail from
the South, the more senior members come from Northeast and Midwest
states.
</P>
<P>
   POWER SHIFT II
</P>
<P>
   While individual Southern lawmakers could lose influence, the
region should continue to gain seats in Congress. New projections
show the South and West will add to their House delegations though
at a slower pace then the past.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the 2000 Census will not produce the dramatic
regional shuffle that characterized redistricting after the 1980
and 1990 counts, according to an analysis by Election Data Services
Inc., a political consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing that we are seeing as you get to the end of
this decade is that we're not getting the major shifts that we saw
previously,'' said Kim Brace, president of the company. He
estimates 16 states will see a change in the size of their
congressional delegations after the 2000 Census and
reapportionment, which is based on state population.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, for instance, would gain just one seat after adding
four after both the 1990 and 1980 counts. North Carolina, which
added a seat last round, would remain stable. Sun Belt centers
Arizona and Texas would win two more House seats while Georgia
would add one along with California, Colorado, Montana and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, Illinois, Ohio, Oklahoma and Wisconsin would each
drop one, along with a rare Southern loser, Mississippi. New York
and Pennsylvania are each expected to lose two seats.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC INFORMATION FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce is testing the strength of a
controversial new public records law championed by Sen. Richard
Shelby of Alabama and other Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the new standard intended to increase public scrutiny of
research used to justify federal regulations, chamber officials
asked the Environmental Protection Agency for data and studies that
provided the basis for recent EPA rulings on air quality, auto
emissions and environmental justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the cost of health and safety regulations now topping
$230 billion a year, it is vitally important that the federal
government provide public access to the data and information
underlying EPA's regulatory proposals,'' said William Kovacs, a
chamber vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the new Shelby rule argue that it could be used to
stifle research that provides the basis for unpopular laws. But
proponents say that study paid for with tax dollars should be
accessible to the public. The chamber intends to take the EPA to
court if it does not honor the requests.
</P>
<P>
   NO FISHING
</P>
<P>
   Federal fishery experts say they now have evidence that putting
large tracts of ocean off limits to fishing can help replenish
dwindling stocks of fish.
</P>
<P>
   A long-term study of a 40-square-kilometer area off Cape
Canaveral, Fla., that has been closed to fishing since 1962 found
that the abundance and size of local species was significantly
greater than in fished areas. Researchers for the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration also found that larger fish
migrating from the protected area can boost spawning in surrounding
waters.
</P>
<P>
   The study is likely to give impetus to the push to ban fishing
in large sections of the Gulf of Mexico and Atlantic Ocean to ease
pressure on declining fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
