<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0101-COX     12-31 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUTIN: WHERE WILL THE 'GRAY CARDINAL' LEAD RUSSIA?
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-YELTSIN-0101.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In just four months, Vladimir Putin emerged from the shadows of
the Kremlin bureaucracy and his KGB past to become one of the most
popular politicians in Russian history.
</P>
<P>
   With the surprise resignation Friday of President Boris Yeltsin,
the enigmatic Putin, 47, a former spy and domestic security chief,
became one of the most important figures in the world as acting
president and the likely victor in new presidential elections
scheduled for March.
</P>
<P>
   Putin now has his finger on the trigger of a vast nuclear
arsenal. He also holds singular power under the country's
constitution to determine Russia's post-Soviet path.
</P>
<P>
   As prime minister, Putin has come to represent stability and
moderation in a country aching from a decade of tumultuous economic
and social upheavals.
</P>
<P>
   But how and where he will lead Russia no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is perhaps the most ominous thing _ how little we know
about the man most likely to lead Russia after Yeltsin,'' analyst
Michael McFaul of the Carnegie Endowment said earlier in December.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was plucked from obscurity by Yeltsin in August to become
the country's fifth prime minister in 17 months. Polls at the time
showed that very few Russians had ever heard his name, much less
developed an opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, Russians have come to appreciate Putin
as a tough-talking protagonist waging war against the breakaway
republic of Chechnya and, in turn, restoring a sense of national
pride and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In a country adrift since the breakup of the Soviet Union in
1991, Russians appeared eager for a man of action. Putin's poll
ratings soared, as Russia's army waded deeper into Chechnya and
Kremlin image-builders posed the stern-faced Putin as the nation's
hands-on leader during Yeltsin's recurring illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   For his own political survival, Putin will have to perpetuate
this role.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has only 90 days to consolidate his power before the
presidential elections on March 26. His success will depend largely
on the course of the war, and his ability to hold together the
influential Kremlin advisers, business tycoons and media barons _
known collectively as ``the family'' _ that have kept Yeltsin in
power.
</P>
<P>
   ting Yeltsin and his inner circle became Putin's first
priority on Friday. As acting president, he signed a decree
guaranteeing immunity from prosecution for Yeltsin and his
relatives who fear political opponents may try to seek vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Chechnya may not be as easy to control. Some 100,000
Russian troops are amassed there against several thousand Islamic
militants. Yet the Russian forces have been unable to secure the
capital, Grozny, and reports filtering out of the republic suggest
that Russian casualties are much higher than the state-controlled
media in Moscow have reported.
</P>
<P>
   The first test facing Putin and Russia is whether the conflict
in Chechnya will become a protracted guerrilla war _ and will the
public care as they did when Russia's 1994-96 operation there ended
in disaster. So far, Putin and the Kremlin have been adept at
pressing the war and manipulating the Russian media to rally public
support.
</P>
<P>
   The popular support for Putin and the war translated into
significant gains for a pro-Kremlin party which fared well in
parliamentary elections in mid-December. Thus, Putin will have
natural allies in the new Duma, the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Deeper questions remain, though, over how Putin will deal with a
long line of Russian ills, including the economy and a social
safety net that has all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Putin made a successful leap from cold warrior to new Russian
policymaker. But his months as prime minister have not given a hint
of his vision for Russia, other than a war that seeks to protect
old boundaries. There is not much of a record to suggest his
political leanings or depth of commitment to democracy and market
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Putin and the Cabinet started a new Internet
Web site which featured a broad policy statement from the prime
minister entitled ``Russia at the Threshold of the Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The manifesto suggests that Russia must find its own way in a
centrist path that rejects both the Soviet past and an allegiance
to bold democratic reforms that have left most Russians poorer than
they were during Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Putin, in an apparent criticism of Yeltsin and his band of
reformers, said Russia's biggest mistake was to seek to transform
itself into a copy of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia will not soon, if ever, become a copy of the U.S.A. or,
say, Britain,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   But the former KGB spy also bluntly criticized the Soviet era,
which he said ``failed to make the country flourish, its society
dynamic, its people free.''
</P>
<P>
   With a long Russian and Soviet history of a central state
authority, ``Russia needs a strong state power and must have it,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can count on a worthy future only if we manage to naturally
combine the principles of a market economy and democracy with
Russia's realities,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, Putin remains allied with many of the reformers
that gained such a bad name working under Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   He started his political life in St. Petersburg (formerly
Leningrad), rising to the post of vice mayor under liberal mayor
Anatoly Sobchak. Known as a colorless, but effective, administrator
Putin earned the nickname the ``gray cardinal'' _ operating in the
shadows of his boss.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he came to Moscow in a move arranged by market reformer
Anatoly Chubais, a close Yeltsin advisor in the mid-1990's. Putin
became the deputy Kremlin administrator and later was put in charge
of the Kremlin's relations with Russia's powerful regional
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Putin was named head of the domestic security
service, the FSB, an arm of the former KGB, and in March was also
named secretary of the president's Security Council. In August, he
replaced Sergei Stepashin as prime minister in a surprise shuffle
by the unpredictable Yeltsin that had many Kremlin-watchers
wondering just how long Putin would last in the job.
</P>
<P>
   (Charles Holmes recently returned to Washington from a
three-year assignment in Moscow as Cox Newspapers' correspondent
there. His email address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
