<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3526 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-MARKET-NYT &LR;      12-31 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN STOCKS SOAR IN WAKE OF YELSTIN'S RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-YELTSIN) 
(bl) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin's resignation Friday drove
Russian stocks to their highest levels since the 1998 economic
collapse, reflecting hope among investors that Acting President
Vladimir Putin would revive stalled economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Trading System stock index, the main stock market
barometer in the country, rose 18 percent to 177.71. The increase
was the greatest one-day jump since July 14, 1998, when the
International Monetary Fund agreed to lend Russia $22.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But a month later, the Russian economy collapsed. Since then,
the market had languished, with periodic rallies occurring on very
low volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Russian company stocks traded in the United States rallied
Friday as well. Shares of cellular provider Vimpel Communications,
the first Russian company to be listed on the New York Stock
Exchange, rose 24.2 percent to $41. The Templeton Russia Fund, a
mutual fund that invests primarily in Russian companies, rose 35
percent to $19.9375.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Telecom Inc., a Russian telecommunications and Internet
company traded on the Nasdaq market, rose 164 percent to $32.
</P>
<P>
   Shares rose on optimism that Yeltsin's surprise resignation will
pave the way for financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund said the resignation would not
change its relationship with Russia. ``We are not into the
political side of things,'' said Stanely Fischer, the deputy
managing director of the Washington-based agency.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yeltsin initiated the changes that have given Russia
the beginnings of a market economy, little progress has occurred in
the last few years. Yeltsin has either been too ill or too
preoccupied with Kremlin political intrigues to forcefully push
reforms through Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The hope among investors now is that the younger, apparently
decisive Putin will take up reforms that have been stalled or
shelved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1559EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
