<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3528 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-0101-     12-31 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-0101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILLENNIUM CELEBRATIONS LINK PLANET AS Y2K FEARS ABATE
 &HT;    EDs: This story will be updated during the evening.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS and MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As clocks ticked past midnight on Friday across the
planet, billions of people from all corners of the Earth joined in
a satellite-linked celebration of a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Casting aside technical arguments that the third millennium of
the Christian Era will not actually start for another year,
hundreds of millions of people partied around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But widespread joy at the long-waited advent of the year 2000
was tempered in some places by fears of terrorism and technology
gone awry. And security concerns threatened to cast a pall over the
millennial festivities in some mega-cities.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly 200 countries, governments, financial firms,
communications' carriers and airlines girded for signs of the
dreaded Y2K bug, which could cause computer systems to fail at the
stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications, however, suggested that the hundreds of
billions of dollars spent stamping out Y2K software bugs appear to
have paid off. As the world's computers moved smoothly through the
transition to 2000, potential problems appeared well in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money has been well spent,'' John Koskinen, the nation's
Y2K czar, said as upbeat reports about computer operations poured
into his Washington command post. As midnight struck in one country
after another around the world, no governments reported significant
problems with telecommunications systems, banks, power grids or
other vital systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Year 2000
Conversion, warned Americans not to relax entirely. The full impact
of the Y2K software flaw may not be felt until factories and
offices open for business next week.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the tiny South Pacific island of Kiribati became the
first nation to see the dawn of the new millennium. It occurred at
5 a.m. EST. Kiribati was so intent on being the first that it
realigned its chunk of the international date line east by two
hours to stage the first ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   While Y2K seemingly fizzled out as a big news story, Russian
President Boris Yeltsin managed to startle the world on the last
day of the 20th century by choosing to resign after eight years as
leader of the world's largest country.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the New Year's Eve ceremonies, world leaders paused to pay
tribute to Yeltsin's key role in stage-managing the collapse, after
more than 70 years, of the communist-led Soviet Union and his
championing of market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under his leadership since 1991, the Russian people have faced
the unprecedented challenge of creating new institutions and
building a new life after decades of corrosive communist rule,''
said President Clinton _ whose own term spans the millennium but
ends in just over a year.
</P>
<P>
   Word that Yeltsin had stepped down and handed the reins of power
to Prime Minister Vladimir Putin had scant impact on Russian and
U.S. military officers who worked jointly at Peterson Air Force
Base in Colorado Springs, Colo. to ensure that the millennial
computer bug does not trigger an unwarranted nuclear alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no glitches, everything is working smoothly.
We're in contact with Moscow all the time,'' U.S. Air Force Col.
Mike Therrien told reporters after the completion of the first duty
shift at the special Center for Year 2000 Strategic Stability.
Russian and American military experts at the command center sat
side by side, jointly monitoring nuclear missile launch warning
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Further reason to celebrate came when five hijackers freed all
155 hostages aboard an Indian Airlines plane in Afghanistan after
India released two Muslim militants and an Islamic cleric, ending a
crisis that began on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   But most New Year revelers seemingly paid scant attention to the
relentless flow of world events. Nearly a million people crowded
the shores of Sydney Harbor as the city that will play host to the
2000 Olympics saw in the new millennium with the biggest fireworks
display and party in Australian history.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial celebration in Fuji, New Zealand, Australia,
Japan, the Russian Far East, the Indian subcontinent and the Middle
East each marked the advent of a new century. None of these regions
reported major problems caused by the Y2K computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said key sectors in his
country were all operating normally ``It's looking good so far,''
echoed Senator Ian Campbell, parliamentary secretary to Australia's
communications minister, after midnight came to Canberra.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, the first of the world's mega-cities to enter the new
millennium, crowds swarmed into the bayside area for rock concerts,
traditional drum performances and another lavish fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expected upwards of two million visitors to jam Times
Square in New York City, the largest such gathering since the
traditional event began in 1904.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 miles to the south, the nation's capital basked for
much of the day in unusual near-spring like temperatures as tens of
thousands of people flocked to the Lincoln Memorial for a
millennium bash to be topped off at midnight with a spectacular
high-tech sound, light and fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 seconds before midnight, Clinton and a group of children
were scheduled to light a fuse at the base of the Lincoln Memorial
that will travel across the reflecting pool in a spout of fireworks
to the base of the Washington Monument. The president's millennium
plans called for no fewer than three speeches and two separate
White House parties.
</P>
<P>
   The final ``Midnight Moment,'' held amid extraordinarily tight
security precautions, required 3,120 hours of preparation, 15 days
to set up, 135 miles of wiring, 26 pyrotechnists and 188 firing
cues.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different sort of technological challenge that, five
years ago, caused the Gartner Group, a technology research firm, to
forecast that it would cost Americans as much as $600 billion to
fix computer programs that read two-digit ``00'' dates as 1900
instead of 2000 in the trillions of lines of code that make up
systems controlling everything from airplane traffic to banking
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, many computer experts feared programmers would not
be able to complete the job by 2000, especially in poorer
countries. But international cooperation appears to have paid off,
with richer countries helping poorer ones move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the firm's prediction proved to be well off the
mark: The Department of Commerce currently estimates U.S. costs at
about $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the need to fix the glitches helped fuel robust growth in
the computer industry and brought out of retirement many
programmers who had created the problem in 1960s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
   It was a millennium that left much of the world wealthier and
healthier than when it began 1,000 years ago. Particularly in the
Western world, the past 250 years has brought a sharp rise in
personal incomes and living standards. Despite many setbacks, since
the French Revolution in 1789, the world has also steadily turned
toward a democratic way of life.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying Industrial Revolution that began around 1750
has seen the world's population increase nearly eight-fold until
today it numbers about 6 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass can be reached by e-mail at:
andyg(at)coxnews.com. Marilyn Geewax can be reached at:
mgeewax(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
