<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN01-COX     12-31 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A simpler turn of century
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ My friend Cathy's grandmother is 106, and of
sounder mind, Cathy suspects, than she is herself, most days. So
Cathy will be spending New Year's Day with the woman who vividly
remembers the last turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandmother remembers her father shaking her awake. ``It's
1900!'' he cried, and the little girl heard the sounds of
celebrations in the streets of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of Y2K hysteria, we can't imagine the unbridled joy
of that celebration. The revelers had no fear of terrorists on
Times Square, computer meltdown, wayward nuclear missiles or
overhyped media events.
</P>
<P>
   But they faced daily terrors nearly inconceivable to us. They
didn't have to worry about some lunatic pulling a pistol on them at
the mall, but they knew they could be carried off any day by
influenza or pneumonia. Dying in childbirth or losing a child to
diphtheria were very real possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have to worry about Y2K, but they knew what it was
like to work 14-hour days, and to stoke a coal furnace.
</P>
<P>
   The things they feared _ and didn't fear _ tell us a great deal
about all that has been marvelous, and all that has been horrible,
about this century.
</P>
<P>
   It was a world without airplanes _ and without the atomic bomb.
It was a world without penicillin _ and without presentiment of
world war, the Holocaust, Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine waking up to a new century without the leaden weight of
those realities, the Pandora's Box of knowledge we dare not open
very often. It's too painful.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why this year _ the biggest New Year of them all _
my heart hasn't been in it. And I usually love New Year's Eve _
none of this namby-pamby ``I just want a nice quiet evening by the
fireplace'' for me.
</P>
<P>
   At first I thought my indifference was a by-product of my desire
never to hear the words ``Y2K'' and ``millennium'' for the rest of
my natural-born days.
</P>
<P>
   The deeper reason is that I haven't wanted to take stock of the
past century. For you can't contemplate the Wright Brothers and the
Man on the Moon (pause a moment here for hometown pride) without
remembering Hiroshima and Nagasaki. You can't celebrate Winston
Churchill and Mahatma Gandhi without confronting Adolf Hitler and
Josef Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   What would it have been like, to wake up New Year's Day 1900,
with only optimism and hope for what the shining new century would
bring?
</P>
<P>
   If only I'd had the brains to ask my grandparents when I still
could. Instead, I called the one friend who was around that night _
revered local educator Evangeline Lindsley, 103, of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   She spent New Year's Eve 1899 tucked in bed at her grandparents'
farm while her parents celebrated at a neighborhood square dance.
``They didn't make an awful lot of fuss about it,'' she recalls.
``They didn't make such a big to-do about it as they do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Her memory stretches from the assassination of President William
McKinley to the Columbine massacre. In the 1920s, she tdents
that Hitler would never be appointed prime minister, ``The German
people,'' she said, ``are too civilized to follow that man with the
funny little mustache.''
</P>
<P>
   Still an avid follower of the news, Lindsley grows disheartened
at times. Yet she has never lost faith that mankind can catch up to
the treacherous miracle of technology: ``They always have, haven't
they?''
</P>
<P>
   That's a hope to hold onto this New Year's Eve. That, and the
image of a small girl, shaken awake by her father _ ``It's 1900!''
_ and greeting the century, gleaming with promise like a newly
minted penny.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
