<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin shocked his
nation and the world Friday by announcing his resignation six
months before the end of his term, and handed over power to his
favored successor, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin. As final act to
an extraordinary career, Yeltsin, 68, chose the last day of the
year and the start of a four-day New Year's holiday in Russia to
upstage the new milennium, and try to assert control over a
succession battle that will set Russia's course for years to come.
By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ A profile of the acting president:
Vladimir Vladimirovich Putin, who loves holidays so much that he
observes Christmas on both the Julian and Gregorian calendars, now
has an extra reason to pop a cork on New Year's Eve. Whether the
145 million other Russians also should celebrate may not be clear
for months. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-HIJACK (Dateline to kum) _ Waving pistols in the air, five
hijackers sped off in waiting cars today with two Islamic militants
and a Muslim cleric released from Indian jails and were given 10
hours to find freedom, ending a tense eight-day standoff in
Afghanistan. All 155 hostages on the Indian Airlines plane were
freed unharmed. (summary from wires) By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
