<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-ADVANCE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arkansas' looks to end string of bowl losses
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Joe Dean Davenport was being flip when he filled out
the sports information questionnaire last summer and said of how he
would favor spending New Year's Eve 1999 ``at home sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows better now.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyb talks to us says, `Y'all have to go down there
and beat the hell out of those Horns,''' the Arkansas tight end
said. ``That's the extent of the conversation. Usually there's a,
`Hello, how're you doing?' Not now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. The Hogs started getting clued in about what
today's Cotton Bowl meant to state pride when former coach Frank
Broyles addressed them at a team meeting shortly after they
accepted the bowl's invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked to us about the '69 shootout,'' Dean said. ``He
remembers it play for play. He remembers the referees' names.''
</P>
<P>
   Today is Arkansas' chance for revenge, albeit 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas is to foil those plans, the Longhorns must:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pass the ball effectively. Texas wants to run, but the Horns
figure the best way to get their offense back on track is through
the air. The Horns will run more three and four-wide sets, trying
to spread out the Hogs and neutralize their pass rush. That will
make halfback Hodges Mitchell a more potent threat on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the Longhorn tight ends, particularly Bo Scaife, to
potentially play a major role.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid an early Arkansas onslaught that would only stoke the
Hogs' motivational fire. If Arkansas can shut down Texas
quarterback Major Applewhite early, the Horns' plan to get Chris
Simms some playing time could mean neither quarterback finds his
rhythm, a necessity if they are to end the frustration of six
consecutive scoreless quarters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep Razorbacks quarterback Clint Stoerner from scrambling and
making the big pass play deep by throwing it up to receivers
Anthony Lucas (6 feet 3 inches) and Boo Williams (6-5). Texas
safeties Lee Jackson and Greg Brown must help deep and bring some
wood.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remind the Hogs where they are. Arkansas hasn't won a bowl
game since an 18-17 victory over Arizona State in the 1985 Holiday
Bowl, a string
</P>
<P>
   of seven straight losses.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
