<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-COTTON-SUSPENSION     12-31 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-SUSPENSIONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four Longhorn players suspended for Cotton Bowl
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls, Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    and Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Four players from the University of Texas football
team, including All-Big 12 Conference performers Kwame Cavil and
Aaron Humphrey, were suspended late Thursday for violating team
rules and will not play in today's Cotton Bowl against Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Coach Mack Brown choked back tears as he announced the
suspensions at 11 p.m. Thursday after an hourlong meeting with his
team. Brown called the meeting ``one of the most emotional things
I've ever seen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two players suspended were backup defensive end J.J.
Kelly and linebacker Jamal Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   Brown would not say what rules the players violated, saying that
federal privacy laws precluded him from doing so. He said he
personally suspended the players.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Athletic Director DeLoss Dodds, who attended the
late-night press briefing, deferred comment to Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown would not say for how long the players were suspended,
only that they will miss the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great young men who I love and care about very much,''
Brown said. ``The team loves and cares about them very much. We
will continue to support them in every way we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this is very difficult. It's a major concern for our
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   A Texas player who attended the team meeting said Brown did not
tell the players why the four were suspended. Brown said the team
as a whole agreed not to speak to the media about the suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   In Humphrey and Cavil, Texas lost its leading pass rusher and
pass receiver. Humphrey was voted a team captain, and he has led
the Big 12 in quarterback sacks for the past two years. Freshman
Cory Redding will start in Humphrey's place, while sophomore
Montrell Flowers will start in Cavil's spot.
</P>
<P>
   Cavil was a third-team All-America selection and a unanimous
all-conference pick. He broke Big 12 records this season for
receptions (100) and total yards (1,188).
</P>
<P>
   Joyner and Kelly were not major contributors to the team this
season.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second scandal in the past four years to rock a
Texas football team during preparations for a bowl game. In 1995,
the day before the Longhorns met Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl in
New Orleans, it was revealed that reserve defensive back Ron
McKelvey actually was a 30-year-old named Ron Weaver, who had
already played six years of college football.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Longhorns were forced to suspend defensive back
Tony Griffin before the 1987 Bluebonnet Bowl after learning that
Griffin had flunked an NCAA drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Cavil missed two days of practice this week. He left Dallas on
Monday to attend the funeral of his grandmother in Waco and did not
return until Wednesday. Humphrey and Joyner missed Thursday's
practice, and team officials said at the time that both were
suffering from the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HARRISON-ATTACK-320&AMP;A     12-31 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRISON-ATTACK-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE HARRISON'S ATTACKER CHARGED WITH ATTEMPTED MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The man accused of stabbing George Harrison on Thursday
was charged with attempted murder on Friday and then sent to a
prison mental clinic for evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exceptional course of action, but we feel you need
treatment immediately,'' the magistrate presiding over the case
told the man, 33-year-old Michael Abram of Liverpool. The
magistrate, Tim Pocock, then adjourned the hearing until Feb. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Abram, who the police said was knocked unconscious by Harrison's
wife during the attack, is said by family members to be a former
heroin addict who is delusional, hears voices in his head and
harbors a strange hatred of the Beatles, whom he believes to be
``witches.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Lynda, told reporters that repeated attempts to get
help for her son had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had no help from anyone,'' she said. ``I feel as though
I have been totally isolated for the last six years. The system is
totally useless unless you commit a serious offense.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear how the intruder managed to gain access to
Harrison's well-secured estate, set inside electronic gates and
razor wire on 34 acres in Henley-on-Thames, about 25 miles west of
London. The struggle, in which Harrison, his wife, Olivia, and the
intruder were all injured, took place in several rooms in the huge
mansion, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, 56, was said to be in pain but recovering well Friday
after treatment for a collapsed lung at Harefield Hospital outside
of London.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Craig, general manager of the hospital, said that doctors
were working to reinflate the lung, which was damaged when Harrison
suffered a one-inch-deep stab wound in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a question of waiting for the treatment to take hold
until his lung reinflates,'' Craig said. ``We hope that he will be
able to go home in a couple of days, but that depends on the next
24 hours.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thames Valley police, who are handling the investigation, said
that it was still too early to say exactly what happened during the
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But what was most likely, police said, is that Abram attacked
Harrison first, slashing him repeatedly and stabbing him in the
chest, before inflicting superficial stab wounds on Mrs. Harrison,
51, when she intervened. Abram, police said, was then knocked
unconscious when Mrs. Harrison picked up a heavy table lamp and hit
him hard over the head.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Harrison suffered cuts and bruises in the attack, but was
released from the hospital. She spent Thursday night at Harrison's
bedside in the Harefield surgery ward.
</P>
<P>
   In his court appearance Friday, Abram had a heavily bruised
forehead and a black left eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
