<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-0101-COX     12-31 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-0101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K FEARS ABATE AS WORLD'S COMPUTERS MOVE SMOOTHLY TO 2000
 &HT;    EDs: You can expect a 1STLD writethru around 10 p.m. EST.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The hundreds of billions of dollars spent stamping
out Y2K software bugs appear to have paid off, with the world's
computers moving smoothly through the transition to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money has been well spent,'' John Koskinen, the nation's
Y2K czar, said Friday as upbeat reports about computer operations
poured into his command post. As midnight struck in one country
after another around the world, no governments reported significant
problems with telecommunications systems, banks, power grids or
other vital systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Year 2000
Conversion, warned Americans not to relax entirely. The full impact
of the Y2K software flaw may not be felt until factories and
offices open for business next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is far too early to declare victory,'' he said. ``I would
stress that we need to continue to monitor all of these systems
over the weekend _ and particularly on Monday when we open for
business again _ to see exactly what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   For several years, business and government leaders have been
pushing computer programmers to find and fix the so-called Y2K bug,
a software flaw that caused computers to read only the last two
digits of a date. For those computers, the date ``00'' was
understood as 1900, rather than 2000. Without repairs, that
seemingly simple problem could cause equipment to malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said Friday that U. S. taxpayers have spent about $8.5
billion fixing federal computers. Private industry has spent
another $100 billion. And perhaps another $200 billion has been
spent collectively by other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Getting business and political leaders to take the Y2K problem
seriously was difficult at first because few believed that a single
flaw could have such big implications. But many became converts in
1998 when store clerks starting finding customers' credit cards
being rejected whenever they had an expiration date of ``00.'' The
computerized equipment mistakenly assumed the cards had expired in
1900.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, the effort to wipe out the bug has been
massive, with the United States helping take the lead around the
world. Koskinen described the anti-bug campaign as ``the biggest
management problem the world has seen in 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, many computer experts feared programmers would not
be able to complete the job by 2000, especially in poorer
countries. But international cooperation appears to have paid off,
with richer countries helping poorer ones move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going as well as can be expected and maybe even
better,'' Bruce McConnell, director of the International Y2K
Cooperation Center, said Friday as developing nations turned in
positive reports as their midnights passed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most encouraging reports came Friday morning when the
first Russian nuclear plant to pass into Jan. 1 did so without
incident. Koskinen said the Bilibino Nuclear Heat and Power Plant
in northeast Siberia above the Arctic Circle operated normally
after rolling into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1636EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
