<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SPORTS-RECORDS01-COX     12-31 1721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-RECORDS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sports records: the core of our fascination with sports
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In ``World Record Breakers in Track and Field
Athletics,'' author Gerald Lawson wrote, ``There has always been a
touch of magic about a world record. At a moment in time, an
athlete has secured a performance unmatched by any other human
being. That is something special, even if the record only lasts one
day.''
</P>
<P>
   And if a record can stand well into a new millennium, that
really is something to savor. After watching Michael Johnson scorch
a world record 19.32-second 200-meter dash in the 1996 Olympics,
John Smith, a UCLA assistant track coach and a former record-holder
himself, gushed, ``What Michael did tonight blows my mind. He put
the record into the year 2105. They have `Star Trek' by that time.
That's just mind-boggling. I was reading the other day projections
for world records in the year 2080. The 200 was projected at
19.48.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been other remarkable, record-shattering performances
as the millennium drew to a close. This year Johnson got the
400-meter record that he chased for a decade, clocking a 43.18 to
take Butch Reynolds' name off the record book. Maurice Greene
blistered a 9.79-second time in the 100 meters, bettering the 9.84
that Donovan Bailey ran in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and equaling
the expunged record that a steroid-laced Ben Johnson ran in the
1988 Seoul Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps foreshadowing a truly memorable Olympics in 2000, a rash
of swimming records was broken, including some of the oldest ones.
South Africa's Penny Heyns broke six records in six weeks.
Australian Susie O'Neill and American Jenny Thompson erased
18-year-old marks of Madame Butterfly, Mary Meagher, although
Meagher's 200-meter long-course butterfly record remained on the
books.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when he walloped 70 homers, Mark McGwire destroyed a
record that had remained almost unchanged, except for an asterisk
attached to Roger Maris' name, for seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this year a giant, Wilt Chamberlain, passed away. He set
some standards that might stand until the next millennium _ along
with those of pitcher Nolan Ryan. As our chronometer rolls over to
2000 how close is man _ and woman _ to achieving their ultimate
athletic potential?
</P>
<P>
   When Frenchman Baron Pierre de Coubertin revived the Olympic
ideal in 1896 after a 1,500-year deep sleep, the world was just
beginning to re-emphasize the kind of athletic competition that had
been such a significant part of the ancient Greek culture. The
marks from the first modern Olympics, set by athletes from a
handful of countries, were rather modest indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-meter dash was won by the United States' Thomas Burke in
12.0 seconds, while the recognized world record at the time was
10.8. The winner of the marathon, a Greek shepherd named Spiridon
Louis, negotiated the 40,000 meters (modern marathons are 42,195
meters) in 2 hours, 58 minutes, 50 seconds. The shot was captured
by the United States' Robert Garrett with a modest put of 36 feet,
9 3/4 inches, while the world record at the time was 47 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Women did not compete in track in the Olympics until the 1928
games when Elizabeth Robinson won the 100 meters in 12.2 seconds.
The most strenuous throwing event that year was the discus, which
Poland's Halina Konopacka won with a world-record throw of 129-11
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Records for men and women have continued to tumble since. In
some events, such as the men's 100 meters, there's been only about
a 10 percent improvement. In other tests of skill, endurance or
strength, there have been leaps of 50 percent and more. The women's
discus record is now more than 250 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The records that stand out are FloJo's (Florence
Griffith-Joyner's) 100 and 200 meters and a lot of the throwing
records for men and women,'' said University of Texas assistant
track coach Dan Pfaff. ``Some of those throwing records were set by
Eastern countries in the rock and roll days.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith-Joyner, who died on Sept. 21, 1998, after suffocating
from an epileptic seizure in her sleep, set world records of 10.49
seconds in the 100 and 21.34 seconds in the 200 at the 1988 Seoul
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The use of steroids by some athletes, which is generally thought
to have started in the 1960s, has made it harder to determine what
the natural human limits really are.
</P>
<P>
   ``When anabolic steroids came on the scene it changed everything
and it changed everything forever,'' said Terry Todd, a UT
professor who is an expert on strength sports.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Pfaff said that advances in training, nutrition and injury
prevention have been such that even with increasingly tighter drug
testing, records will continue to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of technology involved,'' Pfaff said. ``Twenty
years ago it wasn't too cool for a sprinter to be a weightlifter.
That's changed. We're still learning a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Gobel, assistant director of athletic performance at
Nebraska, added, ``It's going to keep growing. It's like Bob
Beamon's long jump. No one ever thought that could be broken. Our
kids keep getting bigger and stronger ... (1972 Heisman Trophy
winner) Johnny Rodgers ran a 4.6-second 40-yard dash and we thought
that was great. Now, 4.6 is average for a guy at that position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see significant improvement. That's without creating
a person who's superhuman,'' said Eddie Coyle who heads UT's Human
Performance Lab.
</P>
<P>
   Coyle elaborated, ``One approach for predicting such performance
is mathematical. It's not linear, it's curvilinear.''
</P>
<P>
   A linear progression would mean that, for example, the time in
the 100 meter dash would drop a tenth of a second every decade. A
curvilinear model would project that performance increases would
slow as better marks were set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another method is physiological,'' Coyle said. ``What if you
had a person who could pump the most blood, whose muscles were the
most efficient? In the marathon people have the potential to run
under two hours. Right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyle, who has worked with Tour de France champion Lance
Armstrong, said a person with the best of everything could run --
marathon in 1:50, about 15 minutes better than the current record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tested 10K runners where we projected they could run the
marathon in two hours. They ran times of 2:10. My guess is they
didn't train the way they needed to train,'' Coyle said.
</P>
<P>
   He said one big way records can be broken is by fast athletes
moving up to longer events. But, there's a natural tendency that
prevents that from happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``In track and field, athletes tend to compete at the shortest
distance they can be successful at,'' Coyle said.
</P>
<P>
   An example might be Tommie Smith, an incredible 200-meter runner
in the 1960s. He ran the 400 meters only a few times. In 1967,
Smith, whose future was so bright in the 400 that he was wearing
shades for the race, convincingly beat Lee Evans while setting a
world record of 44.5. seconds. He didn't race at that distance
again, while Evans won the gold in the Mexico City Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Coyle said, ``Now, you have athletes competing at 200 and 400
meters that 10 to 20 years ago would have been running the 100 and
200.''
</P>
<P>
   The same moving-on-up principle could work in other sports as
well. Coyle said of current University of Texas women's swim coach,
``Jill Sterkel was a world-class sprinter. We did a lot of tests on
her and she also had great endurance, and she had the
determination. She would have been great at the 200 and 400. She
used to say, `Don't tell my coach.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coyle said records could be broken if athletes tried different
sports. He said, ``The talent we see at UT or the Texas Relays, if
it were focused on bicycling, we could have a lot of world records
with the power output that some of those athletes have.''
</P>
<P>
   Men and women are also continuing to set records in strength
events, although comparisons across eras can be tricky.
</P>
<P>
   Todd said, ``One of the problems is the accuracy. Exaggeration
was more common in the early days than steroids are today. You
might have 20 different people claiming they were the world's
strongest man. This is a field in which legends build easily.
People get Paul Bunyanized ... You have to go by competition or
things done in a public fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd said, ``In power lifting, records have shot up. No one
bench pressed 700 pounds in the middle 1970s. Now you have dozens
of guys at 700.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those advances, Todd said, are due to sophisticated
gear. He added that some of the earlier strong men could hold their
own with the implements they used back then. One, turn of the
century strongman, Louis ``Apollon'' Uni, used to lift overhead a
barbell that was actually a set of railroad wheels weighing about
365 pounds. The almost two-inch thickness of the axle and the fact
that the wheels didn't spin the way free weights do made lifting it
quite a feat.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1950, two famous American weightlifters attempted to lift
Apollon's Wheel. John Davis did it on his fourth try, while Norbert
Schemansky was able to jerk it overhead a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   Todd would like to get permission for Mark Henry to try to lift
the wheel, which is in France. He thinks Henry should be able to do
a more difficult lift with it, the press, and make a statement
about just where man stands heading into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1997 book, Lawson projected that 12 of the current track
and field records would still be around in 2015. In addition to
Johnson's 200-meter record, they were the 400-meter hurdles, the
triple jump and discus. For the women it was FloJo's 100- and
200-meter times and the 400, 1,500, 3,000 and 10,000 meters and the
discus and javelin marks.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson wrote, ``The idea that human beings can continue to
improve on what has been achieved in the past is an uplifting one,
whatever the field of endeavor. It would be a sad day if no further
world records were possible. More encouraging is the belief that
out there somewhere are future champions who will one day set world
records that will make us shake our heads in disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   John Maher writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1641EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
