<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3557 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW-YEAREND01-COX     12-31 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-YEAREND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It was a very, very good year on Wall Street
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The longest bull market in history showed no signs of
letup Friday as the major stock averages ended the 20th century at
record highs. The day's action rounded out a year that gave
investors an unprecedented fifth straight year of double-digit
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the surprising resignation of Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, nor the highly anticipated arrival of 2000, put a damper
on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was extremely light in an abbreviated session, with many
professionals leaving early for the New Year's holiday. But the Dow
Jones industrial average closed at 11,497.12, the Nasdaq composite
at 4,069.31, Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 at 1,469.25 and the Russell 2000
at 504.75. All were records.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, most analysts said the year's big stock market
story was technology _ especially the Internet, which allowed
individual investors to bypass Wall Street institutions via
burgeoning online trading.
</P>
<P>
   Two major stock averages broke into new territory last year that
most analysts had not anticipated would be entered for another year
or so.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average topped 10,000 in March and
moved above 11,000 six weeks later. The Nasdaq composite soared
above 3,000 for the first time in November, and 4,000 two months
later.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of the technology-loaded Nasdaq composite confirmed
that a ``new economy'' based on productivity-enhancing
information-age equipment was here, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The technology decade was marked by record-setting economic
growth, minimal inflation and falling interest rates that
encouraged the growth of individual investing.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the stock market became the engine that
drove the economy, thanks to the ``wealth effect'' earned by nearly
79 million Americans from stock and mutual fund investments. One
study showed the total value of the world's stocks was almost $45
trillion, or more than the world's economic output.
</P>
<P>
   Last year also had a downside that might have hurt the markets,
but didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year was full of negative events and surprises that kept
us on our toes,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market strategist
for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was Y2K, the Clinton impeachment trial, expectations for
a weakening economy, economic problems in South America, fear of
the Federal Reserve (interest rate increases).''
</P>
<P>
   He also said 1999 will be remembered as ``a year of few `haves'
and many ``have-not' stocks.'' That's a reference to the narrow
range of investor buying that boosted blue chips and big stocks for
most of the year, while the bulk of stocks lagged the leaders or
lost money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Approximately 63 percent of all New York Stock Exchange stocks
declined an average of 29 percent,'' said Goldman. ``While the S&AMP;P
500 was up some 19 percent, the index would have barely budged if
not for its technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Goldman, investors narrowed their focus last year
out of fear of rising interest rates, prompting them to seek safety
in known quality. The prospect that the Fed might raise interest
rates again in 2000 continued to worry investors at year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the achievement of the indexes was mind-boggling
by any standard. Five straight years of double-digit growth was
regarded by most analysts as practically impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite surged almost 86 percent in 1999 and almost
1,150 percent during the decade, largely on the technology
momentum. Nothing like that had happened since 1915, when the Dow
rose 82 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which was revised in October to better reflect the
``new economy,'' rose 25 percent, significantly better than the
previous year's 16 percent. Four ``new economy'' stocks were added
_ Microsoft, Intel, SBC Communications and Home Depot _ replacing
``old economy'' standbys Chevron, Goodyear, Sears, Roebuck and
Union Carbide.
</P>
<P>
   The broader S&AMP;P-500 index rose more than 19 percent in 1999,
against 27 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the Nasdaq, the best performer was the Russell 2000
index of smaller capitalized stocks, which gained almost 20 percent
in 1999, reversing the year-earlier decline of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts saw the fourth-quarter surge of the Nasdaq and the
Russell 2000 indexes as evidence that trading may finally be
expanding to the mid-sized and smaller laggards _ a trend
strategists say would strengthen the market overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think technology will outperform through 2000 as a whole,
but non-tech stocks with solid fundamentals have appeal for near-
and long-term appreciation,'' said Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst Arnold
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   With little domestic news to move the markets on Friday,
analysts said traders and investors bought the same stocks that had
dominated trading all year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
