<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV07-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL TALKING TO THE ANIMALS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday, Jan. 7)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laura Weeks can bring her two cats to the job and be sung to by
a big bird who knows ``Un Bel Di'' from ``Madame Butterfly,'' so
maybe it's no wonder she's still working full time at age 80.
</P>
<P>
   Laura said she once read that people who work in retail are
happiest in hardware, garden and pet stores. She's been in the pet
business for 53 years and says, ``I can't think of anything else I
would rather do.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling she's always thought this way, that it's not
just a retrospective look. As the Social Security system pushes
people to work longer, Laura is an example of finding something you
love enough to do forever.
</P>
<P>
   She's happy around animals, even the rats and snakes, but also
delights in the mushy, protective way people act around their pets.
``I love seeing a big, tough guy cuddling his tiny dog and talking
baby talk.''
</P>
<P>
   She's learned that ``people will relate to any kind of a living
thing. It brings out the human in them,'' she says, pursing her
lips at Cyrano the toucan, whose trick is to gently take a grape
from Laura's mouth with his beak.
</P>
<P>
   Laura, who works 10-hour days, owns a pet store in Sebastopol,
Calif., with another woman, Dianne Lloyd, whom she met at a dog
show. Their pet shop, full of squawking, crawly things, is the kind
you remember as a Main Street regular if you grew up in a premall
era.
</P>
<P>
   There's a swivel-hipped tangerine-colored iguana who sashays
around the store, and a gray Amazon parrot, named Dorian, who can
sing ``Falling in Love Again'' with a Marlene Dietrich accent.
Another tropical beauty, named Kiri after the singer Kiri Ti
Kanawa, is the Madame Butterfly diva.
</P>
<P>
   This is a pet store where they play opera and serve guests
biscotti and coffee. But it still smells like a pet store _ a rich,
earthy blend of alfalfa, bird feathers and visiting dog. It's how
my daughter's bedroom smelled the year she had mice. It's one of
those places that, when it closes, people will get nostalgic about
and wonder what happened to the older woman in the green apron.
It's a throwback. They don't even take credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Laura maintains, ``You can always make a living in the pet
business. Even in a depression or a recession people take care of
their pets.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura left an oil refinery job and cashed in war bonds to open
her first pet store on Solano Avenue on the Berkeley-Albany border
after World War II. It was 1946 and women business owners were
rare. ``My suppliers bet I'd be gone in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   This was before kibble and pet diet food, and Laura stocked
horsemeat that she cut and ground herself for pet food _ and
sometimes, she suspects, for people food. ``I had people tell me if
you doctor it up with garlic you couldn't tell it wasn't beef.''
</P>
<P>
   She sold the East Bay store in 1982 and bought property in
Healdsburg with her sister, but, she said, ``I'm not any good at
gardening,'' and went looking for another pet store.
</P>
<P>
   All along she's learned as much about people as animals. She has
regulars who stop in ``for their bird fix'' or to make eye contact
with the fierce-looking bearded dragon lizard.
</P>
<P>
   One day a customer came in looking for milk for a baby gopher.
``She'd found a little gopher on the ground and she couldn't kill
it. It ended up becoming her pet. She named it Go-Go and it would
sit on the couch with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no end to what people will bond with,'' says Laura.
</P>
<P>
   If when you are 80 you are still learning about God's creatures,
even the human ones, and you are able to haul your own 40-pound
feed bags, they will say you probably made the right career choice.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
