<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-HIJACKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN PRAISES TALIBAN FOR `MATURITY' IN BROKERING END OF
HIJACKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (With INDIA-HIJACKING) 
(nk) 
 By BARRY BEARAK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistan's government welcomed the
peaceful end of the hijacking ordeal in neighboring Afghanistan
and, like a proud older brother, praised that country's Taliban
leaders on Friday for ``showing great responsibility and maturity''
in managing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their approach throughout this period of stress has been
imbued with a sense of humanitarian concern and care and opposition
to terrorism which has earned them the appreciation of the entire
international community,'' read a testimonial from Pakistan's
ministry of foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan, along with Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates,
are the only countries that recognize the legitimacy of the Taliban
government, which, as the host to Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born
exile accused by the United States of sponsoring terrorism, is not
usually blessed as a peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Javed Jabbar, an aide to Pakistan's military ruler, Gen. Pervez
Musharraf, also credited the Taliban with ``maturity'' in serving
as the stern but judicious broker in securing a deal between the
Indian government and five desperate hijackers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the past week may amend somewhat the Western image of
the Taliban, who control most of Afghanistan and have been fighting
to take the rest, as unyielding religious fanatics preoccupied with
the head-to-toe swathing of Afghanistan's women and the maintenance
of untrimmed facial hair on its men.
</P>
<P>
   Will the world now be ready to declare the Taliban
rehabilitated? Probably not. But the Taliban may not be seen quite
so one-dimensionally as before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West in particular tends to draw pictures entirely in
black and white, and then we act surprised if people don't turn out
to be as bad as we thought,'' said Paula Newberg, who has written
about Afghanistan for the Carnegie Endowment for International
Peace in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Newberg does not believe that recent events will end the
Taliban's pariah status with other countries, though ``this may go
a small way toward changing the adjectives in which the Taliban are
described and considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what role the Taliban played in the hostage ordeal is
still largely unknown, as is the fate of the five hijackers and the
three militants freed from Indian prisons in the bartering.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the hostages were freed, the Taliban
foreign minister, Abdul Wakil Muttawakil, said the hijackers and
released militants were being given 10 hours to leave the country
by road. He said a Taliban official has accompanied the men to
insure their safe passage. He gave no indication where they might
be heading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
