<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-MIAMI-ARENA01-COX     12-31 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MIAMI-ARENA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami Heat ready to unveil a showplace of an arena
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Opening-night jitters for a new NBA arena start long
before the first tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Heat's first game Sunday at the $203million
AmericanAirlines Arena comes after a manic, around-the-clock push
by hundreds of hardhats painting, hauling, sanding, sweeping,
wiring and installing. The sold-out 7:30p.m. game with the Orlando
Magic follows a sold-out Gloria Estefan New Year's Eve concert.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sixth new NBA arena to open this season after Los
Angeles, Toronto, Indianapolis, Denver and Atlanta. American
Airlines paid $42million for naming rights covering 20 years, with
the price including a silhouette of an airplane on the roof and an
airplane design on the carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to christen it right,'' says Alonzo Mourning, the
Heat's center, ``and christening it right means we come out with a
win. That's my only concern going into that new arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Heat players will dress in the kind of luxury that's a
far cry from a locker room. Heat management calls it a ``players'
lounge'' and it's in-the-round. Cherry-wood ``lockers'' trimmed in
black, each the size of a phone booth, circle the room. The ceiling
is a white, acoustic dome sprinkled with pin lights that shine down
on the Heat logo set in marble tile at the room's center.
</P>
<P>
   Heat coach Pat Riley wanted a round locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a circular dining table,'' explains Jay Cross, the Heat's
president of basketball properties, ``everyone is treated equally
and is part of the circle.''
</P>
<P>
   From the round room, players are only a few steps from an
extra-large sauna, whirlpool, showers, grooming area and training
room that Cross describes as ``a miniature sports hospital.'' It's
a short walk to a full-size court in the training center facing
Biscayne Bay.There are two sets of offices for coaches, one just
for game days, along with a video coaching room.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to compare with this in the NBA,'' Cross
says. Or the WNBA, which includes Miami's unnamed expansion team
that begins a 32-game schedule in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' Mourning says. ``I've been to every NBA
arena in the country and we have the best arena by far and I'm not
saying that just to be biased. The best location. It's on the bay.
The suites are beautiful. The architecture is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami architect Bernardo Fort-Brescia designed the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a controversial site,'' he says. ``I was always
concerned about a building of this size on the waterfront being
perceived as obtrusive. I was convinced I could do something
sculptural that would contribute to the betterment of the
waterfront.''
</P>
<P>
   The outside of the arena is a combination of glass and curved
white facades suspended off the ground to create the look of a
ship's sails. The Heat's colors _ red, yellow, orange _ are the
arena's theme from seats to lights. Inside lighting has an inferno
effect that, from a distance on game nights, makes the inside of
the arena appear on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Not building an arena to accommodate hockey, which needs four
times the playing surface of basketball, will please Heat fans,
Cross predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The geometry of the building is different,'' he says. ``It's a
much tighter bowl. Most arenas are built with hockey in mind or ice
shows. Ours is built only for basketball. The seats come down to
the ends of the court, which makes everything much tighter and
allows for 4,000 more seats (than the Miami Arena) in the lower
bowl. The basketball court is built more like a stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans in the cheapest seats will need binoculars to see that
stage. The 3,200 ``end zone'' seats are $5 but will be sold only
when a full house is anticipated for a marquee team such as the
Lakers, Spurs or Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're at center court and look at the last seat in the
balcony, it's no further than the last seat in the Miami Arena,''
Cross says.
</P>
<P>
   Premium seats at premium prices add up to 42 percent of the
arena's 19,600 seats. The additional 4,000 top-dollar seats along
with lounges and boxes are expected to generate $15million a year,
which is why the Heat wanted to leave the 11-year-old, 15,500-seat
Miami Arena three blocks west. The biggest chunk of the arena's
cost was paid by corporate bonds, in part personally guaranteed by
Heat owner Micky Arison.
</P>
<P>
   Seats in the first 10 rows courtside are $150 per game, $6,150
per season. Suites and loge seats range from $10,000 to $160,000
annually, and if those aren't good enough, there are four ``Star
Boxes'' at $500,000 and two ``Junior Star Boxes'' at $400,000, but
they're sold out. Good for any arena event, the big-buck boxes come
with an attendant, catered gourmet food and the best courtside
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County individuals and businesses account for 12
percent of Heat season tickets. All premium-seat season-ticket
owners park under the arena while everyone else competes for $10 to
$20 spaces that can be a three-quarter-mile walk.
</P>
<P>
   What you pay will determine where you can eat. All fans can go
to the Bacardi Bar, but only premium-seat season-tickets holders
can get into Club Chivas Regal and only Star Box owners will be
admitted to the Flagship Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   The plush, new palace opens for the Heat on Sunday, which leads
Mourning to think more work is ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is filling it ... because the more people that are in
the stands, the harder we're going to play. Believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
