<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS PLAYERS' CHOICE: BILL BELICHICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Who would the Patriots want as head coach if
Pete Carroll is dismissed after Sunday's game against the Baltimore
Ravens?
</P>
<P>
   The players' choice is Bill Belichick, the assistant head coach
and defensive coordinator of the New York Jets, though the same
players think owner Bob Kraft would go after former Kansas City
Chiefs coach Marty Schottenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players, there is also a great deal of respect for
in-house candidates such as defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell and
defensive line coach Ray Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Patriots veterans were asked their preference over the
past week with the condition their names not be used. Most don't
want to see Carroll fired but seem resigned to the fact he will be.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the players' choice isn't always the best one, but
there still many players remaining from Belichick's time in New
England who respect him as a defensive guru and leader.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, who returned Friday from a holiday trip to Puerto Rico,
also respects Belichick, but getting him out of New York would be
difficult. Belichick has probably the best contract of any
assistant in the league, making upwards of $800,000 this season
after reportedly receiving a $1 million bonus from owner Leon Hess
after last season.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick also has a contract in place that would make him Jets
coach when Bill Parcells steps down and also would make him one of
the highest-paid coaches in the league. Belichick is loyal to
Parcells, but there is speculation that he is eager to rejoin the
head coaching ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick would need to bring in a good offensive coordinator
because, as Carroll has with the Patriots, he had problems
overseeing the offense in his first head job in Cleveland. He's
also not media friendly, which could pose a problem in a big market
like Boston.
</P>
<P>
   According to one Patriots player, ``He understands this team as
well as anyone. He knows the key players and what makes them
tick.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs spokesman Bob Moore says Kansas City would seek
compensation, similiar to what the Jets gave the Patriots for
Parcells, from a team that hires Schottenheimer. According to the
Chiefs, Schottenheimer is still officially under contract with them
through next season.
</P>
<P>
   There are the annual hot coordinators, such as Jacksonville's
Dom Capers (defense) and St. Louis's Mike Martz (offense). Atlanta
offensive line coach Art Shell, whose team had a horrible year, and
Denver offensive coordinator Gary Kubiak (facing life without John
Elway) saw their stock drop.
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell, 55, wants to be a head coach after several years of
designing effective defenses for the Saints, Oilers, and Patriots.
Sidwell's name has been thrown around in New Orleans as a possible
successor to Mike Ditka.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft went with Sidwell, it would not disrupt the Patriots'
defense, which played very well this season. It would keep the good
parts of the team intact. After all, the Patriots will finish 8-8
or 7-9, not 2-14.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton would be an interesting choice. He's never been a
coordinator, but that doesn't seem to be a prerequisite anymore
after the hirings of Andy Reid in Philadelphia and Mike Riley in
San Diego. Hamilton has been a loyal soldier in the Patriots
organization, a fine player who has gone on and coached the
offensive lines of the Jets, Raiders, Buccaneers, and Patriots, as
well as taken the reigns as head coach of the semi-pro Bay State
Titans, where he brought along Arizona Cardinals pass rusher Eric
Swann.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, also regarded as a player personnel candidate, is one
of the bright young black coaches in the league and the NFL is
encouraging owners to hire blacks. There are only three black head
coaches in the league _ Dennis Green in Minnesota, Tony Dungy in
Tampa Bay, and Ray Rhodes in Green Bay _ while 67 percent of the
players are black.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
