<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SMART-DOLPHIN01-C     12-31 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SMART-DOLPHIN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former `Richie Redskin' playing it smart in Miami
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Coaches call plenty of players smart. The word
frequently shows up on laundry lists of terms describing men who
play football, along with big, strong, fast, athletic. They are
words that quickly lose their meaning when they're used on
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins defensive end Rich Owens, however, truly deserves his
label as smart.
</P>
<P>
   The man is reading a physics book _ and not for a class or to
impress anyone. It's just tossed in his locker and comes out
whenever he has spare time.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``The Elegant Universe'' by Brian Greene and Owens,
27, is reading it because he wants to understand the theories and
science behind the hard science fiction novels he reads regularly.
This book is heavy on Einstein, Newton and the speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something clicked in me and I just couldn't stop,'' he said of
the reading habit he picked up last season while recovering from a
major knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   So when Owens says he doesn't think playing against his former
team Sunday will be difficult or emotional even though he's less
than a year removed from his role as Washington's Richie Redskin
mascot, it's probably a well-considered answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it and I've thought about it,'' Owens said
this week. ``And I don't really see it as being, 'Oh God, the
Redskins.' I have flushed out all the angst about the former
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens spent the first four years of his career with the
Redskins, but he wasn't just any fifth-round draft choice from a
small college in Pennsylvania. The Lehigh graphic design major
became a defensive mascot after a coach called him ``Richie
Redskin'' during a meeting because he always wore a Redskins'
ballcap.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates, fans and the media quickly picked up on it.
</P>
<P>
   His 11-sack season in 1996 and the weekly television show he
co-hosted fueled his fame as a young star. Kids throughout the
Washington area, many of whom he met during his frequent talks at
elementary and junior schools, came to love him because he was
friendly and read comic books and didn't talk down to them.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins' public relations staff even called him ``Richie''
through most of his biography in the 1998 Redskins media guide.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes all that good history will make up for some of the
other moments.
</P>
<P>
   Owens admits he ``whined and moped'' through the 1997 season
after coaches asked him to play tackle instead of his more natural
end. His production fell off, his weight ballooned and then he tore
a knee ligament in a pre-season game in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said he improved his attitude that season but wasn't
around the team enough. He talked to coach Norv Turner and general
manager Charley Casserly after the season about his soon-to-end
contract and whether they wanted to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt honestly that they were kind of neutral about it,'' he
said. ``I didn't really feel like they were big-time enthusiastic,
and I guess coming off an injury, I can't blame them.''
</P>
<P>
   So he jumped at the chance to play for the Dolphins, especially
after watching film and seeing a defensive system he thought might
suit him better than Washington's. He signed a two-year contract in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Owens impressed coaches in training camp, played well early in
the season and earned the starting job at left defensive end after
Kenny Mixon got hurt in a motorcycle accident. And when Dolphins
coaches asked him to try tackle, Owens didn't mind at all this
time. He credited the maturity he gained last year for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult, but with the change in attitude, I was granted
a little bit more use of my brain than I had been using,'' Owens
said with a smile. ``As time went by, I just started picking it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he starts at left end, rotates in at right end, plays left
tackle on third down and rotates in at right tackle. He ranks
fourth on the team in tackles with 73. He has defensed five passes,
forced two fumbles and recovered one fumble. Most impressively,
Owens leads the team in quarterback sacks with 8.5 for 61 yards
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jimmy Johnson expected to get a strong player who would
help with the pass rush when he signed Owens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't anticipate him being as good a player as he is,''
Johnson said. ``The one key factor is he is so intelligent. He's
able to play all four spots and play them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens smiles when asked whether he'd like to reach double digits
in sack totals against his old team, but not because he wants to
show up the Redskins. He still has acquaintances on the team,
although not many friends, and still remembers his four years there
as some of the best of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He even still has fans there. Many write him from Maryland and
Virginia. He doesn't even mind that the Redskins reached the
playoffs for the first time in seven years the season he left
because he feels he's playing the best football of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's not about wins and losses for me,'' Owens said.
``I'd rather be playing some good football and doing what's good
for me. This is definitely a good place.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he's not worried about taking the former mascot home.
Washington's tumultuous season with new owner Daniel Snyder and the
struggling, 28th-ranked defense only make it easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that stuff is gone, the Richie Redskin and everything,
that's all gone,'' Owens said. ``It was fun and it was cool for
those four years, but it's gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
