<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MILLENNIUM-COMMENTARY     12-31 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-COMMENTARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AHEAD, LEAVING BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let it be proclaimed: This morning, this simple winter morning,
represents more than the beginning of a new age. It represents an
accomplishment for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   We have survived. And by doing so, we have warped the physics of
time.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time ever _ this is a moment our parents and our
grandparents and our great-grandparents never experienced,
something our children and grandchildren and great-grandchildren
never will relive _ we awakened with a startling realization:
</P>
<P>
   Today is tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Today, on an ordinary Saturday morning in an ordinary winter, we
begin a new day, a new month, a new year and mark the symbolic
start of a new century and a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But today, most important of all, we begin anew. The future, so
long symbolized by the forbidding number 2000, is here.
</P>
<P>
   This is 1/1/2000. This is the big, fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   But this is also the biggest fresh start ever.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a millennium changed, humankind was a smaller
presence on the planet. Its reach was smaller, its problems
smaller, its resources smaller, its dreams smaller, its need for a
fresh start smaller.
</P>
<P>
   But now we also know _ more than our forebears ever dreamed _
how small we are, how small a place in the universe we occupy, how
small is our capacity to change the course of history, or our
community, or even ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   And yet we know how big this moment is, how big the challenge
is, how big the opportunity is.
</P>
<P>
   It is this big: This morning, for the first time in our lives,
we can say, blithely but truthfully, that the tensions that divided
Europe twice in conflicts that spun into world wars happened in the
last century. We can look upon the divisions between East and West,
between capitalism and communism, between the industrial nations
and the undeveloped world, between big-government liberals and
supply-side conservatives, as vestiges of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The Dark Ages, the bubonic plague, and the Spanish Inquisition;
the Hundred Years' War, the Napoleonic wars, the Civil War, and the
Franco-Prussian War; anti-Semitism, anti-Catholicism, racism, and
sexism _ all these, plus bushels more, occurred in the last
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   We have never been able to say that before.
</P>
<P>
   We have hurtled toward this moment for a thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   We have traveled from a time when knowledge was the precious
province of the few, husbanded by cloistered monks, preserved in
isolated pockets, copied painstakingly by hand, to a time when
knowledge is the casual property of the many, disseminated by the
gentlest stroke on a keyboard, distributed to the farthest reaches
of the earth _ and, yes, even beyond.
</P>
<P>
   We have moved from a world where the top long-distance speed
measured what a man could walk in a day to a point where the speed
of sound has been conquered many times over. For millions of our
forebears, the longest journey they made in their lifetimes was the
trip to the market town. Today the market is on the desktop, and
wealth, once exchanged through barter, then through coins and paper
money, later through plastic credit cards, now moves in electronic
blips.
</P>
<P>
   We have gone so far, and yet there is so much farther to go. We
have tamed much of the savage side of nature, and yet we live in
deeper mortal terror of nuclear fire and chemicals than ever
before. We have eradicated smallpox from the face of the earth, and
yet we are impotent in the face of new diseases. We have achieved
great wealth, and yet we have not achieved the end of the tyranny
of greed.
</P>
<P>
   So much changed at midnight. But one thing, the central,
inescapable fact of human existence did not change.
</P>
<P>
   More than by our rulers, more than by biology, more than by
history, more than by nature, more than even by human nature, our
lives are governed by an inexorable process:
</P>
<P>
   Change.
</P>
<P>
   We can affect its pace and its trajectory, but we cannot affect
its stubborn will to press on, even if we stand in its way, legs
akimbo, arms flailing.
</P>
<P>
   In the last century it happened in the crackle of a single
moment: with bullets at Sarajevo in 1914 and Dallas in 1963, for
example, or with a pen's scratchy movement across a piece of paper
at the signing of the Social Security Act in 1935, or the unanimous
ruling in Brown v. Board of Education in 1954, or with the
combustion produced when Elvis Presley made his national television
debut on the Dorsey Brothers' ``Stage Show'' in 1956, or the
human-rights breakthrough that was the Voting Rights Act of 1965,
or when a Saturn V booster sent Apollo 11 aloft in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But change also happened quietly, while we were looking
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the last century, 14 of the 65 biggest
cities in the nation were in New England. At the conclusion of the
century, only one, Boston, made the cut. And in this case, the lack
of change spoke for big change itself. Boston's population at
century's end was 558,394 _ a loss of 2,398 souls in a hundred
years. In that same period, the population of Los Angeles, only
102,479 in the year 1900, leaped by nearly 3.5 million, far
surpassing Boston.
</P>
<P>
   While we were looking elsewhere, the complection of the country
changed. The slice of the nation represented by foreign-born Latin
Americans grew by a factor of 11. Americans' life expectancy
bounded from 47.3 years to 76.5 years. The portion of the average
family's disposible income devoted to purchasing food dropped from
24 percent to 11 percent. The number of women in the labor force
jumped from 5 million to 64 million. The number of cars registered
in the country grew from 8,000 to 207 million. The number of farms
dropped by more than half. And the percentage of American homes
with VCRs went from 0 to 83.
</P>
<P>
   All that in a century's time. All that in a tenth of a
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   And so this morning, this ordinary winter morning, we are
changing more than the calendar. We are changing, our nation is
changing, our world is changing.
</P>
<P>
   We are leaving behind a millennium where life was so precarious
that the father of Edward Gibbon, who at the height of the British
Empire chronicled the rise and fall of the Roman Empire, named his
six sons Edward because he assumed, correctly, that only one would
survive.
</P>
<P>
   We are leaving behind a millennium that witnessed the rise and
foreshadowed the fall of the nation-state. At the end of this
period the united Europe looks tantalizingly like Charlemagne's
empire, and the boundaries that once were tripwires for conflict
now have been all but erased in our wired world.
</P>
<P>
   We are leaving behind a millennium that perfected the air
conditioner but might have ruined Earth's climate. We are leaving
behind a millennium that put antibiotics in the medicine cabinet
but unleashed gas warfare on the battlefield. We are leaving behind
a millennium that created life in heroic in-vitro procedures but
destroyed lives in horrific concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   We have done good and we have done evil.
</P>
<P>
   We can do better.
</P>
<P>
   And so, this morning, when change is in the air, let's revive a
slogan from the last century and say, with relief, Goodbye to all
that. Let's remember that, after spending so much time getting
here, we finally have survived and arrived, and that today is
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is chief of The Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
