<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ROBERDS-WOES01-COX     12-31 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERDS-WOES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberds Inc. considers closing or selling stores
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Roberds Inc. is considering filing for
bankruptcy, selling the company or shedding portions of the
24-store chain as it struggles to pull out of financial dire
straits, company officials announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The home furnishings company, based in Dayton, saw some
improvement in early 1999 but posted a 54 cent per share loss in
the third quarter and suffered weak sales in October and November,
particularly in Ohio, company officials said. ``This weakness poses
a number of issues with respect to our profitability, line of
credit and liquidity. We need to take immediate action with respect
to all three issues,'' said Roberds President Robert M. Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the company is considering selling or closing
stores, selling or closing some of the company's geographic
marketing regions, reducing or eliminating product lines, or
reorganizing under federal bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we have had at least one outside party
express an interest in acquiring some or all of the company. We are
exploring that and other strategic alternatives,'' Wilson said. The
furniture and appliance retailer hired Deloitte Consulting LLC to
help.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Melvin Baskin said what changes will be made is
unknown but Roberds expects to ``move very rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Roberds violated terms of its line of credit, but the
bank amended the terms, increased the interest rate and required
Roberds to improve its performance, according to a document filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Roberds also failed to
meet the tangible net worth minimum by one of its mortgage loans
and the lender reduced the requirement, the document said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Roberds experienced labor troubles in some of its
stores. In October, Roberds sales clerks ratified their first
contract and dropped a call for a boycott of the chain. The United
Food and Commercial Workers Union Local 1099 represents about 200
sales clerks at seven Roberds stores.
</P>
<P>
   But the labor negotiations distracted sales clerks from their
jobs, the company said. In addition, the boycott may have hurt
sales and a big sales promotion in August fell flat _ all of which
contributed to poor sales figures in the third quarter, according
to the SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the company refinanced its revolving line of credit.
But by the end of September, $22.1 million of the $24.1 million
line of credit was tapped out, according to the SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials promised to spend the last quarter of 1999
boosting business and customer service, beefing up the sales force,
improving warehouse operations and inventory management, and
turning around sales trends, according to the SEC filing. But the
company warned that a regional furniture retailer in the Dayton
market and a new appliance and electronics retailer in the
Cincinnati area would put competitive pressure on prices and profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds has struggled the last few years. Sales totals slipped
from $342.1 million in 1996 to $318.7 million in 1998 and net
losses increased from $910,000 in 1996 to $16.1 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the first nine-months of 1999, net losses totaled $5.2
million and sales were $212.2 million, down 8.2 percent over the
first nine months of
</P>
<P>
   1998.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds' core problems track to its experiment in megastore
retailing. In 1996, the company opened Roberds Grand, a
250,000-square-foot store outside
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati. While the superstore is a success, it came at a
price. The company bragged it could deliver any item in the giant
store the next day.
</P>
<P>
   That required the retailer to stock its Fairborn warehouse with
expensive inventories that cut into profits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the company pared down its inventories, dumped thinly
profitable product lines such as personal computers and cut back on
the number of vendors. That restructuring came out of a plan
devised by Deloitte &AMP; Touche, accountants and consultants hired in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds operates stores in Ohio, Indiana, Georgia and Florida.
Founded in 1971, it has 1,900 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Roberds closed at $1.43 3/4 Friday. Shares fell 30
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
