<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Jan. 1, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the new year begins, the powerful zone of high pressure near
the Northwest Coast which has kept most of the Western states dry
and tranquil will dissipate initiating a trend toward cooler and
increasingly unsettled conditions across the region. Brisk onshore
winds will promote showery rain near the Northwest Coast.
Intermittent snow will be common along west-facing slopes from the
Cascades to the Bitterroots of Idaho and Montana. Valleys of the
interior Northwest will have patchy light snow and a few sprinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Periods of snow will occur from the mountains of northern
Arizona to southern Colorado and northern New Mexico as a jet
stream disturbance crosses the region. Otherwise, breezy and cooler
conditions will develop across the Southwest on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Colder air will spread south through the northern Rockies and
northern Plains. Milder air drawn north by developing low pressure
in western Kansas will be forced to rise over the colder air
resulting in increasing clouds from the central Plains to the
northern Mississippi Valley. A broken area of light snow and rain
will spread across these regions later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will turn milder as winds from the south increase.
Sunshine will be ample from southern New England to the Middle
Atlantic states and eastern Ohio Valley. Farther south, an area of
low clouds and a few light showers will linger near the southern
Appalachians. Otherwise, the Southeast will be mild and dry.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wetter Times
</P>
<P>
   The year that ended Friday was the only year of the 1990s when
precipitation across the nation was below the long term average.
Indeed, although regional droughts have been common, for the nation
as a whole there have only been seven dry years since 1970. One of
the most notable climate trends in the United States during the
past century has been a relatively steady increase in wetness. The
added precipitation has been the result of more days with extreme
rain that can produce flash flooding rather than a large increase
in the total number of days with precipitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
