<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-CITRUS-ADVANCE01-     12-31 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CITRUS-ADVANCE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators hoping to regain their swagger against Michigan State
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ The Florida Gators lost more than a shot at the
national championship and the SEC title when they finished the
season with consecutive losses, including the 34-7 embarrassment to
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   They lost their swagger.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Gators? Now, that really is a crock. ``Yeah, we have lost
some of that,'' Florida coach Steve Spurrier said. ``And the only
way to get it back is to start winning. It's like Vince Lombardi
said: `Winning is a habit. Unfortunately, so is losing.'''
</P>
<P>
   If the 10th-rated Gators (9-3) don't break that habit today
against No.9 Michigan State in the Florida Citrus Bowl, they're
going to be carrying into the off-season the weight of the
program's first three-game losing streak in Spurrier's 10-year
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, that would be unheard of at the University of Florida,''
receiver Travis Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let that happen. Nobody in the country has more
talent than we do. We've got to go out and show everyone we're
still one of the top teams.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's little reason to believe Florida's slide won't
continue. After a 30-23 home loss to Florida State, the Gators put
up little fight against Alabama in the SEC title game, which ended
with defensive end Alex Brown ripping an offense that produced just
114 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Johnson returns at quarterback after shoulder problems made
him a non-factor against the Tide, but he played so poorly late in
the season that he was benched and has just four touchdown passes
in Florida's past seven games. Florida's top running back, Earnest
Graham, is out today with a foot injury, which won't help matters
against a Michigan State defense ranked No.1 in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   So how do the Gators get out of the offensive funk? New plays or
new players?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lost some confidence in our ability to go up and down
the field,'' Spurrier said. ``The only way to get that back is to
do it a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   After Brown's comments convinced Spurrier he had lost control of
the team, he made some changes. He held several team meetings so
the players could privately air their differences, then admitted to
the players he had become too critical and promised a more
enjoyable atmosphere for the bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier's moves have worked _ at least in practice _ as the
players appeared to regain some of their enthusiasm the past two
weeks. Most actually sound like the season didn't end after the FSU
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches have said it's time to let it loose and play
loose, and that's what we're going to do,'' said safety Marquand
Manuel, who leads the team with 118 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try and play like the Gators are supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The one advantage the Gators have over the Spartans is their
recent bowl success. Florida is going for a record fourth
consecutive bowl victory, but Michigan State has lost four in a row
and hasn't won in the post-season since a 17-16 victory over
Southern California in the 1990 Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Just how Michigan State's players react to new coach Bobby
Williams _ who got the job when Nick Saban bolted for LSU after the
regular season _ is anyone's guess. But the players have been
thrilled about kinder, gentler preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a knock on coach Saban, but some of our recent bowl
trips were like concentration camps,'' All-America linebacker
Julian Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the game started, many of our guys were out of
gas. Coach Williams has done a better job of keeping everyone
fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the state of the Gators' mental health that might hold the
key today. Twice before Florida lost two in a row under Spurrier,
only to bounce back with wins over LSU and North Carolina State in
the Gator Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At least one prominent Gator player _ Brown _ disputes the
notion the swagger is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still got it,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three bad days this year. We're still the mighty
Gators.''
</P>
<P>
   By this afternoon, we'll learn if Brown will be regretting those
words, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
