<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-Y2K-0101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NO YELTSIN, NO Y2K GLITCHES: Russians welcome New Millennium,
New Beginning
 &HT;    EDs: This story will be updated at 10 p.m. EST.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The end of the century in Russia didn't mark the end of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Doomsday predictions of accidental nuclear launch, widespread
power outages or ruptures in gas and oil mains caused by Y2K
glitches proved unfounded after the Kremlin clock tower chimed
midnight in the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours leading up to the end of the year, Vladimir
Yakovlev, the head of Russia's strategic nuclear forces, predicted
no catastrophes, telling the Interfax news agency: ``I will be in
my yard setting off fireworks with my kids. These are the only
rockets that will be launched into the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   At Russian Mission Control, space officials called it the most
boring New Year in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   From the Pacific Ocean port of Vladivostock to Moscow _ a span
of 10 time zones _ on-duty army and civil service officers reported
calm, with no interruptions in vital services for Russia's 150
million citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the most dramatic event to start the millennium in
Russia had nothing to do with Y2K. President Boris Yeltsin
surprised the nation by resigning at midday Friday, ending his
eight-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   But political events didn't pre-occupy the thousands of Russians
crammed into Red Square to toast in the New Year. Families,
teenagers and old friends wore smiles and fur coats as a light snow
filled the plaza and bottle rockets arced across the brick red
walls of the Kremlin, where some of the most pivotal moments of
last century took place.
</P>
<P>
   Standing with her middle-aged daughter and son-in-law with a
thick gray wool scarf swathed around her neck, Marina Olibaeva was
hopeful that less bloodshed and more reform would be the hallmark
of her country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Year always brings new hope. We are thankful for
Yeltsin for giving us a beginning. He did the right thing by
starting a new chapter in our history today,'' the 68-year-old
Olibaeva said.
</P>
<P>
   While some looked ahead to further reform, a few clung to the
past. Amid a sea of roaring revelers, one celebrant waved a single
crimson flag bearing the Soviet hammer and sickle in front of
Lenin's tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mood was as bright as the fireworks lighting the
night sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is here to stay, whoever leads the government. We
are moving in the right direction,'' said Sergei Saltovsky, 43,
hugging his 5-year-old daughter Katya.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
