<SLUG> BC-CMGI-ADTECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI TO BUY GERMAN WEB ADVERTISING SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Extending its growing Internet empire to Europe, CMGI Inc. plans
to acquire ADTECH, a German Web advertising service, the company
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, the terms of which were not disclosed, follows a
series of recent CMGI acquisitions and signals the company's
intention to rapidly expand its Internet advertising presence
overseas, offcials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're not done,'' said Krista Thomas, a CMGI
spokeswoman. ``We're moving into the European market in a big
way.''
</P>
<P>
   ADTECH, based in Frankfurt, manages Web-based advertising
campaigns using specialized servers that allow the company to track
and change banner ads at Web sites all over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company started operating in Europe two years ago with
technology leased from a US company, AdForce. CMGI signed a deal to
acquire the company earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sale goes through, CMGI plans to merge AdForce and
ADTECH to form a Web advertising conglomerate that could ultimately
operate around the world, CMGI officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Together with CMGI subsidiary Exchange Technologies, which
tracks people as they browse the Internet and notes the
advertisements they click through, CMGI wants to use the new
companies to tailor advertising to individual Web users according
to their preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the full-service, soup-to-nuts provider in the
online marketing space,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, an Andover, Mass. company that owns or has investment
interests in more than 50 Internet companies, has been expanding
rapidly, especially in untested Internet economies abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, shares in CMGI have more than doubled as the
company made a series of acquisitions and announcements on its
Internet investments, including deals for Internet services in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a wave of investor enthusiasm, the company earlier this
month announced plans to raise $1 billion through the sale of
stocks and bonds for general corporate purposes. It also said it is
preparing to launch venture capital funds to invest in Internet
startups in Europe, Latin America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   While the company says it will continue to pump money into
diverse online ventures, the core of its business strategy will lie
in advertising and marketing services.
</P>
<P>
   Not including Friday's deal, CMGI spent more than $1.4 billion
in 1999 acquiring Internet advertising firms, including San
Francisco-based Flycast Communications Corp., an aggregator of ads
that are distributed over the World Wide Web, and AdKnowledge Inc.,
a marketing-management service.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said CMGI is now large enough to compete with the
current Internet advertising leader, New York-based DoubleClick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
