u w BC-REHNQUIST-REPORT-ART-     12-31 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHNQUIST-REPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF JUSTICE'S ANNUAL REPORT NOTES PROGRESS IN THE JUDICIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. EST EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. EST
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist surveyed the
state of the federal judiciary on Friday and, in contrast to many
of his 13 previous year-end reports, pronounced himself quite
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice noted progress in three areas he had
identified as problems in last year's report. At that time, all
seven seats on the U.S. Sentencing Commission were vacant because
of a political impasse between the White House and Congress. Now,
the seats have been filled as the result of a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Congress had provided neither a raise nor a
cost-of-living adjustment for federal judges. This fall, Congress
approved a 3.4 percent cost-of-living adjustment, taking effect on
Jan. 1, that will bring the annual salaries of federal district
judges to $141,300; of judges on the courts of appeals to $149,900;
of Supreme Court associate justices to $173,600; and of the chief
justice to $181,400.
</P>
<P>
   The judiciary was ``appreciative,'' Rehnquist said Friday, ``but
it should not be confused with a raise in salary.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We must continue to work for more appropriate
compensation for federal judges to maintain the quality and morale
of the federal judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   The third subject on which the chief justice noted progress was
the caseload of the federal courts, which grew only modestly after
sharp increases. Criminal cases in the federal district courts, for
example were up by 4 percent to 59,923, compared with 15 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   As he has often done, the chief justice criticized what he
called the ``unnecessary federalization of traditional state law
matters,'' which he said placed additional burdens on the federal
courts. But he said he was pleased by the increased attention paid
to the issue in the past year as the result of hearings by the
Government Affairs Committee of the Senate and a report by an
American Bar Association task force.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist also asked Congress to appropriate money for higher
pay for lawyers who are appointed to represent indigent defendants
in federal criminal cases. While the authorized rate is $75 an hour
for time the lawyers spend in court, inadequate funding has meant
that in most judicial districts, the lawyers are actually paid only
$65. That is not enough to cover overhead, the chief justice said,
adding, ``Adequate pay for appointed counsel is important to ensure
that a defendant's constitutional right to counsel is fulfilled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
