<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-YELTSIN-CAREER-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     12-31 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-CAREER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 MOSCOW: ... serious blow.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following year, in 1994, Yeltsin sent his army into Chechnya
to stem a separatist rebellion, a disastrous campaign that resulted
in the deaths of tens of thousands of Russian citizens.
</P>
<P>
   But when his presidency was threatened again, by a Communist
challenger in the 1996 presidential elections and by heart disease,
Western leaders, led by President Clinton, voiced strong support
for Yeltsin. And they backed it with billions of dollars of
economic aid for his government.
</P>
<P>
   From Clinton and the West's point of view, Yeltsin represented
Russia's best chance for a democratic future. Under his leadership,
Russia pursued membership or partnership with the international
organizations that the West had created during the Cold War with
the intent of isolating Moscow: NATO, the European Union, and the
Group of Seven industrial powers. Yeltsin also pursued close
personal relationships with Western leaders, especially Clinton,
whom he always referred to as ``My friend Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Yeltsin peppered his speeches with references
to Russia's powerful nuclear arsenal and its need to reclaim its
role as a great nation, and he sent his lieutenants on missions to
Iraq, the Balkans, and elsewhere that often confounded America's
diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Western observers often dismissed these episodes as part of
Yeltsin's need to pay lip service to latent Russian nationalism
rather than a sign of inconsistent idelogy. Insiders familiar with
Yeltsin's autocratic leadership style knew that ideology had little
to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power is his ideology, his friend, his concubine, his
mistress, his passion,'' former Kremlin spokesman Vyacheslav
Kostikov said in 1997. ``Everything that goes beyond that, beyond
the struggle for power, concerns him much less.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's management of power often planted the seeds for his
greatest failures. In 1991, in an attempt to woo the support of
Russian regional leaders, he told them to ``grab as much
sovereignty as you can swallow.'' These words later came back to
haunt Yeltsin in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, Yeltsin promised to ``lie down on the
tracks'' if his policies did not improve living standards. Years
later, this phrase became the buzzword of angry, anti-Yeltsin
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's admitted love for alcohol, which once helped solidify
the man-of-the-people image that carried him to power, most likely
caused some of the erratic public behavior that stirred shame in
his countrymen and probably contributed to his numerous health
woes.
</P>
<P>
   A man who once criticized the doddering Kremlin political elite
was widely ridiculed in his later years for his halting walk,
slurred speech, and embarrassing slips at public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Yeltsin held on to power by playing his allies
off against one another, occasionally bringing the same old face
back into government, occasionally plucking a new face from
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   During his second term, Yeltsin has largely been out of sight,
spending many weeks sidelined at his country residences outside
Moscow. He continued to dominate Russian politics, emerging to fire
his entire government four times over the past two years, but each
shakeup left him looking weaker.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin governed fitfully, preferring to make strong statements
about the workings of government, and often criticizing the
officials he had appointed, rather than getting involved in the
details. He surrounded himself with an ever-changing coterie of
insiders who, it was rumored, were really calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, this clique, known as ``The Family,'' has been
embroiled in financial scandals. Speculation has been rife that
``Family members'' such as the powerful financier, Boris
Berezovsky, and the younger of Yeltsin's two daugthers, Tatyana
Dyachenko, were searching for a successor who would ensure the
entourage a peaceful existence after his time in power ended.
</P>
<P>
   Putin solved that Friday by decreeing that Yeltsin and his
family will enjoy lifetime immunity from prosecution, as well as
many of the perks acquired during his years in power: guards,
special communications systems, property and, presumably, wealth.
</P>
<P>
   When Yeltsin's former chief of staff, Sergei Filatov, Friday
compared the outgoing president with Moses, who brought his people
to the border of the promised land but, because of their sins,
never got to see it, a veteran political observer had a different
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us . . . it's the other way round,'' said Alexei
Venediktov, news editor of Ekho Moskvy radio. ``We know that our
people never entered the promised land for the sins of the leader,
but the leader did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
