NYT-12-31-99 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3585 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-YELTSIN-CAREER-2TAKES     12-31 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-CAREER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABRUPT RESIGNATION PAR FOR THE YELTSIN COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris N. Yeltsin's startling decision Friday
to step down and name Prime Minister Vladimir Putin acting
president was a fitting end for the man who helped bring down the
Soviet Union and led Russia on its stormy post-communist odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Expansive and unpredictable, with a flair for dramatic gestures
and a talent for keeping both his allies and his enemies off
balance, Yeltsin's volatile personality always mirrored his
mercurial political career.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's most dominant political force in the past decade,
Yeltsin profoundly changed the political and economic landscape of
the world's largest nation.
</P>
<P>
   He sought to become the father of a new Russia, where the
watchwords of the Soviet era, the police state and shortages of
goods, would be replaced by democracy and prosperity. But Yeltsin
the politician was a brilliant tactician, not a visionary, and he
stayed in power long after he stopped leading Russia in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   The pale, puffy and grim Yeltsin who announced his resignation
on national television was a shadow of the man who nine years ago
faced down Soviet power. But Yeltsin's political instincts, and
flair for great gestures, remained sharp to the end.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to hand over power to Putin and schedule a speeded
up presidential election in three months appeared timed to
capitalize on the success of parties backing Putin in recent
parliamentary elections. And what other leader could steal the show
on the most watched date of the second millenium? By stepping down
voluntarily and setting new elections, Yeltsin ended Russia's
tragic and bloody century by giving the country a chance for
something it has never seen this century: a peaceful transition of
power by popular vote, not by death, palace coup, or revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin never took much interest in day-to-day government, and
until his resignation speech, he rarely admitted to mistakes. And
after eight years as Russia's president, he leaves behind an
ambiguous legacy. He said he was confident that Russia would not
return to its authoritarian past and would develop as a modern
democratic nation, but he asked forgiveness for failing to complete
the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to beg forgiveness for your dreams that never came
true,'' he said. ``And also I would like to beg forgiveness for not
justifiying your hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a member of the Communist Party elite that ruled the Soviet
Union, Yeltsin dealt the death blow to communism in the country
that for seven decades was world headquarters for Marxist-Leninism.
He turned the country that symbolized totalitarian rule in the 20th
century toward democracy and free markets. He invented the concept
of the political comeback in a land where ousted leaders
traditionally ended up on the dustheap of history. And he steered
the Russian nuclear superpower toward its best relations with its
former Cold War foes in the West since the 1917 Bolshevik
Revolution, only to preside over a pronounced chill when NATO
bombers struck at Yugoslavia, a traditional Slavic ally of Russia,
and when Russia renewed its military effort to subdue rebels in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   It was August 1991 when Yeltsin, in a single stroke of political
genius and courage, stood on a tank outside the Russian parliament
building and faced down a hard-line coup against the last Soviet
president, Mikhail S. Gorbachev. It was Yeltsin's single greatest
moment: it changed the course of history and it symbolized his
legendary talent for winning political battles.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, a seemingly cornered Yeltsin would stare down an
entrenched, powerful foe and come out the winner. Time and again,
the world would write off Yeltsin, only to see him reemerge with a
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's achievements were offset by the great failures of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The father of Russian democracy also will be remembered as the
man who led Russia's army into a disastrous and brutal 1994-1996
war against rebels in Chechnya, and thus as the Kremlin leader
responsible for the greatest number of deaths of his countrymen
since Josef Stalin's Great Terror of the 1930s and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   And after seven years of Yeltsin's leadership, Russia is far
from the market-oriented and law-abiding state he set out to create
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a time of unprecedented economic freedom and growth,
Yeltsin's rule will be remembered as a time when bureaucratic
meddling and mafia-like extortion stifled small entrepreneurs, a
time when Russia built massive debts by borrowing tens of billions
of dollars from Western creditors, only to watch tens of billions
flee the country to offshore bank accounts as the Russian economy
contracted to a fraction of its 1990 size, a time when a few
well-connected insiders gained incredible wealth, but millions of
Russians had their entire life savings wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin was the first Russian leader publicly to renounce the
repression, terror, and police tactics favored by his predecessors
over a millennium of Russian history. But citizens' rights in
Yeltsin's Russia still depend more on the arbitrary powers of
police and bureaucrats than on democratic institutions like
independent courts of law. He helped foster a free press, but then
forced it to support his reelection in 1996, a compromise from
which it has never fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1931 in the Urals region of Sverdlovsk, Yeltsin became
an construction engineer. In 1961, at the height of Soviet leader
Nikita Khrushchev's anti-Stalinist political thaw, Yeltsin became a
member of the Communist Party. He rose quickly through the ranks,
and by 1976 he was heading the Sverdlovsk regional branch of the
Communist Party, a position similar to that of a US governor.
There, he gained a reputation as a reformer, which eventually
caught the attention in 1985 of Gorbachev, recently appointed the
new Soviet leader.
</P>
<P>
   With Gorbachev as his mentor, Yeltsin rose to the post of first
secretary of Moscow's Communist Party organization, a job that
included membership in the Politburo, the Soviet Union's de facto
ruling body.
</P>
<P>
   It was as a Politburo member in 1987 that Yeltsin, spurred by
Gorbachev's calls for ``perestroika (restructuring) and
``glasnost'' (openess), began a vocal campaign against corruption
and abuse of privilege among party elites.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners quickly moved to oust Yeltsin from the Politburo and
have him removed to an obscure job running construction in
Sverdlovsk in the Urals.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been the end of Yeltsin's career. But in the
first of what would be many comebacks, Yeltsin was soon back in the
capital, elected by a landslide as a member of the first Soviet
parliament in which voters were allowed to choose among competing
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   There, the increasingly popular Yeltsin began a two-year
campaign that saw him quit the Communist Party and eventually rise
to become Gorbachev's main rival as the democratically elected
leader of the Russian republic, by far the largest in the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt by hard-line Communists to oust Gorbachev in August
1991 gave Yeltsin the chance he was waiting for; within a few
months after he stood on the tank, Gorbachev was ousted from power
and Yeltsin took office in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the West was slow to take to Yeltsin, whose reputation
as a heavy drinker and penchant for breaches of protocol contrasted
with the urbane, staid Gorbachev. But from 1992 on, Yeltsin enjoyed
unprecedented support in the West, despite moves that would have
brought harsh protests during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1993, a little more than two years after his famous
stand, tanks again rumbled to the Russian parliament buiding, but
this time it was on orders from Yeltsin to drive out lawmakers who
refused to obey his illegal order to disband.
</P>
<P>
   More than 140 people died in the street fighting that ensued.
Yeltsin emerged triumphant, but democracy in Russia suffered a
serious blow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
