<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-FLASTATE-WILLIAMS     12-31 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLASTATE-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMERLY HOMELESS YOUTH HAS HOME ON FLORIDA STATE FOOTBALL TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BRIAN ETTKIN    
 New York Times Regional Newspapers    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The former high school superstars thought
they had it tough. One by one, the Florida State freshman football
players vented their frustrations last year during their first
meeting with the university's director of student development, Pam
Overton:
</P>
<P>
   ``This place isn't fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dining hall is not open when we need to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the last freshman spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm going to tell you,'' Todd Williams said, ``this is
probably the best place I've been. Nobody has ever been this nice
to me before. Maybe it's not everything we want, but it's
everything we need.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is the Florida State campus in Tallahassee, and it is
home to Williams, a redshirt freshman offensive tackle who had been
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   It means three meals a day for Williams, who had stolen food as
a teen-ager to survive. And it gave a football family to a young
man who had lived on his own for years.
</P>
<P>
   This is tough: Williams' father wanted nothing to do with him,
refusing to sign his birth certificate. His father was shot to
death in 1994, en route to visiting his son for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I met my dad was in the casket,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Ozepher Fluker, never was a significant part of his
life because of her own problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just know this, she wasn't there,'' Williams said. ``That is
good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' sister is in jail, and he has not spoken to his
brother, who lives in Miami, for ``so long, I'm embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce James had raised Todd, her grandson, in her Bradenton, ,
home since he was 9. She died on Oct. 2, 1993, of complications
from diabetes, and Todd, then 15, received the news over the phone.
He dropped the receiver and bolted out of the house, then ran laps
at a nearby baseball field, unable to sweat away the anger and
despair swelling within.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when I got through running that it would all be
over,'' Williams said. ``Then it hit, but I still didn't want to
accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like that was the only person that ever cared about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 21, said that after his grandmother's funeral, state
social service representatives arrived to pick him up because he
had no adult relative to care for him. He asked them to come back
the next day, so he could pack his belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Williams, who had a solid academic record in middle
school, fled Bradenton, with a friend, for the Miami area. Williams
had relatives and friends there but nowhere to call home. His
friend soon left, but Williams stayed in Carol City and Opa-locka.
</P>
<P>
   He broke into cars and hotel rooms to sleep, trying to leave
before he was discovered. Sometimes he slept in public restrooms.
``I got shot at a few times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He ate at restaurants, then fled without paying. He stole
clothing from department stores. He was arrested after he tried to
steal a car in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stole, I lied, I got involved in violent activities and
these people who would kill folks and stuff like that,'' Williams
said. ``It wasn't the right way, but I was young at the time and it
was survival.''
</P>
<P>
   After several months on the streets, he returned to Bradenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I didn't want to be like the rest of my family,''
Williams said. ``Like my uncles and stuff, they're in jail. Too
many people in my family didn't graduate from high school or go on
to college.''
</P>
<P>
   He was sent to a juvenile center after he was arrested following
a fight. Nobody picked up Williams upon his release, and he lived
in a halfway house before moving in with an older cousin. She moved
out, and an uncle signed the lease so Williams would have a place
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore at Southeast High School, Williams was
responsible for all the bills and chores and catching up in school.
He worked two and three jobs at a time, as a restaurant cook and a
grocery store stockboy, to pay the rent for his subsidized
apartment in Bradenton. It was 60 yards from a street corner where
drug activity was common.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been real easy with what he had been through to
try to make a quick buck on the corner where some of the boys were,
to take an easy way out,'' said Joanne VanEska, his landlord,
``instead of doing what he did, which was work and go to school and
keep himself clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also began attending church regularly and found people
there who cared.
</P>
<P>
   ``His circumstances were so bad when he was so young, he had to
have something to grasp onto,'' said Faust DeLazzer, who coached
Williams at Southeast. ``He got a sense of belonging and people
caring that he didn't get before.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams had saved enough money, he joined the football
team, biking to work after practice, returning home at night. He
had dreamed since he was a child of playing football at Florida
State, but not even he believed that was possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the potential, if he grows, worked hard in the weight
room,'' DeLazzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams earned Class 6A second-team all-state honors and was
recruited by several major colleges, including Florida State. He
now has a football scholarship that covers his meals, lodging,
books and tuition, and a Pell Grant for about $1,500 a semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great story,'' said Sally Bishop, Williams' guidance
counselor at Southeast. ``I admire him. I knew his background and I
knew he had a lot of potential physically and academically. He
could have very easily done nothing with his life, and he pulled it
together to be somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams still struggles to control the anger rooted in his
abandonment. In high school he was suspended from school for 10
days and a football game for fighting. While at Florida State,
Williams attacked an automatic teller machine on Oct. 10 in
Tallahassee because it swallowed his card. He smacked the machine
several times, witnesses said, and was handcuffed by police. He
later agreed to make restitution to the owners and was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Inner peace is not so easy to find. More than anything, Williams
says, he wants a family someday. ``I've never had that,'' he said.
``To have a wife and a child to come home to.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton recalls during that initial meeting with Williams and
the rest of Florida State's freshman football class, ``You could
just tell that the guys had never thought about the things that
Todd has had to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said: ``I told Todd when he
arrived here, he could be a great story. You really hope it has a
happy ending.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
