<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-YELTSIN-REACT-BOS &LR;      12-31 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATION, UPCOMING US ELECTION COULD BRING NEW ERAA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton awakens in the new year, he
faces a dramatic new uncertainty on the world stage: the future
course of Russia after the surprise resignation of his good friend
Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   US-Russia relations have gone through an extraordinarily
difficult year. There have been no fewer than nine crises beginning
with NATO's expansion into eastern Europe, but Clinton depended on
his complicated friendship with Yeltsin to pull out short-term
solutions to each new setback.
</P>
<P>
   They publicly toasted each other and tussled across the Atlantic
over issues, but privately, said former US aides, Clinton was able
to bully the Russian president into agreements that met US
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a few brief meetings in recent months, Clinton has no
relationship with Vladmir Putin, named by Yeltsin as acting
president until March and the odds-on favorite to be elected then
as Russia's president for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the change now facing Clinton: he had a 20-minute
``frank'' discussion with Yeltsin Friday, said a senior
administration official, but he could not get Putin on the phone
because the new president ``was in a Cabinet meeting,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   With Putin, ex-spymaster and ex-St. Petersburg bureaucrat, as
the power in Moscow, the US administration sees opportunities and
dangers in the unpredictable new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of unknowns,'' the administration official
said. Those looking for positives said Putin will have much more
domestic support than Yeltsin in recent years, giving him great
ability to follow through on his platforms and foreign policy
commitments. He also will be working with a new legislature that
may be more open to reforms pushed by the Clinton administration on
arms control and economic initiatives, US officials believe.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for negatives said Putin's motivations will be to
win the elections, and thus continue a hard line in the war in
Chechnya, which Europe and the United States have condemned as
brutal and indiscriminate. His no-nonsense stand on Chechnya,
beginning immediately with his appointment on Aug. 9, has sent his
job-approval ratings to near 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But a further cloud on Russia's future, and by extension its
ties with the United States, is the transition itself. The US
official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Yeltsin
technically followed constitutional provisions in calling for new
elections in three months, but he said questions are sure to arise
from reports that Putin has granted Yeltsin immunity from
prosecution. There was no word about whether the immunity extended
to Yeltsin's family, who like the leader had come under suspicion
of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Friday, Clinton said he looked ``forward to
working with acting President Putin, as the Russian people begin
the process of making the transition from one democratically
elected president to another.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall I. Goldman, Davis professor of Russian economics at
Wellesley College and associate director at the Davis Center for
Russian Studies at Harvard University, said Yeltsin's resignation
seemed blatantly designed to win immunity for himself and his
family and to catch the opposition off guard, not good starting
points for a democratic transition.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said the original intention of holding elections in June
was a better plan. ``This is a premature birth, and premature
births don't always work out so well,'' he said. ``You have a
better chance if you go all the way to term.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some predicted that Putin would weather the criticism,
and that eventually his election as president may steady the
US-Russia relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, there were broad disagreements over NATO
expansion; policy toward Iraq; Russian technology transfers to
rogue states; the Kosovo war; the dumping of Russian steel in the
United States, corruption scandals, including allegations of money
laundering at the Bank of New York; plans to modify the ABM treaty
to allow missile defense systems; the Chechnya war; and a espionage
incident in which a Russian official allegedly monitored
conversations in a seventh-floor State Department conference room.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts said a Putin presidency would not necessarily
bring an end to the controversy-of-the-month relationship. The
Chechen war looms large in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin built his campaign on what he is doing in Chechnya, and
if we are comfortable in that, we should be comfortable with him,''
said David J. Kramer, associate director of the Russian Program at
the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, a Washington think
tank. ``There is a view in the administration that Putin is a man
they can do business with. I think that remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior US official, who has met with Putin, said he believes
this was not an entirely accurate reading on Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very serious guy,'' the official said. ``The two words
I would say that come to mind about him are `serious' and
`studied.' He comes to the table after he has spent a great deal of
time studying and thinking carefully about how to portray the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Graham Jr., the chief political analyst at the US
Embassy in Moscow from 1994 to 1997 and now a senior associate at
Carnegie, said he believed the entire US-Russian relationship would
undergo a sea change. He predicted a shift from US dominance and a
foundation based largely on the relationship of the two leaders, to
one that gives more weight to Russian concerns and is based on
broader ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever things looked bad in the past, our president picked
up the phone, and they worked things out,'' said Graham, who wrote
dozens of diplomatic cables on the US-Russian political
relationship. ``Yeltsin made concessions to the US that were not
consistent to mainstream Russian thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the confidence that we could manipulate them, which is
what the United States has done,'' Graham said. ``I think a change
is positive. Basing a policy extensively on your ability to
manipulate the leader of a country is not a long-term strategy. The
challenge of the administration now is to build broader contacts
with the Russian elite. If you do that right, you also have a more
stable relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   So, said analysts, a new era in US-Russia relations could be at
hand, a post-Clinton-Yeltsin era, perhaps beginning after the dual
election seasons in Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, asked Friday about his personal relationship with
Yeltsin, who assumed office more than a year ahead of him, said,
``I liked him because he was always very forthright with me. He
always did exactly what he said he would do, and he was willing to
improve our relationship, to try to improve democracy in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin ``genuinely deplored communism,'' Clinton said. ``He
lived with it, he saw it, and he believed that democracy was the
best system. I think it was in every fiber of his being. And we had
our arguments, we had our fights, we had our genuine disagreements
about our national interests from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton added, for a second time, ``I liked him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for a phone call with Putin?
</P>
<P>
   ``It should happen in the next day or two,'' said the US
official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
