<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian Stocks Leap After Yeltsin Steps Aside
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin's surprise resignation drove Russian stock prices
up sharply, reflecting optimism that the acting president, Vladimir
Putin, will revive stalled economic reforms. The Russian Trading
System stock index rose 18 percent. Russian stocks traded in the
United States rallied as well, as did the Templeton Russia Fund, a
mutual fund that invests primarily in Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bond Prices Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices ended the year lower, reversing a two-day gain that
analysts labeled an aberration from the bond market's yearlong
slump. The price of the benchmark 30-year bond fell 24/32, to 95
12/32. The bond's yield rose to 6.48 percent from 6.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing Shares Are Sold
</P>
<P>
   US West said it sold 24 million Global Crossing shares, valued
at $1.15 billion. US West bought the shares before canceling its
planned merger with Global Crossing, which is building a worldwide
phone and data network.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Merger Called Overpriced
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, the nation's biggest hauler of trash, contends
in a lawsuit that it overpaid in its $1.15 billion purchase of
Eastern Environmental Services last year because Eastern's chairman
overstated its profits. The suit seeks nearly $600 million in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia Defers Share Dispute
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia said it had extended by six months a deadline for
resolving an impasse on $3.8 billion worth of Malaysian stocks
frozen on a Singapore exchange. Suspension of trading in the shares
was among economic measures adopted by Mahatir Mohamad, Malaysia's
prime minister, in September 1998, and the two sides have since
clashed over how to return the equities to the Malaysian
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Some Markets Closed
</P>
<P>
   Most overseas stock and financial markets were closed Friday for
New Year's Eve. In the United States, commodity markets were
closed, and the stock market and Treasury market closed early.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
