<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-YAC-VUITTON-BOS &LR;      12-31 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-VUITTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY DISCORD MARKS VUITTON SEMIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, N.Z. _ The Ghost of America's Cups past stalked the
waterfront Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Long before a gun sounded on Hauraki Gulf to begin the semifinal
round of the Louis Vuitton Cup, the series began with a familiar
lurch into rancor and discord among the sailing teams.
</P>
<P>
   The object of wrath at a press conference Thursday was the
Japanese team that, as the other challengers see it, consorted with
the enemy, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Before the challengers' series began last October, the 11
syndicates agreed not to help the defender by sailing or practice
racing against it between rounds. The agreement was in keeping with
a longstanding America's Cup tradition of separation between the
two, though it has been breached at least once before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to tune up against the world's best match racers,''
said Peter Gilmour, an Australian who skippers the Nippon boats for
Japan. ``But Nippon has had tremendous help from New Zealand in the
past and no one else invited us out.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Dennis Conner who tore the top off what had been a
fairly polite press conference when he raised the possibility that
Gilmour had sparred with New Zealand for personal gain, perhaps to
raise money to pay bills.
</P>
<P>
   Conner said he would not be surprised ``if Peter ends up
steering for New Zealand three years from now,'' suggesting that
Gilmour aided New Zealand to gain favor.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility, said Conner, launching into pure derision,
is that ``maybe he feels he's not going to the America's Cup and so
he wanted to have his photograph taken racing against New
Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Conner got serious: ``This is a big edge for New Zealand _
to find out how the challengers are going. It's all win win win for
New Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cayard, skipper of AmericaOne from San Francisco, said he
could not see the upside for Nippon. ``New Zealand learned a little
Friday. They'll learn the rest next week. One of the six of us are
going to try to beat New Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice sailings gave New Zealand a benchmark from which to
gauge the performance level of all the other teams when races begin
Saturday, said Conner and Cayard.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour justified his action by saying his was the only team
without a second world-class helmsman to give him sparring
practice. ``This was the best possible way for us to prepare. It is
a very logical process. This is all a storm in a teacup. I can't
believe on the eve of the new millennium, there are still these
silly prejudices . . . We see this as something really positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitter pre-race conference among the six challengers was
music to the ears of Team New Zealand, which sends its two black
boats out every challenger race day to sail against one another and
watch the competition from afar. By design, there is no other
defender team in New Zealand. So while all the Kiwis' efforts,
wealth, and resources focus on a single campaign, they still have
no one else to spar with.
</P>
<P>
   Team New Zealand tactician Brad Butterworth termed his scrimmage
against Nippon as a ``bloody interesting day. It was encouraging
because both boats were so similar. But we won't really know how
fast we are until we see the results of the semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was somewhat more restrained than the irascible Conner,
Cayard ended his criticism with a sarcastic, Conneresque swipe at
Gilmour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard to understand the advantage of checking in and
the value of that to Team New Zealand. They have been watching us
all along and now they have a measuring stick. I can't really see
what the benefits were to the other side except for the front page
of the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour agreed that making the front page of the paper would
make his sponsors ``delighted,'' especially since Nippon and Team
New Zealand share some sponsors, such as Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely in its modern history has there been an America's Cup
without some significant disagreement and bickering, but rarely has
it been so shrill this early in the trials. Conner finished his
ripping of Gilmour with an echo from America's Cups past. ``Whoa, I
shouldn't have said that!'' he shouted with mock self-effacement.
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to Fremantle in 1986 when he said the same
thing to wind up a diatribe accusing New Zealand of cheating by
building their 12 meter out of fiberglass rather than aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   As the semifinals begin Saturday, each of six boats will have 10
races, meeting each other twice. Four boats will be eliminated,
while the two top point-winners face off in the Louis Vuitton
finals beginning Jan. 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
