<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-Y2K-BUNKER-0101-COX     12-31 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BUNKER-0101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN THE Y2K COMMAND CENTER, THE MEDIA WAITED, AND WAITED, AND
WAITED FOR NEWS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here at Millennial Perennial, where the Year 2000
was always arriving somewhere, they
</P>
<P>
   were ready to swat the Y2K bugs.
</P>
<P>
   At the government's high-tech center located two blocks from the
White House, federal experts watched on high-definition television
monitors as fireworks welcomed the new century in Australia, Hong
Kong and on around the world. Sitting in gray cubicles and staring
at computer screens, they searched for trouble spots on colorful
world maps divided into time zones. Talking into tiny digital
cameras, they communicated by video conference with disembodied
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has never had to deal with this much
information at one time,'' marveled John Koskinen, the chairman of
the President's Council on the Year 2000 Conversion. ``What's
happening in 180 countries, what's happening in 50 states, what's
happening in all the critical infrastructure industries, what's
happening in all of the federal agencies and their abilities to
operate.''
</P>
<P>
   They were ready, all right, in the whiz-bang, $50 million
Information Coordination Center, which most people call the ICC.
But the Y2K bugs _ those dreaded, embedded computer pests _ seemed
to have already been shooed away. Folks from Austria to Austin
apparently fixed the glitch that might have shut computers that
used programs with only two digits to record dates and thus
couldn't distinguish the years 2000 from 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the questions you've begun to see surface a
little around the edges is, well, has this all been hype? You know,
have we wasted a lot of time and money?,'' Koskinen acknowledged.
``Especially this weekend, could we have all been doing something
else?''
</P>
<P>
   He thought not, of course, recalling that ``we should not
underestimate the nature of the problem that was originally
there.''
</P>
<P>
   And the scores of journalists assembled in the media center two
floors above the ICC were hardly in a position to pack up their
laptop computers and TV gear and catered pastries and simply tell
their bosses, ``Never mind. Not much of a story here.''
</P>
<P>
   So the show went on. And on. And on. The ICC operates 24-hours a
day through next Thursday. Workers pull 12-hour shifts, changing at
9 a.m. and 9 p.m. EST. Time is relative when a new millennium is
dawning somewhere every hour and when the Wall Street Deli
downstairs never closes.
</P>
<P>
   After awhile at the ICC, you can tell who is who among the
Y2Kers by their color-coded cotton cardigans emblazed with the
official seal on the left breast. The senior officials wear white
cardigans; the technicians wear black; the public affairs officers
wear green. Support staffers wear navy blue cardigans while the
eighth-floor experts wear royal blue.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth floor ICC hub is off-limits to the media, although
reporters can periodically watch the activity on a silent TV
monitor. The media center is on the 10th floor. Serving as a
backdrop to the network newscasts, a flock of flacks work on
computer terminals. These green-cardiganed public relations
specialists from various government agencies and private industry
are the human links between the eighth and 10th floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core staff of this entire operation is fewer than 30
people, so the 200 people working on each of the 12-hour shifts are
primarily from other agencies, who are experts in each of the
sectors we're monitoring,'' explained Koskinen. They share a
``sense of confidence'' that there will be no major disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think, like all of us, there is also a sense of
curiosity about how this story is really going to unfold and end,
because no one can tell you with any precision exactly what's going
to happen, when, and where,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This sense of suspense was less apparent in the media work room,
however, where idle reporters and technicians played video games or
checked their e-mail or watched the other news events of the day
unfold on TV monitors. There were briefings scheduled for noon EST
and 5 p.m. and 8:30 p.m. and and then Saturday at 2 a.m. and 11
a.m. and 3 p.m. and then Sunday at 2 p.m. and Monday at noon and 5
p.m. Somewhere, outside the ICC, college football teams are playing
bowl games and people are drinking champagne or eating black eyed
peas for good luck....
</P>
<P>
   The ICC will continue to operate around the clock until at next
Thursday and remain in force for a month beyond that. The center
was set up as the government's central point for gathering and
analyzing information on vital computer systems _ in government,
the private sector and internationally _ during the millennium
rollover.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that such a massive effort was needed to tackle
such a tiny quirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This problem is ultimately getting two digits to four, which
is relatively simple,'' Koskinen explained. ``But what's been
fascinating about it and complicated about it is it affects
virtually everything in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Dart can be reached by e-mail at: bobdart(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
