<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING A DEEPER NEW YEAR'S MEANING  
 A CALL FOR NEW MUSIC IN SYNAGOGUES  
 AN INFLUENTIAL BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While there is a legal wall between church and state, no such
barrier separates organized religion from the broader culture. The
former exists within the latter, and each influences the other,
with ideas flowing back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   For an example, one might look to Fort Worth, Texas, where an
aspect of Friday night's New Year's Eve events inspired one
minister to ask clergy members nationwide to preach for peace n
January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, the Rev. R. Scott Colglazier, sat on the Fort
Worth committee charged with planning that city's millennial
events. In an interview, he said that several months ago, the
committee decided the evening ought to be more than just a party,
but should offer people a chance to reflect on something of greater
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we decided to do,'' said Colglazier, senior pastor of the
5,000-member University Christian Church in Fort Worth, ``was to
have a few seconds pause before midnight, a pause for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was that Colglazier began a personal effort
to give the idea a far wider, religious currency, by appealing to
colleagues around the country to dedicate their first sermons of
the new year _ many of which will be preached Sunday _ to the
subject of peace. He wrote letters and made phone calls. And his
church sent out a press release to news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he got a boost from a politically well-known
Texan, former U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright, who praised
Colglazier's idea in an opinion piece Wright wrote for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram last September.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief essay describing his idea, Colglazier wrote,
``Throughout the centuries, religious communities have been
undergirded by a vision of peace grounded in the divine presence.
To touch peace is to touch God and to touch God is to touch
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Although defined in various ways, all religious
communities agree that they have been given by God a responsibility
toward the larger world. Surely no responsibility exceeds that of
bringing peace to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Colglazier has heard from ministers in his denomination, the
Christian Church (Disciples of Christ), and from others who plan to
preach on peace. But he has no idea how many have taken up the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly ecumenical, and that's the reason I wanted to
do it,'' he said. The idea of preaching for peace, he said,
``really cuts across denominational lines, it cuts across world
religious lines.''
</P>
<P>
   A CALL FOR NEW MUSIC IN SYNAGOGUES
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of sermons, it was two weeks ago, on Dec. 18, that
Rabbi Eric Yoffie preached one calling for a ``revolution'' in the
way that Reform Jews worship, asking that synagogues use ritual
music ``that is participatory, warm and accessible,'' which would
be particularly inviting and inspiring to younger families.
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie is the president of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations, which represents 875 Reform synagogues, and his
sermon was directed to the several thousand members attending the
union's biennial assembly, held in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he said the music he meant was composed in a
``new American style,'' with roots in Jewish summer camps and youth
groups _ as opposed to more traditional music of worship that
derives from Eastern European Jewish communities. The traditional
music, he said, is ``soaring and rich and moving,'' but often
difficult to sing, ``and so you might respond to it as you respond
to an opera performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet by singing enthusiastically, people can better focus on
community, God and prayer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the sermon, he asked that the union's congregations undertake
a greater focus on worship and prayer. And among specific
proposals, he called for more emphasis on teaching Hebrew to
adults, through the use of primers the union is developing. ``We
value Hebrew for many reasons, but it is most of all the great
democratic tool of Jewish worship, the vehicle that `opens the
gates of prayer' to the average Jew,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AN INFLUENTIAL BOOK
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the sermon is but one of many ways of communicating
religious ideas. More basic, at least to those who trace their
tradition to the Bible, is the book.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview by e-mail, on the subject of the most
significant religious figures of the 20th century, the eminent
historian of Christianity Martin E. Marty said he believed that the
single most influential book in American religion to have been
written in the last 100 years was ``The Varieties of Religious
Experience,'' by the psychologist William James.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Published in 1902, when James was teaching at
Harvard, it remains in print, a valued text in many university
religion courses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
