<HEADLINE>
STOCK INDEXES PAY OFF FOR SOME INVESTORS AT YEAREND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Stock)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major US stock indexes, which began 1999 looking back on global
financial crises and ahead with concern about the Y2K computer
software glitch, set record levels Friday and gave investors large
profits for a fifth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of major Y2K computer problems as countries welcomed
2000 helped lead a rally during a day of light trading on Wall
Street after world boxing champion Muhammad Ali rang the last
opening bell of the century to the cheers of traders, many in
tuxedos. Markets closed Friday at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The bull market has created unprecedented wealth for many
investors as the Dow Jones industrial index and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 have turned in double-digit gains each of the last five
years. Both indexes have been up every year since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these huge returns, however, investment experts said
1999 was distinguished by a sharp division between a relatively
small group of high tech and telecommunications stocks that were
big winners and a host of losers.
</P>
<P>
   According to a tabulation by Merrill Lynch, 902 NYSE stocks rose
last year, but 1,454 declined. The figures reflect activity through
Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've had a year of the haves and have-nots, big-time, in the
stock market,'' said James Weiss, chief investment officer for
State Street Research &AMP; Management Co. in Boston. ``Some people are
going to be drinking champagne tonight and others will have bread
and water.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock index rose 32.44 points Friday to set another record,
closing at 4069.31. The dramatic increases reflect the dizzying
heights scaled by the technology stocks that dominate the index.
The Nasdaq's 86 percent gain in 1999 was by far the biggest
one-year return of a market index in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial index also set a record, rising 44.26
to 11,497.12. The Dow's 25 percent gain for the year far outpaced
the 16 percent return in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The broad Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index added only 4.78 points
Friday, just enough to reach a record 1469.29 for a 19.53 percent
gain last year. Mobile phone company Qualcomm Inc., the biggest
gainer in 1999 with an annual return approaching 3000 percent, led
Friday's advance; Qualcomm was up 14 3/8 to 176 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Investors set another kind of record last year by pouring $69
billion into 546 first-time stock sales, or IPOs, by US companies.
Almost half were technology companies. That investment eclipsed the
prior record set in 1996 of $50 billion and fueled spectacular
rises in many fledgling Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, investment experts said they do not see US stock
markets _ and particularly Nasdaq _ repeating last year's
performance. Many predicted a correction in technology stocks, with
some saying such a rout could drag down the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. is forecasting declines in the Dow, S&AMP;P500 and
Nasdaq this year.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cliggott, Morgan's manager of equity strategy, said a
``wall of money'' pushed up technology stocks in the fourth quarter
as mutual funds put 80 percent of their money into narrowly
invested funds that specialize in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these (technology) companies are trading at 100, 200,
300 times earnings _ if they have earnings,'' Cliggott said. ``Tech
goes up like a rocket ship. When it goes down, it goes down like a
rocket ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, equity strategist for Salomon Smith Barney in
New York, predicted that a ``divergence`` between strong gains in
technology and lagging performance elsewhere would correct itself
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see some correction'' and ``it's going to be have to
begin in the Internet,'' Acuff said. ``It will have some effect''
on the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   The world's economies and stock markets have also done well this
year. After starting last year under the shadow of 1998's currency
crises and economic downturns from Singapore to Russia, stock
markets in 30 emerging countries had a combined gain of 66.6
percent through Dec. 30, according to Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market in Japan, which is still in the throes of
restructuring the world's second-biggest economy, rose 36.8 percent
last year, while Hong Kong's stock market rose 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, where many economists believe economies will expand
more rapidly this year, the Bloomberg index of 500 European stocks
rose 36.9 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pessimism at the beginning of the year
about international markets,'' said Brian Gendreau, a Salomon
economist, ``and that's all but gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
