<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-SYCAMORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE FROZEN PRAIRIE, A QUIET NIGHT AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and NYT10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYCAMORE, Ill. _ As darkness shrouded the farm fields, Bill
Lenschow milked the cows and finished his chores, then sat down
with his wife, Kathy, to a special dinner of steak and shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   With lights blazing in their cheerfully boisterous old house on
Washington Place, the Newquist children played board games and
watched an old Jimmy Stewart movie with their parents, Tammy and
Howard.
</P>
<P>
   In a hospital on Edward Street, Jeri Delaney clasped the hand of
her husband, Patrick, who is recovering from a stroke, gave him a
kiss and told him that she loved him.
</P>
<P>
   In this small town on the frozen prairie, people tended to mark
the passing of the 20th century in gentle, personal ways.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time to be grateful, said John Garman, 62, who went to
mass then settled in to watch college football on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful time,'' said Garman, who lives in a
five-story housing project for the elderly, known here as the
high-rise. ``There is peace on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillie Jackson, 73, a neighbor of Garman, drifted back in her
memory to a New Year's Eve celebration from her childhood, when she
played with a doll she made out of a corn cob, with string pulled
from a burlap sack for the hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a time,'' she said, ``when people didn't expect so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kate Diedrich, 9, and her brother, Ryan, 8, readied their
noisemakers for the big celebration in the living room of their
farmhouse _ they were doing a countdown at 10 p.m. _ and tried to
imagine life 100 years ago. Their great-grandmother, Ruth Logan,
had explained just the other day how different things had been.
</P>
<P>
   Told that women could not vote, and were expected to stay home,
Mary Kate said she had other plans. ``I want to be president,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no wild celebration on State Street, the main drag
through town. But some people, like Debbie Saalfeld, a 52-year-old
teacher, danced to the music of a disc jockey at the Stratford Inn.
Steve and Nony Roush went to dinner at Johnny's Char House, the new
place out on ``the four-lane,'' as people still call the highway
that leads to the neighboring town of DeKalb. George and Trish
Diedrich, the parents of Mary Kate and Ryan, slipped away for a New
Year's toast at a neighborhood tavern called Hinks.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Lenschows, whose cows need to be milked before dawn,
millennium or not, the old year would pass without much thunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get up at 4 a.m.,'' said Bill Lenschow. ``You don't
stay out too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone remembered dreaming about the year 2000 as
children, calculating how old they would be, and wondering whether
cars would be able to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking, `Boy, I'm going to be old,'' said Steve
Roush, 50, with a chuckle. ``And, well, I guess I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Joseph Thomas, the leader of the Israel of God church on
North Avenue, who was born three years after the turn of the 20th
century, planned to stay on the straight and narrow. To mark this
New Year's Eve, he walked around the corner to his friend Lessie's
house, who was throwing a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the revelry, Thomas was staying away from vices, such as
alcohol and cigars, just as always. ``That's how I got to be
97-years-old,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
