<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TAX-LAWYER-KICKBACKS-     12-31 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-LAWYER-KICKBACKS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE FINDS NOTED TAX ATTORNEY ENGINEERED KICKBACK SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (bl) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A U.S. Tax Court judge has ruled that one of the nation's most
prominent tax lawyers, Burton Kanter of Chicago, was ``the
architect'' of a long-running kickback and tax-evasion scheme in
which money was siphoned from funds managed by the Prudential and
Travelers insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The special trial judge, D. Irvin Couvillion, ruled that the IRS
had overwhelmingly proved its civil fraud case, saying there were
indications of fraud in the existence of ``sham'' companies, the
destruction of documents and evasive testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Kanter said he had done nothing illegal and would appeal. He
said he had not calculated the potential taxes, civil fraud
penalties and interest due, but if the decision was upheld, he
said, it could run into tens of millions of dollars for himself and
a former insurance executive, Claude Ballard, and the estate of
another, Robert Lisle.
</P>
<P>
   The Tax Court held that $13 million in kickbacks were paid from
1972 through 1988 by four developers and another man to Ballard and
Lisle, who were senior executives with Prudential overseeing its
real estate investments.
</P>
<P>
   The kickbacks, the court ruled, were made to them for using
their influence to steer financing and contracts to the developers
and the other man. The executives gave 10 percent of those
kickbacks to Kanter, the court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kanter was the architect who planned and executed the
elaborate scheme,'' Couvillion wrote in his 606-page decision,
issued Dec. 15. ``What we have here, purely and simply, is a
concerted effort by an experienced tax lawyer and two corporate
executives to defeat and evade payment of taxes and to cover up
their acts.''
</P>
<P>
   One tactic, he wrote, was to funnel kickbacks to ``sham''
companies that Kanter controlled. Kanter, the judge wrote, would
then withdraw the cash, replacing it with purported accounts
receivable from other ``sham'' companies. Such an exchange, if done
properly, can be a legal tax-free swap. But, the judge wrote, the
accounts receivable would be written off as worthless, fabricating
a tax loss for the sham company. These transactions, the judge
held, involved no real exchanges and were frauds.
</P>
<P>
   In case after case, he found, these transactions involved ``pure
tax avoidance vehicles'' with no business purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The judge characterized Kanter's testimony at the 1994 trial as
``implausible'' and ``incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Couvillion, who took five years to reach his ruling, sided with
Kanter on only a few minor issues, one of them involving $349.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Kanter said he was shocked that the judge ``could
ignore the testimony of more than a dozen witnesses'' who were all
``of the highest integrity'' that the payments were not kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Kanter, 68, has earned sizeable fees representing many wealthy
Americans over the years, including Chicago's multibillionaire
Pritzker family and a number of Hollywood producers. Although he
said he did not consider himself a wealthy man, five years ago he
had enough financial muscle to try to buy the Miami Dolphins
football team _ the former Chicago Bears coach Mike Ditka and the
Chicago developer Bruce Frey were his partners in that effort.
</P>
<P>
   He has a long history of fights with the IRS, but in many cases
his clients have come away paying far less in taxes than the IRS
sought. When A.N. Pritzker died in 1986 the IRS sought $150 million
in taxes, but because of Kanter's elaborate tax planning the family
paid only $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Stef Tucker, a Washington tax lawyer and former chairman of the
American Bar Association tax section, said Kanter was one of the
most creative tax lawyers in the country and was a pioneer in
seeing how foreign trusts could be used to legally reduce taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was simply using gaps, failures by Congress to focus on
areas in the tax law, to the advantage of his clients,'' Tucker
said, adding that Kanter's willingness to disclose his techniques
in lectures and articles was a strong indicator that they were
lawful ``although he was clearly reaching the edges of the
envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   The court noted that Kanter and his wife, Naomi, filed tax
returns showing a negative income in each of the 12 years from 1978
through 1989. They reported a total income in those 12 years of
negative $9.4 million and paid income taxes in only one of those
years, 1978, when they paid $1,671.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has audited his returns every year but one since 1961,
Kanter said. He said that he had settled the audits through 1973,
but that each return since then was still in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   While Kanter, a senior editor of the Journal of Taxation, is
famous in tax circles for recommending complex trusts to cut taxes,
the judge found that Kanter had committed civil fraud, largely by
using simple accounting tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Couvillion's opinion notes that the IRS Criminal Investigation
Division investigated Kanter, but is silent about why no indictment
was returned. Under federal tax law, once a civil suit is begun, no
criminal case is allowed. The IRS and the Justice Department both
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The kickbacks, the judge wrote, began in the early 1970s with
payments by A.N. Pritzker to J.D. Weaver, a Tenneco executive, for
his help in steering the contract to manage a new San Francisco
hotel to the Pritzker family's Hyatt Hotels chain. Tenneco and
Prudential were partners in financing the hotel. No one answered
repeated calls Friday to the Pritzker family office for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, who could not be located for comment, was to be paid 10
percent of the Hyatt management fees, but soon after the
Embarcadero Hyatt opened, Pritzker, the family patriarch, assigned
Kanter to negotiate a lower fee, the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   As Kanter was negotiating with Weaver, the court found, Kanter
was also ``surreptitiously'' negotiating with Weaver to have 70
percent of the payments turned over to himself, Ballard and Lisle.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver eventually agreed to accept $150,000 cash from a company
Kanter controlled in return for relinquishing that 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it could find ``no reasonable explanation'' for
Weaver to give up millions of dollars of future income in return
for $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the only possible explanation was that Lisle,
Ballard and Kanter wanted to share in the kickbacks for their roles
in steering the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Kanter said that the judge completely mischaracterized financial
deals that were completely unrelated, fashioning from bits of
testimony a kickback scheme where none existed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Later, the court found, Ballard and Lisle steered Prudential
investments to a variety of hotel, condominium and office projects
of four developers: Frey of Glencoe, Ill., William Schaffel of New
York and Kenneth Schnitzer and John Eulich of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ballard and Lisle left Prudential in 1982. Ballard then
became a partner at Goldman Sachs, and has since retired. Lisle
joined Travelers, where, the Tax Court found that for the next six
years, until he retired, he steered Travelers investments to
developers who paid him kickbacks, sharing the proceeds with
Kanter. Travelers is now a unit of Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Ballard and for the estate of Lisle, who died in
1993, said both men acted properly and that no kickbacks were paid.
The lawyer, Royal Martin, said Prudential knew the two men had
unrelated financial dealings with Weaver and the four developers.
He said he was not certain whether Travelers knew.
</P>
<P>
   Kanter, in an interview, also said that the payments were
unrelated to any financings by Prudential and Travelers and that
Prudential, at least, knew about them.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential's chief spokesman, Robert DeFillippo, said the
company was reviewing the case to determine what, if any, action it
might take.
</P>
<P>
   DeFillippo declined to say what rules, if any, Prudential had at
the time, or has now, governing such financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers is ``researching what actions were taken, if any,
regarding Mr. Lisle,'' said Keith Anderson, a Travelers' spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
