<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3625 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILLENNIUM-CELEBRATIO     12-31 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-CELEBRATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NIGHT OF STARS FOR WASHINGTON MILLENNIUM CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's capital looked more like Hollywood on
New Year's eve as President Clinton tapped his long list of
celebrity friends to help him usher in the New Year with a glitzy
White House dinner followed by a Millennium extravaganza on the
National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 guests descended upon the White House for the
``Creator's Dinner,'' which honored America's artists, inventors,
scientists and scholars. Among the guests were Muhammad Ali,
Elizabeth Taylor and Robert De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the guests, the president toasted the crowd and
praised America's ``endless capacity to express freedom and
creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we celebrate all that is great about America, all that
is intrinsic to the American spirit, we welcome the dawn of our
future,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the guests were seated outside in a heated tent in the
Rose Garden, a comfortable shelter with outside temperatures at
dusk in the balmy mid-50s.
</P>
<P>
   Only a select 320 people held invitations to sit with the
president and first lady in the East Room and State Dining Room
inside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Among those chosen to sit down with the Clintons were Ali,
Taylor, De Niro, opera divas Jessye Norman and Kathleen Battle,
historian Arthur Schlesinger, Jr., poet Rita Dove, concert
violinist Itzhak Perlman, playwright Neil Simon, and actors Jack
Nicholson and Mary Tyler Moore. The tables, draped with velvet
tablecloths, were set with white china with a silver _ that's real
silver _ band. In the middle of each table was a solid silver bowl
filled with white Phalenopsis orchids, white roses, white sparkle
holly and crystal balls. Adorning each silver bowl was a silver
candlestick with white tapers.
</P>
<P>
   Diners feasted on beluga caviar, lobster, foie gras and oyster
velout, served with Sterling Chardonnay, before moving on to the
main course of truffle marinated rack of lamb, roasted artichoke
and pepper rogo't and crispy garlic polenta served with Dehlinger
Pinot Noir. The dinner ended with a chocolate and champagne
delight, served with Iron Horse Brut champagne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: FOLLOWING THREE GRAFS ARE EMBARGOED UNTIL 9:30 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, the president gave another toast _ this one to his
wife _ and a short speech about the past and the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must come together to make this a true changing of the
times, a gateway to greater peace and progress and freedom in the
world,'' Clinton said. ``In the new century, we may not be able to
eliminate the hateful intolerance we saw too much of in this
century. But I believe we will see the rise of a healthy
intolerance of bigotry, oppression and abject poverty, not just in
our own communities but across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and their guests then traveled via shuttle vans to
the Lincoln Memorial for the splashy, 3-hour ``America's Millennium
Gala,'' a program hosted by rapper Will Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: END OF EMBARGOED MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment on the Mall also included Robert Duvall, Diane
Keaton, Kathy Mattea, Bobby McFerrin, Don McLean, Brian Stokes
Mitchell, Kenny Rogers, Luther Vandross, Trisha Yearwood, Sam
Waterston, BeBe Winans and Luke Cresswell, accompanied by the
25-member company of the Broadway production ``Stomp.''In the final
half-hour of 1999, large projection screens erected beside the
Lincoln Memorial were scheduled to show an 18-minute millennial
movie, ``The Unfinished Journey'' by Steven Spielberg.At the end of
the movie, the president planned to speak briefly and then start
the evening's pyrotechnic extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   With just 20 seconds left before midnight, Clinton was to light
a fuse that would burn its way along the length of the reflecting
pool, ending at the base of the Washington Monument, now surrounded
by an elaborate scaffold because of refurbishing work.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at 11:59:50 p.m., 10 successive bursts of brilliant white
stars were expected to rain down the sides of the monument, each 55
feet above the one before it. Finally, beginning at midnight, the
entire monument was expected to be covered with ``a stunningly
beautiful waterfall'' of white pyrotechnics, according to Philip
Butler, who is producing the show for Fireworks by Grucci, a Long
Island, N.Y., company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monument is a national icon which is held in great
reverence,'' Butler said last week, ``and we could never use it as
a fireworks stage, except for the scaffolding being there.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the gala, the first couple planned to return to the
White House for another party with about 1,000 guests ``that will
go for quite a while, we think, into the new year,'' said White
House spokeswoman Ann Lewis. For those revelers who make it, the
White House party was scheduled to end with breakfast ``a little
before dawn,'' according to Toby Graff, spokeswoman for the first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
