<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ITALY-Y2K-0101-1STLD-     12-31 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-Y2K-0101-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: updates number in lede; in 6th graf, corrects name of
Italian Prime Minister to 'Massimo D'Alema' sted of 'Romano Prodi';
in final graf, fills out Pope's quote
 &HT;    POPE JOINS NEW YEAR'S PARTY AT THE VATICAN: Y2K FAILS TO DAMPEN
FESTIVITIES
 &HT;    EDs: This story may be updated at 10 p.m. EST.
 &HT;    ADAM L. FREEMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Technology failed to clash with tradition New Year's Eve
as more than 100,000 revelers packed the Vatican's St. Peter's
Square for an evening of music and a papal blessing with no worries
about technological glitches.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation known more for its culinary influence and historical
treasures than for civic organization, Italy passed into the Third
Millennium with barely a nibble from the so-called ``Y2K Bug.''
</P>
<P>
   The historic square witnessed pilgrims and secular revelers
rubbing shoulders with nuns and priests while listening to the
ecclesiastical rhythms of the Harlem Gospel Singers among others.
Periodic pops could be heard from uncorked clandestine champagne
bottles smuggled into the celebration under the noses of the
omnipresent security.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening Pope John Paul II presided over Vespers
in St. Peter's Basilica to celebrate the beginning of the new
millennium and the closing of the 20th Century.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those present at the celebrations had traveled to Rome
for the opening ceremonies of the Roman Catholic Grand Jubilee
which began on Christmas Eve and will end on January 6, 2001, the
day of the Epiphany. Upwards of 30 million pilgrims are expected to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight (local time) the crowd was too festive to worry
about Y2K problems that could complicate Italy's celebration. On
Dec. 30, Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema issued a statement
stating that there would be no problem when the calendar turns to
Year Zero. Forty-thousand people burned the midnight oil to control
possible complications in all aspects of civil infrastructure.
Among them were police, coast guard, doctors and even cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in Rome, a ``war room'' of engineers worked around to
assure that all precautions and interventions had gone smoothly.
Italy's airports were empty Friday as all Alitalia flights were
cancelled between 10:45 p.m. New Year's Eve and 6:20 a.m. January
1, said Enrico Lepri, a spokesman for the airline.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after midnight the 79-year-old Pope appeared on
his balcony to bless the crowd below.
</P>
<P>
   After a festive cheer from the throngs the Pope said: ``The
clock of history strikes an important hour: at this moment the Year
2000 begins, and we enter a new millennium. For believers, this is
the year of the Great Jubilee. A Happy New Year to all of you, men
and women of every part of the world!''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
