<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS REBELS DIG IN, TOLL MOUNTS FOR RUSSIANS IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Refiling to correct dateline to Russia, fix typo in hed.)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ After Dmitry Baidanov's legs were shattered by
mortar fire, he crawled for three days through the streets of
Grozny until he reached the Russian lines.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the 19-year-old private was splayed out on his stomach,
unconscious in a field hospital on the western outskirts of the
Chechen capital. He may be one of the lucky ones. A row of six
corpses lay in the muddy field nearby, wrapped in shiny foil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more than 10 wounded yesterday, and there will be more
wounded today,'' said Dmitry Turkov, a hospital orderly. ``They are
fighting less than 2 miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a side of the Chechen war that most Russians are rarely
shown: patching up the wounded and the grisly task of disposing of
the dead.
</P>
<P>
   When the Russian military began its campaign against the Islamic
rebels, its generals vowed to win a speedy victory and hold down
Russian losses. But as Russia begins the New Year, its troops are
mired in urban warfare and the still popular war is claiming a
higher toll.
</P>
<P>
   Russian artillery is hurling round after round toward Grozny.
The firepower was supposed to break the will of the rebels before
Russian Interior Ministry troops moved block by block to ``clean''
the city. But the rebels are doggedly fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the army is mopping up in Grozny, we have another
wave of casualties,'' said Maj. Oleg E. Zayev, a military doctor
from St. Petersburg and a senior member of the Special Medical Team
Number 600, which runs the tent hospital here.
</P>
<P>
   Zayev said that the vast majority of his patients are stabilized
and then whisked by helicopter to the rear for extended treatment.
But just a few minutes after he spoke the militants claimed another
victim on a nearby hillside.
</P>
<P>
   Russian scouts scampered up a hill hospital to check for snipers
before inviting a small group of Russian and Western journalists to
venture forward for a commanding view of Grozny's Staropromyslovsky
district, the scene of heavy street fighting.
</P>
<P>
   On the march up the hill the reporters passed a soldier who had
just been shot through the neck and was being tended by paramedics.
By the time they marched down the hill 40 minutes later, he was
dead and his comrade torn by grief.
</P>
<P>
   The mood among the soldiers was edgy. Dec. 31 is the fifth
anniversary of the Russian military's disastrous attack on Grozny,
when Russian armored columns rushed into the center of the city
only to be annihilated by Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The troops were worried that the militants might commemorate the
date by mounting a counteroffensive. Some monitored a tactical
radio, trying to intercept the rebels' communications. As they
tried to make out the chatter, trucks full of fresh soldiers drove
toward Grozny for this chance to ``clean'' the city.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there seemed to be little respite from the war at the
field hospital. Rumors of ghastly setbacks have circulated among
the medical team here. Turkov, the hospital orderly, said he had
heard that the fighting inside the city has been intense and that
the corpses of Interior Ministry troops have been ferried out of
Grozny by the truckload.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke thunderous blasts of Russian artillery rippled
through the hospital tents. Several batteries of Russian artillery
are deployed only a few hundred yards away, and they literally
fired 122-millimeter shells over the hospital tents toward Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Pvt. Dmitry N. Kurochkin, a 20 year-old private from southern
Siberia who was wounded in the leg Saturday morning near Grozny's
Zavodskoi district, seemed too dazed to mind the artillery.
</P>
<P>
   His motorized infantry unit was never ordered to enter downtown
Grozny. Its role was to secure the outskirts of the city while
Interior Ministry troops carried out the dirty business of mopping
up. Even Grozny's suburbs, however, are dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never actually go to Grozny,'' he said. ``We were just
outside Grozny for a week and half. I was in a trench and there was
a shot. I was the only one who was hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pvt. Sergei Shirokov, a hospital orderly, kept Kurochkin company
while he waited to be flown by helicopter to the rear. Shirokov
knows what the battle of Grozny is like.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days ago he was driving a T-62 tank that was hit by a
