<HEADER>
A3629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     12-31 1621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS HUDDLE WOULD BE WORTH GETTING INTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would you pay to listen in on this conversation?
</P>
<P>
   In the next few days, the National Football League may very well
have its own version of the Y2K bug if Patriots owner Bob Kraft has
to call the New York Jets asking for permission to speak with
defensive coordinator Bill Belichick about being New England's next
head coach. Kraft, or someone else in a position of power with the
Patriots, will have to ask none other than Bill Parcells for
permission. It would be interesting, since Kraft and Parcells have
not spoken since Parcells departed Foxborough for the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, there would be nothing Parcells could do to stop
Belichick from going to New England, or anywhere else. But
Belichick has a contract that says he &UR;  &LR; will be the next head coach
of the Jets. Owner Leon Hess, before his death last year, gave
Belichick a $1 million bonus to stick around and succeed Parcells.
Meanwhile, Belichick is the highest-paid assistant coach in the
NFL. Parcells has not yet made up his mind whether he is going to
coach another year. It will depend a great deal on what the next
owner has to say. And the next owner will be named in a week. The
Patriots, as soon as their regular season ends, can go after
Belichick, or anyone else they are interested in, right away.
</P>
<P>
   As an assistant coach, Belichick, under normal circumstances,
would have to be allowed to interview for a head coaching vacancy.
However, if Belichick were the Jets' head coach, permission would
not be granted. But Belichick won't be the Jets' head coach Monday
because Parcells, most likely, won't decide on his future until he
meets with the new owner. The Patriots and Jets put commissioner
Paul Tagliabue in a bind three years ago in the battle over whether
Parcells could leave New England. Tagliabue made the Jets pay
compensation in the form of draft choices and New York wasn't happy
about it. What does Tagliabue do if the Patriots want to talk with
Belichick and the Jets say no, pointing out that the process to
bring in a new owner, in which the NFL is involved, has been so
slow that it has delayed Parcells's decision?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Great observation by Joe Morgan, former Red Sox manager: ``ESPN
picks Michael Jordan the best athlete over Babe Ruth. Michael
Jordan tried to play baseball and couldn't even make it in Class A
ball. He was a failure. Babe Ruth is the greatest baseball player
that ever lived. Baseball is a much tougher sport to play than
basketball, yet Michael Jordan is picked over Ruth. How does that
make sense?'' Well Joe, none of these polls make sense. The one we
had here lost all credibility when it started with Warren Spahn,
one of the greatest pitchers in history with more wins than any
other lefthander, ranked 100th. How about picking Babe Ruth at 18?
Ted Williams, our pick as the top sports ``figure,'' couldn't
compare to Bill Russell or Bobby Orr as an athlete. Russell should
have been No. 1, the second greatest basketball player of all-time
behind Jordan. Orr was the greatest hockey player who ever lived.
Everything that Wayne Gretzky could do, Orr could do better. He was
a better skater, better shooter, more physical, better in the
corners, better in open ice. Bobby Schmautz played with both and
had this comment: ``Orr was the greatest player I ever played with.
Gretzky was protected. Orr was a target.'' Rocky Marciano would be
third on my local poll. He retired as the undefeated heavyweight
champion, 49-0 with 46 knockouts, when boxing was boxing in the
1950s. Williams is a great sports figure, perhaps the most beloved
athlete to play here. But for most of his career, he could not run,
throw, or field, all of which has been overshadowed by his
greatness as a hitter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is my take on why Harry Sinden went to New Jersey to meet
with Pat Burns: Sinden got word that Burns was telling friends he
thought he was going to be fired. Sinden told Burns he was not (1)
so the Bruins would have no excuses for the way they were playing
and (2) so Burns would have no excuses at the end of the year if
the team fails to meet expectations. With the additions of Dave
Andreychuk, Marty McSorley, and Joe Murphy, this team should be
much better than it was a year ago, and it is not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette on the future of the Red Sox: ``When I came here I
wanted to develop a farm system that would have a steady flow of
talent. I think we have done that. If you have enough good players
you can do two things _ use them to make your own major league team
better or use them in a trade to get a veteran player from some
other team that fits your need. Some people have asked me why we
have been trading so many of our minor league players the last
couple of years and there is good reason for it. We can't protect
all of them. Sooner of later, if we didn't use them to make trades,
we would lose them in the draft. We lost a couple of young pitchers
this year in the draft.'' Duquette says the team's rule of thumb is
to decide on a minor league player by the end of his fourth year in
the organzation. Once every year Duquette sends his major league
scouts to evaluate all the minor leaguers and project those who
will make the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn did not completely withdraw the appeal of his
suspension. He couldn't get it done before Sunday's season finale
because much of the NFL was shut down for the holiday. Glenn was
suspended for not showing up to meetings, which might not stick
when the grievance is heard in April or May. You can't suspend a
player for missing a meeting but you can suspend him for
insubordination. Reportedly, when Glenn met with Pete Carroll to
explain his actions, Glenn was not responsive, which comes under
the heading of insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a scouting report on the Ravens from a coach whose team
plays them twice a year: ``A very physical team. New England better
be ready to meet the challenge because this is a team that plays
very hard. Outstanding defense. They have one of the fastest
defensive teams in the league. They put extreme pressure on the
quarterback. (Peter) Boulware and (Michael) McCrary are two of the
best pass rushers in the league. They come hard off the corners.
They use their interior down linemen to tie up the blockers so they
can't get out on the linebackers. Those guys inside slant a lot to
cause confusion. The linebackers can really run side to side. New
England won't get outside on them. (Middle linebacker) Ray Lewis is
one of the best in the game. They cover well at the corners, and
Rod Woodson is revived at free safety. Offensively, they are not
consistent, but they can make the big play. The two guys they have
on the outside, (Qadry) Ismail and (Patrick) Johnson, can hurt you
deep. I just watched some film of them playing Cincinnati last
week. They wanted that shutout. You could see it. Cincinnati scored
40 points in the two games before that one, and these guys shut
them right down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rams coach Dick Vermeil and Jim Mora of the Colts show it's not
how old you are, or what happened at your last job, it's whether
you can coach in the right situation. St. Louis wanted to get rid
of Vermeil at the end of last season but reportedly could not work
out a financial settlement, so he stayed. The Rams are now 13-2 and
will have home-field advantage throughout the NFC playoffs. When
Bill Polian took over the Colts two years ago and was looking for a
head coach, he decided on Dick Jauron (another Swampscott
connection). Polian was just hours away from calling Jauron in
Jacksonville, where he was the defensive coordinator, to tell him
he had the job. However, Polian got a call from Chiefs general
manager Carl Peterson, recommending Mora. Polian had been told Mora
didn't want to coach anymore. Peterson said it wasn't so, and when
Polian spoke with Mora, he decided Mora was the guy. The Colts are
now 13-2 and AFC East champions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People close to the University of Virginia football program
thought veteran head coach George Welsh would retire if his team
didn't win its bowl game Thursday night. The Cavaliers not only
lost, they got clobbered. However, the man in Virginia's future was
supposed to be Tom O'Brien and his Boston College Eagles got buried
a day later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot of talk about the Canadian government
possibly giving financial help to struggling NHL teams to keep them
in the country. If that fails, Bruins owner Jeremy Jacobs thinks
the league might have to step in. ``We can't let some of those
teams fail,'' he said. ``It shouldn't be allowed to happen. These
Canadian players are still the lifeblood of our league. I think
eventually the league might have to ask the American teams to pitch
in financially to save them. If asked, I think we should do it.
It's a must as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. Running back Cecil Collins didn't play for the
Dolphins the last six weeks because he was injured. In the interim,
he was arrested for allegedly climbing into a first floor apartment
and then, when surprised by the couple living there, jumped out the
window and ran away. By the way, the reason he can't play football
is he has a broken ankle. Not bad for a guy with a broken ankle.
But he'll have plenty of time to heal. He's facing four years in
jail in his native Louisiana for violating his parole agreement and
is expected to be shipped back their shortly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
