<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-YAC-RILEY-BOS &LR;      12-31 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-RILEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RILEY, AMERICA TRUE ON COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, N.Z. _ In the closing weeks of the century, Dawn Riley
seemed destined to make sailing's year-end list as the most
significant American woman ever to haul a mainsheet or spin a
rudder.
</P>
<P>
   Two Whitbreads and an America's Cup women's breakthrough aboard
Mighty Mary in 1995 _ followed by her own current campaign _ would
easily earn the 35-year-old from San Francisco nomination to the
top of that list. Whitbread and America's Cup are the two biggest
sailing races in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But that was last century. And as a new one started
bombastically on this frenzied waterfront, a rather amazing
transformation has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   All week as America True's canary yellow hull thrashed through
the big seas of Hauraki Gulf practicing for the semifinal round of
the Cup trials that begin here Saturday, somehow the ``woman'' has
fallen away from Riley's mixed-gender team from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   So has the patronizing smirk at the notion that women can
compete at the very top. Compete and win.
</P>
<P>
   Now the yellow boat looks dangerous under sail. Now it is
serious, far from the days when the women's entry into this, the
very pinnacle of international regattas, was thought by many a
glorified publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Even some on her own team gave a gentle chuckle when Riley set
as an early goal for her one-boat, underfunded campaign the role of
giant-killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day before the first round (in October), I had an informal
talk with a group of our people, including sailors, and they asked
me what I thought we were going to do,'' Riley said last week. ``I
said I'd be happy if we were first or second. Some of them said,
`Oh really?' Others just looked at me and laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the patronizing smiles disappeared the December
afternoon America True beat her bitter cross-town rival, Paul
Cayard in AmericaOne, to take an overall lead from Cayard, the
steadiest and highest-scoring American to that point.
</P>
<P>
   And most certainly, the crew aboard the New York Yacht Club's
Young America became true believers in Riley the day America True
sailed past them for the 9-point win in Round 3 of the trials,
driving the first serious nails into the coffin of the
high-rolling, pre-race favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an even sweeter moment of triumph came when the
combination of her team's powerful sailing and Young America's
stumbling performance put the fate of the once-powerful New Yorkers
in Riley's hands. Not even a pallet load of Sam Adams beer sent to
Riley's camp by Young America as a ``diplomacy gesture'' would sway
the tough-minded Riley to race against her will.
</P>
<P>
   After losing to Riley, Cayard, and Dennis Conner within days,
Young America arrived at the final weekend of the December series
needing not only a win of their own, but help from Riley. To have
any hope of gaining enough points to enter the top six slots in the
semifinals, Riley had to beat the French boat, Le Defi, on the
final day of racing.
</P>
<P>
   To Riley, who had already qualified for the semis, the points
meant nothing, and it was the night before race day that Young
America's John Marshall sent over the beer just to wedge open a
``friendly discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall now recalls the gesture with a mournful chuckle: ``Our
attempts at diplomacy failed.'' More seriously, some team members
from Young America complained that Riley had committed bad
sportsmanship in failing to give the French a fair race and New
York their shot at the semis.
</P>
<P>
   And an even darker theory has emerged, passed on via the
Internet by at least one Young America team member, that the other
Americans _ Cayard, Conner, and Riley _ had mathematically rigged
the series against New York by throwing races to weaker opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The mere mention of that theory, which circulated as ``dock
talk'' for the week after the series, still sends the flame into
Riley's cheek and tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's absolutely ridiculous, and if we could prove who had
written it we would have taken legal action against them. It really
makes New York look like a bunch of whiners.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, says Riley, her decision not to race the French was
based largely on her not wanting to risk her single boat in rough
conditions. Especially in light of the breakup and near sinking of
Young America's hull 53 in November. ``In the end, we had to do
what was best for our chances. I would always rather sail than do
anything else, but there was nothing for us to gain out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, not with a bang but a whimper, New York was out, leaving
Riley's AmericaTrue not just in the semis but tied for second
place. Just where Riley said she wanted to be back when the bright
yellow boat from San Francisco was eye-catching in color only.
</P>
<P>
   It was a surprise to most Cup watchers who figured New York for
somewhere near the top and Riley's bid little more than a noble
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, however, the official word from Marshall and
Young America is that Riley made the correct pragmatic choice,
though it hurt them. Marshall disclaims any knowledge or belief in
the conspiracy theory about the other Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``America True is my life, my personal life, everything,'' said
Riley, who has raced sailboats twice around the world, once as
skipper of her own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That simple quote seems to say it all about the powerfully built
athlete with the blond ponytail. When she started working on the
America True campaign after the last Whitbread, she had no doubts
about her sailing ability. Her first taste of Cup racing came
aboard Mighty Mary, Bill Koch's all-women entry in 1995 that ended
with a man joining the crew as race coach, Dave Dellenbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The move split the crew into two camps. Lest anyone mistake
Riley for a doctrinaire feminist, she led the pro-Dellenbaugh
faction on the simple grounds: ``If that will help us win, I'm all
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a question of sailing ability as she formed America
True, the real doubts concerned money. Some competitors have spent
from $50 million to more than $100 million to win the Cup in its
post-modern era that began in 1992 with the adoption of the new
International America's Cup Class 75-footers.
</P>
<P>
   But on Riley pushed in the early days, with a feisty doggedness
underlying her friendly casual nature. At one point, she was
raising funds on her personal credit card just to keep the ball
rolling, if ever so slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Helmsman Chris Coffin happened like a race-winning windshift.
The 41-year-old Internet entrepreneur, who now acts as CEO of the
syndicate, had just left the company he founded, the $1.9 billion
US Robotics, and decided to put seed money into the campaign and
take over as financial manager.
</P>
<P>
   With no intention of funding America True himself, Coffin sought
sponsors to help support the campaign's relatively barebones $21
million budget with its single-boat program and designer Phil
Kaiko.
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders in the top four, America One, Nippon Challenge,
and Prada, have built two new boats apiece and have much larger
budgets. But especially after the demise of New York, Riley
believes the America's Cup is not a crown to be bestowed upon the
royals in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's infallible. Because the America's Cup is more than
just a yacht race. It's an overall organization. It's a
corporation. It has motivation. It has momentum, and it has
interpersonal relationships. It has all these things and more put
into a pressure cooker once you start competing. To win an
America's Cup you have to find a way to manage it all.''
</P>
<P>
   With former Kiwi racer John Cutler on the helm, Riley prefers
the job in the pit, one of the physical jobs on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the pit, and then I come back and do the runners
(winched backstays) and help with the strategy and direct crew
work. Generally I call the mark roundings _ how we're going to drop
the sails and get them up again.''
</P>
<P>
   But does Dawn Riley, the first woman to enter an America's Cup
campaign in 149 years, believe she can be the first woman to win
the America's Cup at the dawn of the new century?
</P>
<P>
   In a word that she neither shouts nor hurries nor thinks about
for very long: ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Note: Because New Zealand is 18 hours ahead of US East Coast time,
all action takes place a day ahead (i.e. a Sunday noon race there
is taking place Saturday evening here). To avoid confusion, all
time references in Boston Globe America's Cup stories will reflect
when the events took place according to Eastern Standard Time.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
