<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3631 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-31 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE PARTY, NEW BEGINNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slowly the sun rose Friday _ over Auckland, Sydney, Jerusalem,
the battered-but-unbowed Champs-Elysees. The world bathed in a
once-in-a-lifetime glow, rarer by far than Halley's comet.
</P>
<P>
   The impending birth of a new era called for grand gestures, and
those calls were heeded: Boris Yeltsin surprised the world Friday
by handing in his resignation, while the Dalai Lama sought to
provide an opening note of inspiration, urging the world to seize
the chance to render the next millennium one of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Over Times Square, a giant ball appeared in the New Year's Eve
dawn, delighting New Yorkers already awaiting the big night. In
South Africa, Nelson Mandela declared himself disappointed by the
20th century, and called for a more caring world in the one to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia, where for some reason it is only 1992, responded to
the big event with a collective yawn.
</P>
<P>
   As midnight ticked by across the time zones, the end of the
world seemed to be confounding predictions of its arrival: power
didn't fail, computers weren't crashing, and ATMs seemed to
function. Destiny travels on its own schedule.
</P>
<P>
   For all the round-the-clock coverage on television, the
worldwide party seemed to be fizzling a bit. I started thinking
that all the party-planners had missed something. Maybe, for all
the festivity, this New Year's was more personal than public, more
a time of local reflection, than global merriment. Maybe the people
who passed up the tours to New Zealand and Greenwich were on to the
true spirit of the thing.
</P>
<P>
   I can't let the old year go without recalling a few tidbits from
1999 that I won't miss.
</P>
<P>
   Like reading and writing about controversies over a new home for
the New England Patriots _ the parking squabbles, the relocation of
tenants in the trailer park, Connecticut's overreaching Governor
John G. Rowland, and the all-star posturing at the Massachusetts
State House.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also happy to wave goodbye to Stephen Fagan, a kidnapper and
con artist whose greatest scam was to manipulate his daughters, the
media, and the public in a bizarre but successful bid for
martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   Not many tears will be shed in South Boston for the lost
companionship of Peggy Davis-Mullen, the self-styled conscience of
the neighborhood who moved to West Roxbury with guns blazing. Once
she was an anti-heroin crusader, but before long she said drugs had
driven her out of the neighborhood. It had nothing, of course, to
do with her dwindling popularity among the voters who know her
best.
</P>
<P>
   It was an inauspicious year for some of the causes I care about,
with the continued erosion of affirmative action in the schools,
the Police Department, and the Fire Department. The new MCAS exam
also threatens to erode educational opportunities for minority
students, who so far have flunked it in droves.
</P>
<P>
   But New Year's Day is not a day for politics or causes. It is
local in a different way: a time for new beginnings, the first day
_ like every day _ of the rest of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   The hype has died down; the last champagne has stopped flowing.
The orchestra has packed up; the world didn't end. (Alas, your
hangover may be proving Y2K compliant.)
</P>
<P>
   Now what? Has your party ended, or is it just beginning? What,
exactly, did you ring in? What is your 2000 about?
</P>
<P>
   We all have our old-standby resolutions, the ones carried over
from last year and the year before that and the year before that.
The gym memberships. The resolve to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, New Year's Eve 1999 was supposed to be the
excuse for the party to end all parties. More recently, it was
supposed to be the end of the computer age as we know it. Then,
after fewer people than expected chose to circle the globe and the
world seemed unlikely to end, we were left without the party or the
chaos, left to chart our own courses.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's a small victory in that, a triumph of the personal
over the huge and commercial. It isn't only politics that ends up
being local.
</P>
<P>
   So as the new day dawns, I wish for all of you simply what I
wish for myself: peace, a bit of prosperity, and a bit of luck. Now
that the holiday is over, we get the real party, the daily
celebration of our ordinary lives.
</P>
<P>
   Happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
