<HEADER>
A3644 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-Y2K-0101-COX     12-31 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-Y2K-0101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THIRD MILLENNIUM COMES TO BRITAIN: It's Zulu Time!
 &HT;    EDs: Thiswill be updated by 10 p.m. EST.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The new millennium arrived in London with the familiar
midnight toll of Big Ben followed by minutes of thundering,
dazzling bursts of fireworks over the rushing currents of the River
Thames.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.6 billion worth of fireworks filled the sky for more than
20 minutes. It was the much-anticipated climax of years of planning
to transform the British capital into party central for millennium
celebrations. By all early indicators, it was a rousing success _
or as rousing a success as such a celebration can be given its
tendency to attract hundreds of thousands of alcohol-soused
revelers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, police reported few more than routine incidents during the
night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night in which Britain confronted its past and present.
In the waning hours of the millennium, the BBC Concert Orchestra
played ``Rule, Britannia!'' for the final time of the age in Royal
Albert Hall. The 6,000 concert-goers _ some in tuxedos, some in
jeans _ stood and sang jubilantly while waving British flags.
</P>
<P>
   The song holds a far different resonance at the end of a century
that has seen the dissolution of one of the world's great empires.
As it enters the 21st century, Britain faces the real prospect of
being reduced to only England, with Scotland, Northern Ireland and
Wales now enjoying a measure of independence from the central
government in London.
</P>
<P>
   But for Edgar Robertson who had come to the Albert Hall concert
with his family from Birmingham _ the one in England _ the night
and century seemed full of promise. ``There isn't an empire anymore
at the end of this century, ``but Britain remains such an important
force in the world,'' he said. ``Could anybody really imagine a day
when you would see American troops heading into some hot spot
without their British cousins at their sides? But this will be
America's millennium, won't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the elegant confines of Albert Hall, the night took on a
substantially less refined air. On The Mall, the broad ceremonial
boulevard that terminates at Buckingham Palace, a carnival lit the
night with the wattage of stomach churning rides.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds jammed the city's ancient thoroughfares and squares. Much
of the central city was turned into a huge pedestrian zone.
</P>
<P>
   By 11:30 p.m. (GMT), Admiral Nelson's column rose from a solid
mass of human bodies crammed into Trafalgar Square. Dominating the
skyline near Big Ben and the Houses of Parliament was the one
annoying glitch: the stunning, five-story London Eye. The
state-of-the-art Ferris wheel was idle because it failed a safety
test earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, none of the dreaded snags expected with the feared Y2K bug
appeared. So pleased was the government in the country's successful
performance that it issued a statement before midnight declaring
that all was running without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic visual scene was the Thames River, its swift
currents lit by dozens of spotlights and laser beams to be the
``river of fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth II sailed down the River Thames, the center of
festivities, to light a huge millennium beacon afloat on a barge,
two hours before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen smaller beacons blazed on bridges, and hundreds of
thousands of people gathered along the riverbanks in the center of
the capital to watch a 120-foot wall of flame race across the
</P>
<P>
   water's surface at the moment the century turned.
</P>
<P>
   That was the cue to light 40,000 fireworks waiting on barges
moored along the river for a 15-minute display of color and light.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
