u a BC-Y2K-INTERNET &LR;      12-31 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-INTERNET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET REMAINS STABLE, AS USERS TRACK ARRIVAL OF NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the world slid nervously Friday through the shadow of its
first global technology challenge, many Year 2000 experts took
special comfort in the relatively stable behavior of one of their
key tools in dealing with the problem: the not-always-reliable
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Service in the vast network of networks linking 60 million
computers and over 150 users appeared to sag at times in isolated
locations as Internet users turned to e-mail, Web sites, newsgroups
and electronic chat rooms to track the arrival of the Year 2000 in
more and more time zones.
</P>
<P>
   But experts who mounted the most extensive effort ever to
monitor the Internet's global reliability said that the overall
performance was impressive and highlighted the indispensable role
the Internet had played in reducing Year 2000 risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might look back on this as graduation day for the
Internet,'' said Michael L. Todd, a computer consultant in Irvine,
Calif., who heads the Los Angeles chapter of the Internet Society,
an international organization of Internet users and developers.
</P>
<P>
   The sense that the Internet was facing a trial of sorts during
the Year 2000 rollover had grown steadily in recent weeks. Some
hospitals, government agencies and manufacturers decided to close
down World Wide Web sites or cut off e-mail during the rollover
after hearing predictions that hackers would be treating Y2K as an
occasion to spread computer viruses.
</P>
<P>
   And a poll last week by the Information Technology Association
of America _ carried out over the Internet _ reported that
technology managers viewed the Internet as more likely to be hit by
Y2K glitches than any other computer system or public utility.
</P>
<P>
   But organizations monitoring performance Friday said there were
no signs yet of major problems. One broad measure of all equipment
on the Internet, including local service providers and some
customers, showed a slow decline in the percentage of sites
reachable during the day on both the Internet as a whole and the
World Wide Web in particular, but that may have been the result of
some regular Internet users disconnecting as a precautionary
measure, according to John D. Quarterman, chief executive of Matrix
Information and Directory Services, which publishes Internet
performance data.
</P>
<P>
   Most users stayed wired, though, and the unsubstantiated Y2K
rumors and anecdotes for which the Internet is infamous began
flowing within hours of the arrival of Jan. 1 in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   One breathless e-mail signed ``familyman'' claimed that an IBM
emergency parts center (later said to be in Pennsylvania) was being
swamped by orders from New Zealand and Australia. IBM was
scrambling to charter aircraft to meet the demand, it claimed. An
hour later an IBM spokesman in Japan issued a sharp denial.
</P>
<P>
   But as they have regularly been doing with far less fanfare than
Y2K activists, workers in the Year 2000 project trenches also
flocked to Internet Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the Internet has emerged as a major
vehicle for distribution of Year 2000 reports and data within
companies and government agencies, for regulators like the Food and
Drug Administration, which used it to provide information on the
Year 2000 readiness of medical equipment, and industry groups like
Global 2000, the consortium of international banks that gathered
and shared data on the readiness of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Computer companies like Hewlett-Packard and Microsoft that
increasingly rely on the Internet to quickly and inexpensively
distribute new versions of products or patches to old ones became
especially reliant on that new distribution channel as the end of
1999 neared. Hewlett-Packard said its web site listing technical
information about the Year 2000 status of its various products had
received over three million inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   One boomlet of traffic Friday involved a new report of a
potential Year 2000 problem for computers, traffic lights and
military equipment that get the time and date from the government's
atomic clock in Fort Collins, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Glass, a computer consultant based in Laramie, Wyo., had
recently learned that the atomic clock uses just two digits to
record the date. After a search this week of documents posted on
the Internet by the government, Glass concluded that the government
had never warned the public that some equipment linked to the clock
might need reprogramming or replacement to avoid mistaking Saturday
for Jan. 1, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Glass' work was relayed rapidly into computer circles primarily
through David Farber, a University of Pennsylvania computer expert
who has more than 20,000 people on his e-mail list. ``There is no
other way to instantaneously alert so many people of a potential
problem,'' said Farber.
</P>
<P>
   Or to reassure them. The Australian government reported seven
million visitors to its Y2K site in a matter of hours Friday, all
of whom learned there were no major problems to report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 1956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
