<HEADLINE>
SECURITY OF LOUISIANA PRISON QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three days after a prison guard and an inmate were
killed in an escape attempt at the Louisiana State Penitentiary,
law enforcement officials in the area raised questions Friday about
the security of the infamous prison farm, known as Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the incident on Tuesday night, there were lapses and
escape attempts at the 18,000-acre maximum-security prison, said
Charles Shropshire, the district attorney for the section of the
state that includes the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a number of events that have raised questions
about the practices there,'' said Shropshire, who is weighing
whether to seek the death penalty for five surviving inmates
involved in the hostage-taking incident. ``You know, twice a year,
I have to take a grand jury to the prison to report on conditions
there to the court. I'm going to have to review how we conduct that
tour to make sure I don't expose the jurors to a hostage
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, four men sawed their way out of death row and nearly
made it out of the prison before being caught. The hacksaws they
used were apparently smuggled inside books. In January, four
convicted murderers escaped after a jail employee helped smuggle a
can containing guns inside the walls. They were caught, and the
employee is about to be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days before the incident, the Baton Rouge Sunday Advocate
published a lengthy article outlining how lapses and collusion by
prison guards had led to several escapes and life-threatening
situations. Citing internal prison documents, the newspaper
reported, an inmate with a six-inch knife walked out of the main
prison building and into another part of the complex, where he
nearly stabbed a guard before being overpowered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been going on for quite some time,'' said Sheriff W.M.
Daniel of East Feliciana parish, where Angola is located. ``It's
been kind of deteriorating over a period of time where the inmates
are losing respect for the security personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper article was quite critical of the prison warden,
Burl Cain, who was not available for comment Friday. But Richard L.
Stalder, the secretary of the Louisiana Department of Public Safety
and Corrections, said in an interview Friday that the reports of
negligence were overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidents of violence at Angola are as low as they have
been since records have been kept,'' he said. ``The fact that this
escape did not take place, that a captain sacrificed his life to
protect public safety, that the tactical response was swift and
decisive, shows me that you don't have a security system with a
fatal flaw.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The uprising on Tuesday night was by far the most serious of the
recent incidents at Angola. Six convicted murderers serving life
sentences took three guards hostage after a botched escape attempt,
armed with metal shards and a plastic craft mallet stolen from a
leatherworking area. One of the guards, Capt. David Knapps, was
bludgeoned and stabbed to death in a bathroom after he refused to
give up his keys, before other guards subdued the rebellion with
percussion grenades. One of the inmates was shot and killed in the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Knapps was buried Friday in Tunica, down the road from the
prison gates.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a state judge signed arrest warrants for the
remaining five inmates, accusing each of first-degree murder and
aggravated kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Shropshire said the repeated incidents at the prison made it
unclear whether this attempt was provoked by another hostage
standoff earlier this month in the parish, or county, jail in St.
Martinville, La. After a six-day siege, an unusual deal with Cuba
allowed seven Cuban inmates involved in the uprising to be
deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say whether they were related, because we've had
so many escapes,'' Shropshire said. ``But I do know they have a
problem there that the Department of Corrections needs to look
into.''
</P>
</TEXT>
