<HEADER>
A3654 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-SUGAR-BOWDEN-BOS &LR;      12-31 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-BOWDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BOWDEN, A LIFETIME OF PLUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The question came out as a ``What if''
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   What if Florida State beat Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl
Tuesday night, won its second national championship, and completed
its first unbeaten, untied season?
</P>
<P>
   ``What, exactly, would you do, Bobby Bowden?''
</P>
<P>
   The questioner was on a fishing expedition. What more could
Bowden accomplish in his career at Florida State? Wouldn't
everything else be a disappointment, a letdown?
</P>
<P>
   For a man with 303 victories in 34 seasons, for a man who is 70
and has accomplished every goal a coach can set for himself, it
sounded like a legitimate question. Why not ride off into the next
millennium on the shoulders of your team and on the highest
possible note?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win it, are you ready to ride off into the sunset?''
said Bowden. ``No, I'm not. When you retire, there is just one more
big event left. And I ain't ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden says the answer is the simplest one he can give for a
simple reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love to coach,'' he said. ``I love to take a take a
group of young men in the late summer and turn them into a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has done that year in and year out since arriving at
Florida State in 1976. Since 1987, no Florida State team has
finished lower than fourth in the national polls, a mind-boggling
stretch of consistency. Even if the Seminoles should lose to
Virginia Tech Tuesday, they should drop no lower than third in this
season's final balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden says he wants to continue coaching because that's not
only what he does, but who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was supposed to be a coach,'' he said. ``I was born
to be a coach. I lived behind goal posts at Woodlawn High School
(in Birmingham, Ala.). They kicked extra points in my backyard. I
had a garage there and a 12-foot-high fence. I'd get up there and
watch practice. I lived up there until I was 5. Then we moved three
blocks and there was a college campus with a football field. I
watched practice. I did that up until I was 17. So, I've always
been around college football. That's what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   His son Tommy is the coach at Clemson. His son Terry used to be
the coach at Auburn. His son Jeff is an assistant at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   If you looked up the definition of coach in the dictionary, you
might find a picture of Bobby and his clan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet times have changed. Athletes are different, society is
different, and Bowden has taken some hits, none harder than this
season when a series of off-the-field incidents, highlighted by the
transgressions of wide receiver Peter Warrick, tarnished not only
the image of Florida State, but, to some extent, that of Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I didn't think it affected us,'' said Bowden at
Friday's Sugar Bowl media day. ``I said, `They're kids. They can
shrug it off.' But thinking back at it, I think it did affect us to
some extent. Now, I think we're over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is Bowden. He has reached the point where he
is more a CEO than a coach. He delegates authority to his
assistants, most specifically to offensive coordinator Mark Richt
and defensive coordinator Mickey Andrews. Yet, Bowden is very much
aware of what is happening around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Bowden is successful because he is a winner,'' said
Andrews. ``He hasn't backed off from working. He's a great
motivator who knows when to push and when to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   Never has that been more the case than this season as the
Seminoles have dealt not only with maintaining a No. 1 ranking but
an unbeaten season, as well as a spate of off-the-field problems.
``There are times you have to compromise,'' said Andrews, who has
been on Bowden's staff for 16 seasons. ``There are times when the
players have to think they have gotten away with something, even if
they really haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden says with 100 players to oversee he can't control or know
everything. ``There are a lot of things the players know that I
know nothing about,'' he said. ``They think it's Halloween.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden hopes it's Christmas again Tuesday. He knows the world
won't come to an end if Tech wins. After all, this will be the
third time in four years the Seminoles will be playing for the
national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't go home and cut my throat or slit my wrists,'' he
said. ``We'll just try and get it again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're for real,'' said Virginia Tech's Frank Beamer, who
will be coaching in his first national title game. ``They have done
it over and over and that goes back to Bobby and his staff. Bobby
is for real. To do what they have done year after year is
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden says he is comfortable with the success he has achieved,
but concedes he is not entirely comfortable being cast in the role
of favorite. ``I've always been the underdog,'' he said with a
laugh. ``If I had been one of a litter of puppies, they would have
thrown me away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, of course, is years past that role and he knows it.
During the 1990s, the Seminoles were an incredible 108-13-1. But
Bowden still feels like an underdog, which is what keeps him going
and keeps him fresh and enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   And like he says, after you retire, there is only one big event
remaining in a man's life and he's not ready for that.
</P>
<P>
   Not even close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
