<HEADLINE>
INTERNET SURVIVES INITIAL ARRIVAL OF MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Power on, Internet fine, dogs healthy, and beer still cold.''
</P>
<P>
   After days of angst and uncertainty, that was about all there
was to the millennium madness on the Internet early Friday, at
least according to Perry Morrison, a management consultant in
Darwin, Australia. Exactly five minutes after the New Year arrived
down under in the Northern Territory (just after 8 a.m. EST),
Morrison posted that reassuring missive on Zone 2000, a grassroots
Web site set up to monitor Y2K-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that sentiment was echoed on Web sites, in chat rooms,
on bulletin boards, and in e-mail beamed across time zones as
Internet users went on line to gather news and get a glimpse of the
worldwide reverie. ``Everything is perfect,'' reported a Zone 2000
scribe in Beijing. ``Power is on. TV is on. Mobile is on.
Celebration is on.'' On the CNN message board, Vikki Ruth from
Canada noted, ``The only bug that has hit thus far is the flu
bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as reports from official government and amateur sources
alike allayed fears of pending disaster, Internet users flocked on
line in droves throughout the day, causing sluggish response times
and repeated error messages on the most popular Y2K watch sites. At
various times during the afternoon, the Net was almost as slow as
the day the Starr Report was released on line.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly impossible, for instance, to access the live
images at Earthcam.com, a site that was billing its event as ``The
Webcast of the Century.'' The site had placed about 100 Web cams
all over the globe, promising a bird's eye view of the millennium
as it moved west from New Zealand to New York. But several hours
after the calendar turned over in New Zealand, the Web cam in
Gisborne showed the clock tower stuck at 10:40.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting unbelievable traffic,'' Bruce Schartz,
Earthcam's vice president of marketing, said. The New Jersey-based
company had to borrow servers from other Web companies to boost its
network capability; by early evening, the Web cams were still
inaccessible, but the site was showing a live video stream from
Times Square, featuring miniature grainy images of the revelers in
the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Even if traffic was slow, for the most part, the Internet got a
green light Friday, both literally and figuratively. An
entrepreneur in Dortmund, Germany set up a site that automatically
checks the top 500 Web sites in the United States, New Zealand, and
Germany; some 99 percent of those sites were marked with a flashing
green light Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take more than 20 minutes to check all these sites if
you did it one at a time, but with a simple program you can do it
with light speed,'' said Marc Wasche, who launched the
www.inferno2000.com because he thought it was ``a cool idea.''
Along with other Net enthusiasts, he spent the day glued to his
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Wasche and other amateurs joined professionals and government
officials who planned to keep constant vigil on line. Folks at
Keynote Systems, a San Mateo, Calif., Internet performance
measuring company, tracked Web sites in each time zone. ``Overall,
the Internet appears to have cleared the hurdle in the first time
zones,'' Keynote spokesperson Mary Lindsay said Friday evening.
``The only anomoly is in countries with a large online community,
where performance degrades considerably after midnight. There is a
rush of traffic as people log on to make sure the Internet is still
operating.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those people was Matt Sullivan, a computer-aided
draftsman in Glen Massey, New Zealand, who planned to stay up
around the clock as the millennium progressed around the globe. He
surfed the Net constantly before and after midnight (which was at 5
a.m. our time). Like the dog-loving Internet enthusiast in
Australia, he fired off an urgent missive about the four-legged in
his rural village. ``No cows strayed, the electric fence units kept
working, and the rain water still flowed,'' he wrote, confirming
that all was well in Glen Massey on the first day of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the anxiety subsided on line, some Internet users
continued to point out that the real millennium doesn't begin until
Jan. 1, 2001, since there was no year zero. One user on the CNN
message board dismissed Friday's celebration as ``the
phoney-baloney balonium.'' Y2K reassurance notwithstanding, the
issue is sure to burn on line for yet another year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
