<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM ARRIVES _ AS A TV EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The global village shrank to the size of a television screen
Friday, as nonstop coverage ushered in a millennium that, as of
early evening, had mercifully failed to produce any newsworthy
disasters and instead linked the planet in a celebration of
humanity's common culture.
</P>
<P>
   From the dance that greeted the sunrise in the Kiribati Islands
to the fireworks display that lit up Shanghai's skyline to a
haunting choral rendition of ``Danny Boy'' in Derry, Northern
Ireland, the message of Friday's millennium vigil was inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   As comedian Barry Humphries, who plays ``Dame Edna'' in the hit
Broadway play, told ABC's Peter Jennings, ``You feel perhaps, peace
among men is a possiblity.''
</P>
<P>
   Three very different networks _ broadcast giant ABC, public
broadcasting's PBS, and cable news outlet CNN _ offered
wall-to-wall coverage of the opening hours of the millennium.
Despite the widespread fear of possible disasters ranging from the
technological (the Y2K bug) to the human (terrorism), the big news
stories Friday had nothing to do with the turn of the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The major news was the surprise resignation of President Boris
Yeltsin of Russia and an end to the hostage crisis aboard the
hijacked Indian Airlines plane. In an acknowledgment of the
incredible US economic boom at the turn of the millennium, the
networks also cut live to the 1 p.m. close of the New York Stock
Exchange on a day when the Dow again broke a record.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, ABC's Times Square headquarters looked to be at
the epicenter of breaking news when smoke began billowing from the
building, firetrucks gathered, and Jennings noted that ``something
is going on above us . . . but we don't believe it is serious.''
The scare turned out to be a routine matter.
</P>
<P>
   The fear that the Y2K computer bug would create immediate and
significant problems was all but put to rest early Friday. Shortly
after 11 a.m., ABC's Sam Donaldson declared that there were no
reported problems in crucial locales like Australia, Japan, and
Russia. Following a similarly reassuring CNN report _ indicating no
glitches at Russian nuclear plants _ anchor Jim Clancy wondered
aloud if a lot of viewers were sitting in their living rooms
saying, ``I told you so.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a palpable sense of relief from potential trouble
spots when the millennium dawned with fireworks and celebration in
Moscow's Red Square and with singing and the release of doves in
the West Bank town of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   For one passing moment, however, there was anxiety when a US
military briefer announced the detection of ``three theater missile
events'' at a 4:30 p.m. press conference. Jennings quickly called
in ABC national security correspondent John McWethy, who explained
that the missile launches were related to the ``situation in
Chechnya'' and represented nothing dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three networks devoting extraordinary resources to
Friday's event covered the story from different perspectives. PBS's
approach was more anthropological and documentary in tone, letting
the camera linger on events such as the ``Millennium Birth'' dance
performed in Uhuru, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its newsier approach, CNN devoted more attention
to the other events of the day, particularly the hostage release
and the changing of the guard in Moscow. Having broken the news of
Yeltsin's resignation in the early morning hours, the network then
aired segments of an exclusive interview with his successor,
Vladimir Putin, who reaffirmed his commitment to democratic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's coverage, glued together by Jennings, was the most
analytical and chatty, featuring interviews with everyone from
scientist Stephen Jay Gould to singer Billy Joel and showcasing the
network's cast of star correspondents like Cokie Roberts and
Barbara Walters. In an unusual and touching moment, the Rome-based
Roberts interviewed her mother, Lindy Boggs, the US ambassador to
the Vatican. ``Thank you, mom, happy New Year,'' she said. ``Happy
New Year, beautiful,'' Boggs responded.
</P>
<P>
   The real story, however, was captured by the sounds and pictures
of people from all over the map celebrating the same event in
eminently recognizable fashion. There was rap music and break
dancing from Castle Square in Poland, flashing lights and gyrating
dancers partying along the Nile River, and a beautifully
choreographed pageant in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Amid these images, good will seemed almost infectious. Quizzed
by Jennings for a new millennial prediction, Gould said he thought
some of mankind's most intractable problems could be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the basic goodness within us if we can only muster the
will,'' he noted. ``I remain a tragic optimist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
