<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MILLENNIUM-NATION-BOS     12-31 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-NATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION AWAITS LONG-PREPARED-FOR EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With equal parts anxiety and excitement, the nation awaited the
arrival of the epochal year 2000 amid festivals, fireworks, and
vast efforts to stave off feared computer-glitch disasters and
terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in charge of cornerstones of modern society _ power,
water, public safety, and telecommunications _ were confident years
of work to fix the potentially system-crippling Y2K computer bug
would pay off with a smooth changeover to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2,200-member Massachusetts State Police, ``Nobody's
being granted a day off tonight,'' said Sgt. Tim White. Troopers
with blue lights spinning kept watch for terrorists at the Boston
Harbor tunnels and Tobin Bridge as 40 patrol teams fanned out
across the state targeting the chronic New Year's spate of drunken
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But repeated reports of New Year's Day arriving uneventfully in
industrialized nations like Australia, New Zealand, and Japan and
later Europe bolstered officials' confidence that the United States
would also see few problems related to the date changeover. Nuclear
weapons arsenals and power plants in China and Russia remained
secure, and by 6 p.m. Eastern Time time 36 countries from Vietnam
to Egypt reported no critical incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initial reports are positive,'' said John Koskinen, the top
White House official overseeing year 2000 preparations. ``The
chances of some unknown or unmanageable catastrophe happening are
minimized significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a common sentiment of officials who have spent years
preparing, Skip Patterson, the top Bell Atlantic official in charge
of its $430 million preparations, said: ``Let's get it over with,
and let's get on with the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of 2000 had been anticipated with widespread concern
by public officials, both because of worries that older computer
systems would misread the date 01-01-00 as 1900 and shut down or go
haywire, and because of fears anti-American or anti-technology
terrorists might have wanted to mark the watershed date with a
crippling attack.
</P>
<P>
   In rural Oregon late Thursday night, an electric transmission
line that feeds power from the Pacific Northwest to California was
toppled by saboteurs. However, computers automatically rerouted
power around the downed line in less than a second, and FBI
Portland chief David Szady said there was ``no evidence or
intelligence that this was Y2K- or millennial-related.''
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom had held that impoverished and developing
countries like India, Indonesia, and Russia were most likely to be
plagued by Y2K problems. So reports last evening of an almost
entirely uneventful New Year's in those countries boosted US
officials' confidence 2000 would arrive smoothly here.
</P>
<P>
   At the stroke of 7 p.m. time _ midnight at the Greenwich
observatory near London _ fireworks dazzled crowds at a
``children's celebration'' on Boston Common, the first of several
displays planned across the region. From huge TV screens erected on
the park, Bostonians could also watch the fireworks displays at
Paris's Eiffel Tower, Berlin, and Vatican City.
</P>
<P>
   Seven o'clock was also a key hour for utilities, because many of
their computer systems work on Greenwich time. Initial reports
indicated the power grid that serves 12 million New Englanders
passed through what officials call ``the millennial boundary''
without incident.
</P>
<P>
   While many people already seemed turned off by the months of
hype about 2000 and planned to stay home, plenty of parties were
still scheduled throughout the region on a clear, starry night with
temperatures hovering at the freezing mark.
</P>
<P>
   Eastport, Maine, officials had planned a boat race ``back in
time'' from Campobello Island in New Brunswick, with captains
dressed as Santa Claus and Father Time at the helm. The idea was
that participants could celebrate New Year's twice: once at
midnight Atlantic time in Canada, and a second time at midnight
Eastern Standard Time in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the Mashantucket Pequots expected up to 70,000
people to flock to their Foxwoods casino, the continent's largest,
to sip champagne, gamble at the 5,500 slot machines and gaming
tables, and take in performances by pop crooner Barry Manilow and
other stars.
</P>
<P>
   Woonsocket, R.I., staged a ``Jour de L'An'' French-Canadian New
Year's celebration with dancing, singing, and family gatherings.
And Bethel, Maine, residents hoped for snowfall to help their plans
to build 2,000 snowmen.
</P>
<P>
   But fed up with hype about the ``new millennium'' _ which
purists insist will not arrive until 2001, the first year of the
21st century _ many New Englanders were boycotting public
festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're staying home where it's nice and safe,'' said Heather
Libby of South Portland, Maine. ``I've decided I don't want to be
around crowds. I'm not worried about Y2K, but I am worried about
terrorists and crazy people.''
</P>
<P>
   As of late last evening, however, officials in charge of key
sectors felt well prepared and optimistic. A rundown of Y2K
preparedness efforts in crucial fields:
</P>
<P>
   - Utilities: Because of the cascading chaos they could inflict,
Y2K-triggered power failures had been considered the single biggest
millennium bug risk, but New England electric grid officials were
confident utilities would come through without trouble, grid
spokesman Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   - Finance: As Wall Street closed early for the holiday and
global markets from Singapore to Moscow passed smoothly into the
new millennium, local financial services companies reported few, if
any, problems by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bangladesh supposedly cancelled its foreign exchange trading
for Monday, but I think we'll survive that,'' quipped one executive
at a Boston financial firm.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, State Street Corp., the giant money manager
and back-office financial transactions processor, said things had
gone off without a hitch. ``There have not been any glitches, and
at this point, we have experienced a smooth transition in all
markets globally,'' said Greg Ahern, the company's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments' Anne Crowley said calls from investors to
company representatives ``are even a little less than is typical
for this time of the year. Everything has worked fine.''
</P>
<P>
   And banks, which had feared a possible run on cash machines and
branches, found their efforts to boost cash supplies largely
unnecessary. ``We're seeing a very surprising and pleasing customer
reaction to Y2K,'' said Jim Schepker of FleetBoston Financial, New
England's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   While even President Clinton had recommended people take out
some extra cash to cover household needs, Schepker said average ATM
withdrawals Friday were up by only ``several percentage points''
compared with a typical day.
</P>
<P>
   Stock brokerages and other securities firms that collectively
spent $5 billion to fix their computers for the new century also
reported a smooth transition. ``So far, the processing of these
first trades to cross over into 2000 has been proceeding
normally,'' said Donald Kittell of the Securities Industry
Association, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   (Proving the point, at the stroke of midnight in Auckland, New
Zealand, a visiting Australian woman named Miriam Betcher ignored
the fireworks and took her place at a portable ATM in the Maritime
Village. As bells pealed, cannons fired, and boat horns roared
across the waterfront, Betcher inserted her card and withdrew a
fistful of bills she waved to a Globe correspondent.)
</P>
<P>
   - The Internet: Friday night is never an especially busy time on
the Net _ and the waning hours of 1999 were no different. ``So far,
we're seeing nothing but business as usual,'' said Craig Bailey,
director of customer care for GTE Internetworking of Burlington,
Mass., which serves a half-million residential users and 5,000
corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT) at Carnegie Mellon
University in Pittsburgh, monitoring Y2K-related software viruses
or attacks on computer systems, said by late Friday things were
``fairly normal and quiet,'' center manager Kathy Fithen said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the worldwide Y2K picture looked overwhelmingly
positive as of last evening, the White House's Koskinen warned that
problems may still develop and become noticeable as the work week
begins Monday. ``We should all remember we have many miles to go
before we sleep,'' he said. ``Not all problems will be apparent
immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3661 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-BOS &LR;      12-31 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN TAKES REINS AS YELTSIN BOWS TO `NEW POLITICIANS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia entered the new century with a new leader, as
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin took over as acting president after
Boris N. Yeltsin resigned suddenly with a plea for Russians to
forgive him for the shortcomings of his eight years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it was time for ``new politicians'' to run Russia,
Yeltsin said he was stepping down immediately to clear the way for
his handpicked successor. Putin, a tough-talking former KGB spy who
has rapidly become the country's most popular leader in four months
as premier, quickly assumed control of the government and called
for a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin showed Putin, 47, into his Kremlin office, where the
acting president took possesion of the suitcase that contains the
controls to launch Russia's nuclear arsenal. While Russia's
Orthodox Patriarch Alexy II looked on, Yeltsin, 68, also handed
Putin his presidential pen and medals symbolizing his presidential
status.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic resignation made Yeltsin, the first democratically
elected leader in Russian history, also the only Kremlin chief to
voluntarily part with power in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's move was most likely motivated as much by his
political and personal concerns as by his desire to enshrine his
place in history. His resignation automatically moved up elections
that had been planned for next summer to March 26, which is perfect
timing for Putin, who has declared himself a candidate. The
premier's approval rating has soared to 70 percent, largely as a
result of his leadership of Russia's military campaign against
separatists in Chechnya. Putin's supporters scored a surprise
triumph in parliamentary elections just two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   One of Putin's first decrees offered Yeltsin immunity from
prosecution and a lifetime pension. It also provided a government
country home and bodyguards and medical care for the former
president and his family. Yeltsin and his entourage, known here as
``The Family,'' have been buffeted by widespread allegations of
corruption in recent months, and have reportedly been looking for
assurances for their safety after he steps down. In a further sign
of loyalty to the outgoing president's team, Putin reappointed
Yeltsin's chief of administration, Alexander Voloshin, seen here as
a key member of the ``Family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To cling to power for another six months when the country has
a strong person worthy of becoming president _ why should I stand
in his way?,'' said Yeltsin, looking pale and speaking slowly and
with apparent difficulty, in an address from his Kremlin office. He
sat in front of a glittering New Year's tree, the Russian tricolor,
and the golden state symbol, a doubleheaded Russian eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later, Acting President Putin, speaking to the
nation from the same Kremlin office in a televised address just
before midnight, said Russia would continue to observe basic
freedoms gained under Yeltsin. Sounding his favorite theme _ law
and order _ Putin also vowed to guide the country to elections in
an orderly manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for one minute will there be a power vacuum,'' Putin said.
``The state has stood, and will stand, on guard for the safety of
each citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, whose popularity early in his presidency has faded to
nil during the hardships and inequities of his rule, said he deeply
regretted not meeting people's expectations after leading Russia
away from Soviet-style Communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to beg forgiveness for your dreams that never came
true. And also I would like to beg forgiveness for not having
justified your hopes,'' Yeltsin said. ``I beg your forgiveness for
having failed to jump in one leap from the gray, stagnant,
totalitarian past to the light, rich, and civilized future.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton paid tribute to Yeltsin for
dismantling the communist system and putting a democratic structure
in place.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin's sudden rise to power caused quiet concern both in
the West and Russia, and not only because of Putin's KGB past and
his flinty rebuttal of Western criticism of Russia's heavy-handed
offensive against rebels in the breakaway republic of Chechnya. The
new acting president likes to talk about reviving Russia as a great
power, and he warns of ``outside enemies'' and the need for a
strong state. He also rejects transformation to a liberal,
European-style democracy any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western and Russian critics see in all that the seeds for a
new authoritarian regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel shock, fear and sorrow,'' said Yevgeniya Albats, a
prominent Russian journalist. ``We have once again shown that we
are an unpredictable country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Putin's quiet confidence and no-nonsense matter appeals to
many Russians, who see him as a leader who can bring order after
the economic decline, political chaos, and social inequities that
marked the later Yeltsin years.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian stock market jumped to a 15-month high on the news,
with dealers saying hopes of strong new leadership would boost the
economy, which is already enjoying a revival thanks to high world
prices for oil and precious metals, Russia's main exports. Putin
has never laid out his plans for the economy and usually speaks of
the need for the state to take a stronger regulatory role over
Russia's markets.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to reassure doubters, Putin promised no changes in
government policies, including foreign relations. But he said
efforts to modernize and strengthen Russia's military would
continue and the state would ensure stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freedom of speech, the freedom of worship, the freedom of
the press, the freedom of property rights _ these fundamentals of
civilized society _ will be reliably protected by the state,''
Putin said in his a New Year's address.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Yeltsin's resignation, while sudden, was no surprise
to many Russians, who have known about his many ailments for years
and who could see from his increasingly rare appearances that his
health was fading.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians had doubted the leader who half-jokingly called
himself Czar Boris would ever step down. Unpredictable to the end,
Yeltsin confounded those expectations by stepping down early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times I have heard it said, Yeltsin will try to hold onto
power by any means, he won't hand it over to anyone,'' Yeltsin
said. ``That is all lies.''
</P>
<P>
   The move left Putin's main rivals for the presidency _ Communist
leader Gennady Zyuganov, Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov, and former
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov _ with the difficult task of
catching up to Putin in only three months.
</P>
<P>
   The task is made more difficult by Putin's positions as prime
minister, a job he will keep, and acting president. State
television was instrumental in the strong showing by three parties
he backed in last month's elections to the lower house of
parliament, the State Duma, and now the Kremlin-controlled media is
expected go to work for Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, meanwhile, stood for a while with aides at a Kremlin
doorway, then gingerly stepped out into the snow and rode off in
his limousine to his suburban residence, out of politics forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``In saying farewell, I wish to say to each of you the
following,'' Yeltsin said in his last address as president. ``Be
happy. You deserve happiness. You deserve happiness and peace.
Happy new year, happy new century, my dear people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
