<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3663 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-31 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BOSTON E-PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last summer I was changing planes at Singapore's swank new
airport, which has lounges spread all over, at which transit
passengers can watch satellite TV. As I walked through the airport,
I bought a snack and sat down in one of these lounges.
</P>
<P>
   There I found two elderly Indian women, in traditional sari
robes, watching American professional wrestling. These two petite
Indian ladies were sitting transfixed, gazing at huge wrestlers in
Tarzan suits body-slamming one another. All I could think was:
``What in the world are they making of this?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've thought back on that scene often, because it captured an
essential truth about the world we are about to enter _ a world
increasingly without walls in which countries, cultures and
economies are going to meet, and wrestle with, each other so much
more directly _ for better and for worse. For months Cisco Systems,
makers of the Internet, have been running an ad showing young
people from all corners of the earth asking: ``Are you ready?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm afraid we're not. There's an old adage in the computer
business that the hardware always runs ahead of the software. That
is, the computer and chip makers are always building faster
machines that the software writers have to catch up with. It's true
of people, too.
</P>
<P>
   As we enter the new millennium the agents of change in our lives
_ the technologies and networks that are tearing down walls,
weaving us together and forcing us all to speed up, downsize,
download, integrate and streamline _ are running ahead of the human
capacity to adjust and absorb. Our computers and robots may be Y2K
ready, but our bodies and our politics are not.
</P>
<P>
   Well then, some people say, let's put the walls back up, put
some sand in the gears and slow down the world _ not so I can get
off, but so I can stay on! Not so easy. Every time you try to
rebuild a wall, some new technology comes along and erases it. We
have no choice but to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   You'd never know that, though, listening to the presidential
candidates. We have candidates out in Iowa debating ethanol while
the Internet is transforming the world, and it doesn't even get a
mention. That's because, for the moment, the Internet is primarily
ripping apart, and radically restructuring, business and shopping.
But in the next decade its creative destruction will hit education
and government with full force.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the candidates are talking about this at all,''
remarked one Internet exec, ``but then I guess if any of them
really understood the magnitude of the changes that are coming in
the next eight years they'd never run for office.``
</P>
<P>
   Steve Case, the head of America Online, put it to me best: ``I
think we need to reconvene the Founding Fathers.'' I agree, because
the next decade is going to be as revolutionary and creative a
period in American politics as was the period between the
Declaration of Independence in 1776 and the Constitutional
Convention in 1787.
</P>
<P>
   The fuse will be e-commerce and a new Boston Tea Party, led by
governors and mayors throwing computers overboard. Because as they
discover that their tax base is being lost to untaxed Internet
commerce, we will have to move to a national sales tax. This will
require a restructuring of relations between cities, states and the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Issues such as freedom of speech and libel are going to have to
be rethought as the Internet makes everyone a potential publisher
in cyberspace _ but with no censor or editor in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy protection is going to have to be rethought in a world
where for $39 Web sites will search out anyone's assets and home
address for you. And our safety nets are going to have to be
rethought in a world in which access to the Internet is going to be
viewed as a human right, essential for basic survival _ especially
as governments move more services to the Web. (Are you going to
wait in line for hours at city hall to get a license renewed when
you can now buy your whole car with one click on the Web?)
</P>
<P>
   Getting through this transition is going to require the best of
America, and for America to be at its best and help others. The
best of America was that unique blend of wisdom and fresh, youthful
thinking of the Founding Fathers. To re-engineer our society and
country we're going to have to revive that youthful, radically
creative spirit. This may be the millennium, but it's no time for
us to get old.
</P>
<P>
   I was once asked what I wished Israel on its 50th birthday, and
I said I hoped it would always remain true to the last lines of Bob
Dylan's ballad ``Forever Young.'' I wish that even more for America
today:
</P>
<P>
   ``May your hands always be busy / May your feet always be swift
/ May you have a strong foundation when the winds of changes shift
/ May your heart always be joyful / May your song always be sung /
May you stay forever young.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-RICHARDSON-B     12-31 1940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-RICHARDSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLIOT RICHARDSON, VERSATILE MAN, IS DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Elliot L. Richardson, the Boston Brahmin who as US
attorney general in 1973 refused to fire Watergate special
prosecutor Archibald Cox, thus making himself a national symbol of
political integrity, died in Massachusetts General Hospital Friday
of a brain hemorrhage. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson's action as attorney general triggered the
``Saturday Night Massacre,'' which helped lead to Richard Nixon's
resignation the following year.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Friday that Mr. Richardson ``put the
nation's interests first even when the personal cost was very high.
He was an unparalleled public servant.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci and
Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift called Mr. Richardson a ``true
hero'' who ``served the Commonwealth and his country with courage,
dignity, and uncompromising valor.''
</P>
<P>
   The patrician as pluperfect public servant, Mr. Richardson
amassed an extraordinary resume that earned him the nickname ``The
Man for All Positions.'' He liked to joke that his versatility
meant he ``never held a job for more than two years.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being elected Massachusetts lieutenant governor
and attorney general during the 1960s, he served as assistant US
secretary of health, education and welfare and US attorney for
Massachusetts in the Eisenhower administration; undersecretary of
state, secretary of health, education and welfare, secretary of
defense, and attorney general in the Nixon administration;
ambassador to the Court of St. James' and secretary of commerce in
the Ford administration; and ambassador at large in the Carter
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approach any job in essentially the same way,'' Mr.
Richardson once said. ``I don't consider that the subject matter
makes any particular difference. If I don't know it, I learn it. I
try to find out what it is necessary to do, and then do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the aristocratic background that helped produce such
self-assurance worked against him when he ran for the GOP
nomination for US senator from Massachusetts in 1984. A
self-described ``radical moderate'' who liked to joke about the
burden of bearing three last names, Elliot Lee Richardson found
little support in a party that had come to be dominated by
conservative and ethnic voters. His opponent, Raymond V. Shamie,
defeated him by nearly 25 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   It was a startling reversal for a man who had been regarded as a
possible vice presidential or even presidential nominee in 1976.
What had earned Mr. Richardson such consideration was his steadfast
performance in the face of mounting White House pressure during the
five months he served as attorney general, culminating in his
resignation on Oct. 20, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   It was a measure of Mr. Richardson's indispensability to the
Nixon administration that he was presiding over the Justice
Department at that time. As undersecretary of state, he had played
a crucial role as intermediary in the battles between Secretary of
State William Rogers and National Security Adviser Henry Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1970, Mr. Richardson had taken over at HEW, a department
in considerable disarray and one responsible for such controversial
issues of the day as welfare reform and school desegregation. Mr.
Richardson's surehandedness there inspired Nixon to make him
secretary of defense 2 1/2 years later. He'd been at the Pentagon
barely four months when growing suspicions about White House
involvement in the Watergate scandal and the resignation of
Attorney General Richard Kleindienst forced Nixon to turn to Mr.
Richardson, with his double-barreled image as a ``Mr. Clean and Mr.
Fix-It,'' to head the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson's first decision was to appoint a special
prosecutor. He chose Harvard Law School Professor Archibald Cox and
guaranteed the Senate Judiciary Committee that Cox would have
complete independence.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Mr. Richardson began to meet with opposition
from the Oval Office. In the 10 weeks preceding his resignation,
Nixon met with him only once, and Mr. Richardson quipped that he
might soon be writing a book called ``Situation Wanted.'' He
likened his battles with the White House to his experience of
landing on Utah Beach on D-Day. ``All I could do was put down one
foot after the other, hoping each time that (no mine) would go
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating matters was the ongoing investigation of
Vice President Spiro Agnew on charges of tax fraud and bribery. Mr.
Richardson negotiated a settlement whereby Agnew would plead no
contest to a tax-evasion charge and resign from office. ``That guy
was so straight that he could not even think corrupt,'' an
investigator who worked on the case later said of Mr. Richardson's
handling of the episode.
</P>
<P>
   It became increasingly clear that Nixon wanted Mr. Richardson to
fire Cox. Matters came to a head when the White House refused to
surrender a group of subpoenaed tape recordings to US District
Judge John J. Sirica, offering instead a set of edited transcripts
to be authenticated by US Sen. John Stennis (D-Miss.). Cox rejected
the proposal. In what Mr. Richardson later described as a
``low-keyed but tense'' meeting, Nixon ordered him to fire Cox,
saying that at a time of international crisis _ superpower
negotiations over ending the Yom Kippur War were then underway _ it
would make him appear weak to the Soviet leadership if Cox could
flout presidential authority.
</P>
<P>
   When Mr. Richardson demurred, an angry Nixon said, ``I'm sorry
that you insist on putting your personal commitments ahead of the
public interest.'' ``Mr. President,'' the attorney general replied,
``I can only say that I believe my resignation (itals)is(unitals)
in the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson's deputy, William Ruckelshaus, also refused to
dismiss Cox and was fired. Solicitor General Robert Bork carried
out the order, setting off what White House chief of staff
Alexander M. Haig termed ``a firestorm'' of protest. Telegrams and
letters poured into Washington. Nixon was forced to appoint another
special prosecutor, Leon Jaworski, and calls for the president's
impeachment mounted.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson simultaneously found himself out of work and a
political folk hero. ``I sometimes feel like a walking
anticlimax,'' he ruefully confessed in 1974. ``I can hardly reenact
my resignation.'' He worked on a book, ``The Creative Balance''
(1976), delivered numerous speaking engagements, and, after Nixon's
resignation, served as Gerald Ford's ambassador in London for a
year before taking over the Commerce department.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his sterling reputation, Mr. Richardson faced severe
handicaps in any pursuit of higher office. For one, he belonged to
the dwindling band of Republican liberals. For another, his
penchant for reflection often made him seem verbose. ``Let me
finish this paragraph,'' he once told a reporter who had
interrupted him, not a word often heard in an age of sound bites.
Nor did he project a winning manner. Stiffness is a concomitant of
rectitude, and Mr. Richardson _ a warm, witty man in private _ came
across as stuffy and unbending in public.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson did not lack political genes. An uncle, Henry Lee
Shattuck, was a prominent Republican who served on the Boston City
Council and in the Legislature. But the family calling was
medicine. Mr. Richardson's great-grandfather, both grandfathers, a
grandmother, three uncles, his father, and both his brothers were
physicians. Mr. Richardson said of his failure to go to medical
school, ``Medicine is like reading a book where you know what's
going to happen. I wanted a life with more surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of Edward P. Richardson and Clara (Shattuck) Richardson,
he was born in Boston on July 20, 1920. Mr. Richardson grew up in
Brookline and graduated from Milton Academy. A philosophy major at
Harvard, he later described his ``main college activity'' as
cartooning for the undergraduate humor magazine, the Lampoon, and
he remained an inveterate doodler. Other hobbies included bird
watching and painting water colors. A devoted outdoorsman and
athlete, Mr. Richardson was Harvard middleweight boxing champion
and enjoyed fishing, mountain climbing, and tennis.
</P>
<P>
   As a combat litter bearer, Mr. Richardson won a Bronze Star and
two Purple Hearts during World War II. He rose to the rank of
lieutenant and was in the first US Army unit to enter Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson graduated from Harvard Law School in 1947, having
been president and editor of the law review. He clerked for US
Appeals Court Judge Learned Hand and US Supreme Court Justice Felix
Frankfurter. The latter was so impressed with him that in 1953 he
proposed the 33-year-old Mr. Richardson for the presidency of
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Two years earlier, Mr. Richardson met his future wife, Anne F.
(Hazard) Richardson, at a Bachelors Ball in Boston. She was a
Radcliffe senior, 10 years his junior. ``I looked around for the
most attractive girl I could spot so that I could cut in on her,''
he later recalled. ``Which I did.''
</P>
<P>
   She died in July.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson spent four years at the Boston law firm of Ropes
&AMP; Gray, joined the Washington staff of US Sen. Leverett
Salstonstall (R-Mass.) for two years, returned to Ropes &AMP; Gray,
then served as acting counsel to Governor Christian A. Herter.
Named assistant secretary for legislation at HEW in 1957, he played
a major role in drafting the National Defense Education Act. He
returned to Boston two years later, as US attorney. His most
important case was the successful tax-evasion prosecution of
Bernard Goldfine, a wealthy manufacturer whose gifts to White House
chief of staff Sherman Adams led to Adams's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Mr. Richardson ran for the Republican nomination for
attorney general, losing to future US Sen. Edward W. Brooke. Two
years later, he was elected lieutenant governor. He played an
activist role in what had been a largely ceremonial office,
coordinating social welfare programs for the administration and
urging Gov. John A. Volpe to sponsor the state's Racial Imbalance
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson was elected attorney general in 1966. Shortly
before Election Day, he charged his opponent, Francis X. Bellotti,
with improperly taking a retainer from an insurance company while
Bellotti was lieutenant governor. The accusation was widely
denounced as reckless and unfair, and Mr. Richardson later admitted
he was unwise to have made the charge.
</P>
<P>
   What Mr. Richardson called his ``longest and most demanding tour
of duty in any government job'' was the nearly four years he spent
as head of the US delegation to the United Nations Conference on
the Law of the Sea in the late '70s. He was the primary draftsman
of the global treaty the conference produced.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 Mr. Richardson joined the Washington office of the New
York law firm Milbank, Tweed Hadley, &AMP; McCloy as a senior partner.
He did not abandon public life, however, serving, for example, as a
monitor in UN-supervised elections in Namibia in 1988 and, a year
later, as the UN Secretary-General's personal representative at the
Nicaraguan national elections.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom,
the nation's highest civilian honor, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two sons, Henry of Washington, D.C., and Michael of
Montclair, N.J.; a daughter, Nancy Carlson of Burlington, Vt.; a
brother, George of Nahant; and seven grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is being planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
