<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3665 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MILLENNIUM-WORLD-BOS &LR;      12-31 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLITCH-FREE MILLENNIUM ARRIVES THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Whatever 2000 becomes, initial indications suggest it
is not the Year of the Bug.
</P>
<P>
   Fears about the computer malfunction known as the Millennium
Bug, not to mention terrorist attacks, turned out to be largely
exaggerated. While not glitch-free, the new year, new century, and
new millennium began with far less chaos across the globe than had
been expected.
</P>
<P>
   There were problems reported in some telecommunication systems,
particularly cellular phone networks, but they were attributed not
to the Millennium Bug but to heavy volume, a phenomenon known as
the ``Mother's Day effect,'' as millions dialed to wish a happy new
year to friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   As midnight passed in the first industrialized nations of New
Zealand, Australia, and Japan, there were no reports of major
disruptions in gas, water and electricity distribution systems. One
power outage in New Zealand was attributed to bad weather. There
were minor glitches in devices monitoring Japanese nuclear power
plants and weather and seismological conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were there reports of major infrastructure problems in the
less developed nations, from China, through India, and across the
vast African continent. Italy, considered western Europe's least
prepared country, reported no major glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Mother nature and human error had more of an impact than the
dreaded Millennium Bug. In France, some 2 million people saw the
new century in without electricity, victims of last week's storms.
In London, the Millennium Wheel known as the London Eye, the
world's newest and biggest Ferris wheel, began to turn but could
not take passengers because it failed a safety test.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively smooth start to the new year in the Asia-Pacific
region led officials in Paris, London, Washington and other major
western capitals to predict that the Y2K transition would come off
smoother than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial reports are positive,'' said John Koskinen, the
chairman of the President's Council on Y2K Conversion in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Koskinen and other experts warned that the gradual
deterioration of some computer systems could lead to
slowly-developing degradation of information systems in some of the
nations that have made the Y2K transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should all remember we have many miles to go before we
sleep,'' he said. ``Not all problems will be apparent
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen was particularly encouraged by reports from Japan,
which while heavily reliant on information technology had been
tardy in launching a Y2K compliance program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has always been a bellwether,'' said Koskinen.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, the bombshell was political, not technological, as
Russians watched their longtime president Boris Yeltsin resign and
interim president Vladmir Putin gave the traditional New Year's
television address. In Eastern Russia, the Bilibino nuclear power
plant made the transition without any difficulty and the industrial
port city of Vladivostok was operating normally.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, China, and Indonesia were among the countries that US
officials thought most at risk. Experts had suggested that Belize,
Egypt, Oman, Qatar, Madagascar, Tajikistan, and Ukraine were the
countries least prepared and most at risk for Millenium Bug
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty minutes into the new millennium, Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi went on live television to proclaim that Japan had not
fallen victim to any major Y2K disasters. He may have spoken too
soon, however. Hours later, reports emerged that minor problems had
affected two nuclear plants. The radiation monitoring system
stopped functioning at a nuclear power plant in Ishikawa prefecture
in western Japan. At another nuclear plant in northern Japan, a
radiation monitor stopped transmitting data for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A few other glitches in the country's meteorological and
seismological monitoring capabilities were also detected. The
national meteorological agency's internal clock changed from the
year 1999 to 100.
</P>
<P>
   At Gokokuji temple and other places of worship in central Tokyo
_ the traditional places in Japan to ring in the new year _ many
people did not come until well after midnight. Security officials
reasoned that many Japanese waited to venture out until after the
New Year began, to make sure that no Y2K problems had occurred.
Those who did come out complained about fear mongerers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media hyped Y2K too much,'' said Shiro Yamada, 57, a
construction company worker. ``I didn't see any reason to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 million people crammed into central London, many of them
lining up at ATMs to withdraw money, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect any major problems, but I don't want to risk
having no money, either,'' said John Forry, a 32-year-old computer
technician who planned to spend the night on Tower Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite assurances from government officials throughout Latin
America that most main services were Y2K compliant, sporadic
reports of problems and concerns over uncertainty surfaced
throughout the region. Officials in Mexico City were unable to
renew drivers licenses for thousands of motorists this week because
of computer problems blamed on Y2K conversion software.
Nevertheless, officials throughout Latin America, a region less
dependent on computer technology than the United States, Europe or
Asia, said utilities, banks and emergency agencies were ready for
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the world, and particularly in the Middle East and
Europe, officials had been worried about terrorists seeking to
exploit the millennium with a high-profile atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   But even the writer Salman Rushdie, who last year was told the
fatwah, or death sentence imposed by Islamic militants, against him
had been lifted, felt comfortable enough to attend the London
opening of the Millennium Dome, the $1.3 billion exhibition center
that is the focal point of Britain's celebrations. Rushdie said he
was unconcerned by warnings about possible terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an astonishing building,'' Rushdie said after viewing the
Dome, whose 20-acre roof is the biggest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, more than 2 million firefighters, police officers,
civil servants and members of the defense forces were on alert. No
major disturbances were reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Friday was a unique confluence of the calendars of
the Muslim, Jewish, and Christian calendars. It was the last Friday
prayer of the Muslim holy month of Ramadan, the ushering in of
Shabbat for Jews at sunset, and the marking of the 2,000th year of
the Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn Brown, 65, of Manhattan's West Side, was strolling
through the streets of the Old City packed with some 400,000 Muslim
believers exiting their noon prayer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is wonderful to see all of these faiths together,
and to be here for the new millennium,'' she said, shouldering an
old Nikon camera and a packback.
</P>
<P>
   The US State Department's travel warnings seemed to have
deterred many American tourists from coming, but they meant nothing
to Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, come on, I'm from New York,'' she said. ``I wouldn't
have missed this for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But when night fell in Jerusalem, the streets emptied.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Chief Rabbinate had decreed that there should be no
public celebrations, no fireworks, or parties that would violate
the Jewish sabbath. The most visible presence on the streets were
the Israeli police and soldiers clad in riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the 12,000 police and military who fanned out
across the country was in Jerusalem's Old City, where calm
prevailed. Islam's holy site, the Dome of the Rock, sits literally
atop Judaism's most sacred site, the Western Wall of the Temple
Mount. The Holy Sepulchre, where Jesus was crucified and buried,
lies within a few hundred yards.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity of all the sites has created concerns over a
profound security risk in Israel, where officials feared an attack
on the Dome of the Rock by extremist Christians or Jews who believe
the Muslim shrine must be destroyed in order for the Jewish Temple
to be rebuilt, and the messiah to return.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem, birthplace of Jesus, Palestinian security forces
were also out in full force. Dressed in camouflage fatigues, they
ringed Manger Square.
</P>
<P>
   In London, more than 6,000 police were on the streets.
Antiterrorist police officers had spent the last few days scouring
the capital for bombs, fearing that, among others, dissidents from
Northern Ireland would seek to undermine the recent progress in the
peace process there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared,'' said Metropolitan Police assistant chief
constable Ian Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, it appeared, was the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(This story was reported by Globe staff writers Kevin Cullen in
London, Charles M. Sennott in Jerusalem, Indira Lakshmanan in Hong
Kong, John Farrell in Washington, Richard Chacon in Mexico Citym
and Globe correspondents Nicole Veash in Brazil, Kurt Shillinger in
Johannesburg, Sharon Moshavi in Tokyo, Marion Lloyd in New Delhim
and Joyce Hor-Chung Lau in Hong Kong.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
