<HEADER>
A3676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-COTTON-SUSPENSION     12-31 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-SUSPENSIONS01-COX1s </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longhorns press on without their suspended stars
 &HT;    (Eds: Adds statements from coach)
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton, Kirk Bohls and Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The four suspended University of Texas football players
left Dallas on Friday morning, while their coach refused to discuss
if or when the three underclassmen will be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mack Brown said Friday he will not talk about the duration
of the suspensions of junior wide receiver Kwame Cavil, junior
defensive end J.J. Kelly and redshirt freshman linebacker Jamal
Joyner until after the Longhorns complete their season today
against Arkansas in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Senior defensive end Aaron Humphrey also was suspended, and his
career at Texas is finished.
</P>
<P>
   The four were suspended late Thursday for violating team rules,
Brown said. The players were drug-tested earlier this week by the
NCAA, and if any of them flunked the test, they would be subject to
a year's suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Brown nor Athletic Director DeLoss Dodds would discuss
specifics of the suspensions, saying the Buckley amendment
precluded them from doing so. The federal law prevents school
officials from discussing a student's academic record.
</P>
<P>
   Jafus Cavil, father of Kwame Cavil, said Friday that no decision
has been made concerning his son's future at UT. The younger Cavil,
long before the suspensions surfaced, had been contemplating giving
up his final year of eligibility to apply for the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Jafus Cavil said he has yet to be told how long his son's
suspension will be.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if his son had flunked a drug test, Jafus Cavil said,
``I've been told not to answer that by my attorneys, so I'll have
no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Humphrey, father of Aaron Humphrey, also declined
comment, saying, ``We'll let his four years there speak for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls placed to Kelly's home were not returned, and Joyner could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns went through a brief practice Friday afternoon at
the Cotton Bowl. Brown and his players then met on the field for
about 30 minutes. Former Longhorns great James Street, the
quarterback who led Texas to a 15-14 win to clinch the national
championship against Arkansas in 1969, spoke to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little family setback (Thursday),'' Brown said after
Friday's practice. ``We've got great kids, and when you have great
kids, when something happens, you pull together. You'll see a great
effort (today) from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're scrambling a little bit. I told the coaches that it's no
different than an injury in the first quarter. We have to take what
we have and plug it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Late suspensions before a bowl game are not unprecedented. Coach
Lou Holtz, who coached Arkansas when the Razorbacks played in the
1978 Orange Bowl, suspended three players on the eve of the game,
including star running back Ben Cowins and leading wide receiver
Danny Bobo. Arkansas beat Oklahoma 31-6, and Cowins' replacement,
Roland Sales, set an Orange Bowl record with 205 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas Coach Houston Nutt was a freshman backup quarterback on
that Razorbacks team. Nutt, coincidentally, announced that starting
tailback Cedric Cobbs missed a team meeting and will not start as
planned today.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience just from being in the Orange Bowl is that (the
Texas suspensions) will be a rally cry,'' Nutt said. ``That'll be a
good wakeup. When Coach Holtz kicked off three of our best players,
we got a little closer. We played a little harder. That's what I
told our team (Friday).
</P>
<P>
   ``They have depth, they have players. It's just names we're not
familiar with. We'll see as the game goes on, but personally I
don't think it will matter much.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Texas four years ago was rocked by scandal the day
before the Longhorns took on Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl, when
it was discovered that defensive back Ron McKelvey was actually a
30-year-old named Ron Weaver who had played six years of college
football.
</P>
<P>
   Cavil and Humphrey, both All-Big 12 Conference selections, were
two prime reasons for the Longhorns' success this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cavil's 100 catches for 1,188 yards broke the conference record
for catches and yards in a season. Humphrey's 10 sacks also led the
conference. He was selected as the Longhorns' most valuable player
in a vote by his teammates last month and also was named team
captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 16 years as a head coach,'' Mack Brown said, ``I have never
suspended a player. I've been very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas offensive coordinator Greg Davis tried to put the best
face on the scenario but said: ``Look at the numbers. Obviously
it's going to hurt us, but our biggest concern is for the kids. I
really don't know for sure, but I feel like we'll play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
