A3677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-SUGAR-MOORE01-COX     12-31 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-MOORE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hokies' Moore too explosive to be ignored
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ You can't really blame Virginia Tech sackmaster
Corey Moore for going off on reporters at the opening bell of
Friday's Sugar Bowl media day interview session.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, how much restraint is a man supposed to show when the
first thing he's asked is so vile, so incendiary ... well, let's
just say it took a great deal of discussion on the part of my
bosses before the decision was made to run the provocative question
in full.
</P>
<P>
   Here it comes, but be warned, this is the raw and unedited
version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, Corey. How are you enjoying New Orleans so far
and how do you plan to celebrate the new year?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, as you might expect, the Big East defensive player of the
year wasn't about to allow a bunch of pantywaist reporters to
challenge his manhood in such an unspeakable manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrate for what?'' Moore said. ``I don't give a damn about
the new year and I don't give a crap about the millennium. You guys
aren't gonna win for us. Who cares? I don't care about the city
right now. I don't care about being here. I don't care about you
all and I don't particularly care to have those cameras in my face.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to write about something, write about how I dissed
you guys. Now get the hell out of my face.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the defensive end with the offensive mouth left the
specially marked podium where he was assigned to spend 90 minutes
of interview time and stormed off across the Superdome carpet to
tell various other groups of national reporters, most of whom had
never even met Moore before Friday, that he hates them and their
``little stories,'' too. Oh, and he also hates the BCS formula that
``almost screwed'' Virginia Tech out of its shot at No.1 Florida
State in the national title game Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways for a reporter to interpret a performance
like that. One may seriously ponder whether Moore has a reason to
be angry at the media, who merely voted him the Bronko Nagurski
Trophy winner (college football's defensive player of the year) and
the Lombardi Award winner (the nation's top lineman) but stopped
well short of electing him president or pope. Or one may go to the
Virginia Tech media guide for clues to Moore's motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, it says under personal interests that Moore likes
watching pro basketball, until recently the domain of dizzy Dennis
Rodman, and PlayStation, the video conduit to an entire universe of
indiscriminate explosions, and pro wrestling, where the actors are
athletes and each angry script is spattered with spittle.
</P>
<P>
   What we've got here is a football player too explosive to be
ignored, the most dominating Hokies defensive end since Bruce
Smith, and yet he revels still in the theatrical role of snarling
underdog. It is a misguided leadership ploy calculated by an
intelligent man who actually graduated from Virginia Tech last May,
who plans to study law, who calls his mother before every game.
</P>
<P>
   It is the logical extension of a sports culture where the most
memorable sound bites have nasty teeth in them and the most honored
coaches are willing to indulge the indiscretions of their
All-Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Corey Moore a great deal,'' Virginia Tech coach
Frank Beamer said Friday when told of his star's illogical
ramblings. ``He's a bright guy. He says what he means and he
believes what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   Charley Wiles, the Hokies' defensive line coach, threw a similar
blanket of absolution over anything Moore might say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see Corey do that,'' Wiles said of Moore's verbal
implosion. ``He's a first-class kid. But I don't know what he's
feeling. I don't know what kind of pressure he's under. That's kind
of how he gets ready to play. You've got to get yourself ready.
Corey's gonna be right. He's got his game face on.''
</P>
<P>
   If only he can hold that ugly sneer for three more days, the
senior will have his wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win, lose or draw,'' said Moore, ``I want to go out with a
bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy New Year? Better smile when you say that, partner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
