<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-Y2K-CZAR-1STLD-WRITET     12-31 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CZAR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     Y2K BUG HAS NO BITE IN THE NEW YEAR _ BUT SOME SLOT MACHINES GO
BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Updating and editing throughout)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most of the world rolled into the new century
Friday with only a smattering of Y2K glitches _ the most
significant at a Japanese nuclear plant.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear plant, the Shika Nuclear Power Station about 170
miles northwest of Tokyo, lost its radiation alarm system shortly
after midnight there. John Koskinen, chief of the White House's Y2K
command center, said Japanese officials described the problem as
minor and that the plant would remain in operation.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, slot machines went bonkers in Delaware, as
if to underline the lack of serious problems here. The 150 slot
machines at three Delaware rack tracks temporarily shut down
Thursday night after the slots' time-based computer chips _
programmed to read three days ahead _ became confused when they
rolled over to 2000. The slots were quickly repaired, Koskinen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen and Thomas Pickering, the No. 2 official at the State
Department, gave upbeat reports all day Friday as the new year
swept across the globe's 24 time zones.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, after the new year had been greeted in Europe, Asia
and Africa, Pickering said there were `no significant Y2K
difficulties there.''
</P>
<P>
   `Nothing out of the ordinary has been experienced,'' Pickering
declared. The biggest problem was the `Mothers' Day phenomenon'' of
telephone circuits being overloaded, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. EST Friday _ midnight Greenwich Mean Time _ computers
that control airline traffic, power grids and military operations
appeared to roll over into the new year without incident. The
computers are based on GMT.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation's airspace system is up and running safely,''
Federal Aviation Administration chief Jane Garvey said. She was
aboard a jet traveling from Washington, D.C. to Dallas when air
traffic computers passed midnight GMT.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate his confidence in the air traffic control system,
Koskinen took a commercial airline flight to New York so that he
was in the air at midnight GMT. After landing safely, he returned
to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen cautioned that he wouldn't have a clear picture of any
computer-related problems in the United States until late Monday
after a day of normal business operations following the long
holiday weekend. He said he would withhold any decision about
problems in the developing world until the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   But, he also appeared confident that the United States would
weather the transition into the New Year with smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never felt that there was any significant chance that
the United States would have would have a major problem in the
infrastructure, either nationally or regionally,'' Koskinen said.
``And I continue to believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Russian joint operation center located near Colorado
Springs, Colo., reported no incidents. The center was set up to
protect against any mistaken perceptions that one or the other
nuclear powers had launched a missile.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Koskinen said the Y2K transition was `the biggest
management challenge the world has had in 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that industrialized society moved into the new year
without any problems should not lead to anyone to `underestimate
the nature of the problem that was originally there.''
</P>
<P>
   `Had the effort not been made, had the money not been spent, we
would be in a very different situation than we find ourselves in
right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department estimates that some $100 billion was
spent in the United States over the past five years to fix the Y2K
problem _ which would occur if computers interpreted the digits
``00'' as 1900 rather than 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Early good news came to the White House center as New Year's eve
slipped past midnight in Western Pacific time zones first. For
example, New Zealand celebrated the arrival of the New Year at 6
a.m. EST. As Japan, Australia and other industrialized nations
joined the '00 honor roll, optimism grew at the White House Y2K
coordination center that years of preparedness were paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, undersecretary of state, reported that the Bilibino
nuclear reactor in the Russian Far East passed into the new year
without incident, a reassuring note because of concern about
Russia's attention to the Y2K issue and its aging nuclear reactors.
Later, he reported that all of Russia's reactors had smoothly
rolled over into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen noted an increase in public interest in the Y2K
phenomenon as Jan. 1 approached. The White House Y2K web site had
about 250,000 hits on Thursday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guam was the first U.S. territory to make the transition without
incident; Koskinen said, noting that officials on the island
reported soon after midnight that a baby was born and an airplane
had landed there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
