<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS IN FREE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins ended 1999 stumbling badly, 2-9-4 in their
last 15 games, and they lost their last two in overtime. So, what's
really going on here? It isn't just a blip on the screen. After an
0-5-4 beginning and now this latest skid, there are some key
factors that can't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   --Lack of training camps for key players. Jason Allison, Byron
Dafoe, P.J. Axelsson, and Hal Gill were absent from or late for
camp. In addition, the two players added during the season _ Marty
McSorley and Joe Murphy _ missed about eight months of hockey
before being signed. That's practically half the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check Owen Nolan's stats last year, when he missed training
camp, and this year,'' said coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose forward had 19 goals and 45 points in 78 games last
season. In only 41 games this year, he has 27 goals and 52 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't miss training camp,'' said Burns. ``These are facts.
These are not excuses. I know it's a problem and I know it's a
problem for other teams, too. If you have that many guys miss
training camp, you'd better hang on. It's unfair to the team and
it's unfair to the coach when you miss training camp. I know it's
all contractual stuff. I don't blame the players. A lot of times
it's not the players, it's who is running their lives. If Byron
wouldn't have gotten mad and come in, he'd probably still be out.
(Gill), the poor kid, hasn't been the same because he came in
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said it was painful to watch Gill in the third period of
Thursday's loss in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a left winger but he ends up playing left wing
because he just got out of the penalty box,'' he said. ``We just
killed a penalty for two minutes and he ends up along the boards
trying to get the puck out and he's sitting there like a moose in
the water trying to fight to get the puck out. I almost ran out on
the ice, took the puck, and threw it in the net because I knew it
was going to go in. Sure as Jesus, it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   That tied the game at 4-4 with 5:23 left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   --Byron Dafoe. Last season, Dafoe was the MVP of the team, hands
down. This year, he has played very well at times and outstanding a
couple of times (such as in Ottawa), but Dafoe has yet to steal a
game for the Bruins as he's done so many times before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think the Leafs are so good?'' asked Burns.
``Curtis Joseph wins how many games for them? Why do you think the
Buffalo Sabres had so much success last year? Dominik Hasek won a
bunch of games for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe agreed that he hasn't yet been the same player he was last
year in terms of dominance. When asked if he felt he'd stolen any
games, Dafoe said, ``No, definitely not the same amount. Maybe the
Phoenix game, but no, Ottawa maybe would've been the closest
second. If you look at it that way, missing six months of hockey
definitely doesn't give you the fresh start of the season and the
exhibition games to get into it. It could be a bit of a factor in
terms of my personal statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   --Penalty killing. Simply put, it stinks. The Bruins were tops
in the league last year. This year, they're dead last.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't not bring up Tim Taylor and Dmitri Khristich,'' said
Dafoe. ``I know (president/general manager Harry Sinden) doesn't
want us talking about them because what's done is done, but I'm
telling you, look at our PK last year and they were key players.
Dmitri being able to play center, Tim is a center, we only have one
center on this team. Robbie DiMaio doesn't know how to play center
and he'd be the first to tell you that. People say, `So what,' but
it's what they do in our own end.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's confusion. If you look at the goals that are being
scored against us, it's a lot of open men on open sides with open
nets. Why is that? It's missed coverage. Is it someone's fault?
Well, yeah, it is and it isn't. They're not used to their position
and they get confused, but it is their guy and they don't realize
it and that's why we're having problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say why are we doing this and we didn't do it last
year, that we're the same team. But it's not the same team. It's
only a couple of guys, but they were key guys. I'm not taking away
from the guys we got to replace them, but you look at our PK, going
from first in the league to worst? That's a huge differential when
you're talking about one-goal hockey games.''
</P>
<P>
   --Lack of centermen. Joe Thornton is the only healthy natural
center on the team. Allison can't take draws and everyone is trying
to fill in, with disastrous results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anson Carter's not a center,'' said Burns. ``DiMaio is not a
center. You can only do it one or two games and get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins play the New Jersey Devils Saturday night and the
club is hoping the new year will be the beginning of a new start.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there's a silver lining,'' said Dafoe, ``but you've
got to find it soon because you don't want to let our playoff spot
go too far away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
