<SLUG> BC-FBC-INSIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO RAMBLES OVER BC, 62-28 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Boston College's first bowl game in five years
began ominously enough when the University of Colorado's mascot, a
buffalo called Ralphie IV, was released from her holding pen at the
south end of Arizona Stadium and taken by her handlers for a romp
around the field just before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   It was a forecast of the stampede that followed.
</P>
<P>
   After earning their first postseason berth since the 1994 Aloha
Bowl, the Eagles arrived in Tucson _ by United Parcel Service
charter flight, no less _ ranked 25th in the Associated Press poll
and installed as 8-point underdogs. But BC wound up spread eagle
after getting flattened by the Buffaloes, 62-28, in Friday's
Insight.com Bowl before an announced crowd of 35,662.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this was a very disappointing end to a great season,''
said BC coach Tom O'Brien. ``As I said before, if we couldn't
contain their speed, then we'd have a lot of trouble, and we did.
We didn't tackle well, we turned the ball over on offense, which
you can't do against a good football team, we had breakdowns in the
kicking game. It was a bad game all around and in all phases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to take responsibility because I didn't do a good
enough job in getting this football team ready to play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles managed just 255 total yards (96 rushing) and
struggled to mount any offense after Colorado scored on its first
two possessions to take a 14-0 lead on a 10-yard run by sophomore
running back Cortlen Johnson _ who was selected offensive and
overall MVP with 15 carries for 201 yards and a pair of touchdowns
_ and a 2-yard keeper by quarterback Mike Moschetti (14 of 24, 149
yards).
</P>
<P>
   The Buffaloes, playing to remove the lingering aftertaste of a
bitter 33-30 overtime loss against Nebraska in their regular-season
finale Nov. 26, established eight school bowl records _ six by
halftime _ in delivering coach Gary Barnett his first bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably our most dominant performance,'' said Barnett.
``But as dominant as we were, I know this was a bad day for Boston
College, so I don't want to harp too much on our dominance, but I
know how things can happen to you like what happened to them today.
Things like that happen sometimes, but we played pretty well, we
played consistently, and had a pretty good game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   BC, whose senior-laden defense had been hit by a flu bug that
caused six of 11 starters to miss practice time this week, allowed
the most points in school history, and surrendered 523 total yards,
including 365 rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck also struggled, completing 13
of 32 passes for 146 yards, and wound up getting victimized when
Colorado linebacker Jashon Sykes stepped in front of a screen pass
intended for Cedric Washington and returned it 29 yards for a
touchdown for a 21-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the play that just took the wind out of their
sails,'' said Johnson, who did his best to do the same by pacing
Colorado's offensive assault. ``It was just a bad game all around
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   And it only got worse.
</P>
<P>
   With 11:41 remaining in the second quarter, redshirt freshman
quarterback Brian St. Pierre came on in relief of Hasselbeck for a
series and proceeded to expand Colorado's lead to 28-0, throwing an
interception on his second attempt that was returned 21 yards by
safety Rashidi Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Kelly, Colorado's outstanding junior cornerback and return
man, dealt the Eagles another blow when he fielded a booming
55-yard punt by Kevin McMyler and returned it 88 yards to give the
Buffaloes a commanding 35-0 lead with 8:50 remaining before
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   BC senior strong safety George White finally put the Eagles on
the board when he intercepted Moschetti and brought it back 78
yards for a touchdown, but White scored no style points with
O'Brien when he did a swan dive into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping that it would be a jump-start for the
team,'' White said. ``I just did what I could to help the team get
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was it wasn't enough as Colorado kept up the
offensive pressure, getting a 2-yard TD run by Johnson and a
26-yard Jeremy Aldrich field goalfor a 45-7 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime, we challenged the guys that the rankings were out
of our control,'' Barnett said. ``But we had a little sign in our
room with a `1999' and `Final Rankings' and a question mark by it.
We knew this was our only chance to get that question mark changed
to a number.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the Buffaloes succeeded in doing so by
continuing the onslaught in the second half. After Aldrich
converted a 21-yard field goal to make it 48-17, BC's Bryan Arndt
recovered a William Green fumble in the end zone to cut the deficit
to 48-14. But Roman Hollowell tallied on an 18-yard lateral and
backup quarterback Zac Colvin converted on a 4-yard keeper to make
it 62-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles scored twice in the final 7:37 as Hasselbeck hit
Jamal Burke with a 1-yard TD toss that capped a tortuous 18-play,
72-yard drive, and on Doug Bessette's 9-yard return of a Ralph
Parent blocked punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to everybody in their conference and they said they
were the most talented team and the fastest team in the (Big 12),''
O'Brien said. ``We knew coming in as a coaching staff that we'd
have some problems, but obviously I didn't get that across to these
kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
