<HEADER>
A3688 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-STOCKS-STOCKS_SFCHRON     12-31 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-STOCKS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Tech Stocks Uncork Champagne Year  
 By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Unless you spent the past 12 months in a cave waiting for Y2K to
run its course, you already know the two words that were sweet
music to Wall Street in 1999: tech stocks.
<P>
   ``All of the gains in the major indexes were produced by
technology stocks,'' said Al Kugel, senior investment strategist at
Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham in Chicago. ``You take them away, and the
market was basically flat.''
</P>
<P>
   No index benefited more from the trend than the tech-heavy
Nasdaq composite index, which soared an additional 32.44 points to
a record close of 4,069.31 yesterday, bringing its gain for the
year to 85.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This surpassed the previous annual record gain for a leading
index _ an 81.7 percent rise posted by the Dow Jones industrial
average way back in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow turned in a respectable performance in '99, but nowhere
near the Nasdaq's stratospheric ascent. The benchmark index
advanced 25.2 percent, to 11,497.12, for the year, including a
44.26 point gain yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 brought up the rear with a more modest 19.5- &LR; 
percent gain for the year. It climbed 4.78 points yesterday to a
record 1,469.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news of strong earnings more than offset the bad news
of rising interest rates,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment
officer at First Albany in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Bay Area's tech leaders, database softwaremaker Oracle
Corp. was typical of those posting white-hot results. The Redwood
Shores company blew by analysts' estimates last month with
quarterly profit of $384 million (26 cents per share).
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Oracle's stock handsomely rewarded investors,
emerging in the fall from months of doldrums to more than triple to
$112.06. But despite its impressive showing, Oracle wasn't among
the Bay Area's pacesetters when it came to annual percentage gains.
</P>
<P>
   According to data on 370 local firms compiled by San Francisco's
Davis Skaggs Investment Management, a subsidiary of Salomon Smith
Barney, the shares covering the most ground belonged to San Jose's
Puma Technology, a provider of mobile computing systems. The
company's stock jumped more than 3,770 percent during the past 12
months to finish at $130.63.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the 370 Bay Area companies saw their stocks rise by a
weighted average of 197 percent for the year, including an average
74 percent gain in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skyrocketing over the broad S&AMP;P 500 market by 10 times and
even dwarfing the high-flying Nasdaq, the Bay Area stocks are in
the stratosphere,'' said Paul Tiao, vice president of Davis Skaggs.
</P>
<P>
   Tech companies, not surprisingly, thoroughly overwhelmed their
analog cousins in terms of local stock performance.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing Puma in the top 10 were Redwood City's Broadvision (up
1,494 percent for the year), Los Gatos' Metricom (1,416 percent),
Mountain View's Verisign (1,190 percent), San Jose's BEA Systems
(1,042 percent), Santa Rosa's Optical Coating Lab (1,038 percent),
Santa Clara's Exodus Communications (1,006 percent), San Jose's SDL
(1,000 percent), Milpitas' Network Peripherals (950 percent) and
Sunnyvale's Harmonic (913 percent).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Silicon Valley's domination of the Bay Area rankings is
so complete that you have to travel all the way down the list to
No. 96 _ import retailer Cost Plus _ to come across a company not
involved in one way or another with tech, telecom or biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   (Oakland's Cost Plus saw its stock rise 155 percent in '99,
proving that wicker furniture and Indonesian knickknacks still have
their place in a world of routers, servers and broadband
connections.)
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, while the Internet figures prominently in the
operations of most local companies on the Davis Skaggs list, you
don't come across a pure Internet play until No.42 _ San
Francisco's Cnet, which saw its share price rise by 326 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara's Yahoo placed No.56 with a 265 percent advance,
while San Mateo's Inktomi was No.86 with a 174 percent increase and
Menlo Park's E-Trade Group came in No.124 with a 123 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Among softwaremakers, Oracle was No.48 with a 290- &LR;  percent
rise, Mountain View's Intuit No.101 with a 148 percent increase and
Emeryville's Sybase No.113 with a 130 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the better-known, and widely held, tech powerhouses took
a back seat to newer arrivals on the list. Palo Alto's Sun
Microsystems finished the year at No.58 with a 262 percent rise,
while San Jose's Cisco Systems was No.112 with a 131 percent
increase and Santa Clara's Intel Corp. ended all the way down in
the No.191 spot with a 39 percent advance.
</P>
<P>
   Sunnyvale's Cardiac Pathways Corp., a maker of heart diagnostic
products, was at the very bottom of the list, with its stock down
82 percent for the year. The company is still awaiting approval
from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for a system that uses
ultrasound technology to treat heart abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, taking a longer and broader view, it's clear that
tech stocks were the engine driving Wall Street's advance through
the entire decade. In terms of percentage gain, no one topped
mighty Cisco, which has risen about 125,000 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   America Online was a distant second with a more than 81,000
percent gain, followed by Dell Computer Corp. (up more than 72,000
percent), data-storage dynamo EMC Corp. (68,000 percent) and
Internet investment firm CMGI (57,000 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech will continue to lead the way in 2000,'' said Allan
Roness, research director at JW Genesis Securities in Boca Raton,
Fla. ``But some will powder out, and some others will become
leaders again.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to crawl out on a limb with specific predictions.
However, Roness noted that ``there was a ton of IPOs that won't be
profitable anytime soon. There are e-tailers who don't understand
the costs of doing business on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   As for IPOs, while it's not yet clear how much 1999's crop
contributed to the Nasdaq's massive run-up, they certainly had an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bloomberg News, about 70 IPOs nationwide
subsequently appreciated from their offer price by at least 500
percent, 40 climbed by at least 700 percent and no fewer than 30
new share offerings soared by more than 1,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While United Parcel Service won the blue ribbon for money raised
in '99, walking off with a cool $5.5 billion, VA Linux Systems
shattered all records for first-day gains, skyrocketing almost 700
percent in its trading debut.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bay Area companies, Redwood City's Liberate Technologies,
a developer of software for bringing Internet content to TV set-top
boxes and other appliances, set the pace for IPO gains, surging
1,161 percent since arriving on the market at an initial $16 in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Prudential Securities' influential technical
analyst Ralph Acampora said he expects the Nasdaq to top 5,000 this
year _ a forecast that, in light of the index's recent advances,
doesn't seem like such a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the Dow moving as high as 14,000, and the S&AMP;P 500
cruising as high as 1,800.
</P>
<P>
   Another closely watched analyst, Goldman Sachs' Abby Joseph
Cohen, said she envisions the Dow hitting 12,300 by year's end and
the S&AMP;P 500 reaching 1,525. These numbers jibe with most other
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money's going to continue to pour into the market,'' said
Brian Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum and Co.
in Kansas City. ``This will keep growth-fund portfolio managers
fully employed.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects the market's tech leaders in 1999 to remain out front
in 2000. Among Belski's top picks are Cisco, Microsoft Corp.,
Lucent Technologies, Oracle and Dell.
</P>
<P>
   First Albany's Johnson likes these stocks as well but is finding
that the higher they go, the less comfortable he feels about their
valuations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I own Oracle, I own Cisco,'' he observed. ``But I have to ask
myself why I'm not having more fun. The answer is because the
market has not been entirely rational over the past year.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an understatement. With the Nasdaq setting no fewer than
61 records in 1999, ``rational'' is probably the last word that
comes to mind in describing the market's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get a return in the double digits, you're taking
a fair amount of risk to get there,'' said Steve Adams, managing
director of First Security Van Kasper in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we'll see some of these crazy valuations calm down in
2000,'' he said. ``Historically, all bubbles pop. There's no
rationale for the current run-up.''
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts foresee the gravy train continuing. ``The
general expectation in early 1999 was that the U.S. economy would
slow down,'' noted Stein Roe's Kugel. ``Things ended up being
better than expected, and that set the tone for the market.''
</P>
<P>
   As for 2000, he said it doesn't look like an economic downturn
is likely. ``If anything,'' Kugel said, ``economic growth worldwide
will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq 6,000, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
