<HEADLINE>
GROZNY: A FEW HOLIDAY TOKENS IN THE MIDDLE OF A WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fighting still rages in Grozny, but the soldiers there made a
few bows to the holiday, and seemed oblivious to the political
earthquake of President Boris Yeltsin's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In a hospital's mess tent, cooks prepared a special holiday
dinner. One soldier, a woman, dragged a yolka, a Russian holiday
tree, past a row of corpses and toward a complex of tents.
</P>
<P>
   Officers of a nearby armored unit received a small plastic bag
filled with cheap cologne, a plastic pen and ``Dear Soldier''
letters from Russian schoolchildren, like one from Andrei Malakhov,
a seven-year-old boy from Yefremov, a small town south of Moscow,
who said he hoped all the Russian soldiers would come home alive.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, they had already broken open several bottles
of vodka and were feasting on bread and pickled cabbage. They had
set up camp in a series of trenches that separatist rebels had
occupied just weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   One officer, who gave only his first name, Aleksandr, said the
``terrorists'' in Chechnya would be finished off within six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-Y2K-0101-1STL     12-31 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-Y2K-0101-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: writethru updates, polishes throughout
 &HT;    THIRD MILLENNIUM COMES TO BRITAIN: It's Zulu Time!
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The new millennium arrived in London with the familiar
midnight toll of Big Ben followed by 20 minutes of thundering,
dazzling bursts of multi-colored fireworks reflected in the rushing
currents of the River Thames.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, Queen Elizabeth II marked the millennium with a
glass of champagne and very circumspect peck on the cheek for her
husband, Prince Philip. The royal couple linked arms with Prime
Minister Tony Blair and his wife, Cherie, to sing ''Auld Lang
Syne.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the much-anticipated climax of years of planning intended
to make London the center of the worldwide millennium celebrations.
By all early indicators, it was a rousing success _ or as rousing a
success as such a celebration can be given its tendency to attract
hundreds of thousands of alcohol-soused revelers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, police reported few extraordinary incidents during the
night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night in which Britain confronted its past and present
by saying good-bye to a century that has engulfed ``the empire'' in
two devastating wars and forced it to relinquish its colonial
interests.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning hours of the 20th Century, the BBC Concert
Orchestra played a rousing ``Rule, Britannia!'' for the final time
of the age in Royal Albert Hall. The 6,000 concert goers _ some in
tuxedos some in jeans _ stood and sang jubilantly while waving
British flags.
</P>
<P>
   The song holds a far different resonance at the end of a century
that has seen the dissolution of one of the world's great empires.
As it enters the 21st Century, Britain faces the real prospect of
being reduced to only England with Scotland, Northern Ireland and
Wales now enjoying a measure of independence.
</P>
<P>
   But for Edgar Robertson who had come to the Albert Hall concert
with his family from Birmingham _ the one in England _ the night
and century seemed full of promise. ``There isn't an empire anymore
at the end of this century, but Britain remains such an important
force in the world,'' he said. ``Could anybody really imagine a day
when you would see American troops heading into some hot spot
without their British cousins at their sides? But this will be
America's millennium, won't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the elegant confines of Albert Hall, the night took on a
substantially less refined air. On The Mall, the broad ceremonial
boulevard that terminates at Buckingham palace, a carnival of
stomach-churning rides formed a fairway that would rival any
American state fair.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds jammed the city's ancient thoroughfares and squares. Much
of the central city was converted into a pedestrian zone.
</P>
<P>
   By 11:30 p.m. (GMT), Admiral Nelson's column rose from a solid
mass of human bodies crammed into Trafalgar Square. Dominating the
skyline near Big Ben and the Houses of Parliament was the one
annoying glitch: the stunning, five-story London Eye. The
state-of-the-art Ferris wheel was idle because it failed a safety
test earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, none of the dreaded snags expected with the feared
``Millennium Bug'' appeared. So pleased was the government with the
country's success at avoiding Y2K pitfalls, that it issued a
statement before midnight declaring that all was running without a
hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic visual scene was the Thames River, its swift
currents lit by dozens of spotlights and laser beams to be the
``river of fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours before midnight, the queen sailed down the Thames, the
center of festivities, to light a huge millennium beacon afloat on
a barge. A dozen smaller beacons blazed on bridges, and hundreds of
thousands of people gathered along the riverbanks in the center of
the capital to watch a 120-foot wall of flame race across the
water's surface at the moment the century turned.
</P>
<P>
   That was the cue to light 40,000 fireworks waiting on barges
moored along the river.
</P>
<P>
   In typical British fashion, the crowds eventually were dispersed
by perhaps the most English of all methods _ the rain. A cold
drizzle began to fall shortly after midnight sending the partygoers
capable of deliberate movement to seek refuge and head home.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
