<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     12-31 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES THAT STING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ The score was not the worst part, and frankly, the
score is never what hurts most in games like this. It just looks
that way when you're watching on television.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with basic cable service could have watched Colorado
score 62 points on Boston College. Knowing that millions of people
watched you on your worst day of the year can easily extend a bad
afternoon to a bad month. But that's not what the BC players were
thinking about after they lost the Insight.com Bowl to the
Buffaloes, 62-28.
</P>
<P>
   Really, what hurts most for players are the scenes their fans
don't see on TV.
</P>
<P>
   What makes you angry _ and what hurts _ is when you're standing
on the Arizona Stadium sideline late in the fourth quarter and look
across at the Colorado players. If you look near the 25-yard line,
you can see two defensive linemen, Sean Jarne and Jesse Warren,
laughing and posing for a photo. During the game. You never forget
things like that.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffaloes rewrote eight of this game's records and had set
six by halftime. But that didn't hurt as much as having to walk
back to your locker room afterward, only to be met by several boxes
of pizza and disappointed teammates (some of whom you'll never play
with again). Your friends tell you that they understand how you
feel, but they really don't if they weren't here experiencing
everything with you. And that includes the New Year's Eve party at
the team hotel, the party that was not as fun as it could have
been.
</P>
<P>
   You don't forget things like that, either.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in Iowa and Indiana and Georgia, a bored
channel-surfer flicked to this game, laughed at the lopsided score,
passed out shortly after the ball dropped on 2000, and couldn't
remember this morning who won and where the game was played. But BC
senior Chris Hovan, who will most likely be a first-round draft
pick in the spring, will be able to recite all the details 10 or 20
years from now. He may win a Super Bowl some day, but he'll never
forget this one.
</P>
<P>
   So, I guess if you were watching on TV it would be easy to laugh
at these guys. They dropped passes, missed tackles, and always
appeared to be chasing Olympic sprinter Maurice Greene even though
they were actually running after guys named Cortlen Johnson and
Mike ``Machete'' Moschetti. If they wanted they could make a
documentary on the weirdness of time, how everything can go wrong
in three hours.
</P>
<P>
   There were two interceptions returned for touchdowns, one each
thrown by Matt Hasselbeck and Brian St. Pierre. As one of those
touchdowns was unfolding, a BC cheerleader sprained an ankle. There
was a punt returned 88 yards for a touchdown. There were the 62
points, the most allowed in BC history. There was rain here for the
first time since September. There was the strange dynamic of not
seeing many people in the stands (announced attendance was 35,762)
but knowing that anybody in the country could be watching. Even
after all the penalties and turnovers were coming to a close, the
Spirit of Unlikeliness reached outside the stadium when the person
delivering pizza to the BC locker room momentarily lost her sense
of direction.
</P>
<P>
   There was too much Colorado speed. ``I think Virginia Tech
probably is the fastest team we've played all year,'' Hasselbeck
said, ``but Colorado's defensive backs . . . those guys can fly.''
There was also miscommunication. BC coach Tom O'Brien said he
obviously didn't get his message across to his players and took
responsibility for the loss. Hasselbeck tossed another interception
when he threw to one area and Carlton Rowe turned in the other
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing all of that, it was almost impossible to make fun of the
huge target. Before the season, the Eagles didn't expect to be here
and there was a good reason for that: They willed themselves here
with good fortune moreso than extraordinary talent. They struggled
with Northeastern, Baylor, and Navy. They lost to an unofficial
Division 2 team, Temple. The truth? The 8-4 Eagles aren't quite at
the level of the Buffaloes, despite Colorado's 7-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll say that,'' Hovan said. ``I'll just say
they were better today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovan said he was just as disappointed as his teammates, but
``I'm not going to throw any chairs or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buffaloes spent most of the week looking disinterested. They
would have gone to a more prestigious bowl if they could have
defeated Nebraska Nov. 26, but they lost in overtime. It must have
been clear to any Eagle that the Colorado players didn't have a lot
of respect for their work. Colorado borders Arizona, yet BC sold
more tickets to the game. So, yes, BC wanted to smash this team,
although the opposite happened.
</P>
<P>
   As Hovan said, losses like this don't make you throw chairs.
There are players on this team who have had more devastating things
happen to them than losing a football game on national TV. But if
you are an actor, ballerina, or engineer, you understand how hard
it is to forget your worst day.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with the athletes from BC, especially those like Rowe
and Hovan and Pedro Cirino, who have played their final games at
the Heights. The score? It doesn't hurt as much as you might think.
Memories can imprison you sometimes, and it's the memories that
sting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
