<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MILLENNIUM-ALOFT-BOS &LR;      12-31 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-ALOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA CHIEF FLIES CONFIDENTLY INTO THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON BOARD AMERICAN AIRLINES FLIGHT 1099 _ Wearing a navy pants
suit with a single strand of pearls and showing absolutely no
trepidation, Jane F. Garvey, the nation's top aviation official,
sat in the first row of the coach section on board American
Airlines flight 1099 Friday, so she could be airborne as the
country's air-traffic control system struck midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last-minute Y2K-related fixes to the system, Garvey was
supremely confident that the flight would be uneventful. In a
preflight press conference at Washington's National Airport, US
Transportation Secretary Rodney E. Slater praised Garvey and US
Senator Slade Gorton of Washington, chairman of the Senate aviation
subcommittee, for being on a flight that ``will take off in the
20th century and land in the 21st century.'' The flight, he said,
is ``a visible symbol of the journey the nation is taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Garvey's agency, the Federal Aviation Administration, has spent
more than $350 million making sure its computer-dependent
air-traffic control systems function smoothly. The airlines spent
another $750 million domestically to insure that flying today is as
safe as any other day.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the FAA invested millions of man hours in checking
computer code so antiquated that retired IBM employees were called
in to assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of FAA men and women have worked on this, and they
have responded just wonderfully to a remarkable challenge,'' Garvey
said on the first leg of the trip, to Dallas-Fort Worth. Television
cameras jostled for space in the single-aisle airplane to record
Garvey selecting her seat.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute change to the air-traffic-control software _
involving less than 10 lines of computer code _ took place this
week and was tested Thursday, when it was discovered there was a
remote possibility that if two pieces of equipment failed
simultaneously on Jan. 1 it could momentarily shut down the main
computers at the nation's 21 en route centers, which direct all of
the high-altitude air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1099, a McDonnell-Douglas MD-80, pushed back from the
gate at 5:12 p.m. at National Airport and was roaring down the
runway at 5:22, in plenty of time to insure that Garvey would be in
the air at midnight Greenwich Mean Time (7 p.m. Eastern Standard
Time). That's the hour at which the nation's air-traffic control
system, which is coordinated with computers all over the world,
would recognize the date change to Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was scheduled to land in Dallas at 8:43 p.m. Eastern
time. Following another press conference, Garvey was to take off
for San Francisco aboard American Flight 1435, which was scheduled
to land at 3:09 a.m. Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 7 p.m., as the aircraft flew over Trenton, Tenn.,
Garvey, Slater, and President Clinton's chief Y2K adviser, John
Koskinen, were linked in a telephone conference call through the
FAA operations center. Koskinen was on a plane to New York, and
Slater was at the FAA Air Traffic Control Command Center in
Herndon, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of happy faces up here,'' Garvey reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our flight is as uneventful as yours,'' Koskinen replied.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne was uncorked as Janet S. Rhodes, a passenger from Long
Beach, Calif., exclaimed, ``We're still flying and heading in the
same direction. Isn't it marvelous!''
</P>
<P>
   Garvey also read a copy of a letter faxed from her office to
President Clinton, saying that ``the nation's airspace system is up
and running safely and efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   She closed the letter with a quotation from a telegram sent by
flight pioneers Orville and Wilbur Wright nearly a century ago,
``Success (Stop) . . . Inform press (Stop).''
</P>
<P>
   No indications of trouble were reported in the minutes after 7
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The 133-seat flight to Dallas was nearly empty, save for Garvey;
some members of her staff; Ray Long, the former head of the FAA's
Y2K office; Senator Gorton; a dozen members of the news media; and
about 25 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a struggle in many ways for Garvey, a former commissioner
of the Massachusetts Department of Public Works, to make this
flight at all.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after she was named to head the FAA in August 1997,
Garvey was confronted with the fact that the agency was not
adequately prepared for potential year 2000 problems. But long
before she knew how the problems would be fixed, she vowed that
they would be. Two years ago, she promised to make this flight
across the country to show that the United States has the world's
safest aviation system.
</P>
<P>
   But due to a lack of demand for travel on this date, Garvey
notwithstanding, American Airlines kept canceling flights she
wanted to take.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, American canceled about 20 percent of its domestic
flights on Dec. 31, virtually all of them after 2 p.m. Garvey's
plane is the last American flight scheduled to land at the
airline's busy Dallas hub.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA reported that about 3,000 planes were in the air at 4
p.m. Eastern time, and that number was expected to drop steadily
through the evening. The San Francisco leg of Garvey's trip is
considered to be pure public relations, an opportunity to be in the
air over the United States when it is midnight on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey has boasted that she will celebrate the New Year three
times in one night. If her timing is good, that will happen. In
addition to the all-important Greenwich Mean Time system rollover,
she is scheduled to be in the air at midnight in the Mountain and
Pacific time zones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
