<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3700 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i BC-WHO'S-PUTIN?-INDEPEND     12-31 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHO'S-PUTIN?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VLADIMIR PUTIN: BORIS' BLUE-EYED, BLACK-BELT SUCCESSOR  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: TIMELY for Yeltsin resignation coverage!)   (This TIMELY 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news, ``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In four months as Russian prime minister, Vladimir Putin has
gone from a dry and derided nobody to the Russians' favorite for
president next year.
</P>
<P>
   Recent history shows how volatile Russian politics can be, but
if nothing changes between now and the rescheduled presidential
elections next March, we are probably looking at the new master of
the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a wave of popularity since launching the second Chechnya
war in September, the 47-year old former spymaster was designated
Friday by outgoing President Boris Yeltsin as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Although Putin did not run in the parliamentary elections on
Dec. 19, his hard-line policy is seen as having contributed to the
success of a new pro-Kremlin bloc Unity which he endorsed in the
poll.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of polling, Russian television showed the black-belt
judo expert throwing an opponent to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The man who is encouraging Russians to feel pride in themselves
owes his sudden rise to an act of expediency by Boris Yeltsin who,
earlier this year, appeared to be in danger of sinking in the mire
of post-communist corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Few now remember the prime minister's ignominious beginning or
stop to reflect that Putin is still linked to the hated Yeltsin
regime. The Russians were ready for a national savior and soon saw
Putin as their avenging angel.
</P>
<P>
   President Yeltsin's blue-eyed protege has exceeded all
expectations and, right across the spectrum, Russian politicians
now find it advisable to express support for Putin. Anyone who
dares criticize him risks being called a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   All it took for Putin, who has never held elected office, to win
Russian hearts was one impassioned outburst.
</P>
<P>
   After terrorist bombs destroyed four apartment blocks in
September, killing Muscovites and other Russians as they slept in
their beds, the prime minister allowed himself the use of vulgar
language: ``We will wipe the terrorists out wherever we find them.
If we find them sitting on the toilet, then that's where we will do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That short sentence expressed all the pent-up frustration not
only over Chechnya but over all the failures of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The average Russian responded to this tough guy talk in the same
emotional way he once worshipped Yeltsin for showing that he could
drink vodka as well as the next man.
</P>
<P>
   Russian women seemed to experience an almost sexual thrill _ at
least one woman confessed in a newspaper article that she had
erotic dreams about Putin.
</P>
<P>
   At last, masochistic Russians had what they wanted, a strong
hand and someone else to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, Putin's popularity rating soared from the miserable 2
percent of public support he could count on in August when
President Yeltsin appointed him prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Russians were angry that the Kremlin leader,
casting about for a successor he could trust to protect him from
prosecution in retirement, had dumped another perfectly good prime
minister, the youthful and amiable Sergei Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
   They openly laughed at Putin and laid bets as to how long he
would last. But the promise that the terrorists would get their
comeuppance, even on the toilet, changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   The grey suit _ a man who began his career serving the KGB in
Germany, went on to deputize for the liberal mayor of St.
Petersburg, Anatoly Sobchak, then helped to run Yeltsin's
administration and headed the Federal Security Service (former KGB)
_ suddenly had character.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls show that 47 percent of Russians see Putin as
their next president, almost enough for him to win the election in
a single round.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he has done virtually nothing to tackle the
problems of the Russian economy, apart from reassuring investors
that he sees no sense in renationalizing what has been privatized.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he called for a regulated market economy which would
avoid both blind adherence to Western liberalism and a return to
the Soviet past.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made clear that because of its history, Russia could
not become a Western-style democracy like the United States because
of its history.
</P>
<P>
   Higher world oil prices have cushioned Russia financially during
its latest Chechnya offensive. The financial cost will be felt
later, and perhaps, if the war drags on, there will be a higher
human price for Moscow as well
</P>
<P>
   For the moment Russians feel it is all worth it, because they
are bombing Chechnya, which is not only a place but also a symbol
of all that ails them. And no amount of hand-wringing by the West,
perceived to have given bad advice in the period of ``reforms,''
will stop them. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
