<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3716 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN     12-31 1519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T GIVE STEVENS' CAREER SHORT SHRIFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ When Gary Stevens, then the leading jockey at
Longacres Park near Seattle, moved to the tougher Southern
California circuit in 1984, he had the audacity to think it was
``ripe for the taking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Shoemaker had to be getting close to retirement,''
Stevens said this week, recounting his reasoning. ``Fernando Toro
had to be getting close to retirement. Laffit Pincay had to have
only four or five years left. Eddie Delahoussaye and Chris McCarron
had to be getting close to retirement ...''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Shoemaker and Toro did retire _ six years later, when Shoe
was 58 and the master of the turf was 49. ``The rest,'' Stevens
noted, ``outlasted me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday afternoon, after wincing through four rides on
opening day at Santa Anita, Stevens surprised everyone except his
family and close friends by announcing his retirement. He's only
36, but has an arthritic right knee and just can't do it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCarron, 44, and Delahoussaye, 48, are still in the
top 10, and Pincay, who turned 53 Wednesday, just won the Hollywood
Park riding title.
</P>
<P>
   All the attention paid lately to Pincay, to Shoemaker (whose
career-wins record Pincay broke Dec. 10), and to Johnny Longden
(who was 59 when he retired in 1966 with the record Shoemaker would
overtake), might have left the impression that every great jockey
goes on riding until the racetrack grit is permanently embedded in
his wrinkled cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   In all the writing about Pincay, Shoemaker and Longden, we might
have implied that a jockey must pile up years and victories to be
considered great.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' career proves otherwise. It's only a bit too dramatic
to say the 5-foot-3 Idaho native, taking nearly every trophy
available into a premature retirement, is horse racing's Sandy
Koufax or Jim Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he should be remembered as the rider of the '90s on
the Santa Anita-Hollywood Park-Del Mar circuit _ despite having
competed in the deepest jockey colony in the nation _ his
versatility, intelligence and competitive drive making him
virtually slump-proof when healthy.
</P>
<P>
   National recognition came slowly. Stevens deserved to go into
the Hall of Fame before finally making it in 1997. And he deserved
an Eclipse Award before he finally won that annual honor in 1998 _
by which time, he was winning races with his savvy, admittedly not
the athlete he'd been on two good legs.
</P>
<P>
   But as a go-to guy for the nation's leading stakes trainers,
Stevens was the West's answer to the East's Jerry Bailey and the
Midwest's Pat Day.
</P>
<P>
   He won two Kentucky Derbies (with Winning Colors, 1988, and
Thunder Gulch, 1995) for D. Wayne Lukas, and one (with Silver
Charm, 1997) for Bob Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   He won seven Santa Anita Derbies, including 1999's aboard
Baffert's General Challenge, to tie Pincay for second behind
Shoemaker, who won eight.
</P>
<P>
   He won three Santa Anita Handicaps and three Hollywood Gold Cups
always on or near the lead.
</P>
<P>
   He won Breeders' Cup races seven times, including the 1999
Juvenile aboard Anees, the winter-book favorite for the 2000
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   He was adventurous about exploring the racing world beyond the
United States, riding in Hong Kong for three months in 1995 and in
Europe as the stable jockey for English trainer Michael Stoute.
</P>
<P>
   What eluded him, in 20 years of winning races, was the Breeders'
Cup Classic, in which he finished second aboard Pleasant Tap in
1992, Bertrando in 1993 and Silver Charm in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to go after that one some other way some day,''
Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, son of a trainer, brother of a jockey, president of the
national Jockeys' Guild (an office he'll have to relinquish) and a
well-reviewed television analyst from time to time, will have his
pick of a variety of job offers.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said he received a ``tempting'' offer _ he wouldn't
specify the responsibilities from Saudi Prince Ahmed bin Salman's
Thoroughbred Corp., the owner for which he'd ridden under contract
since August.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'll take at least a month to think about his future,
meanwhile enjoying more time with his family and at the dinner
table.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens retired with 4,512 victories. That's about half of what
Pincay is likely to end up with.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not only how long you ride that counts.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream opens: Gulfstream Park north of Miami begins a 63-day
season Monday, highlighted by the Feb. 5 Donn Handicap for the
heavyweights and the March 11 Florida Derby for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The track shares the national spotlight with Santa Anita for
most of the winter, and now the two tracks share an owner as well,
since this is Gulfstream's first meet under Frank Stronach.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach _ who also owns Golden Gate Fields, Remington Park and
Thistledown _ faces a Jan. 15 deadline to decide if his tracks will
remain members of the National Thoroughbred Racing Association. In
a press conference on opening day at Santa Anita, he repeated his
demands that the NTRA clarify its mandate, select its board
democratically and fight state regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: Brave Act (Alex Solis riding) will try to defend
his title in the San Gabriel Handicap on turf today, facing Native
Desert, Bouccaneer and Ladies Din, who were second, third and sixth
behind him in the recent Citation at Hollywood Park. The young
challenger is new 4-year-old Manndar, coming off a second to Super
Quercus in the Hollywood Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Kona Gold (Solis), an unlucky second to Artax in the Breeders'
Cup Sprint, heads the El Conejo Handicap on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's Monrovia Handicap sprint for fillies and mares was
moved off the wet turf. Show Me the Stage and Kent Desormeaux led
all the way to upset Honest Lady. Tuzla was among the scratches.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity stunt of the millennium: The year's final race
happened too late to get the result in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The Pompano Park harness track in Florida scheduled its 14th
race on New Year's Eve to begin at 11:59 p.m., meaning the roughly
two-minute event will start in 1999 and finish in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, also, the nine pacers will literally take their
birthdays in stride, since Jan. 1 is the day every racehorse
officially turns a year older. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (through Thursday): David Flores, 5
wins; Kent Desormeaux, Corey Nakatani, Laffit Pincay, Alex Solis
and Pat Valenzuela, 4. Trainers: John Dolan, 3; Bob Baffert,
Leonard Duncan, Ron Ellis, Bobby Frankel and Richard Mandella, 2. &QL; 
Handicapper helper: At first glance the Santa Anita main track is
favoring horses with come-from-behind ability. The first 14 sprints
of the meet were won from behind. Counting sprints and mile-and-up
races, front-runners were a weak 3 for 26 through Thursday, after
winning 32 percent during the Oak Tree meet. &QL; 
On the stakes schedule: At Santa Anita: today, $150,000 San Gabriel
Handicap, 4-year-olds and up, 1[ miles on turf, and $75,000 Run for
the Roses Handicap, fillies and mares 4 and up, 1 mile; Sunday,
$100,000 El Conejo Handicap, 4-year-olds and up, 5{ furlongs, and
$75,000 Hill Rise Handicap, 3-year-olds, 1 mile on turf. At Golden
Gate Fields: today, $75,000 Millennium Mile, 4-year-olds and up, 1
mile on turf. At Gulfstream Park: Monday, $100,000 Appleton
Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 1 1/16 miles on turf; Wednesday,
$75,000 Spectacular Bid, 3-year-olds, 6 furlongs. &QL; 
Mileposts: Laffit Pincay was ordered to serve a suspension Jan. 5-7
for causing interference will riding Captain Ben to seventh place
in Thursday's fourth race.... Turf Paradise in Phoenix, which was
the last racetrack owned by R.D. Hubbard's Hollywood Park, Inc., is
being sold to Jerry Simms, a real-estate developer who describes
himself as a big racing fan.... Cavonnier, the 1996 Santa Anita
Derby winner and heartbreak Kentucky Derby runner-up, has finally
been retired after finishing an indifferent fourth in Monday's Ack
Ack Stakes. The California-bred trained by Bob Baffert went 1 for 5
in his comeback 2 years after being injured in the Belmont
Stakes.... Edgar Prado's victory aboard Prince of Theater Thursday
at Miami's Calder Race Course took him to the 400-wins mark for the
third straight year, a streak accomplished previously only by
Russell Baze and Chris McCarron. The Northern California-based Baze
will finish in the 370s this time after missing more than a month
with back injuries.... With four wins in the first four days at
Santa Anita, jockey Kent Desormeauxequaled his total for the entire
Hollywood Park autumn meet.... Kentucky-based Storm Cat leads the
1999 national sire standings in both the overall (his offspring
earning nearly $10 million) and 2-year-old (nearly $1.5 million)
categories. California-based sires are led by General Meeting....
Los Alamitos' on-site attendance average dropped to 1,731 but
overall wagering averaged a track-record $1.2 million at the latest
quarterhorse meet. The Orange County track began its harness season
Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
