<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3717 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-YELTSIN-QUITS-INDEPEN     12-31 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-QUITS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORIS YELTSIN DROPS HIS ULTIMATE BOMBSHELL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: TIMELY for Yeltsin resignation coverage!)   (This TIMELY 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news, ``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin astonished the world
and his people Friday by announcing on the last day of the 20th
century that he was stepping down after almost a decade in office.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing around making their last-minute preparations for the
millennium, Russians were taken completely off guard by his
theatrically timed announcement that he was retiring early and
entrusting the country to Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   As the news broke at noon, when the first television channel
broadcast an extraordinary New Year speech from the 68-year old
president, most Muscovites were doing battle in the shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a kind of weightlessness,'' said Masha a trainee
journalist. ``Not the same shock as Russians felt on the death of
Stalin, of course, but a milder version of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know the real motives of the people in the Kremlin.
And we do not know whether for us this means positive change or
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shocked, I am stunned, I am bewildered,'' said Tamara, a
housewife who was scouring the city for tin foil to decorate her
home for the Year of the Dragon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot say I feel relieved by this news. While the rest of
the world is worrying about computers, we are still living with our
political chaos. People say Putin will be the next president but to
me right now, our future looks quite foggy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Attentive Kremlin watchers might have sensed that the
unpredictable and ailing Yeltsin was about to deliver a millennium
surprise because, significantly, he allowed Putin to preside over a
grand New Year party for the political establishment on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before that, Yeltsin had also handed over the
presidential prerogative of medal awarding to his prime minister,
hugely popular because of the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But most ordinary Russians, tired of politics after the
parliamentary elections on Dec. 19, had taken their eyes off state
affairs to concentrate on their private celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Independent NTV said Yeltsin, who in recent days has sounded
gruff-voiced but otherwise looked well, had made the decision to
retire only on Thursday, when he sent Putin, 47, to the Kremlin
party in his place.
</P>
<P>
   The president's traditional New Year speech, broadcast at
midnight, was re-recorded in haste Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Usually Russians, drinking out the old year with vodka and
drinking in the New Year with champagne, listen to the speech with
about as much attention as sated Britons watch the Queen after
Christmas dinner. But after the sensational news, Russians were
glued to their television sets when the Kremlin clock struck
twelve.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing that he was bowing out to give the younger generation
a chance, Yeltsin apologized to Russians for failing to fulfill
their dreams and take them in one leap from the grey, totalitarian
past into a bright, prosperous future.
</P>
<P>
   Given the disappointments that Russians have suffered through
the Yeltsin years, it was perhaps surprising that more people did
not express joy Friday that the sick, old man they so hated was
finally leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Some did, such as pensioner Nina Alexeyevna, who was selling
eggs and yoghurt from a table protected only by an umbrella on the
snow-swept street. ``I could have had a quiet retirement if it were
not for Yeltsin. As it is, at 61, I have to sit here in the
freezing cold until late afternoon on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good riddance to Yeltsin. I'm glad to see the back of him.''
</P>
<P>
   But others had kind words for the president as he made history
by becoming the first Russian leader to hand over power
voluntarily. ``You have to respect him for having the courage to
admit to himself his own unpopularity. It was a beautiful
gesture,'' said Dasha, an art student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not one of those who has criticized Yeltsin,'' said Vera
Belostatskaya, a doctor who unlike other interviewees was prepared
to give her full name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have supported Yeltsin all along and put my trust in him,''
she said. ``If he has chosen Putin, then now I will vote for him.
But I am sad for Yeltsin. I had hoped to see him finish his term.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Muscovites, while welcoming Yeltsin's decision and his
choice of successor, were annoyed by his timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he have to do it today?'' asked Valentina, a cook. ``Could
it not have waited until after Christmas (Russian Orthodox, from
Jan. 6-7)? To be frank with you, he has spoilt my holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Valery, an artist, saw Yeltsin's resignation as nothing more
than a ``cunning trick'' to give his chosen successor the best
possible springboard for elections which are to be held in March.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians were wandering around Friday in a state of dazed
uncertainty. ``I have mixed feelings,'' said Olga, a secretary.
``At least with Yeltsin, always `working on documents' (the
euphemism when he was ill), there was a kind of stability but now
we are going into the unknown.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 850-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
