r a BC-YELTSIN-CHRONOLOGY-IN     12-31 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-CHRONOLOGY-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YELTSIN YEARS: A CHRONOLOGY  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This convenient 300-word ``separate-buy'' compilation of outgoing
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's history is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE INDEPENDENT OF LONDON  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   June 16, 1991: Boris Yeltsin, a former member of the ruling
Politburo and ex-Communist Party boss for Sverdlovsk, becomes
Russia's first directly elected president.
</P>
<P>
   August 1991: Yeltsin plays a key role in putting down a
hard-line coup against Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   Sept 21, 1993: Yeltsin dissolves parliament, accusing deputies
of blocking reform. Tanks storm the parliament and put down a
rebellion by deputies on Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Dec 12, 1993: Voters approve a constitution giving Yeltsin
increased powers.
</P>
<P>
   Dec 11, 1994: Yeltsin sends troops to separatist Chechnya
republic to try to quell a separatist drive. The war ends in August
1996.
</P>
<P>
   December 17, 1995: Communists win more than one-third of seats
in elections to a new Duma.
</P>
<P>
   July 3, 1996: Yeltsin wins a second term in office despite
disappearing from view with recurrent heart problems. He has
quintuple bypass surgery in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   March 23, 1998: Yeltsin sacks Prime Minster Viktor Chernomyrdin
and names the youthful Sergei Kiriyenko, whose reform program
produces a $22.6 billion IMF credit package.
</P>
<P>
   Aug 17, 1998: The government is forced to let the ruble slide
and to default on some debts, triggering a severe economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Aug 23, 1998: Yeltsin sacks Kiriyenko but fails to win
parliamentary approval for Chernomyrdin. Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov takes over as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   May 12, 1999: Yeltsin sacks Primakov and names loyal top
policeman Sergei Stepashin as premier.
</P>
<P>
   Aug 9, 1999: Yeltsin sacks Stepashin, names little-known
security chief Vladimir Putin as new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Sept 1999: After bomb blasts in Russia and Islamic militant
attacks in Dagestan, Russia launches new Chechnya war.
</P>
<P>
   Dec 19, 1999: Putin's supporters perform surprisingly well in a
parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
   Dec 31, 1999: Yeltsin resigns, names Putin acting president. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this handy 300-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
