<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MET-TERROR-U.S.-840&AMP;A     12-31 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-TERROR-U.S.-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN MAN CHARGED IN TERROR PLOT IS HELD WITHOUT BOND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Algerian man arrested in Brooklyn on charges of
being part of a terrorist bomb plot was ordered held without bond
Friday in a court proceeding that otherwise offered few new details
about the suspect or his activities.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Abdel Ghani, sat quietly in a gray turtleneck
sweater as his lawyer sought unsuccessfully to have the charges
dismissed, contending that the specific acts Ghani was accused of
had not occurred in Manhattan, where the charges had been filed.
</P>
<P>
   The magistrate, Ronald L. Ellis of U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, agreed that the issue was a ``close issue,'' but sided
with the government after a prosecutor said the case was properly
charged given Ghani's flights into New York and phone calls in the
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Ghani, 31, was arrested on Thursday and accused in a criminal
complaint of being an accomplice of Ahmed Ressam, an Algerian who
was arrested at the Canadian border near Seattle in mid-December as
he tried to bring explosives and bomb components into the United
States. Ressam is believed to be part of a gangster-terrorist group
with a base in Montreal, anti-terrorism investigators have said.
</P>
<P>
   In court Friday, an assistant U.S. attorney, David N. Kelley,
revealed that Ghani, an Algerian national, had been in the United
States illegally. He said little else about Ghani, whose name and
phone number in Brooklyn were found on a scrap of paper Ressam had
when he was arrested, according to a criminal complaint filed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said in the complaint that they had tracked
Ghani's activities. FBI agents staked out his apartment building at
944 Newkirk Ave. in the Midwood section of Brooklyn, went through a
trash bin where he had discarded several documents including a
ripped up plane ticket for a flight from Seattle to New York, and
ultimately established that he had been in Seattle, waiting to meet
Ressam, between Dec. 11 and Dec. 16, according to the criminal
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint charged that Ghani had knowledge of ``a terrorist
network of Algerian nationals'' that also included Ressam, and that
Ghani was also planning to travel with Ressam to Chicago to raise
money for the group.
</P>
<P>
   After court Friday, Ghani's lawyer, Roland Thau, of the federal
defender's office, said his client would plead not guilty to the
charges, including one that contends that he supported and
concealed Ressam's effort to carry out the bomb plot and another of
credit card fraud. Thau refused further comment about Ghani's
activities or background.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery about the defendant and continuing questions about
any broader plot only underscored Friday that his arrest may signal
the beginning rather than the end of a long and far-reaching
investigation into what the authorities described as a
well-organized Algerian group with anti-American aims.
</P>
<P>
   The government, for example, has not said whether Ghani is a
member of the violent terrorist organization in Algeria called the
Armed Islamic Group. A Canadian woman arrested last month as she
crossed the border into Vermont with another Algerian man has been
described by the authorities as having ties to two members of the
Armed Islamic Group.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. intelligence official has said that the CIA's latest
assessment is still that the Armed Islamic Group, as an
organization, is not coordinating attacks against the United
States, although members of the group may be involved in carrying
out attacks on their own.
</P>
<P>
   An official has said that contingency plans to arrest Ghani had
been in place for several days. That raised the possibility that
the authorities timed Ghani's arrest to coincide with planning for
the millennium celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest came on a day when the FBI questioned, and in some
cases held, Algerian immigrants in several cities. Federal agents
indicated privately that they had intended the sweep as a warning
or deterrent to potential terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Manhattan announcing Ghani's arrest,
both the police commissioner, Howard Safir, and Lewis D. Schiliro,
the assistant director of the FBI in charge of the New York office,
opened their remarks by stressing that New York would be safe for a
festive New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   They each also repeated that there was no evidence of specific
credible threats to New York City or its environs, and Schiliro
said that no explosives or explosive devices had been found in
connection with the arrest and investigation of Ghani.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Thau challenged the evidence against Ghani, saying
there was ``not an iota of factual assertion in the complaint
showing that the defendant assisted Mr. Ressam.''
</P>
<P>
   Thau said that the detailed criminal complaint, based on an
affidavit filed by an FBI agent, ``does not even assert that the
defendant ever met Mr. Ressam or spoke with him or communicated
with him in any fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor, Kelley, disagreed, and added that Ghani had
sought to conceal his role in the plot, traveling under an assumed
name, and later destroying his airplane ticket.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Brooklyn Friday, Newkirk Avenue residents said they had
noticed what they believed to be undercover officers in the
neighborhood for at least a week. Plainclothes officers sat in
unmarked cars, they said, and a small plane even repeatedly circled
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the residents interviewed said they knew the men
apprehended _ the authorities had initially detained a total of
four men _ and believed they were innocent. They said they feared
that the arrests would only add to bias against Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are giving the impression that all Muslims are involved
in terrorism,'' said Tariq Mahood Khokhar as he walked down Newkirk
Avenue late Thursday night from his mosque. He said one of the men
taken into custody had worked at a corner convenience store and had
never been involved in any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a police state,'' Khokhar said. ``Why are they blaming
Muslims?''
</P>
<P>
   A man who answered the door at the apartment where the arrest
occurred said late Thursday night that he had no comment. The door
to the apartment _ which still had a large hole where the lock had
been ripped out _ had been propped shut.
</P>
</TEXT>
