<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3731 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-PUTIN-PROSPECTS-TOUGH     12-31 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-PROSPECTS-TOUGH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN: THE ENCHANTED WANDERER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this timely ``separate buy'' article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By VYACHESLAV KOSTIKOV  
 c.1999 Moscow News  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Vladimir Putin is Russia's Mr. Nice Guy.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone admires him. Like a young prince, he exudes the charm
of political freshness.
</P>
<P>
   Constantly on the move, this man with a sailor's gait still
appears to be shy, even though in a mere five months he has
ascended from being an unknown bureaucrat to prime minister and now
_ as of New Year's Eve _ to acting president of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   And the people's affection for the young, dynamic politician,
who is never at a loss for words, has been growing even as he has
tried to avoid being labeled a Russian hero.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has long yearned for light at the end of the tunnel, and
with Putin we have received hope that we are going to see it after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Putin, 47, a former KGB official and, more recently,
head of the domestic intelligence agency, has for months exercised
control of the military and much of the government's daily
operation, given the increasing inconsistency and infirmity of the
68-year-old Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   By now, I honestly believe, Putin is ready to work selflessly
for the good of this humiliated country.
</P>
<P>
   There are people who think that Putin's popularity is
exclusively the result of the Chechen factor _ that is, his tough
prosecution of what the Kremlin has called a ``fight against
Islamic bandits and terrorists'' in the rebellious republic of
Chechnya. I beg to differ.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is the focus of many old and new aspirations of the
Russian people: for a strong arm, for youthfulness and integrity of
political leadership, and for national revival. Liberals and
patriots, pro-marketeers and statists, rich and poor, generals and
human-rights activists are equally willing to stake their hopes on
him.
</P>
<P>
   As prime minister, Putin showed the rare talent of being all
things to all men. Placing their bets on him were men as different
as media mogul Boris Berezovsky, economic reformer Yegor T. Gaidar
and former Vice President Aleksandr Rutskoi, who led a '93 coup
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   In August, when Yeltsin _ with his corruption scandals, health
debacles and single-digit approval ratings _ abruptly named Putin
heir-apparent, it was predicted that surely this would nip Putin's
career in the bud. Actually Putin appeared to thrive on the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dec. 19, when Russia's parliamentary elections were
dominated by the new pro-government Unity political bloc, and other
candidates who backed Putin, the Kremlin has been in a state of
euphoric glee. At last it found a winner! Although Yeltsin could be
rightly criticized for a lot of things and certainly lost plenty of
authority, it must be admitted that he was determined to keep the
country under control _ indeed to his last political breath.
</P>
<P>
   To Putin's credit, however, the hoopla did not swell his head.
He seemed little inclined to overrate his own success: One has to
hand it to him. Presumably, he realized that soon enough there
would be harder things to accomplish. Now, the most difficult
questions he may be asking himself are these: What is my most
effective political resource? How long will this training flight
last? What will I have to face when I touch down?
</P>
<P>
   Being a sensible person, Putin must realize that there is a good
deal of the irrational and fairytale-like in the popular affection
for him, which is generally characteristic of the Russian people.
Putin says he will improve the people's life, and they believe him.
He says he will get the better of the Chechen rebels, and everyone
gives a cheer. He swears he will uproot corruption, and we
desperately want to take it on trust.
</P>
<P>
   Yet lurking behind Putin's sudden and effortless emergence are
some formidable problems. Suppose, as everyone is predicting, he
does win the election, which is now rescheduled for March 26, and
he becomes Yeltsin's successor?
</P>
<P>
   What will happen the day after he is installed at the Kremlin?
Who will be the first to enter his office and get down to real
work? Will he have anyone to rely on? His ``king makers,'' perhaps?
Or an enchanted nation of people who, having cast their votes, will
expect him to wave his magic wand and put all things right?
</P>
<P>
   Among the crowd of eager political associates, itching to share
the ``spoils of war'' and bust through the Kremlin gate, there are
none disinterested enough to share the burden and responsibility of
stabilizing the country.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it is one thing to say: ``I assume responsibility for
Chechnya,'' using Yeltsin's backing and power, but quite another to
run the country full-time.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Kremlin's aggressiveness in the run-up to the
December parliamentary election certainly was Putin's most
effective resource. The public was treated to a barrage of
pro-Chechen-war, pro-government, pro-Putin, anti-opposition
propaganda on the major national media outlets, which are
monopolized and controlled by the Kremlin and its allies such as
Berezovsky. But popularity cannot be kept up indefinitely by these
means alone.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, by tacitly encouraging the persecution of his
political opponents, Putin not only made powerful rivals but also
effectively brought them to a boiling point. Very soon he will need
to set efficient policies _ economic, financial, social, scientific
and cultural. Will Putin be able to mobilize the type of contacts
and resources he needs for this?
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's political demise, as well as a ``change of guard'' at
the top, will surely reanimate the political power blocs that have,
especially in recent months, been deactivated and suppressed by the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far Putin has won out because his approval ratings have
soared to a dizzy height. I am afraid that in the long term,
however, the backing of his newfound liberal Kremlin allies will
not be strong enough. Putin's political fate largely hinges on
himself. Above all, on his readiness to meet halfway those who are
currently, and somewhat artificially, presented as his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia's tradition of intrigue and ugly power politics,
even if Putin does achieve success in the presidential election, he
will have an uphill struggle lying ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1999 Moscow News &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Vyacheslav Kostikov is the former press spokesman for Russian
president Boris Yeltsin and the current Russian ambassador to the
Holy See. Kostikov's memoir, ``Parting With the President,''
recounts his three years in the Kremlin.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
