<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-Y2K-FLIGHT01-COX     12-31 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-FLIGHT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON'S Y2K CZAR ABOARD DELTA FLIGHT AS 2000 ARRIVES
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD DELTA FLIGHT 1764 _ An ebullient John Koskinen, the White
House's Y2K czar, declared victory over the Y2K bug Friday night
aboard Delta's Washington-to-New York shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen told the handful of reporters who tagged along on the
flight that he felt like he had been ``completely successful'' in
the job President Clinton gave him nearly two years ago, heading
the President's Council on Year 2000 Compliance.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that it would several days ``before it is
completely clear that the problem is fixed,'' Koskinen declared,
``We've got the systems fixed, and we've got enough information to
the public so that there has been no gratuitous reaction to create
a secondary problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen was obviously pleased with the reports coming in
throughout the day indicating virtually no problems in computers
shifting from 1999 to 2000 as the New Year dawned around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest problem I've had today has been to schedule a time
to eat,'' he said. He brought a turkey sandwich with him for the
flight and tried to eat it as he answered questions from reporters
aboard the immaculate 727 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was originally intended to demonstrate the
administration's confidence in its Y2K efforts. ``I thought it was
important for people to understand that somebody who knew about
this was willing to do that,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   But the flight became for Koskinen a ``nice respite'' from a day
of meetings and conference calls as the New Year began in the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, during the flight, he participated in yet another
conference call. Using a seatback phone, he spoke with FAA
Administrator Jane Garvey and Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater. Garvey was on a cross-country American Airlines flight, and
Slater was at the FAA Traffic Control Center in Herndon, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The conference call began at 7:05 p.m. EST, just five minutes
after the world's airlines, all of which use Greenwich Mean Time,
flew into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aviation has reached the year 2000, and I am pleased to report
to you and Secretary Slater that the nation's air-space system is
up and running safely and efficiently,'' Garvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen acknowledged that people who feared problems arising
from computer chips imbedded in thousands of different electronic
devices ``would not be on this plane with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 157-seat aircraft carried only 11 paying passengers,
including three reporters. The flight from Washington's Reagan
National Airport to New York's La Guardia is typically filled to
capacity, according to Delta officials.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Koskinen, Flight 1764 was a victory lap. Although he
said he had been warning people all day that ``it's too early to
declare victory,'' he said of his own efforts: ``I wouldn't have
done anything different.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said the success of the administration's efforts
``shows the public can handle and deal with complicated information
a lot better than people have given it credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted how only two weeks ago, news organizations were warning
of problems that ``did not materialize.'' But he acknowledged that
when he took on the job of White House Y2K czar, ``it was not clear
... that it was going to work this way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, there were people on Web sites saying it would
be impossible to solve this problem _ there would be urban riots
and it's time to buy a lot in Mexico,'' he recalled, jokingly.
``What the public wanted to know was that people were taking the
problem seriously and working to solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tapped Koskinen for the job not for his computer skills
but for his reputation as a trouble-shooter, having spent nearly
two decades overhauling financially failing corporations, among
them Penn Central Transportation Co. and Levitt and Sons.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen admitted on the Friday night flight that prior to
taking on the Y2K job, he had ``never used the computer to get on
the Internet or send e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen was met at LaGuardia airport by New York Port Authority
police with a bomb-sniffing dog. He conducted several interviews at
the airport before catching a return shuttle flight back to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As he boarded the return flight, he signed boarding passes as
souvenirs for some of the 17 passengers bound for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving back at the nation's capital, Koskinen took the subway
back to the federal government's Y2K command center. He said he
feared a taxi could not get through the crowded streets around the
Mall, the site of a huge New Year's celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
