<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-Y2K-0101-COX     12-31 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-Y2K-0101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THIRD MILLENNIUM CELEBRATIONS CAST LIGHT ON TWO MEXICOS
 &HT;    EDs: This story may be updated at 12:30 a.m. EST.
 &HT;    By FRANC CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAXACA CITY, Mexico _ As much of Mexico welcomed the Third
Millennium with fireworks, concerts and dancing, the celebration
was muted in rural areas by fear of rebel attacks and the so-called
Y2K bug's negative impact on tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in this well-known colonial city, hotel operators blamed a
drop off in tourism on international travelers _ especially those
from the United States _ over possible Y2K computer troubles.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mexico City airport director Roberto Canovas Therio
said 40 percent of flights on Dec. 31 were cancelled because of
``mostly last-minute cancellations. Many (customers) feared
traveling in airplanes that could fall victim to Y2K computer
troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, young Mexican boys in Oaxaca City celebrated the new
millennium as they do any New Year's Eve, by tossing firecrackers
in the fiesta-filled streets.
</P>
<P>
   It was a prelude to a planned massive fireworks display that
would take place over the colonial-era cathedral in the city
center, although many residents said they planned to celebrate
quietly with a traditional family New Year's Eve supper.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from the more festive atmosphere prevailing in
streets of the capital Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The historic Paseo de la Reforma, the city's main boulevard, was
filled with tens of thousands of revelers, coming to see parades
and live concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Cathedral bells rang in the main square, called the Zocalo,
where 300,000 people would turn out for shows by Mexico's famous
singer Juan Gabriel and to hear 200 mariachis sing Las Golondrinas,
a traditional song that says good-bye to the old year.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the millennium fervor, President Ernesto Zedillo, in a
video-taped address, said, ``We are a country that does not measure
our history in months or years, but in millenniums.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Mexican capital, there was little talk of Y2K computer
glitches following months of claims by government officials that
Mexico is among the most Y2K-complaint nations in the hemisphere.
It has installed computer programs to prevent banking errors, and
to keep the national stock market _ the Bolsa Mexicana de Valores _
from crashing on the new year's first day of business.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mexico's central bank has gone overboard trying to
assure Mexicans that their accounts are safe from Y2K errors, and
urging people with accounts to wait until after Jan. 1 to make
large withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing that, you will have the security of knowing your
money is safe,'' said Gilberto Cavillo, the central bank's systems
director.
</P>
<P>
   Few problems were expected in more rural areas, like Oaxaca
City, where water and electric systems rely on technology that
pre-dates computers.
</P>
<P>
   A larger concern for the government is the threat of armed
guerillas of the Popular Revolutionary Army, or EPR, in the
mountain villages of the Sierra Madre del Sur in southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily armed soldiers could be seen watching over villages near
Oaxaca City, thought to be rebel strongholds and stopping vehicles
at military checkpoints on the highways outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the government is bringing troops to indigenous
villages to stop the rebels,'' said Pedro Nava Rodriguez, director
of the Organization of Towns and Neighborhoods in Guerrero. ``But
they are violating the human rights of innocent people who have
nothing to do with guerilla struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
