<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-1STLD-WR     12-31 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S NEW PRESIDENT STEPS OUT FROM THE SHADOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (CORRECTS party name in graf begin.: ``But whether Putin...''
CORRECTS spelling of ``putsches'' in 3rd graf from end.) 
 (With RUSSIA-YELTSIN) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After the Kremlin's newborn political party registered
a thumping victory in parliamentary elections last week, reporters
asked Prime Minister Vladimir Putin whether his strengthened hand
might lead to changes in the government. Putin was
characteristically forthcoming. ``We'll see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That much Russia now sees, in spades. But in its new president's
fashion, much about the man who now runs Russia, and who seems
likely to win the suddenly scheduled election for the presidency in
March, remains behind a veil.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is extolled by admirers as the ideal man for Russia's
darkest hour. He is, they say, for a strong Kremlin, but democratic
to the marrow; dedicated to government economic controls, but
pro-market; former President Boris Yeltsin's man, but apart from
his infamous entourage of tycoons, schemers and supposed thieves.
</P>
<P>
   And that may all be true. But President Putin so far remains an
empty vessel, his public record distinguished mostly by a popular
but brutal war in Chechnya and an election victory this month
which, by most experts' reckoning, made a hash of democratic
campaign norms.
</P>
<P>
   His private record _ and much of it is private _ conceals some
15 years with the KGB, largely as an intelligence officer based in
East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to say who he is. He's just a nicely
wrapped package,'' Andre Piontkovsky, a political analyst and one
of Putin's most merciless critics, said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, he suggested, may be the kind of strongman that some
liberal and democratic reformers now say they long for: a leader
willing to wring the last czarist and Communist impulses out of the
nation so that capitalism may come to full flower.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who may know Putin best, former St. Petersburg mayor
Anatoly Sobchak, says that is simply wrongheaded.
</P>
<P>
   Sobchak taught law to Putin at Leningrad State University nearly
30 years ago, and later recruited him to a mayoral team of
democratic, pro-market activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is relying not on the army, but on political power,'' he
said in a telephone interview Friday. ``He's created his own
political party. And he is planning to work through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin certainly speaks the lines of a democratic reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Russian society does not identify a strong and
effective state with a totalitarian state,'' he wrote in a newly
published treatise on Russia at the cusp of the millennium. ``We
have come to value the benefits of democracy, a law-based state,
and personal and political freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``at the same time,'' he added in the next sentence,
``people are alarmed by the obvious weakening of state power. The
public looks forward to the restoration of the guiding and
regulating role of the state to a degree which is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciphering Vladimir Vladimirovich Putin is not made any easier
by the fact that his analysis is very likely correct on both
counts.
</P>
<P>
   Trim, blue-eyed, balding, and, at 47, resembling more an actuary
than a politician, Putin is by all counts an extremely competent,
cautious and intelligent man. Born in Leningrad, later St.
Petersburg, he graduated with honors in 1975 from Leningrad State
University's law department, where he studied economic law under
Sobchak.
</P>
<P>
   He did not become a lawyer. Instead, he joined the KGB's foreign
intelligence arm, the First Chief Directorate, and by various
reports, served in Moscow before being assigned to Dresden, then
part of East Germany, in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Officially _ and perhaps actually _ his task was to track the
political leanings of East Germans and their contacts with the
West.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, according to news reports and Sobchak, Putin was
involved in economic intelligence-gathering, perhaps the KGB's
central task in the 1980s as the Soviet economic engine began
throwing rods and lurching toward collapse.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Leningrad in 1989, speaking fluent German and
steeped in Western business knowledge, and left active KGB service
to join the university's international affairs department. Then and
now, many speculated that Col. Putin remained a KGB operative and
that his job was to monitor the city's flourishing democratic
reform movement.
</P>
<P>
   Sobchak, a leader of that movement, was by then chairman of the
Soviet equivalent of the Leningrad legislature, and he hired Putin
as an aide. When Sobchak became mayor in June 1991, Putin followed
him into city government, steadily rising to the post of first
deputy mayor.
</P>
<P>
   He was widely known then as ``the gray cardinal,'' a reference
not just to his influence but also to his penchant for remaining
out of public view. And he played a key role in bringing Western
investors to the city, signing the American firm KPMG to advise
officials on economic policy and luring Germany's BNP-Dresdner Bank
to set up offices there.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview Friday, Sergei Stepashin, a former
Russian prime minister and now a Russian parliament deputy from St.
Petersburg, said Putin had another nickname: ``Stasi,'' after the
feared East German secret service.
</P>
<P>
   ``In outside appearance, he is a calm, inconspicuous, quiet
man,'' he told the television network NTV. ``But his grip, which
was felt by all the financiers in St. Petersburg, was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sobchak lost a re-election bid in 1996, but Putin continued to
rise, apparently brought to Moscow and the Kremlin by another St.
Petersburg reformer, Anatoly A. Chubais.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's first Kremlin job was as a top aide to Pavel Borodin,
the Kremlin property manager who is now at the center of bribery
and corruption charges surrounding the vastly expensive renovation
of Yeltsin's residence and other official buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Putin rose swiftly through the ranks, first overseeing the
implementation of Yeltsin's presidential decrees, then in 1998
becoming head of the KGB's successor, the Federal Security Service,
with a mandate to focus on economic intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   By last March, he was head of Yeltsin's security council,
roughly responsible for internal security and national defense. And
on Aug. 9, he replaced Stepashin as prime minister and Yeltsin's
heir-apparent.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Putin's political potential was dismissed from the start, but
wrongly. His aggressive pursuit of the war in Chechnya, which
followed the bombings of five buildings in Moscow and other cities,
blamed on terrorists, established his image as a tough and
no-nonsense leader at a time when Russians were seeking just such a
person.
</P>
<P>
   When Putin, a refined man by any standards, pointedly said last
fall that he would wipe out Chechen rebels even if they were killed
in their toilets _ a vulgar piece of Russian army slang _ he began
to rocket upward in the polls. By this month, nearly half of the
respondents in some polls favored him as Yeltsin's successor, an
astronomical figure in a nation where a politician with a 20
percent rating is considered a comer.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Putin was the originator or the beneficiary of such
shrewdness is less easily gauged. As a politician, his record is
mixed: He was one of the leaders of Sobchak's losing mayoral
campaign, and he oversaw a lackluster parliamentary campaign there
in the mid-1990s as a local leader of the pro-Yeltsin political
party Our Home Is Russia.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As prime minister, he has benefited not just from the war and
the patriotic fervor enveloping it, but from an economic comeback
propelled by a rise in world oil prices and a devalued ruble. The
Russian media, much of it state-controlled or under the Kremlin's
sway, has been equally devoted: Putin's fondness for running and
contact sports like judo has been lovingly detailed in front-page
photos and television footage.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's new Unity party is widely agreed to have performed
so well in December's parliamentary elections because its
candidates rode the coattails of Putin's popularity and because the
Kremlin waged a war of character assassination, disinformation and
manipulation against its principal rivals.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   None of this says much about what kind of president Putin will
be when, and if, he is elected and becomes leader of a vast nation
on his own right rather than by fiat of his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Sobchak has no doubts. ``Together with Putin I went through two
putsches, in '91 and '93, and I know how he carried himself during
these trials. This is a completely courageous person on whom one
can rely and would never deceive you,'' he said. ``He does indeed
have democratic views regarding the future of the country. But he
understands very well that such a country as Russia requires strong
power. Without such a power, Russia will stop existing as a unified
state.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a senior administration official speaking on
condition of anonymity offered a Putin-esque assessment of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know him. He's a cool character. He's smart. I believe his
instincts are democratic,'' the official said. ``But we'll see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
