<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-Y2K-0101-1STLD     12-31 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-Y2K-0101-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: sub out final 2 grafs with grafs beginning 'In
Palestinian-controlled Bethlehem . . . '
 &HT;    RELIGIOUS FERVOR, HEIGHTENED SECURITY IN MIDEAST
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ New Year's Day arrived with two hallmarks of the
Middle East _ religious fervor and the security concerns that so
often accompany it.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, more than a thousand people _ Israelis,
Palestinians and foreign tourists _ cheered the new millennium and
watched small fireworks displays from the summit of the Mount of
Olives. They overlooked Jerusalem's Old City and some joked, while
toasting with champagne, that the ``messiah'' had not arrived as
some believers said he would.
</P>
<P>
   While New Year's might be just a turn of the calendar on many
lands, here it was seen in its more original form _ roughly the
anniversary of Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   There were Catholic masses in the Basilica of Gethsemane, where
Christ is believed to have sweated blood. Protestants prayed in the
Garden Tomb, where they believe Christ was crucified. A few planned
to walk with a trumpet around Jerusalem's Old City walls, calling
in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   By a quirk of fate, Friday was a holy day for all three faiths
here.
</P>
<P>
   The focus was on the small hill-top campus area known to Jews as
the Temple Mount and to Muslims as the Haram esh-Sharif. The site
is home to the rock where Jews believe God asked Abraham to
sacrifice a son and where Muslims believe the Prophet Mohammed
ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, more than 350,000 Muslims prayed there as part
of the annual holy month of Ramadan. Friday evening, hundreds of
Jews brought in the weekly Sabbath with prayers at the Wailing
Wall, a retaining wall at the base of the mount.
</P>
<P>
   But, there were also record numbers of Israeli police and
paramilitary troops on duty. About 7,000 police and 5,000 police
volunteers patrolled the night shift Friday _ more than four times
the usual amount. Many though, seemed bored, talking on mobile
phones and chatting with each other.
</P>
<P>
   In Palestinian-controlled Bethlehem, police were searching
crowds at a New Year's celebration for members of the so-called
``Concerned Christians.'' U.S. authorities reportedly believed that
members of the Denver, Colo.-based group intend to commit violence
in the Holy Land in order to hasten the return of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several hours after midnight, the lights of Jerusalem
were still shining brightly. Emergency operations officials
reported that electric, water, traffic and telephone systems were
all functioning throughout Israel. The country had made extensive
preparations to combat computer and other infrastructure problems.
No problems were reported in Palestinian areas either.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
