<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NEWYEAR-TIMESSQUARE-A     12-31 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-TIMESSQUARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TIMES SQUARE, CELEBRANTS COME EARLY, STAY LONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Story may be updated.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YEAR _ From the black drizzle of dawn until the pyrotechnic
spectacle of midnight, a mighty crush of New Year's merrymakers
welcomed the year 2000 in Times Square, the world's most famous
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by fears of terrorism or Y2K havoc, the Times Square
crowd showed every sign of being the biggest and noisiest ever,
bent on watching history happen, watching themselves on huge video
screens and hoping that friends and relatives were watching them on
television at home.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, at an early-evening briefing at the
city's command center, said that Times Square was as full at 5 p.m.
as it had been at midnight last year. ``I'm not in the business of
crowd counts,'' the mayor said. ``But the streets are pretty well
full.''
</P>
<P>
   The most die-hard of the revelers arrived a day ahead of
schedule, camping overnight in soggy cardboard huts and sleeping
bags, unmolested by battalions of police officers, in order to
stake out prime viewing spots for the party to end all parties.
</P>
<P>
   They won the bragging rights for being in Times Square at 7 in
the morning, when the year 2000 arrived in the islands of the South
Pacific, 17 time zones away. At that moment, with the sky still
dark and the streets rain-slick, the 83,000-watt Waterford crystal
ball was hoisted to the top of its tower to the strains of
Copland's ``Fanfare for the Common Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamar Stratyevskaya, 23, could have used a hot shower by then.
She had spent the night in a makeshift village of cardboard
lean-tos, just the sort of encampment mayors from coast to coast
have been trying to dismantle. She had brought soda, cookies,
noisemakers, a bottle of contraband Champagne and a quilt. When the
rain started, she moved under a movie marquee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I know thought I was crazy,'' said Ms. Stratyevskaya,
a resident of Washington Heights in upper Manhattan. ``But
actually, it's kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Other less compulsive celebrants came in waves throughout the
day: families who wanted a taste of the excitement before
nightfall, when Times Square can become a rowdy place; immigrants
eager to ring in the New Year twice, once along with their homeland
and once in their new home; and tourists and New Yorkers alike who
wedged themselves into spectator pens set up by the police to await
the midnight saturnalia.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Rogers and Troy Blakely, sweethearts living in New York for
less than a year, ventured forth from their East Side apartment
shortly before noon, the New Year in Indonesia, for a quick peek.
``We came to see it before it got crazy,'' said Ms. Rogers, a
special education teacher. ``It was a fun feeling. And someday we
can tell people we were there at 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Another New Yorker with an appetite only for a glimpse was Diane
Keller, a social worker, who had a simple game plan. She would stay
long enough to shoot one roll of film, for posterity, and then head
for the sales at Lord &AMP; Taylor. ``I wouldn't be here at night, no
way,'' Ms. Keller said. ``I'll be home in front of my fireplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosalia Aragon, with her 10-year-old son and several colleagues
from work, zipped in and out of Times Square in under two hours,
watching the New Year arrive in Southeast Asia. Then they all took
the train back to New Jersey for quiet celebrations at home.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Aragon kept the trip a secret from her mother, who thought
it was dangerous. One of her co-workers , Ed Czekaj, came despite
the objections of his wife, who hates crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this way we got both worlds,'' Czekaj said. ``Boom, boom,
just to say we were here, and then back to our families.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Aragon would have liked to see her home country, Mexico,
usher in the New Year, but that would not come until after
midnight. Kazutaka Noma and his family were luckier _ they were
able to celebrate at 10 a.m., just as his parents were popping
champagne in Japan. A hail of pink confetti, meant to resemble
cherry blossoms, rained down on Noma, a graduate student, his wife
and their 10-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By accident, an hour later, Li Zhong and Ke Xu of Raleigh, N.C.,
arrived in Times Square just as a million Chinese marked the New
Year in Tiananmen Square. ``It's incredible to be here and watching
everyone at home at the same time,'' said Li, a computer
programmer.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists, as usual, seemed to dominate the crowd, many of them
college kids doing a cold weather version of spring break in Fort
Lauderdale. Typical was a pile of five young men, who had met just
moments before but were sharing an air mattress and what smelled
suspiciously like a marijuana cigarette. They boasted of long bus
trips to New York, pockets empty of money and all-night adventures
in Harlem and Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   A quieter group was the Thompsett family from Kentucky, who were
saving money by staying in a Holiday Inn in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., and
hoping to catch a 1 a.m. train after watching the ball drop. They
reached Times Square at mid-afternoon, when spectator pens were
already full up to 47th Street. There, they claimed a spot, which
they dared not abandon, with a decent view of the ball and a
barricade to lean on when they got tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them it's going to be long and boring,'' said John
Thompsett, an Army recruiter, as his children, Aaron, 13, and
Lillian, 15, rolled their eyes. ``I'm trying to get them educated
in once-in-a-lifetime things.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Janet Mouradian, a surgical pathologist at Cornell Medical
Center and a most unlikely denizen of Times Square on this
particular night, kept herself busy editing an Armenian play,
written by her New Year's companion, Herand Markarian. Dr.
Mouradian, an Armenian immigrant, had braved this scene once
before, in 1964, her first year in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do what I enjoy in life and there's only one millennium,''
Dr. Mouradian said, undaunted by the crowded spectators' pen and
the hours of waiting, which had given her time to make new, young
friends. ``He's from Oregon,'' she said, her voice full of marvel.
``And he's from Alaska. And that one, next door, he's from Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking down on the square at intervals through the day and
evening was Peter Jennings, the anchorman for ABC-TV's 24-hour
broadcast. He would stand pressed to the bulletproof windows of the
studio, staring at the mobs below. They, in turn, would wave to
him, seeking the perfect position in front of an ABC camera so they
could simultaneously wave to the folks back home.
</P>
<P>
   The pantomime was a perfect metaphor. New Year's Eve here,
despite the extravagant performance _ dancers, puppets, souvenirs,
sound-and-light shows, commissioned by the Times Square Business
Improvement District _ is all about seeing and being seen. Thus the
run on camcorders at the electronics stores along Broadway. And the
posters (Mom, We Made It Fine, Trust Jesus, Sammy Loves Christine)
raised high to any camera nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Yury Verduga, a salesman at an electronics store, repeated a
conversation he had had dozens of times. ``Camcorder? $199? Let me
see it! OK.'' Also a fast seller, Verduga said, were disposable
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Many people came prepared with supplies to keep them
comfortable, occupied and fed: beach chairs and blankets, chess
sets and mystery novels, and munchies of all kinds. One family
turned a carton upside down to make an ad hoc picnic table, then
unpacked a loaf of bread, jars of peanut butter and jelly and a
half gallon of milk.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd for the most part was jolly. But not Shelley Brown,
from Maryland, who sat sniffling and hacking in a lawn chair,
wrapped head to toe in scarves and blankets. At her feet was an
overnight bag, stuffed with tissues and cough syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brown had come down with the flu at the most inopportune of
times. But she didn't want to disappoint her husband, Ryan. ``I've
been talking about this for the last seven years,'' he said. ``I
grew up watching Dick Clark on television and thought it would be
so cool. We had to be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-1STLD     12-31 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILLENNIUM CELEBRATIONS LINK PLANET AS Y2K FEARS ABATE
 &HT;    EDs: Writethru beginning with 3rd graf.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS and MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As clocks ticked past midnight on Friday across the
planet, billions of people from all corners of the Earth joined in
a satellite-linked celebration of a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Casting aside technical arguments that the third millennium of
the Christian Era will not actually start for another year,
hundreds of millions of people partied around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But widespread joy at the long-waited advent of the year 2000
was tempered in some places by fears of terrorism and technology
gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly 200 countries, governments, financial firms,
communications' carriers and airlines girded for signs of the
dreaded Y2K bug, which could cause computer systems to fail at the
stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications, however, suggested that the hundreds of
billions of dollars spent stamping out Y2K software bugs appear to
have paid off. As the world's computers moved smoothly through the
transition to 2000, potential problems appeared well in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money has been well spent,'' John Koskinen, the nation's
Y2K czar, said as upbeat reports about computer operations poured
into his Washington command post. As midnight struck in one country
after another around the world, no governments reported significant
problems with telecommunications systems, banks, power grids or
other vital systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Year 2000
Conversion, warned Americans not to relax entirely. The full impact
of the Y2K software flaw may not be felt until factories and
offices open for business next week.
</P>
<P>
   The nations that most worried Y2K experts _ Russia, Ukraine and
China _ appeared to have passed into the New Year with all nuclear
weapons, reactors and other vital facilities in good shape.
``Nothing out of the ordinary has been experienced,'' said Thomas
Pickering, the No. 2 official at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the tiny South Pacific island of Kiribati became the
first nation to see the dawn of the new millennium. It occurred at
5 a.m. EST. Kiribati was so intent on being the first that it
realigned its chunk of the international date line east by two
hours to stage the first ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   While Y2K seemingly fizzled out as a big news story, Russian
President Boris Yeltsin managed to startle the world on the last
day of the 20th century by choosing to resign after eight years as
leader of the world's largest country.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the New Year's Eve ceremonies, world leaders paused to pay
tribute to Yeltsin's key role in stage-managing the collapse, after
more than 70 years, of the communist-led Soviet Union and his
championing of market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's capital, President Clinton opened the extended
ceremonies on the National Mall during the morning, spoke to
children and to diplomats in the afternoon, and then hosted
millennial ceremonies late in the evening and into New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   In his New Year's Eve remarks, Clinton returned to a favorite
theme: the need for national unity to promote racial harmony.
Citing the legacy of Abraham Lincoln, Clinton said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us pledge that each year will be closer to this, our
founding principle. Let us pledge that the new millennium will
bring, in the words of the great emancipator, 'a new birth of
freedom.'''
</P>
<P>
   The first family also hosted a special millennial dinner for
more than 300 VIP guests at the White House, followed by a
celebrity-studded gala and a huge fireworks display at the Lincoln
Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with a 95-year tradition, the single largest party in
the United States took place in New York's Times Square, where
hundreds of thousands of exuberant people gathered for a
24-hour-long millennium gala that went forward amid a large police
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Atlantic, Britain's Queen Elizabeth II served as the
guest of honor at a so-called ``Millennium Dome Party,'' held under
the largest roof in the world at a newly built futuristic $1.2
billion edifice south of London.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated two million people lining the river banks, the
heart of the city appeared ablaze with thousands of flaming
beacons. Hours before a 200-foot ``River of Flames''' was set to
sweep down the River Thames at midnight, in a fireworks display
visible from space, police shut two London bridges to traffic
because of the crush of people pouring into the center of the
venerable British capital.
</P>
<P>
   The London festivities were to have included rides on the
world's largest Ferris wheel, but at the last moment the
450-foot-high wheel was declared unsafe for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   One time zone earlier, across the English Channel, the
millennial countdown clock on the Eiffel Tower, which had been
running steadily for 1,000 days, suddenly stopped five hours before
Paris ushered in the new year. A light rain failed to halt what has
been called the ``ultimate block party'' on one of the world's most
famous boulevards _ the Champs Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   In Vatican City, St. Peter's Square was packed with the
faithful. They held a candlelight vigil while listening to Pope
John Paul II issue his first blessing of the new millennium in a
halting voice just after the stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 arrived in Bethlehem on the wings of 2,000 doves
released on the stroke of midnight in Manger Square. A huge crowd
gathered to celebrate both the New Year and the Palestinian control
of Bethlehem, the biblical birthplace of Jesus 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei issued a New
Year's Eve call for the destruction of Israel, as millions
nationwide held rallies to protest Jewish control of Jerusalem on
what Iranians call Al-Quds Day. Al-Quds is the Arabic name for
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Pyramids, built more than two millennia before Christ,
served as the focal point of Egypt's New Year's celebrations.
Lasers lit the ancient funerary monuments while hard rock music
blasted across the desert under the watchful eye of security guards
mounted on camels.
</P>
<P>
   Muscovites celebrated New Year's Eve eight hours ahead of
Washington time after learning earlier in the day that Yeltsin had
resigned. Accepting the news in their stride, hundreds of thousands
of Russians threw vodka-fuelled parties near the blazing lights of
the Kremlin's onion domes.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military leaders said the country's nuclear missiles
were safe from any potential Y2K computer glitches. Meantime, a
joint American-Russian task force uneventfully monitored the
strategic polar scene from an air force base in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   At the Great Wall of China, revelers in the world's most
populous nation lit up the clear night skies with fireworks and
dragon dancers weaved through the ancient parapets that stretch
across China.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese President Jiang Zemin, who heads an officially atheistic
regime, touched on religion in a televised address he delivered
moments before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight the people of all countries of the world, whether in
the east, west, north or south, regardless of their nationalities
and faiths, are elated over the arrival of this historic moment,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   There had been fears of terrorist attacks throughout the world.
But the only terrorist activity came when five hijackers freed all
155 hostages aboard an Indian Airlines plane in Afghanistan after
India released two Muslim militants and an Islamic cleric, ending a
crisis that began on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   At the bash in Washington, enormous crowds gathered for a
fireworks-studded evening of entertainment led by movie stars and
musical artists. The carefully choreographed show called for the
president and a group of children, at precisely 10 seconds before
midnight, to light a fuse at the base of the Lincoln Memorial that
would travel across the reflecting pool in a spout of fireworks to
the base of the Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The final ``Midnight Moment,'' held amid extraordinarily tight
security precautions, required 3,120 hours of preparation, 15 days
to set up, 135 miles of wiring, 26 pyrotechnists and 188 firing
cues.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different sort of technological challenge that, five
years ago, caused the Gartner Group, a technology research firm, to
forecast that it would cost Americans as much as $600 billion to
fix computer programs that read two-digit ``00'' dates as 1900
instead of 2000 in the trillions of lines of code that make up
systems controlling everything from airplane traffic to banking
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, many computer experts feared programmers would not
be able to complete the job by 2000, especially in poorer
countries. But international cooperation appears to have paid off,
with richer countries helping poorer ones move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the firm's prediction proved to be well off the
mark: The Department of Commerce currently estimates U.S. costs at
about $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass can be reached by e-mail at:
andyg(at)coxnews.com. Marilyn Geewax can be reached at:
mgeewax(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-1STLD     12-31 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-MAIN-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILLENNIUM CELEBRATIONS LINK PLANET AS Y2K FEARS ABATE
 &HT;    EDs: Writethru beginning with 3rd graf.
