Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Y2K Conversion,
briefs reporters in Washington on Friday. The hundreds of billions
of dollars spent stamping out Y2K software bugs appear to have paid
off, with the world's computers moving smoothly through the
transition to 2000. ``The money has been well spent,'' Koskinen
said. (Rick McKay/The Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MOSCOW -- Dec. 31, 1999 -- RUSSIA-REACT-2 -- Valentina
V. Paranina, 62, a vendor for 46 years in what used to be GUM, the
glum Soviet state department store on Red Square, tends to
customers on Friday. ``We've needed this for a long time,'' said
Mrs. Paranina about Russian President Boris Yeltsin's resignation
on Friday. ``What was he doing already? Nothing. He was old and
sick and did nothing.'' (Jacqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MOSCOW -- Dec. 31, 1999 -- RUSSIA-REACT -- ``Boris
Nikolayevich can't spoil our mood today,'' exulted Mikhail, 39,
right, a mathematician who refused to give his last name as he
joked with friends at an outdoor stand on New Year's Eve,
traditionally Russia's most thoroughly celebrated holiday. Without
Yeltsin, Mikhail continued, ``things definitely won't get worse.''
If Russian President Boris Yeltsin really meant it about being
forgiven for his mistakes when he made the stunning announcement of
his resignation on Friday, as far as many people on the streets of
Moscow were concerned, he needn't have bothered. (Jacqueline Mia
Foster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 31, 1999 -- NEWYEAR-NY-POLICE -- Police
secure a barricade on Times Square, Friday. Some 37,000 police
officers were deployed throughout the city to help maintain order
as New Yorkers rang in the year 2000. (Keith Meyers/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
