<HEADLINE>
BANK EMPLOYEES HELD HOSTAGE IN ROBBERY ATTEMPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRAD COOPER, MATT STEARNS and RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ Two female robbers held between four and six bank
employees hostage Friday night in a botched heist, as more than 50
FBI agents and Olathe police officers surrounded the bank.
</P>
<P>
   About 9 p.m. _ four hours into the ordeal _ two women left the
bank. One was a freed hostage, leaving three to five hostages in
the bank. The other woman re-entered the bank. Authorities did not
know whether she was a robber or a hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Police had made phone contact with the robbers, but declined to
describe the robbers' state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting demands,'' said Lt. Larry Griffin of the
Olathe Police Department. ``We're just trying to get them to come
out without hurting anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were called to the Bank of America at 175 N.
Clairborne Road in Olathe at about 5 p.m. after a phone call to
police from inside the bank.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Jeff Lanza said the robbery was interrupted by the
arrival of Olathe police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did try to rob the bank,'' Lanza said. ``There's no
indication it's related to Y2K or terrorism or anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanza said he had heard reports that a shot was fired about 5:15
p.m. inside the bank, but could not confirm them.
</P>
<P>
   SWAT teams from the Olathe Police Department and the FBI
surrounded the bank as the sun set on 1999 _ a year that saw a
record-breaking 71 bank robberies in the Kansas City metro area.
</P>
<P>
   But this bank robbery attempt was unique in two ways _ hostages
were taken for the first time in at least nine years, and the
robbers were women, Lanza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a blue moon we get a female bank robber,'' Lanza said.
``I don't remember having two female bank robbers in Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Lights on the side and front of the bank were cut off about 6:45
p.m. so police and FBI teams could take positions without being
seen by anyone inside the bank.
</P>
<P>
   But police said there were no immediate plans to storm the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're confident nobody's being hurt,'' Griffin
said, ``we'll keep talking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
