<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-TAX-TRUCE-KAN &LR;      12-31 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-TRUCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT TO LIMIT TAX INCENTIVES FALLS BY THE WAYSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRAD COOPER and MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City-area leaders are scrapping an
ineffective truce designed to discourage local governments from
using tax incentives to entice businesses from neighboring cities.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, brokered by the Mid-America Regional Council
nearly three years ago, was touted as a treaty to curb
cross-boundary business raids. Nineteen cities and five counties
adopted the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kansas City Metropolitan Alliance for Economic
Cooperation has done little to limit tax breaks, because businesses
are savvy at playing growth-hungry communities against each other
to get incentives.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, area politicians and economic development officials
are not extending the truce, which expires today.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is here on paper is a soft agreement,'' said David Warm,
executive director of the MARC. ``As soft as the agreement was, it
was very hard to get to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   While forging the agreement, many leaders balked at provisions
that would have required cities to conduct a cost-benefit analysis
of tax breaks and to share information regarding incentives offered
to companies.
</P>
<P>
   Olathe, Kan., for example, did not join in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Olathe Mayor Larry Campbell said the goals of the agreement did
not mesh well with what his city has been trying to accomplish. His
city gave out 15 tax abatements between 1993 and 1998 in hopes of
building up a commercial tax base to help support public services
demanded by booming residential growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a mode where we've got to attract commercial
business, and the tax incentives that we offer is the way we do
it,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could get everyone to do away with abatements, we
should,'' Campbell said. ``If (the agreement) would have achieved
that, then that's a whole different story. But it wasn't going to
achieve it. It wasn't practical.''
</P>
<P>
   Development lawyer Charles Miller said the agreement did not
have a noticeable impact on how cities dealt with businesses
regarding tax incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had anybody say to me, `We're not going to do this
or that because of this agreement,' '' Miller said. ``I've never
had anybody bring it up as part of our discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cities would contact other cities when a company was about
to relocate and receive tax breaks, Miller said, but that was ``to
minimize the appearance of plundering another city's tax base.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Miller said such a limited metropolitan area agreement
could not eliminate a bigger issue - the use of tax breaks in
cities across the country. He said the only resolution is a
``global settlement'' at the federal level that restricts the use
of tax breaks nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The MARC-brokered agreement did not prohibit cities from
offering tax breaks, but it encouraged leaders to share information
about incentives awarded throughout the metropolitan area. Many
leaders said they thought that the MARC would collect and compile
that data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policies are great, but unless there's some accountability to
make sure you're following them and measuring them, I am not sure
it was very valuable time that was spent discussing it in cities
around the area,'' said Overland Park, Kan., City Council President
Greg Musil.
</P>
<P>
   Warm said the agreement had not been intended to set standards
or set up MARC as a clearinghouse for information.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement's simple rules urged cities to talk to each other,
to put economic-development policies in writing, to analyze the
effectiveness of incentives and to create an annual report of tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Cities interpreted those rules differently. Some cities filed
copies of their economic policies in MARC's office, while others
maintained their own records.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, which has been the area's most aggressive purveyor
of tax breaks as it attempts to rebuild older parts of the city,
simply did not provide information to MARC. Instead, the city kept
records on file with each agency that handles tax incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Manager Bob Collins said the agreement was only
marginally effective because corporate executives shop to find the
biggest tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Farmland Industries Inc. is building a new
headquarters near Kansas City International Airport. The
farmer-owned cooperative considered sites on the Kansas side of the
state line before accepting a package of tax breaks worth about $10
million from Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox Electric, now called Airsys ATM Inc., reviewed proposals
from Lee's Summit and Shawnee, Kan., before leaving Kansas City for
a new tax-abated building in Shawnee.
</P>
<P>
   Shawnee also gave $1.5 million in tax incentives for Harte Hanks
Kansas City to move its office space from Lenexa and Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Before the MARC-brokered metropolitan area agreement, Lenexa
City Administrator David Watkins said Missouri cities would send
letters directly to Lenexa businesses encouraging them to move
across the state line. Since the MARC agreement, Watkins said, that
practice has stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But Watkins said there's not much that can be done if cities
want to use tax breaks in hopes of building their tax base.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just come to accept it and hope in the long run that
communities...quit relying on incentives as much as they have,''
Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's Summit Mayor Karen Messerli noted that her city,
Independence and Blue Springs have an agreement not to actively
recruit businesses away from one another.
</P>
<P>
   Messerli also questioned MARC's ability to hold cities
accountable throughout the wider metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the enforcement?'' Messerli asked. ``Where's the
ability that MARC has to hold someone accountable and say, `You did
not live up to the terms of this agreement'?''
</P>
<P>
   In light of such skepticism, MARC officials have concluded that
the agreement should expire today without follow-up studies. Warm
said the group might reconsider the issue of incentives at a later
date, but the study is not a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much a non-issue as it's not a front-and-center
issue,'' Warm said. ``The concept of an agreement has taken us as
far as we could go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
