<HEADER>
A3863 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-Y2K-AWARDS-KAN &LR;      12-31 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-AWARDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K WATCH: HIGHLIGHTS AS THE BUG BITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so this isn't the Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   But after covering this year 2000 thing for nearly 17 months,
it's time for the first and only Bug Bite Highlights, our way of
drawing attention to the good, bad and indifferent of the Y2K
world.
</P>
<P>
   Here goes:
</P>
<P>
   Lamest excuse to cloak concerns about Y2K...
</P>
<P>
   Goes to eBay, the online auction site. This notice was posted on
the Web site this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``The eBay system will be unavailable ... from 23:00 PST,
Friday, Dec. 31, to 03:00 PST, Saturday, Jan 1. During this
downtime, we will perform routine maintenance on the database.''
</P>
<P>
   Most off-the-wall Y2K prediction...
</P>
<P>
   Goes to Gary North, a Tyler, Texas, Christian-oriented historian
and poster boy of the Y2K doomer crowd. In a Jan. 7, 1999, online
interview in which he questioned himself, and provided his own
answers, North said:
</P>
<P>
   Q. You're saying that all production will stop (because of Y2K
problems)?
</P>
<P>
   A. Close enough to ``all'' to threaten your life and the lives
of a billion or more people. ... I worry about the industrial
world. ... Two billion people could die.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst financial advice...
</P>
<P>
   Goes to Y2K doom-and-gloom author Jim Lord, a Maryland software
consultant and author of A Survival Guide for the Year 2000
Problem. Here's his stock market advice from March 1998:
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is too significant that there will be serious, even
terrible, problems with the stock market and the economy in
general. I think the prudent person should get out. And I think
Dec. 31, 1998, is the latest point in time to pull the plug.''
</P>
<P>
   The market has since risen more than 2,300 points _ about 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The ``why hurry?'' award...
</P>
<P>
   Goes to Microsoft Corp., which posted a Y2K fix for Microsoft
Excel 2000, a popular spreadsheet program used by millions of
computer owners, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Best-tasting glitch...
</P>
<P>
   Goes jointly to gift merchant Harry and David, and gift
recipient Teddi Oppenheimer of Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Writes Oppenheimer:
</P>
<P>
   ``Had my first Y2K glitch _ and it isn't even 2000! Got a Harry
and David gift package for Christmas and a package of nuts was
included. On the back of the package it said, `Use by July 1900.' I
took a chance and ate them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst economic prediction...
</P>
<P>
   Goes to Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank
Securities, for this report from March 1998:
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is that we're going to suffer a year of
technological disruptions, followed by a decade of depression. ...
We're likely to be living in an environment much like the Third
World countries some of us have visited, where nothing works
particularly well.''
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni also gave his Y2K stock prediction for late 1999 and
early 2000 (note: the Dow on Friday closed at 11,497):
</P>
<P>
   ``A possible recession that would drag the market back down to
6,500 sometime in 1999 or early 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Y2K hypester of the year...
</P>
<P>
   Goes to Mike Adams of the Y2kNewswire. From the beginning, Adams
and his followers have been convinced there is a conspiracy to keep
the truth from the American people. Although earnest, Adams began
each Y2K dispatch from a point of view and then tried to make the
facts fit.
</P>
<P>
   At his zenith, he accused Kansas City's Mid-America Regional
Council of orchestrating a conspiracy to block NBC from airing
``Y2K: The Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   He also gave those conducting countless Y2K studies far too much
credit for the ability to sway public opinion and promote hidden
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Bungled information
</P>
<P>
   The National Emergency Number Association put an undue scare
throughout the country in the final months of the year when it
released a study to the White House saying only half of the
nation's emergency 911 call centers were ready for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Not true.
</P>
<P>
   The study, a simple, two-question Internet poll that went to
less than half the call centers, was poorly handled, admitted the
organization's executive director. Nonetheless, the results were
picked up without question by major news outlets and sparked many
cities to re-evaluate 911 readiness.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll, released Dec. 15, contacted nearly every one of
the nation's 4,300 call centers and shows 98 percent are prepared
to provide enhanced services.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up is the U.S. Navy, which released a study saying
many major cities were unprepared for Y2K. Again, the methodology
was flawed. The study assumed that in cases where researchers could
get no information, the city was ill-prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Shame-on-you award...
</P>
<P>
   Goes to all the freeze-dried food peddlers who took Y2K for a
profitable ride. After decades without a major disaster to energize
their industry, the pinto-bean and powdered-drink set seized on Y2K
to make bucks. It happened in Kansas City, and it happened across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Best prediction about Y2K...
</P>
<P>
   Again goes to economist Yardeni. In qualifying his March 1998
prediction of a stock crash, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Might I be wrong about all of this? Absolutely!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
