<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3864 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-STOCKCERTIFICATE-HIST     12-31 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKCERTIFICATE-HISTORY-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Stock certificates, now a dying breed, have a fascinating history  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1972, author and business journalist Bob Tamarkin got this
idea of writing a book about stock certificates, those often
elaborately engraved and decorated pieces of paper showing we own a
piece of corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until last year that Tamarkin and co-author Les
Krantz, along with stock certificate dealer George LaBarre,
actually got around to taking on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The result is The Art of the Market, an informative and
sometimes fascinating look at the history of designing and
producing stock certificates, which in our computerized age are on
the brink of becoming extinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies no longer issue stock certificates,'' Tamarkin
said. ``Instead they issue electronic `book entries.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The pieces of paper provide a unique glimpse of corporate
America. For instance, during this country's great Industrial Age,
some stock certificates depicted great columns of black, billowing
smoke. Now, Tamarkin said, stock certificates are environmentally
sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Most early certificates reflected only shades of grays, blacks
and browns. But after the Civil War and then the Gilded Age, they
became more colorful and elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Large-scale interest in stock certificates as collectible items
first took off in Europe in the late 1970s, mostly in Switzerland
and Germany. Next came England. As supplies tightened there,
European dealers turned their eyes toward the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Factors that determine the value of a certificate, besides
supply and demand, the book states, include condition, age,
historical significance, aesthetics, the type of company, the type
of engraving process and the quality of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Another whole aspect to the collectibility of a security is
signatures, Tamarkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes some of these particularly valuable is the
signature of some of the great capitalistic titans of America,''
Tamarkin said. ``Plus, some of the designs are magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   Many also reflect changing social mores. For instance, when
Playboy founder Hugh Hefner was running his empire, stock
certificates for Playboy Enterprises showed a reclining nude.
</P>
<P>
   Once his daughter, Christie Hefner, took over, the certificates
were changed to show a robed woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an example of social sensitivity,'' Tamarkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that determines value is scarcity. For instance,
many of the certificates for Chicago area companies from the 1840s,
1850s and 1860s are scant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Great Chicago Fire in 1871, a lot of them burned,''
Tamarkin said. ``Today many of them are difficult to find.''
</P>
<P>
   The record price for a certificate for an American company is
thought to be $33,000, one bought by an American collector for the
Bank of North America. The certificate, dated June 7, 1783, is
thought to be the nation's oldest existing stock certificate.
</P>
<P>
   So does Tamarkin think his book will send people scurrying to
their attics, hunting through Grandpa's old trunk?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early yet to tell,'' Tamarkin said. ``There aren't a
lot of collectors worldwide, but it's starting to catch on. It's
still relatively cheap to start a collection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
