<HEADLINE>
ANNOUNCEMENT ON MERGER OF KCP&AMP;L, WESTERN RESOURCES COULD BE MADE
SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An announcement about the fate of the
problem-plagued merger of Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. and Western
Resources Inc. _ possibly even to kill the deal _ could be made in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Both Western Resources and KCP&AMP;L have the option to undo the
merger because it wasn't completed by midnight New Year's Eve.
Western Resources said it wouldn't stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to do the deal,'' said Michel' Philipp, a
spokeswoman for Topeka, Kan.-based Western Resources.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L was more circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only comment I can give is that the board will carefully
examine all of KCP&AMP;L's options ... consistent with KCP&AMP;L's
obligations under the merger agreement,'' said Phyllis Tilden, a
KCP&AMP;L spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L shareholders who called the utility in recent days asking
for an update were told to call back next week, when more could be
said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, which the utilities have been trying to complete
since early 1997, has been dogged in the past year by the plunging
price of Western Resources. Shares in Western Resources this week
dropped to their lowest level since the deal was announced, closing
Friday at 16 15/16, down 3/16. The stock had traded in the mid-40s.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in KCP&AMP;L closed Friday at 22 1/16, up 1.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal had closed Friday, KCP&AMP;L shareholders would have
received about a third less than they were originally told to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L management cashed out most of its stock options when the
stock price was near 30.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L and Western Resources have two options to end the merger
without penalties. Under the first choice, the board of either
company would vote to end the merger if the deal wasn't completed
by Dec. 31. If they wanted to continue the merger, they would do
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The second opportunity to cancel would probably come early this
year, just before the deal closes, and would allow the merger to be
dismantled if Western's stock price drops below $29.79.
</P>
<P>
   For some frustrated KCP&AMP;L shareholders, the time has come to
make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to complete it or get out,'' said Stuart Johnson, a
KCP&AMP;L shareholder. ``I'm for getting out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
