<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUGAR ADDS THE SPICE TO THE BOWL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ They are the first college football matchups of
the 21st century, these eight remaining bowl games. All of them
promise to be entertaining, but only one will decide the national
title: the Sugar Bowl on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech defensive end Corey Moore has already predicted
the upset of top-ranked Florida State by his No. 2-ranked Hokies in
the Bowl Championship Series title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt we will win,'' said Moore, this season's
Lombardi Award winner as the nation's best lineman. ``It's been a
dream season. It's going to be even better after we win and burn
down New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   But before those 11-0 teams match up, 12 teams square off
Saturday and two more Sunday for big bowl payouts and with the
hopes of moving up in the final polls. The best game of the first
day of 2000 should be the last one, when Alabama (10-2) meets
Michigan (9-2) in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson Tide overcame a preseason sexual harassment
controversy involving Coach Mike DuBose and an early loss to
Louisiana Tech to win the Southeastern Conference and a berth in
one of the coveted BCS games.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Alabama guaranteed $11 million to $13 million (the
per-team payout in the BCS bowls), but reaching the Orange Bowl
demonstrates that the Crimson Tide is back among the elite after
coming off probation imposed by the NCAA. Michigan quarterback Tom
Brady, coming off his second consecutive 2,000-yard passing season,
will have help from running back Anthony Thomas, who has gained
more than 100 yards in each of his last five games.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Michigan wins will depend on how it handles Alabama
running back Shaun Alexander, who gained 1,383 yards in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Shaun Alexander very well,'' Michigan Coach Lloyd Carr
said. ``We recruited him at Michigan, and I've had a number of
people tell me that he is the best back in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The other big-money game Saturday is the Rose Bowl, where the
Heisman Trophy winner, Ron Dayne, and Wisconsin (9-2) take on
Stanford (8-3). The Badgers are trying to become the first Big Ten
team to win consecutive Rose Bowls _ they beat UCLA last January,
38-31, behind Dayne's 246 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just one of the best backs to play in a long time,''
Stanford Coach Tyrone Willingham said. ``He has the size, speed and
ability to anticipate running lanes. That's what really separated
him from the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   As if stopping the 253-pound Dayne is not enough of a challenge,
the Cardinal apparently lost an integral part of its offense when
the all-American wide receiver Troy Walters dislocated his wrist
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, Nebraska (11-1) plays Tennessee (9-2) in the
Fiesta Bowl, the same game in which the Volunteers capped an
undefeated 1998 season by beating Florida State for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Tee Martin, Tennessee's senior quarterback,
will try to finish his career with a 22-2 record. Coach Frank
Solich will try to recall the Huskers' winning tradition. After
being picked by the legendary Tom Osborne to replace him as
Nebraska coach in 1998, Solich led his first team to an
unsatisfying 9-4 record. Big Red fans were not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but that's also why you go to Nebraska, because
there are those expectations,'' tight end Tracey Wistrom said.
``There'd be a lot of schools out there that would be happy with a
9-4 record. They'd think of it as a pretty successful season. But
in Nebraska, you're going to be looked upon as not very
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The early matchups, Purdue (7-4) versus Georgia (7-4) in the
Outback and Georgia Tech (8-3) against Miami (8-4) in the Gator,
feature intriguing quarterback duels.
</P>
<P>
   In the Outback, Purdue's Drew Brees will face off against one of
his probable challengers for the 2000 Heisman Trophy in Quincy
Carter. In the Gator, Joe Hamilton of Georgia Tech, the runner-up
to Dayne in the Heisman voting, might face the heralded freshman
Ken Dorsey, who is 3-0 after replacing the injured Kenny Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   In the Citrus Bowl, Florida (9-3) will try to snap a two-game
losing streak and calm its volatile coach, Steve Spurrier, while
Michigan State (9-2) seeks its first victory for a new coach. Bobby
Williams replaced Nick Saban in December after Saban took the head
job at Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, in the Cotton Bowl, Texas (9-4) takes on a former
rival from the defunct Southwest Conference, Arkansas (7-4). The
Longhorns had a major disruption in their preparation when Coach
Mack Brown suspended four players for the game late Thursday for
violating team rules, including the senior defensive lineman Aaron
Humphrey and the junior wide receiver Kwame Cavil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just held a team meeting, which was one of the most
emotional that I have experienced,'' said Brown, who was shaken and
tearful at a late-night news conference. ``This was the hardest
thing I have ever had to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
