<HEADER>
A3871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ARSONIST-RAP-REVIEW-A     12-31 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARSONIST-RAP-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPPERS WHO WON'T LET THE AUDIENCE BE LAZY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q-Unique, one of the rappers in the Bushwick-based Arsonists
crew, was home after a European tour, and he wasn't going to suffer
a bland reception. ``You paid some good money to see a show,'' he
urged the crowd Wednesday night at S.O.B.'s. ``Be part of the
show!''
</P>
<P>
   The fans soon complied. Q-Unique's command came in the middle of
the show's ``beat machine'' segment, in which the group's five
rappers create the sound of a percussion section, augmented by the
audience's singing. The first round hardly resonated, but the
second shook the room. The only surprise was that it took taunting
to get the response.
</P>
<P>
   The Arsonists hungrily absorb the energy generated by audience
participation, using banter and improvisation to cultivate the
excitement of a house party. At S.O.B.'s, the rappers were looser
than usual, often stopping in midsong to exchange barbs or rant.
But these pauses were part of the fun in routines that never quite
ended up where they started.
</P>
<P>
   Known for silly skits like ``Rhyme Time Traveler,'' in which
Q-Unique dons different hats and necklaces to enact a history of
rap, and ``Hip Hop Aerobics,'' a fancy term for getting everyone to
jump around, the Arsonists play the most boisterous, popular kids
in school. The crew's rapping style seamlessly connects to this
image; the quintet usually raps its choruses in unison, with
individual members trading verses with sparring grace.
</P>
<P>
   Their styles varied, from the smooth and mellow tone of Swel
Boogie to the freneticism of D-Stroy, whose approach recalled
another comical Latin artist, John Leguizamo. During ``Lunchroom
Take-Out,'' a boasting match between Swel Boogie and the guest
rapper Great Scott, D-Stroy occasionally burst through the banter
with hilarious off-color exclamations.
</P>
<P>
   DJ Daddy Dogg gently worked the turntables during the Arsonists'
set, showing skills but sometimes seeming overwhelmed. It isn't
easy to keep up with so much verbal gunfire. Spinning for the
opening act, Non-Phixion, DJ Eclipse had more room to create
intriguing soundscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Arsonists, Non-Phixion espouses an approach that values
complicated rhyming over easy hooks and live charisma over studio
wizardry. In between those acts, two members of the veteran Cold
Crush Brothers performed a short set, reinforcing another tenet of
underground hip-hop: that the culture's original passions, from
break-dancing to the hearty raps of such early performers, are
still the most potent. The infectious joy of the Arsonists did much
to fortify that message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 2324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991231.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NEWYEAR-RIO-1STLD-WRI     12-31 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-RIO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES ON THE BEACH, THEN PIOUS REFLECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS fireworks in 11th graf) 
 (rk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The land that made Carnival and the samba art forms loves
nothing more than a party. So the beginning of the 2000s in Rio de
Janeiro turned into what authorities proudly called the largest
celebration in Brazilian history: an estimated 3.5 million people
lining Copacabana, Ipanema and more than 25 miles of other beaches
in an event that blended the spiritual and the profane.
</P>
<P>
   For believers of Candomble, Brazil's home-grown mixture of
Catholicism and African-derived animist beliefs, New Year's Eve is
traditionally the feast day of Iemanja, the fair-skinned goddess of
the sea who appears in the guise of the Virgin Mary and is
considered the mother of all living things. Beaches are always
packed with worshipers who come to seek her blessing on that night,
but with the celebration of the millennium, everything that has
gone on in the past was multiplied.
</P>
<P>
   The day had been cloudless and sunny; the hottest of the summer
so far. Rio's beaches were crowded with sunbathers, surfers and
volleyball and paddleball players.
</P>
<P>
   But as the sun dipped over Gavea Peak and sank into the sea, the
sportsmen retired, a cooling breeze appeared and individuals,
couples and entire families began emerging from apartments,
restaurants, buses or the subway and streaming to the shore.
</P>
<P>
   To turn away from the sea was to glimpse silhouetted figures
clinking their glasses, dancing and kissing as they watched the
goings-on from the verandas of million-dollar apartments in
Ipanema.
</P>
<P>
   At the water's edge, though, the scene was largely one of piety,
as devotees of Iemanja stood quietly, their heads bowed and arms
outstretched, and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women alike were dressed entirely in white in deference
to Iemanja. Many of the bouquets of roses, lilies, carnations and
gladioli they carried also were white, and were ceremoniously
thrown into the Atlantic as offerings to the goddess. Other
worshipers tossed wads of money or even pieces of jewelry into the
sea in her honor, or let the waves wash over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new millennium, a new start,'' said Maria Zenaida Rodrigues
Alves as she emerged soaked from the surf. ``I have washed away my
sins and the Lady of the Sea has made me a new person.''
</P>
<P>
   Delia Correia Costa put it another way: ``If we cleanse
ourselves at the start of this new millennium, then maybe the world
can also be cleansed and we can usher in an era of universal peace
and harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar celebrations were going on in other cities along
Brazil's 4,000 miles of coastline, but Copacabana was clearly the
focal point of the nation's celebration.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen cruise ships and assorted yachts and sailboats
floated just offshore, hundreds of jet-setters and political
dignitaries joined President Fernando Henrique Cardoso in a special
tent set up at Fort Copacabana, and some of Brazil's most renowned
pop music stars performed on stages that had been erected at four
points along the beach. &UR;  &LR; To cap things off, an ornate 20-minute
fireworks display began prompt- ly at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the working poor, though, the night was primarily a
chance to make a little money. They circulated among the revelers,
selling coconuts, ears of corn, beer, soft drinks and even bottles
of Champagne. ``Whether it is 1999 or 2000, I still have to put
food in the mouths of my children,'' said Jose Ovidio Ramos
Mendonca, a vendor of grilled meats. ``I can always rest
tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-99 2329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
