<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN ADS, CANDIDATES' GLOVES STAY ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a new commercial running in early primary states this past
week, Gov. George W. Bush comes out squarely in favor of phonics.
``See,'' he explains, ``I believe every child can learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's two leading rivals for the Republican presidential
nomination, Sen. John McCain and Steve Forbes, as well as Vice
President Al Gore, unveiled spots this week in which they reaffirm
their vows to continue sending monthly government checks to retired
people.
</P>
<P>
   And in a new infomercial-length advertisement on cable channels
in Iowa, Bill Bradley lays out a major rationale for his challenge
to Gore for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be president of the United States,'' Bradley says,
``in order to use the power of that office to do good.''
</P>
<P>
   Few in the political world can recall a competitive primary
season in which the candidates were so eager to spend so much to
say so little. Fearful, it seems, of being labeled the first to
``go negative'' with advertising, and thus draw the enmity of a
public that is perceived to be fed up with divisive messages, the
candidates are spending millions of dollars on a cautious, fiercely
noncombative television campaign that is relentlessly
uncontroversial and, in the eyes of many who are watching it, more
than a little dull.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sort of heightened civility this year, not only in
the ads but also in the discourse in general,'' said Lynn Vavreck,
an assistant professor of government at Dartmouth College in
Hanover, N.H., who worked on the staff of Dan Quayle's
vice-presidential campaign in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Vavreck has noticed, too, that the positions staked out in the
television advertisements in New Hampshire are largely of the
don't-step-on-any-toes variety. ``They talk about things that
nobody can be against,'' she said. ``Even when they do talk about
issues, they say, `I want to improve education.' Well, is that a
position? Who's against teaching kids to read?''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the various candidates point out that the political
season is still young. The tenor of the commercials in the early
primary states, they say, could quickly grow sharper. In fact, as
the campaigns gear up next week with the beginning of the new year
_ one campaign estimates that television spending in Iowa and New
Hampshire by candidates of both parties may total $6 million in
January _ the media strategists are behaving like anxious generals,
wondering whether the sniper fire begins just over the next ridge.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of just how sensitively the campaigns are trying
to read the public mood with regard to drawing distinctions between
candidacies, and how delicately the candidates are tiptoeing around
one another, that their advertising at times seems enveloped in
virtually indecipherable code.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very pinkies up,'' said Lee Miringoff, director of
the Marist Institute for Public Opinion, in Poughkeepsie, N.Y.
``The candidates are being offered as separate products; it's not
comparison shopping now. On the Democratic side, there is more
discussion of competing issues, but it's being discussed as genuine
versus inauthentic, inside-the-Beltway versus out. The issues
become surrogates for something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, for instance, has been running spots that are such heavily
veiled critiques of Bradley's positions on health care and
education that it takes several viewings to fully grasp their
meaning. In his latest advertisement, a disembodied voice promises
that the vice president will ``fight against vouchers that draw
money from public schools,'' an apparent reference to Bradley's
acknowledgment that while in the Senate, he voted for some
experimental school-voucher programs.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Dunn, the Bradley campaign's communications director, sees
the Gore advertisements as falling into a rarefied category:
``implicit negative ads.'' They are, she said, a manifestation of
Gore's increasingly antagonistic approach. ``The attacks started in
September and haven't stopped,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That type of attack, if that is what it is, hardly seems to have
much growl to it. Still, Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the Gore
campaign, offered an implicit message of his own: that things may
get rougher if circumstances warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get into January, you have a very focused electorate
who are going to be looking at differences in policy and
substance,'' Lehane said. ``We have made it absolutely clear we're
going to fight for the voters in New Hampshire and Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements with a sting are certainly not unknown to the
primary voters of New Hampshire. One of the most famous, in 1988 by
Vice President George Bush, labeled Bob Dole ``Senator Straddle''
for refusing to pledge not to raise taxes; the spot, run in the
closing days of the campaign, is widely thought to have contributed
to Dole's defeat there.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the public's patience with attack ads has worn thin.
Forbes, who ran blistering spots against other Republicans in the
1996 New Hampshire race, is regarded as the recipient of residual
voter resentment this year, even though his commercials this time
have been considerably more restrained.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for voter backlash has made some media advisers
wary, and that may be why the campaigns are more adventurous with
format than with policy issues. A result is that though issues are
what the various camps purport to highlight in their spots, it is
character that seems the predominant theme.
</P>
<P>
   The varied ways in which the commercials accentuate character
range from the eye-catching documentary style of the Bush team's
new ``crash ads'' _ 30-second spots taped at real campaign events,
quickly edited and put on the air the same night or the next day _
to the straightforward evocations of the plain-spoken McCain,
delivering parts of the speech announcing his candidacy, to the
unvarnished 20-minute tape of Bradley mixing with voters at a
town-hall meeting in Sioux City, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we filmed Gov. Bush in a free-form style
was we were trying to capture some of the magic when he is out
there with the people,'' said Stuart Stevens, one of Bush's media
advisers. Similarly, Greg Stevens, McCain's media consultant (and
no relation to Bush's adviser), says the senator's ability to
``connect to people'' gives his commercials their power.
</P>
<P>
   But how much magic and power get through to the viewers is
unclear. Bruce Gronbeck, a communications professor at the
University of Iowa, said the overall effect this year was a bit of
a blur. Even when a candidate appears to be taking a strong stand,
Gronbeck said, when ``you look at the next guy's, they're pretty
much the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
