<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: recasts lede, 5th graf to show the new millennium
 &HT;    FAR FROM Y2K BUG WORRIES, REVELERS IN CARIBBEAN LAY BACK AND
SOAK IT IN
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CROIX, U.S. Virgin Islands _ Steel drums rattled through
``Auld Lang Syne,'' fireworks lit the blue Caribbean and conch
shells blasted in celebration as the new millennium swept over the
easternmost U.S. territory in this hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in shorts and sandals, many visitors marveled as much at
the balmy weather as at the dawning of a new age _ and few voiced
concerns about Y2K computer glitches as they slathered on more
suntan lotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't happen again for 1,000 years, so this is the place
to be,'' said Hope Paddock, a transplanted Texan whose daughter
lives in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   While far-away Wake Island in the Pacific Ocean was actually the
first U.S. possession to welcome the new millennium, St. Croix
capitalized on its location to host its own ``millennium-first''
party.
</P>
<P>
   Remote, rocky Point Udall on the island's eastern tip is the
easternmost spot of U.S. soil in the Atlantic basin. Officials
constructed a millennium monument there, a 20-foot-tall stone
affair resembling a sundial that was unveiled at midnight at a
ceremony attended by top government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like this back home in Philadelphia,'' said
Mariellen Heffner, who spent New Years' Eve snorkeling with her
husband and young son, earning rosy sunburns as a keepsake. ``If we
were home, we wouldn't be doing anything special.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix hoteliers were hoping millennium fever would help them
recover some of the business lost in November when late-season
Hurricane Lenny lashed the island. Damage was light, but the storm
hit right at the start of the lucrative winter tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   But the island appeared packed with tourists, sailboats crowding
the harbors and large cruise ships berthed at the pier on St.
Croix's western tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came all the way from Seattle,'' said David Wilhite, who
was visiting friends on the island. ``We're hoping all the Y2K
problems will happen, and then we'll get stuck here. Stranded in
paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
