<HEADLINE>
TOUGHER RULES OF THE ROAD 
 BY CAROL SOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC 
(Phoenix) - Teens must have more training before they can get a
driver's license and will face harsher penalties for misbehaving
behind the wheel under a law that goes into effect Saturday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time, teen drivers will face mandatory suspensions
after two traffic convictions are on the record.
</P>
<P>
   Passed in the 1999 legislative session, Arizona's Graduated
Driver's License Law is similar to those in 36 other states where
lawmakers phased in teen driv ing privileges in hopes of reduc ing
youths' high accident rate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 in Arizona, drivers under 18 were involved in 47 fatal
crashes, compared with 37 for 19-year-olds and 31 for 20-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers don't say if the young drivers were at fault, but
without training, ``it is like send ing soldiers into battle
without first going to boot camp,'' said Jeanie La Velle,
Glendale's traffic safety officer.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Goodwin, 18, of Glen dale, one of four students who
produced a brochure on the law for distribution by the Arizona
Motor Vehicle Division, AAA and others, agrees that teen driving
deserves more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focus on so many other things like gangs and drugs,'' she
said. ``But no one focuses on simple things, like driving cars,
that we do every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Automobile As sociation wants to see a version of
the law in every state by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's law says 16- and 17-year-old drivers must pass a road
test and prove that they have had driving instruction to get the
new Class G license.
</P>
<P>
   Holders of that license face tougher penalties, including the
new mandatory license suspen sions after three convictions, for
offenses ranging from speeding to reckless driving. The first
offense would be wiped from the record if the driver attended
defensive driving school, but two more would trigger the suspen
sion.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Butler and his son, Chris, 16, of Phoenix, support the
train ing and tougher penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three convictions, they should lose their licenses,''
Mike Butler said of teens.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Butler, who was waiting to get his license at a state
office, said he isn't worried about the penalties, because ``I'm
not going to get any citations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly Mathers, 16, who was applying for a learner's per mit
at a licensing office, said it isn't fair that young drivers face
stiffer penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Noted Mathers, who will take a commercial driving course be fore
applying for her Class G license, ``Adult drivers make mistakes,
too.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT: New teen driving law takes effect Saturday.
 &UR; HOW IT WORKS: Age 15 years and 7 months _ teens get learner's
permit. &QL; 
Age 16 _ Eligible for new Class G driver's license after passing
road test, taking a driver's education class, or having
parents/guardian certify that teen had 25 hours of supervised
driver training. Harsher penalties apply for driving convictions. &QL; 
 &UR; PENALTIES: First violation _ traffic school, no violation on
record. Second violation _ first conviction, tough traffic survival
school, all violations on record 39 months. Third violation _
second conviction, three-month suspension. Fourth violation _ third
conviction, six-month suspension. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
