<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SIX-GUNS TO CELL PHONES 
 BY DENNIS WAGNER  
  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(Phoenix) - Sometime during the 20th cen tury in Arizona, the
six-gun sur rendered to the cell phone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Old West faded into the sunset, and a remote territory
populated by Indians and pio neers became America's 48th state,
overrun by city slick ers.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a young country like the United States, seldom has any
region undergone such a grand metamorphosis in a mere 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   We've changed the food we eat, the work we do, the clothes we
wear _ for many of us, even the air we breathe.
</P>
<P>
   A century that opened under the fist of Anglo males is closing
amid the burgeoning influence of Hispanics and with women occu
pying the state's top political offices.
</P>
<P>
   Many impoverished Native Americans have grown flush with casino
wealth. Schools and neighborhoods were desegre gated, deserts
irrigated into gar dens; family shops were replaced by superstores,
trails by free ways, cowboys by capitalists, tel egraphs by
satellites, ranches by country clubs. Television grew from a
novelty to a lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   A region that Edward Abbey once described as ``an appalling,
burned-out wasteland'' is now among the nation's leaders in boats
and swimming pools per capita.
</P>
<P>
   But of all Arizona's 20th-cen tury changes, the most obvious
involves people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, Phoenix counted 5,544 residents. The first automobile
rolled into town that year, spell ing doom for electric trolleys.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, Phoenix is America's sixth-largest city; plan
ners dream of bringing back the trolleys to combat traffic snarls
and smog.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona was among the na tion's fastest-growing states in nine
of the past 10 decades. Its construction explosion now eats an acre
a day _ not just in Peoria and Phoenix, but also in rural burgs
like Payson and Pres cott.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Wilder, director of the University of Arizona's South
west Center, says the paradigm shift was swift and dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this century, Arizona changed from a place that epito mizes
the old Southwest to a place that epitomizes the Sun Belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's famous ``five C's'' (copper, cotton, cattle, citrus
and climate) no longer control the economy, he says.
</P>
<P>
   They've been supplanted by construction, computers and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Mining has been devalued like a copper penny. Ranching rode to
its last roundup long before Phoenix adopted the slogan ``From
Cowtown to Wowtown.'' Cotton fields and citrus groves have been
overrun by tract hous ing.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix area towns that were once distinct have all blurred
together. You can drive from Apache Junc tion to Avondale without
seeing anything like a desert except for the xeriscape medians
installed by state government workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all urbanized into one big megalopolis,'' observes
Jack Pfister, a lifetime resident and an executive with Salt River
Project. &QL; 
CATALYSTS OF CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   Historians, always argumenta tive, quibble over Arizona's prin
cipal catalysts of change.
</P>
<P>
   David Tatum, chief curator with the Arizona Historical Soci ety,
believes power tools were instrumental in a 20th-century shift
``from muscle power to mechanization.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Robert Woznicki, au thor of The History of Arizona,
says the World War II arrival of military bases and high-tech
companies was crucial. Motorola, he insists, was ``the Padre Kino
of industries here.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Iverson, an Arizona State University history professor,
says federal spending _ on dams, railroads, mining opera tions,
agriculture, forestry and parks _ made Arizona possible. It is no
small irony, he adds, that a state renowned for political
independence was grubstaked by Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Creighton, publisher of Arizona Capitol Times and a 33-year
Phoenix area journalist, says the 1960s adoption of a one-man,
one-vote rule ripped power away from country folks and gave it to
urbanites, especially in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the greatest politi cal change in the history of
Arizona,'' Creighton asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever most prompted Ari zona's evolution, the human out come
is undisputed: A territory born of sweat and blood has been overrun
by city folk with mani cured hands and yards.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the 1940s, more than half the population lived on
farms or ranches. Today, the number is under 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder, of the UA's Southwest Center, speaks of a ``monumental
change'' from isolated families who lived off the land and helped
one another to urban transients who squeeze together yet remain
socially alienated and ``largely disinterested in their historical
antecedents.'' &QL; 
WAY BACK WHEN
</P>
<P>
   Real development began with prospectors in the 1800s, digging up
the landscape in search of shiny rocks. They found enough to create
a few gold rushes and leave a few ghost towns.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1880s, cattle barons had moved in with monster herds,
creating their own rule on the range. But nature's laws proved
stronger: Drought and overgraz ing wiped out the grasses, eroded
the soil and littered the state with bovine skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   As gold and silver veins tapped out, a quest for copper brought
giant corporations with giant ma chines. Labor was imported from
Europe, Mexico and China. Com pany towns arose overnight in
Clifton, Globe and Jerome.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the railroads. Prompted by government contracts that
included millions of acres of free land, they opened Arizona to
more development. Settlers moved in to start tilling soil long
abandoned by the Hohokam.
</P>
<P>
   But nature didn't make it easy. The state's inhospitableness
prompted Gen. William Tecum seh Sherman to remark: ``We went to war
with Mexico to get Arizona, and now we should go to war with her
again to make her take it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculators, always a fixture on the Arizona scene, didn't quote
Sherman in their brochures. Nor did they mention scorpions, rat
tlers and dust storms.
</P>
<P>
   Grady Gammage Jr., attorney and author of Phoenix in Per
spective, says land scammers ultimately helped settle this state,
attracting hapless immi grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the children of gener ations of con men,'' Gammage
notes. ``This whole place really is the product of real-estate
specu lation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, notions of manifest des tiny prevailed, thanks to two of
the key developments in Arizona history: dams and air-condition
ing. &QL; 
FLOOD AND DROUGHT
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, the Salt, Verde, Gila and Colorado rivers staged
periodic rebellions, flooding towns and farms, then trickling to
drought levels.
</P>
<P>
   Early settlers were obsessed with harnessing the water for
safety and progress. In 1902, Congress approved construction of
Roosevelt Dam. Nine years later, Arizona had the world's largest
man-made lake _ a mar vel of engineering, a monolithic start on
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing decades saw many more dams go up, along with a
Central Arizona Project that delivers water from the Colorado
River. Dams meant ag riculture and electricity, semi conductor
plants and golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Waves of Americans moved into the ``Nile of the West.'' During
the Dust Bowl era, refu gees en route to California stopped and
settled. World War II introduced Air Force personnel and suppliers.
Motorola arrived in 1948, drawing more industry.
</P>
<P>
   But summers remained hellish, until air-conditioning arrived in
the 1950s. First used to cool factories, refrigeration was a
godsend to homeowners and builders. Arizona finally had an answer
to the desert's cruelest element. &QL; 
CULTURAL STEW
</P>
<P>
   Today, Arizona contains 113,596 square miles of people who are
as diverse as their landscape.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mongrel state full of folks who mostly weren't born here
and don't plan on staying. Each year 300,000 new ones ar rive and
100,000 move out.
</P>
<P>
   What some mistake for an Arizona identity crisis is really a
multiple personality. From Navajos to New Agers, the one thing we
have in common is that we don't have much in common.
</P>
<P>
   Rootless diversity sometimes means conflict, often alienation.
Just in the past decade, Arizo nans passed a Martin Luther King Jr.
holiday, adopted an Eng lish-only law and fought over whether this
is a Christian nation.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Goode, the former Phoenix councilman, recalls be ing
turned away from high school in Yuma a half-century ago be cause of
his African heritage. Today, Goode says, ``we have made some
progress, but we have not yet arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Gutierrez, a former state senator, says Hispanics
achieved stunning advances in education and economics here after
the civil-rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was, in the '50s, a kind of hierarchy where Hispanics
and Native Americans were at the bottom of the heap,'' Gutier rez
said. ``That kind of psycho logical state has been demolished,
wonderfully. . . . There's a helluva lot of reason for hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix area economist Elliott Pol lack also stresses the
brighter side of modernization.
</P>
<P>
   As 2000 begins, Arizona's popu lace is more educated, diverse
and active than ever, Pollack says. Jobs are plentiful, crime is
down, opportunities abound. Even the state's environment has
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy here has in creased 80 percent since 1900.
Residents earn about six times more in real dollars _ not count ing
the benefit of indoor plumb ing, modern medicine, phones and other
conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   Those with nostalgic yearnings might recall that a century ago,
folks seldom had time for such luxuries. Instead, Pollack notes
bluntly, ``they were working their (butts) off.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
