<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-NY-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GIULIANI, NO NEWS IS GOOD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's $13 million crisis center in the World
Trade Center came suddenly to life. Dozens of beefy officials
wearing uniforms or windbreakers or suits _ the mark of real power
_ hustled to their positions. The crowded press room fell into a
hush.
</P>
<P>
   And in walked Mayor Rudolph Giuliani with the latest news:
</P>
<P>
   There was no news.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday night, the city's preparations for a New Year's Eve
disaster were beginning to look almost like overkill, at least as
viewed from the inside of Giuliani's hardened command and
communications center, built to withstand bullets, bombs and bugs _
the Year 2000 kind.
</P>
<P>
   With fears of widespread computer power and electrical-system
failures around the world fizzling as fast as the Earth's rotation,
the mayor announced just after 5 p.m. that nothing surprising had
happened so far. ``The only thing we're concerned about is the
unexpected and the unanticipated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said there had been more bomb threats than usual Friday
_ 16 spread throughout the five boroughs, as against nine on an
average day _ but that all had been checked out immediately and
``proved bogus.''
</P>
<P>
   Times Square had filled up much faster than in earlier years,
the mayor said; by 5 p.m. there were already as many people in
Times Square as there had been at midnight a year ago. ``The areas
near the ball drop are already completely full,'' he said. He said
he had spoken with visitors from Germany, Japan and elsewhere, many
of whom had been waiting in the cold ``12, 14, 15, 16 hours,'' the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani would not say how many people had chosen to brave the
weather, fears of a terrorist act and each other's elbows to stake
out a spot in the epicenter of what he likes to call the capital of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the business of crowd estimates,'' he said. ``The
streets are pretty well full.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to Police Commissioner Howard Safir, Giuliani
heaped praise on the department, which Safir said was spending
about $6 million for overtime for New Year's security.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,000 officers were assigned to Times Square and 37,000 of
the department's 40,000 officers were scheduled to work, many of
them in 12-hour shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for the New York Police Department to
demonstrate how to deal with crowds,'' Giuliani said. ``There's
nobody that does it better.''
</P>
<P>
   With no emergencies to manage, officials in the Office of
Emergency Management's celebrated bunker _ including
representatives of local utilities and dozens of city, state,
regional and federal agencies _ infuriated the 75 or so journalists
watching them work through a glass wall Friday by repeatedly
lowering a screen specially installed to block the view. Only when
television reporters went live, and when the mayor appeared, was
the screen raised.
</P>
<P>
   Asked five times why the view could not be kept clear, a mayoral
spokesman, Matt Higgins, said only, ``Because it's not being
done.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his briefing, the mayor suggested a simple explanation.
``It's easier for people to do their work if people aren't staring
at them,'' he said. ``Who knows what they may want to scratch or do
or whatever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
